Name: Chipotle Mexican Grill, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Dow reclaims close over 20,000; Nasdaq notches record\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                          DJIA, -0.30%                                                                                                                                                rallied 186.55 points, or 0.9%, to 20,071.46, its first close above 20,000 since Jan. 27, led by a 4.6% surge in shares of Visa Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          V, +0.61%                                                                                                                                                 For the week, however, the average closed down 0.1% lower.', u'The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                rose 30.57 points, or 0.5%, to close at a record 5,666.77, for a weekly gain of 0.1%.', u'The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                climbed 16.57 points, or 0.7%, to finish at 2,297.42, with 10 of the 11 main sectors closing in positive territory, for a weekly gain of 0.1%. ', u'The financial sector popped 2%, and was by far the biggest gainer of any S&P 500\u2019s sector. Shares of J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          JPM, +0.22%                                                                                                                                                 Bank of America Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          BAC, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                and Citigroup Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          C, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                 all closed up more than 2%, while Goldman Sachs Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          GS, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                and Morgan Stanley                                                                                                                                                                                                          MS, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                 both finished up more than 4%. Goldman alone contributed about 40% of the Dow\u2019s daily gains, or about 72 points. ', u'Trump signed an executive order directing the Treasury secretary to review Dodd-Frank legislation, implemented in the aftermath of the 2008-09 financial crisis. The president signed a separate order that will delay the implementation of the \u201cfiduciary rule,\u201d which requires that the financial advisers and brokers who handle individual retirement and 401(k) accounts act in the best interest of their clients. Deregulation, proponents say, could improve the sector\u2019s profitability, especially in an environment with rising interest rates, which is typically good for banks.', u' Key Words:  Trump economic adviser Gary Cohn likens Wall Street regulatory regime to an unappealing restaurant menu ', u'  ', u'Strong jobs data also contributed to the rise in stocks. The U.S. generated 227,000 new jobs in January, the biggest gain in four months, comfortably topping the 197,000 that had been expected. However, the unemployment rate rose to 4.8%, and wage growth was an anemic 0.1%.', u' See: Job report\u2019s downside: slower wage growth ', u' Clorox Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CLX, -0.57%                                                                                                                                                and Hershey Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          HSY, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                each reported earnings ahead of the open. Clorox added 4.1%, while Hershey advanced 1.3%.', u'In other economic news, factory orders rose 1.3% in December, more than twice as fast as had been forecast, while the service sector grew at a slightly slower pace than had been expected.', u'Shares of Amazon.com Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          AMZN, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                dropped 3.5% following disappointment over fourth-quarter revenue. Then company reported earnings late Thursday. ', u' Read: Buy Amazon \u2018aggressively\u2019 on any post-earnings dip, say bullish analysts ', u'  FireEye Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FEYE, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                tumbled nearly 16% as investors focused on continuing heavy losses for the company over another earnings beat. ', u' GoPro Inc. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                          GPRO, -2.38%                                                                                                                                                were down 13% after the company missed fourth-quarter revenue expectations and issued a weak forecast late Thursday. ', u' Read:  As GoPro drowns, is it begging for Apple to save it? ', u'  Visa Inc. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           V, +0.61%                                                                                                                                                rallied after the credit-card company late Thursday beat earnings forecasts.', u' Chipotle Mexican Grill Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CMG, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                                              CMG, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                fell 4.5% as earnings missed Wall Street forecasts.', u' Hanesbrands Inc. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                          HBI, -1.22%                                                                                                                                                fell more than 16% after the company cut its outlook following a weak quarter. ', u' Macy\u2019s Inc. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                          M, -1.55%                                                                                                                                                rallied 6.4% on a report that Hudson\u2019s Bay Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          HBC, -1.48%                                                                                                                                                has approached the retailer over a possible takeover.', u' Other markets: Asian markets                                                                                                                                                                                                          ADOW, -1.58%                                                                                                                                                closed flat to lower, while European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                logged gains across the board, led by banks. The dollar                                                                                                                                                                                                          DXY, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                slipped, while gold                                                                                                                                                                                                          GCH7, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                ticked up 0.1% to settle at $1,220.80 an ounce, and oil prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0settled up 0.5% at $53.83 a barrel.']

Name: Ross Stores, Inc.
Article: 9 : [u"\r\n         Department-store shares sell off after Kohl's, Macy's reports\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Shares of traditional department stores fell in the extended session Wednesday after Kohl\'s Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KSS, -0.60%                                                                                                                                                 lowered its outlook and Macy\'s Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           M, -1.35%                                                                                                                                                 announced store closures. Kohl\'s shares dropped 12% to $45.60 after the company cut its fiscal 2016 earnings outlook after volatile holiday sales. Macy\'s shares fell 8.6% to $32.80 after hours after the company announced plans to close 68 stores and lay off 6,200 employees in 2017. The news caused a ripple effect across department store shares after hours with shares of Nordstrom Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JWN, -0.98%                                                                                                                                                 down 6% at $46, J.C. Penney Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JCP, -2.46%                                                                                                                                                 shares down 4.4% at $8.10, Dillard\'s Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DDS, -1.97%                                                                                                                                                 shares falling 3.1% to $61, Sears Holdings Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHLD, -14.97%                                                                                                                                                 shares down 2.4% at $10.11, and Ross Stores Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ROST, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                 shares declining 1.5% to $65.55.']

Name: VanEck Vectors Biotech ETF
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Dow moves within 50 points of 20,000 after Trump news conference  \r\n    ']
Body: [u'Major indexes oscillated between small gains and losses during the session while biotech stocks were notable losers after Trump said companies were \u201cgetting away with murder\u201d with respect to drug prices. Energy shares were among the day\u2019s biggest gainers, rising alongside a jump in the price of crude oil. ', u' Read: MarketWatch\u2019s live blog on Donald Trump\u2019s press conference ', u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                 rose 98.75 points, or 0.5%, to close at 19,954.28, while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:ESH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 6.42 points, or 0.3%, to end at 2,275.32. The Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.34%                                                                                                                                                 added 11.83 points, or 0.2%, to finish at a record 5,563.65. ', u' See: How U.S. stocks tend to perform after presidential inaugurations ', u'In a measure of how uncertainty wasn\'t alleviated by the news conference, the CBOE Volatility                                                                                                                                                                                                           VIX, -2.73%                                                                                                                                                \xa0at one time rose more than 5%, though it remains well below its long-term average. Typically, the so-called \u201cfear index\u201d has an inverse correlation with stocks. ', u' Read: Why chasing after high-yield dividend stocks is bad news ', u'Investors also watched the confirmation hearings of Rex Tillerson, Trump\u2019s nominee to head the State Department. Russia and China were major topics of discussion in the hearings.', u' Need to know: The biggest risk as markets shrug at the Trump-Russia imbroglio ', u' Read:   Trump\u2019s game of chicken with China is a lose-lose situation ', u' Economic docket: Investors will hear from several Fed officials over the next two days, including Chairwoman Janet Yellen, and retail sales data are due Friday. ', u' Stocks to watch: The iShares Nasdaq Biotechnology ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                            IBB, +0.42%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 3% while the SPDR S&P Biotech ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                          XBI, +0.80%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 3.4% and the VanEck Vectors Biotech ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           BBH, +0.46%                                                                                                                                                 dropped 2.7%. More broadly, the Health Care Select Sector SPDR ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLV, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 1%.', u' Supervalu Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SVU, -1.94%                                                                                                                                                \xa0reported sales below forecasts, sending shares down 7.5% in early trading.', u' Merck & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MRK, -0.60%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 2.9% after the drugmaker said the Food and Drug Administration would grant a priority review for one of its lung-cancer drug treatments.', u' Ford Motor Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           F, +0.73%                                                                                                                                                \xa0announced a special dividend and gave updates on its forecasts late Tuesday. Shares fell 1.4%.', u'  Read:  Is this the year for stock pickers? Here are 20 picks from Citi ', u' Other markets: European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.38%                                                                                                                                                ended modestly higher. In Asia,                                                                                                                                                                                                           ADOW, -1.59%                                                                                                                                                 stocks outside of China broadly rose. ', u'The dollar                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0regained some strength across the board, particularly against the British pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.0240%                                                                                                                                                 which weakened after a reports on industrial production and the trade deficit. ', u'Crude-oil prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLG7                                                                                                                                                \xa0rebounded, adding more than 2%, after two straight day of losses, with investors focusing on a report on U.S. supply data due later. Gold prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:GCG7                                                                                                                                                \xa0extended gains. ', u'  \u2014Barbara Kollmeyer contributed to this article  ']

Name: Sears Holdings Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         This is where the real risk for oil prices kicks in\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Oil is throwing a massive tantrum right now, just in time to spoil the 8th anniversary of the stock market\u2019s bull run.', u'Even if equities largely pay no mind to calendar dates, and yesterday\u2019s stock slide wasn\u2019t too severe, the slick stuff is tossing some shade this morning as Wednesday\u2019s sell-off reloads. (Thank shale-oil pioneer Harold Hamm\u2019s oil-killer comment for that meltdown, say some). ', u'\u201cIf we were vulnerable to a collapse, it would have happened by now. Most likely we are setting up for another sideways consolidation like we saw between December and February,\u201d he says on his blog.', u'Our call of the day is sticking to crude, compliments of a tweet from Raoul Pal:', u'The Global Macro Investor founder and former Goldman Sachs alum been here before. Like others, he\u2019s been warning that oil is vulnerable to a change of heart from big money managers and hedge funds. They\u2019ve been piling into the commodity for months, on a bet prices will keep moving higher, but may now jump out.', u'Those bullish bets on crude are becoming less popular, going by data last week from the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. It was the first reduction in three weeks and the strongest since early November for Brent, said Commerzbank. But the bank warned earlier this week that there are still too many long positions and that high optimism could turn into a \u201csword of Damocles\u201d threat to prices if selling by those investors intensifies.', u'Echoing that $45-a-barrel warning this morning, analysts at National Bank, say it\u2019s a \u201creasonable target\u201d right now. Meanwhile, Saxo Bank\u2019s chief commodity guy, Ole Hansen, says $47.18 a barrel opens a path to $42.20 a barrel.', u'Oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0is under $50 a barrel and the Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.23%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and the Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.42%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are all under some pressure.', u'Don\u2019t forget Thursday is European Central Bank meeting day. Here\u2019s what to watch out for from Draghi and the gang. And follow all the action on our live blog', u'Elsewhere, gold                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCJ7, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is slipping, and the dollar                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, -0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is moving up.', u'See the Market Snapshot column for the latest action.', u' Read: Bull market\u2019s 8-year anniversary reminds us that the Dow rewards the bold ', u'As MarketWatch\u2019s Ryan Vlastelica explains, short interest \u2014 a bet on declining prices \u2014 in the bond market has been climbing. It has hit historic highs for the big iShares High Yield Corporate Bond ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           HYG, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                \xa0(pictured).', u'Dutch paints and chemicals maker Akzo Nobel                                                                                                                                                                                                           AKZO, +21.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has rejected an unsolicited $22.1 billion offer from U.S. peer PPG                                                                                                                                                                                                           PPG, -1.42%                                                                                                                                                \xa0.', u'Signet Jewelers                                                                                                                                                                                                           SIG, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0missed sales estimates and offered a softer outlook, but shares are up a bit. Staples                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPLS, -0.82%                                                                                                                                                \xa0earnings also missed, and shares are falling. Sears                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHLD, -14.81%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is up after results beat Wall Street forecasts.', u'After the close, Ulta Salon                                                                                                                                                                                                           ULTA, +0.85%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u2014 a momentum stock that has lots of believers \u2014 will report. ', u'Shell                                                                                                                                                                                                           RDS.A, -0.95%                                                                                                                                                                              RDSB, -0.77%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is selling its Canada oil sands business for $7.25 billion', u'E.L.F. Beauty                                                                                                                                                                                                           ELF, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0soared 14% late Wednesday after the cosmetics company swung to a profit and guided above consensus.', u'Women\u2019s apparel retailer J. Jill                                                                                                                                                                                                           JILL, +0.89%                                                                                                                                                \xa0priced its IPO below the expected range ahead of Thursday\u2019s NYSE debut.', u'AT&T                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0said that 911 outage for some cellphone callers on Wednesday is now fixed.', u'RadioShack owner General Wireless Operations filed for chapter 11 protection late Wednesday, the electronics retailer\u2019s second filing in as many years. ', u' Read:  The five internet stocks you should buy right now, says Citi  ', u'Weekly jobless claims surged 20,000 to 243,000, but layoffs are still near a 45-year low. Import prices surged, spreading beyond into other industrial and consumer goods. The fourth-quarter report on services at 10 a.m.', u'In China, producer prices rose at the fastest pace in 8 1/2 years, due to a sharp depreciation of the yuan. At the same time, consumer prices rose less than expected, which some say could encourage tighter monetary conditions. ', u'30% \u2014 That\u2019s how many U.S. college students intend to tap into their student loans to pay for spring break this year. ', u' His idea: single-player coverage for the above, then standard health care for the rest.', u'The pet police pig that\u2019s taking New York by storm', u'When a woman loves ... a robot', u'  Just wow...', u'Stock bulls share a birthday of sorts, with Barbie', u'Planned Parenthood\u2019s defiant response to the GOP: \u201cNo way\u201d', u' Movie theaters with jungle gyms try to lure parents from Netflix', u' Need to Know starts early and is updated until the opening bell, but sign up here to get it delivered once to your email box. Name: Extra Space Storage Inc
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Bull trend pauses:  Charting the S&P 500\u2019s early-2017 holding pattern\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Still, while a near-term consolidation phase has been long overdue, and remains underway, the U.S. benchmarks\u2019 more important longer-term backdrop continues to support a firmly-bullish bias. ', u'Before detailing the U.S. markets\u2019 wider view, the S&P 500\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                 hourly chart highlights the past two weeks. ', u'Moving to the small-caps, the iShares Russell 2000 ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           IWM, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                 is acting well technically.', u'Meanwhile, the SPDR Trust S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPY, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0violated its 20-day moving average to conclude 2016 amid a seasonally uncharacteristic volume uptick. ', u'To reiterate, the S&P\u2019s 20-day, currently 2,249, closely matches a near-term inflection point, and remains firmly in play early Tuesday. This area defines the immediate bull-bear technical tension. ', u'The charts below detail names that are technically well positioned. These are radar screen names \u2014 sectors or stocks poised to move in the near term. For the original comments on the stocks below, see The Technical Indicator Library. ', u'Technically, the PowerShares U.S. Dollar Bullish ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           UUP, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                 has sustained a break to seven-year highs, staging its second consecutive successful test of first support. (Recall that the December low matched the top of the November gap.)', u'The orderly two-week range is a continuation pattern, and dovetails with a bullish multi-year backdrop, illustrated on the monthly chart. The dollar\u2019s longer-term path of least resistance points firmly higher. ', u'More broadly, the U.S. Dollar Index has reached its latest 14-year high early Tuesday, following stronger-than-expected manufacturing data. Conversely, the CurrencyShares Euro ETF remains under pressure, briefly tagging a record low early Tuesday. ', u'Meanwhile, the United States Oil Fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           USO, -1.29%                                                                                                                                                 continues to act well technically. The fund tracks the price of West Texas Intermediate (WTI) light, sweet crude oil. ', u'To reiterate, a breakout would resolve a massive double bottom, opening the path to potentially material follow-through. A projected target matches the 2016 peak of 12.45, illustrated on the weekly chart.', u'Moving to specific names, Rowan Companies                                                                                                                                                                                                           RDC, +0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is a well positioned mid-cap oil driller. ', u'The subsequent pullback has been fueled by decreased volume, placing the shares at an attractive entry near the breakout point, and 14.7% under the December peak. The shares are also well positioned on the weekly chart.', u'Initially profiled Aug. 2, Micron Technology, Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MU, +1.57%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has returned 61.7% and remains well positioned. ', u'ASML Holding N.V.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ASML, +1.20%                                                                                                                                                 is a large-cap chip equipment name based in the Netherlands. ', u'Separately, ASML Holding is within striking distance of all-time highs \u2014 uncharted territory \u2014 better illustrated on the monthly chart.', u'Extra Space Storage, Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           EXR, -0.86%                                                                                                                                                 is a large-cap REIT showing signs of life. (Yield = 4.0%.)', u'The table below includes names recently profiled in The Technical Indicator that remain well positioned. For the original comments, see The Technical Indicator Library.']

Name: GlaxoSmithKline PLC
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         FTSE 100 ekes out a slight gain ahead of key Brexit vote\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The FTSE 100                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.93%                                                                                                                                                 closed out 0.04% higher at 7,188.82, after a session that lacked momentum.', u'The muted action came ahead of a key vote on a Brexit bill in the House of Commons slated to come at 8 p.m. London time, or 3 p.m. Eastern Time, the BBC reported. Lawmakers are expected to give a green light to amendments to legislation allowing the government to start the process of leaving the European Union.', u' Read: Brexit bill clears key hurdle in parliament\u2014what happens next? ', u'The pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.3686%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was buying $1.2542, down up from $1.2513 late Tuesday in New York, drawing support from Bank of England policy maker Kristin Forbes saying U.K. interest rates may need to rise soon to keep inflation in check. ', u' Mining moves: After opening in positive territory, gains for the U.K.\u2019s miners fizzled through the day to end at the bottom of the FTSE. ', u'Rio Tinto                                                                                                                                                                                                           RIO, -1.65%                                                                                                                                                                              RIO, +0.44%                                                                                                                                                                              BHP, -0.73%                                                                                                                                                \xa0ended down 1.7%, even after the Anglo-Australian miner said it swung to a profit in 2016 and announced a full-year dividend of $1.70 a share. The dividend was down from a year ago, but higher than expectations.', u'BHP Billiton PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           BLT, -2.18%                                                                                                                                                                              BHP, -0.73%                                                                                                                                                                              BHP, -2.92%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 3.4% as workers at the company\u2019s majority-owned Minera Escondida in Chile were expected to strike Thursday. ', u'Glencore PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           GLEN, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                                              GLCNF, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 1.8% and Anglo American PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAL, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 0.3%. ', u' Other movers: Also on the downside, Hargreaves Lansdown PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           HL., -1.39%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 1.6%. The provider of investment products posted a 21% rise in first-half pretax profit, but said the second half of the year will be impacted by the financial services compensation scheme levy, Dow Jones Newswires reported.', u'Oil giants Royal Dutch Shell PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           RDSB, -1.04%                                                                                                                                                                              RDS.B, -1.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0dropped 1.8% and BP                                                                                                                                                                                                           BP., -0.95%                                                                                                                                                                              BP, -1.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 0.3%. Name: Twitter, Inc.
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Here\u2019s why Snap will reward investors like Facebook \u2014 instead of failing them like Twitter\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Let\u2019s face it, the question on the minds of most investors is straightforward. Will Snapchat parent                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +7.75%                                                                                                                                                \xa0be more like Facebook                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, +0.56%                                                                                                                                                 and reward shareholders nicely? Or will it be a dud like Twitter                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWTR, +2.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and let them down?', u' Read: Snap shares soar in debut after largest IPO since 2014 ', u' 1. Snapchat is rolling out ads without killing off robust user growth  ', u'\u201cDuring Twitter\u2019s stumble, Snapchat accelerated its user and revenue growth. They are experiencing astronomical growth,\u201d says Matthew Kennedy, an analyst with Renaissance Capital, which manages the Renaissance IPO ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           IPO, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                 \u201cSnapchat has already proven it can grow and compete with the established players.\u201d ', u' 2. Like Facebook, Snapchat will remain founder-run ', u' Read: Snap IPO boils down to one question: Do you trust Evan Spiegel? ', u'The downside here for investors is that in business \u2014 as in life \u2014 the biggest rewards often go to those who focus on long-term strategic goals over short-term gratification. Remember the marshmallow experiment?', u'There\u2019s good news in this for anyone who couldn\u2019t get IPO shares at $17 because they aren\u2019t favored clients at Goldman Sachs                                                                                                                                                                                                          GS, -0.55%                                                                                                                                                 Morgan Stanley                                                                                                                                                                                                           MS, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                 J.P. Morgan                                                                                                                                                                                                           JPM, +0.72%                                                                                                                                                 Deutsche Bank                                                                                                                                                                                                           DB, +0.12%                                                                                                                                                 Barclays                                                                                                                                                                                                           BCS, -0.66%                                                                                                                                                 Credit Suisse                                                                                                                                                                                                           CS, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0or any of the other investment banks assisting with the IPO. ', u'This happened with other high profile founder-run companies like Facebook, Alphabet                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOGL, +0.43%                                                                                                                                                                              GOOG, +0.42%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Amazon.com                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.65%                                                                                                                                                \xa0early on, and it was one reason I suggested them as buys at the time in my stock newsletter Brush Up on Stocks. Since those points in time, Facebook, Alphabet and Amazon.com are all up four to nine times. So this is a dynamic worth watching at founder run companies. ', u' 3. Snapchat is a major player in a big trend ', u' Michael Brush is a Manhattan-based financial writer. At the time of publication, he had no positions in any stocks mentioned in this column. Brush has suggested FB, GOOGL, AMZN and JPM in his stock newsletter Brush Up on Stocks.  ']

Name: General Dynamics Corporation
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Trump stokes rally in defense stocks toward record highs\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of defense and aerospace companies got a nice lift Monday, after President Donald Trump said his first budget will seek a big boost in defense spending. The iShares U.S. Aerospace & Defense ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           ITA, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                 climbed 1.1% toward a record high, with 37 of 39 components trading higher. Trump said he would seek $54 billion in extra spending on defense, to be offset by decreases elsewhere, which he didn\'t mention. Among the ETF\'s most heavily weighted components, shares of Boeing Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BA, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                 rallied 1%, of United Technologies Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UTX, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                 tacked on 0.4%, of Lockheed Martin Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LMT, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                 rose 1.5%, of General Dynamics Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GD, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                 gained 0.5% and of Raytheon Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           RTN, -0.27%                                                                                                                                                 tacked on 1.4%. Of those five stocks, only United Technologies\' wasn\'t trading in record territory. The biggest gainer within the ETF was Triumph Group Inc.\'s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           TGI, -0.82%                                                                                                                                                 which shot up 3.4%. The only components not gaining were ManTech Interational Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MANT, -0.71%                                                                                                                                                 which was down 0.5%, and TransDigm Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TDG, -3.51%                                                                                                                                                 which eased less than 0.1%. The sector ETF has now run up 17% since the election while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                 has rallied 11%.']

The Michaels Companies, Inc.
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         Michaels Cos. stock jumps 7% after earnings beat and upbeat outlook\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Michaels Cos. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           MIK, -0.51%                                                                                                                                                 jumped 7% in premarket trade Tuesday, after the company beat fourth-quarter earnings estimates and offered a higher-than-expected outlook for 2017. The arts and crafts store chain said it had net income of $195.3 million, or 95 cents a share, in the quarter, up from $183.7 million, or 87 cents a share, in the year-earlier period. Adjusted per-share earnings came to 96 cents, ahead of the FactSet consensus of 95 cents. Sales rose 4.1% to $1.8 billion, matching the FactSet consensus. For 2017, the company is expecting sales growth of 2.5% to 4.0% and same-store sales to be flat to up 1.5%. It\'s expecting 2017 EPS to range from $2.05 to $2.17. For the first quarter, the company is expecting same-store sales to be flat to down 1% and for EPS of 38 cents to 40 cents. The FactSet consensus is for full-year EPS of $2.02 and first-quarter EPS of 39 cents. Shares have fallen 14% in the last 12 months, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 19%. ']

Name: IDEXX Laboratories, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Should Wall Street let God guide stock-market investments?\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Inspire Global Hope Large Cap ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           BLES, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                \u2014which made its debut on Tuesday, along with a small and midcap fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           ISMD, -0.46%                                                                                                                                                 with an identical strategy\u2014was designed for religious investors looking to have their portfolio holdings align with their personal beliefs.', u'Religious investing has a long history on Wall Street, with a number of mutual-fund providers offering Christian or Islamic products that adhere to the particulars of those faiths. Shariah-compliant funds for Muslim investors, for example, don\u2019t invest in banks because the religion forbids charging interest. ', u'Among ETFs, there is the Global X S&P 500 Catholic Values ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           CATH, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                 which was launched in April 2016 and is built around the investment guidelines of the U.S. Council of Catholic Bishops. Those guidelines prohibit investing in companies based on their services\u2014including ones that provide abortion, weapons, or which work with embryonic stem cells\u2014or other practices. It bars companies that discriminate on the basis of race or gender, and it doesn\u2019t include screens for sexual orientation.', u'Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.57%                                                                                                                                                 whose chief executive Tim Cook is openly gay, is the top component of the Catholic Values fund; it is not a holding of the Inspire ETF.', u'The Global X fund dipped 0.2% on Tuesday, though it is up 5.9% thus far in 2017, slightly better than the 5.6% rise of the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                 ', u'Based on data about the underlying index, the equally weighted fund\u2019s top holding is Mead Johnson Nutrition Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MJN, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                 though it only comprises 0.31% of the portfolio. Other top names include Idexx Laboratories Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           IDXX, +1.56%                                                                                                                                                 U.S. Steel Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           X, +2.70%                                                                                                                                                 and Invesco Ltd                                                                                                                                                                                                           IVZ, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                 The fund has heavy overseas exposure. While 46.3% of its composition is U.S. names, an additional 20% is from Great Britain (9.1%), Australia (7.8%), and China (3.5%). The remaining third is from \u201cother\u201d countries.']

Name: Hudson Pacific Properties, Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Netflix spreads roots in Hollywood, with lease for more office space\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Netflix Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NFLX, -0.46%                                                                                                                                                 is expanding its presence in Hollywood, signing a lease to occupy another office building in La La Land. Hudson Pacific Properties Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPP, -0.67%                                                                                                                                                 said on Friday Netflix has signed to fully occupy a 91,953 square feet, five-story building called CUE. The building is part of an entertainment production complex Hudson Pacific is building at Sunset Bronson Studios. Netflix has already leased a 14-story, 323,000 square feet space called ICON on the complex. Netflix has leased more than 500,000 square feet of space in Hollywood from Hudson Pacific, according to a news release. Netflix has been maneuvering into film and TV production and over the last year has been planting its roots in Hollywood. Shares of Netflix are up 12% in the last 12 months, while the S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 is up 14%. Hudson Pacific shares have gained 30% in the trailing 12 month period.']

Name: Micron Technology, Inc.
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Micron CEO announces plans to retire \r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of Micron Technology Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MU, +1.72%                                                                                                                                                 climbed roughly 2% in afternoon trade Thursday following the announcement of CEO Mark Durcan\'s planned retirement. The chip maker said it has formed a special committee to oversee the succession process and has initiated a search for his replacement. The company doesn\'t have a timeframe regarding when the switch will happen, and said Durcan will continue to lead Micron in the meantime. Shares of Micron traded around $25.15 shortly after the announcement. They\'ve increased 51% in the past there months and 137% in the past year, vastly outperforming the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                 which is up 8.5% in past three months and 20% in the past year. ']

Name: First Solar, Inc.
Article: 11 : [u'\r\n         First Solar shares higher after company beats sales, earnings predictions\r\n    ']
Body: [u'First Solar Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FSLR, -2.79%                                                                                                                                                 shares rose 1.6% late Tuesday after the solar-panel maker and solar-power developer reported fourth-quarter adjusted earnings and sales above expectations. First Solar said it lost $6.92 a share in the quarter, versus earnings of $1.63 a share in the year-ago period. Adjusted for one-time items, First Solar earned $1.24 a share in the quarter. Sales fell to $480 million in the quarter from $942 million a year ago. Analysts polled by FactSet had expected adjusted earnings of $1.01 a share on sales of $404 million for the Tempe, Ariz., company in the quarter. First Solar also tweaked higher its expectations for 2017 sales to between $2.8 billion and $2.9 billion, from a range between $2.5 billion and $2.6 billion. Shares ended the regular trading session up 5.1%. ']

Name: Caterpillar, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Report accuses Caterpillar of tax fraud to prop up its stock price\r\n    ']
Body: [u'\u201cCaterpillar did not comply with either U.S. tax law or U.S. financial reporting rules,\u201d the report said, according to the New York Times, which obtained a copy of it. \u201cI believe that the company\u2019s noncompliance with these rules was deliberate and primarily with the intention of maintaining a higher share price. These actions were fraudulent rather than negligent.\u201d', u'  Caterpillar said it has been fighting the IRS over up to $2 billion in taxes and penalties on profits earned by its Swiss unit, CSARL. The Times reported the company\u2019s taxes have been under investigation since 2014.', u'Last week, federal investigators searched three Caterpillar offices near its Peoria, Illinois, headquarters. The company later said the raids were likely related to the tax investigation.', u'Caterpillar                                                                                                                                                                                                           CAT, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 shares have declined 1.4% over the past three months, but are up more than 28% over the past 12 months, according to FactSet. The S&P 500 has gained 20% in the last 12 months. ']

Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Nutanix plunges after disappointing forecast\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Nutanix Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NTNX, -0.15%                                                                                                                                                 one of the hottest tech IPOs of 2016, plunged more than 17% Thursday after its second earnings report as a public company issued a forecast that didn\'t meet Wall Street\'s expectations. The company, which sells cloud computing resources focused on combining storage and computing power, reported a net loss of $93.2 million, or 66 cents a share, on sales of $182.2 million. After adjusting for stock-based compensation, the company claimed a loss of 28 cents a share. That performance in the company\'s second fiscal quarter easily beat analysts\' estimates of adjusted losses of 35 cents a share on sales of $178.4 million, according to FactSet. Nutanix\'s forecast for the current quarter did not meet expectations, however. The company said it expects adjusted losses of 45 cents to 48 cents a share in the fiscal third quarter on revenue of $180 million to $190 million. Analysts on average projected adjusted losses of 35 cents a share on sales of $188.5 million, FactSet reported. Nutanix Chief Financial Officer Duston Williams noted in the announcement that increased costs of some components were affecting the company\'s costs; Hewlett Packard Enterprise Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPE, +0.56%                                                                                                                                                 said in its earnings call last week that increased prices for some memory chips had affected its results. Nutanix, which also suffered after its first earnings report as a public company, fell lower than $26 in late trading after closing with a 1.3% gain at $31.12.']

Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         Trump and the bulls look to rip a hole in oil prices\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Of course, some will tell you all that uncertainty may eventually be good for stocks. Our call of the day comes from Raoul Pal, founder of Global Macro Investor. He says it\u2019s time to buck the big-money trend and short oil, because those who produce the black stuff think the price right now really should be at $30. ', u'Pal\u2019s call comes after the latest weekly Commitment of Traders report from the U.S. Commodity Futures Trading Commission (ending Jan. 17) showed hedge funds and other money managers placed more bullish oil positions than any week since 2006. Name: Alibaba Group Holding Limited
Article: 7 : [u"\r\n         Mattel's stock surges after Alibaba partnership\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Shares of Mattel Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MAT, -0.84%                                                                                                                                                 rallied 2.4% in premarket trade Tuesday, after the toy maker announced a partnership with Alibaba Group Holding Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BABA, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                 which includes selling Mattel toys in China through Alibaba\'s Tmall.com marketplace. Mattel will work with Alibaba\'s A.I. lab to develop new products for Chinese consumers. "By combining Mattel\'s unmatched expertise in childhood learning and development, with Alibaba\'s immense reach and unique consumer insights, our goal is to help parents in China raise children to be their personal best," said Mattel Chief Executive Margo Georgiadis. Mattel will begin product development immediately, with initial availability expected in mid 2017. Alibaba\'s stock tacked on 0.3% ahead of the open. Mattel shares have tumbled 17% over the past 12 months, while Alibaba\'s stock has soared 69% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                 has climbed 25%.']
