                                        MJN, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0might find itself spoonfed to British consumer-products giant Reckitt Benckiser                                                                                                                                                                                                           RB., -0.48%                                                                                                                                                \xa0.', u'In other M&A news, Macy\u2019s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           M, -1.30%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is up premarket on talk of a sale.', u'Storied short seller Andrew Left is now targeting TransDigm                                                                                                                                                                                                           TDG, -3.65%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, which makes aerospace components.', u'Like Loeb, Barclays strategists are also touting investing in net exporters, as they turn on their BAT signal for Raytheon                                                                                                                                                                                                           RTN, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Dow Chemical                                                                                                                                                                                                           DOW, -1.47%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and the other stocks shown in their chart below. ', u'And while hedge-fund boss Loeb says it\u2019s active management\u2019s moment, that\u2019s not likely to win over critic Larry Swedroe from Buckingham Strategic Wealth, who says hedge funds are \u201ccompensation schemes, not investment vehicles.\u201d', u' Weekly jobless claims fell while economists expected a rise, and productivity increased. There also will be more buzz about tomorrow\u2019s report on nonfarm payrolls.', u'Across the pond, it\u2019s the Bank of England\u2019s \u201cSuper Thursday,\u201d and the British government has published its white paper on Brexit. The BOE signaled it\u2019s in no rush to raise interest rates, weighing on the pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.1843%                                                                                                                                                \xa0.', u' Check out: MarketWatch\u2019s Economic Calendar ', u'\u201cI decided that an opportunity like this, with a company that is blowing up, was the perfect next chapter of my life. I understand some people might be upset about the fact that I won\u2019t be kicking balls on 4th downs for the Colts anymore.\u201d \u201429-year-old Pat McAfee is getting attention for retiring from the NFL to work for website Barstool Sports.', u'A Barstool staffer suggested it\u2019s a bad idea for McAfee to be \u201cleaving a million-dollar career in sports to become a blogger.\u201d The Indianapolis Star reported: \u201cThis isn\u2019t a joke.\u201d', u'There is a \u201cTinder for orangutans.\u201d', u'Aporkalypse No \u2014 why there isn\u2019t a U.S. bacon shortage.', u'Reddit shut down its alt-right community, but not for hate speech.', u'Ollie the bobcat once was lost, but now is found.', u'Inmates at a Delaware prison are holding two staff members hostage.', u'Don\u2019t like the cold? A famous rodent has bad news for you:', u'Berkeley has been burning and #MiloAtCal has been trending:', u' Need to Know starts early and is updated until the opening bell, but sign up here to get it delivered once to your email box. Be sure to check the Need to Know item. The emailed version will be sent out at about 7:30 a.m. Eastern. ', u'  Or Follow MarketWatch on Twitter or Facebook. ', u' And sign up here to get the Friday email highlighting 10 of the best MarketWatch articles of the week. ']

Name: Estee Lauder Companies, Inc. (The)
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Estee Lauder shares slip after weak guidance\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Estee Lauder Cos.                                                                                                                                                                                                           EL, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                 shares fell 1.2% in Thursday premarket trading after the beauty company gave fiscal full-year 2017 guidance below consensus. Net income was $428.0 million, or $1.15 per share, down from $447.0 million, or $1.19 per share. Adjusted EPS was $1.22, beating the $1.17 FactSet consensus. Revenue totaled $3.21 billion, up from $3.12 billion, and just below the $3.24 billion FactSet estimate. Acquisitions of the By Kilian, Becca and Too Faced brands added about 90 basis points to sales growth, about half of which was attributed to Too Faced, the company said. Estee Lauder sees full-year fiscal 2017 sales increasing between 4% and 5%, EPS between $3.07 and $3.14, and adjusted EPS between $3.29 and $3.33. The full-year FactSet revenue consensus is $11.88 billion, about 5.5% higher than full-year 2016 sales results. The FactSet EPS consensus is $3.39. Estee Lauder shares are down 6% for the past year while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                 is up 19.8% for the same period.']

Name: Alphabet Inc.
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Why the U.S. workforce needs immigrants more than ever\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The U.S. economy churned out 235,000 new jobs in February in the first full month of the Trump White House, signaling steady growth, helped by weather-sensitive industries like construction. \u201cThe economy has added almost half a million jobs in the first two months of 2017, the best back-to-back performance since last summer,\u201d MarketWatch reporter Jeffrey Bartash reported Friday. President Donald Trump has vowed to clamp down on immigration from certain countries and restrict H1B visas for skilled workers. But new data released this week suggests the U.S. will need more immigrants to keep the workforce growing.', u'For most of the past half-century, baby boomers \u2014 those born after World War Two and before 1965 \u2014 have been the main driver of the nation\u2019s expanding workforce, but now that they\u2019re heading into retirement only two groups of workers are projected to grow over the next two decades: immigrants and those whose parents are first-generation immigrants, a new report by the Pew Research Center, a nonprofit think tank in Washington, D.C., concluded. \u201cThe most important component of the growth in the working-age population over the next two decades will be the arrival of future immigrants,\u201d it said.', u' \u201cThe U.S. tech industry is utterly dependent upon foreigners, not only for workers, but for ideas and entrepreneurship,\u201d MarketWatch columnist Rex Nutting wrote earlier this month. \u201cMany of Silicon Valley\u2019s best-known names were founded by immigrants (Google                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOG, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                 Apple                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.55%                                                                                                                                                 Intel                                                                                                                                                                                                           INC, +6.54%                                                                                                                                                 Tesla                                                                                                                                                                                                           TSLA, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                 Uber, Yahoo                                                                                                                                                                                                           YHOO, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                 eBay                                                                                                                                                                                                           EBAY, +0.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and more than half of recent startups were started by immigrants.\u201d Last month, 97 companies, including many Silicon Valley firms, signed a legal \u201camicus brief\u201d protesting President\u2019s Trump\u2019s recent immigration ban.', u' Don\u2019t miss:  5 blue-collar jobs that pay $100,000 a year ']

Name: The Blackstone Group L.P.
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Trump Today: President \u2018very happy\u2019 over jobs report as he meets with CEOs\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Read MarketWatch\u2019s story on the January jobs report. ', u' PLAYING WITH FIRE  ', u'\u2022 Trump didn\u2019t start the day sounding like he was happy. Early Friday morning, he fired off a tweet saying \u201cIran is playing with fire,\u201d and said President Obama was \u201ckind\u201d to the Middle Eastern country. \u201cNot me!\u201d he said. Later in the day, the Treasury Department put a finer point on it, slapping new sanctions on companies and individuals involved in aiding Tehran\u2019s ballistic missile program.', u' ARNOLD\u2026AND ANARCHISTS ', u' LOUVRE ATTACK  ', u' MEET THE C-SUITE ', u'\u2022 Trump hosted the first meeting of his \u201cstrategic and policy forum\u201d on Friday, which saw a parade of CEOs enter the White House. The high-powered gathering touched on \u201call the major issues that are in front of the administration now,\u201d Mark Weinberger, the chief executive of EY, told MarketWatch. One item that the White House appears to still be chewing on is tax policy. Weinberger said the group discussed the \u201cpros and cons\u201d of House Republicans\u2019 border adjustability tax plan. ', u'At the very least, Trump got a lot of input from the group. Its head, Blackstone                                                                                                                                                                                                           BX, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 CEO Stephen Schwarzman, said \u201cwe probably had over 100 types of ideas\u201d on economic policy. ', u' FAREWELL, FIDUCIARY RULE  ', u'\u2022 Trump also signed executive orders Friday to begin the process of rolling back the Dodd-Frank bank reform law and the fiduciary rule, making good on a longstanding financial deregulation pledge. Read text of executive order on \u201ccore principles\u201d of financial regulation.', u' Read presidential memorandum on the fiduciary rule. ']

Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Shares of manufacturers whose CEOs met Trump today are slumping, led by U.S. Steel\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Don\u2019t miss: America doesn\u2019t just need more factory jobs; it needs more good jobs ', u' Opinion: Donald Trump can bully auto makers all he wants, but he can\u2019t repeal the laws of economics ', u'The president highlighted his talks with Lockheed Martin Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          LMT, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                Chief Executive Marilyn Hewson over the costs of her company\u2019s F-35 fighter jet, which he said led to a more than $700 million saving for the government. \u201cShe\u2019s tough, but it worked out well I think for everybody,\u201d Trump told the group. ', u' Don\u2019t miss: Mnuchin in no rush to label China a currency manipulator ', u' Also:  Trump may struggle to live up to campaign promises on China ', u'Other prominent attendees included General Electric Co. ', u'On Wednesday, the Business Roundtable, a trade group representing large U.S. companies, delivered a letter to the White House outlining the regulations it would like to see repealed or modified by the Trump administration, as the Wall Street Journal reported.', u' See: Chris Christie reportedly turned down labor secretary offer ', u' See:  Trump is playing a starring role on U.S. companies\u2019 quarterly conference calls ', u'Companies are less enthused by Trump\u2019s stance on immigration and trade, which they fear will hamper their ability to hire foreign talent and could potentially trigger a trade war. ', u'U.S. companies are generally welcoming of deregulatory moves and a lowering of corporate taxes, which are the highest in the world. But they are divided on Trump\u2019s proposed border tax, which would levy as much as a 20% tax on imports, while exempting exporters through rebates. Major exporters, including Dow Chemical, favor the tax, while major importers like retailers are aggressively opposed to it. ', u'U.S. Steel Corp. Name: Voya Global Advantage and Premium Opportunity Fund
Citigroup Inc.
Article: 12 : [u'\r\n         SEC fines Citigroup $18 million for overbilling investment advisory clients \r\n    ']
Body: [u'Citigroup Global Markets                                                                                                                                                                                                           C, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 will pay $18.3 million to settle charges brought by the Securities and Exchange Commission that it overbilled at least 60,000 advisory clients over a 15-year period by approximately $18 million and misplaced client contracts. The SEC said Citigroup cannot locate approximately 83,000 advisory account contracts that were initiated between 1990 and 2012. Citigroup, according to the SEC, failed to match billing rates in client contracts, billing histories, and other documents with those entered into its computer systems for new fees. Citigroup also collected fees even though client accounts were inactive. The affected clients have been reimbursed. Citigroup consented to the SEC\'s order and agreed to improve its fee-billing and books-and-records practices. The firm will pay a $14.3 million penalty and $800,000 in interest and give up $3.2 million in excess fees collected due to the missing contracts']

Name: Independence Realty Trust, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Fund that almost tripled the S&P 500\u2019s gain last year is now big on health-care stocks\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The mutual fund\u2019s Class A shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZAX, -2.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0returned 31.6% in 2016, compared with returns of 12% for the large-cap S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and 21.3% for the small-cap Russell 2000 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                \xa0', u'Gregory is chief investment officer of Highland Alternative Investors, a unit of Highland Capital Management, which is based in Dallas and manages about $15.4 billion. He oversees the small-cap stock fund with James Dondero, the president and co-founder of Highland Capital Management. The fund itself is small, with about $55 million in assets. ', u'Two MLP winners in 2016 were Energy Transfer Equity LP                                                                                                                                                                                                           ETE, -2.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and SemGroup Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SEMG, -1.19%                                                                                                                                                 each of which gained nearly 100% for the fund last year. But Gregory said the fund had taken \u201cabout two-thirds of the chips off the table\u201d for each position.', u'\u201cSo we have done a good job harvesting our gains and capturing our profit and sizing down to a position we think is appropriate,\u201d Gregory said. He said the price of crude oil\xa0\u201ccan head into the $60s near-term.\u201d West Texas crude oil for March delivery                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed at $52.75 on Jan. 25.', u'One example of a company with a new approach to pain relief is Collegium Pharmaceutical Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           COLL, -3.54%                                                                                                                                                 which has developed Xtampza ER, an oxycodone medication designed to reduce the chances of addiction or abuse through the combination of oxycodone \u201cwith fatty acid and waxes to form small spherical beads (microspheres) that are filled into a capsule.\u201d', u'Another company with an interesting new pain-relief product is Pacira Pharmaceuticals Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PCRX, +0.43%                                                                                                                                                 which makes Exparel, a non-opioid pain reliever used for soft-tissue surgeries and orthopedic procedures. The medication is injected during surgery.', u'Gregory said he was focused on multifamily real estate investment trusts (REITs) and has looked at \u201ca concept we\u2019ve proven ourselves,\u201d through NexPoint Residential Trust Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NXRT, -1.16%                                                                                                                                                 which Highland manages but does not hold within the Highland Small Cap Equity Fund. That concept is acquiring multifamily properties and improving them, justifying higher rents. NexPoint\u2019s stock returned 79.5% last year.', u'The first REIT holding that Gregory mentioned in an interview was Independence Realty Trust Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           IRT, -2.29%                                                                                                                                                 a multifamily REIT he said was \u201cvery similar in strategy\u201d to NexPoint. ', u'The other REIT Gregory said he favored was Jernigan Capital Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JCAP, -1.47%                                                                                                                                                 which invests in self-storage facilities.\xa0\xa0\u201cThink of the demographic boom going on in cities like Dallas, San Antonio, Nashville and Austin. When people move, they need to put their things somewhere, and ... when they do, they never leave. So we get a mid- to high-single-digit dividend yield [of 6.75%], with increasing operating income,\u201d he said.', u'Gregory named two pipeline operators, Western Gas Equity Partners LP                                                                                                                                                                                                           WGP, -0.67%                                                                                                                                                 which has a dividend yield of 4.08% and has what Gregory calls a \u201cvery strong sponsor\u201d in Anadarko Petroleum Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           APC, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                ; and Tesoro Logistics LP                                                                                                                                                                                                           TLLP, -0.49%                                                                                                                                                 which has a dividend yield of 6.36%, and is sponsored by Tesoro Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TSO, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0', u'Highland Alternative Investors acquired the Small Cap Equity Fund from GE Asset Management in 2010. A series of subadvisers helped manage the fund until July 2015, when Gregory and Dondero took over. The fund has three share classes, and it\u2019s important to consider sales charges and expenses carefully by looking at the prospectus for this or any other mutual fund:', u'It\u2019s pretty obvious when looking at the performance of the Russell 2000 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                 that 2016 was a big year for small-cap stocks.', u'The Highland Small Cap Equity Fund\u2019s Class A shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZAX, -2.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have an upfront sales charge of 5.75% and total annual expenses of 1.60% of assets. Class C                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZCX, -2.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares have no upfront sales charge, carry a 1% deferred sales charge for shares sold within six months of purchase, and have total annual expenses of 2.35%. Class Y                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZYX, -2.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares have no sales charge, and annual expenses of 1.35%, but are available only to institutional investors. All of those expense figures reflect the waiver of 0.42% of annual expenses, which will continue at least until Jan. 31, 2018.']

Name: Kohl's Corporation
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Dow logs 10th straight record, but Nasdaq stumbles a second day\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.15%                                                                                                                                                 closed up 34.72 points, or 0.2%, at a record 20,810.32, led by gains in health-care stocks Pfizer Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          PFE, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Johnson & Johnson Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          JNJ, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                 ', u' See also: Charting the Dow\u2019s longest record-setting streak since 1987 ', u'The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, +0.01%                                                                                                                                                 finished up 0.99 points at 2,363.81, just short of Tuesday\u2019s closing record of 2,365.38, led by gains in utilities and telecom shares, but held back by declines in the industrials and consumer-discretionary sectors, even as manufacturing CEOs met with President Donald Trump at the White House Thursday. The benchmark index set a intraday record of 2,368.00 before retreating.', u'The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                          COMP, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                 saw the worst daily performance among the major equity benchmarks, off 25.12 points, or 0.4%, to close at 5,835.51. The index was weighed down by shares of Nvidia Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NVDA, +0.30%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Tesla Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          TSLA, +0.81%                                                                                                                                                Meanwhile, the Technology Select Sector SPDR ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLK, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                 declined 0.1%, snapping a 13-day winning streak, the longest such streak ever for the ETF.', u'The Nasdaq\u2019s decline for a second day in a row marks the first time in 2017 that the index has seen back-to-back drops', u'Markets have been in an uptrend since Trump\u2019s election in November, but concerns have been growing that economic fundamentals don\u2019t justify current market prices. By one measure, stock valuations are at their highest level since 2004.', u' Read: Mnuchin says the stock market is a report card. Here\u2019s where you can find the grade ', u' Oil rally: An oil price rally helped to lift shares of U.S. energy giants. Crude oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0settled up 1.6% at $54.45 a barrel while data showed crude inventories rose by a smaller-than-expected 600,000 barrels in the latest week.', u' Read: Why oil experts think OPEC\u2019s U.S. headache won\u2019t go away this year ', u' And: OPEC chief Barkindo plays down threat from rise in U.S. oil output ', u'Shares of Dow component Exxon Mobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                closed up 1.1%, while shares of Transocean Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                           RIG, +1.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 7.8% and Valero Energy Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          VLO, +0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0advanced 1.6%.', u' Stock movers: Among other stock-market movers, shares of Tesla dropped 6.4% after the electric-car maker late Wednesday reported a wider-than-expected quarterly loss, though its beat sales expectations. ', u'Nvidia shares closed down 9.3% after a round of bearish analyst comments prompted investors to take profits from the highflying chip maker, which has more than tripled over the past 12 months. Instinet downgraded the stock to reduce from buy, while BMO Capital Markets cut its price target to $85 from $100.', u'On the other hand, shares of HP Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          HPQ, +0.32%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rallied 8.6% after quarterly results topped Wall Street estimates. Also, shares of First Solar Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          FSLR, -2.77%                                                                                                                                                \xa0led S&P 500 gainers, rising 11%.', u'On a downbeat note, shares of L Brands Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          LB, -2.58%                                                                                                                                                sank 16% after the Victoria\u2019s Secret parent late Wednesday issued weaker-than-forecast guidance for 2017. ', u' Hormel Foods Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HRL, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                shares lost 5.4% after the food company cut its earnings forecast for the year following a sharp decline in profit from its Jennie-O turkey brand. ', u' Kohl\u2019s Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KSS, -0.74%                                                                                                                                                shares, which had traded higher earlier after earnings beating forecasts, closed down 2.1%', u' Economic news: In the latest economic data, the number of U.S. workers who applied for unemployment benefits rose slightly in the latest week, but layoffs remained near ultralow levels last seen in the early 1970s.', u' See: MarketWatch\u2019s economic calendar ', u' Other markets: Stocks in Asia closed mostly lower as investors pored over the Fed minutes. ', u' European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.71%                                                                                                                                                bounced between gains and losses after a string of corporate updates and finished down 0.1%. ', u'Gold                                                                                                                                                                                                          GCJ7, +0.26%                                                                                                                                                 prices rose 1.5% to settle at $1,251.40, their best finish in three months, while silver                                                                                                                                                                                                          SIH7, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 finished up 0.9%. The ICE Dollar index                                                                                                                                                                                                          DXY, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                was slightly lower at 100.98.', u' \u2014Sara Sjolin in London contributed to this article.  ']

Name: Medtronic plc
Article: 9 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Corporate insiders have a stock market surprise for you\r\n    ']
Body: [u'That they\u2019re not selling into recent strength is therefore quite bullish, according to Nejat Seyhun, a finance professor at the University of Michigan and a leading expert on the behavior of corporate insiders.', u'To be sure, the message of the insiders isn\u2019t always right. But history has shown that they\u2019re far more right than wrong. The last time I reported on Seyhun\u2019s research, in October 2015, he projected a 15% return for the broad market over the subsequent 12 months. In fact, the S&P 500\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0total return over those 12 months was \u201cjust\u201d 11%. In the inexact world of stock market forecasting, that October 2015 projection has to be graded as remarkably accurate.', u'David Miller, manager of the Catalyst Insider Buying Fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           INSAX, -1.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, and one of Seyhun\u2019s graduate students at Michigan, draws special attention right now to the financials sector. In an interview, he mentioned four small- and mid-tier banks where there has been noteworthy insider buying: Carolina Financial                                                                                                                                                                                                           CARO, +0.67%                                                                                                                                                 FNB Bancorp                                                                                                                                                                                                           FNBG, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                ; Medley Capital                                                                                                                                                                                                           MCC, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, and Paragon Commercial                                                                                                                                                                                                           PBNC, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0.', u'The other sector that Miller notes for recent insider buying is health care. Five companies in that sector he mentions are: Baxter International                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAX, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                ; Edwards Lifesciences                                                                                                                                                                                                           EW, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                ; Insulet                                                                                                                                                                                                           PODD, -1.27%                                                                                                                                                ; McKesson,                                                                                                                                                                                                           MCK, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Medtronic                                                                                                                                                                                                           MDT, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. The firm serves as the manager for the AMG Managers Fairpointe Focused Equity Fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           AFPTX, -1.43%                                                                                                                                                 which follows precisely the same strategy.', u'In an interview on Dec. 27, Burnstine called 2015 a \u201ctough year\u201d for his strategy, and said a handful of major tech players were \u201csort of falsely leading the market to be flat.\u201d Those included Amazon.com                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                 Netflix Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NFLX, -0.92%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 Facebook Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, -0.43%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Alphabet Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOG, -0.38%                                                                                                                                                 which holds Google. ', u'Hewlett Packard Enterprise Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPE, -0.65%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was created in October 2015 when the \u201cold\u201d Hewlett was split into this company and HP Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPQ, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                 As you can see in the table below, which lists all of the stocks held in the portfolio as of Nov. 30, Burnstine\u2019s position in HPE is far bigger than the one in HPQ. ', u'\u201cWhat [CEO] Meg Whitman has done is tremendous for the company,\u201d he said, because she has \u201cslowly been peeling it apart and unlocking value in the entity.\u201d Following the spinoff of HP Inc., which retained the old HP\u2019s PC and printer businesses, HP Enterprise agreed in May to spin off its enterprise business and merge it with Computer Sciences Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CSC, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                 and agreed in September to spin off its software business and merge it with Micro Focus International PLC. ', u'Take a look at this two-year chart for Wal-Mart Stores Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           WMT, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0stock:', u'21st Century Fox Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FOXA, +0.46%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was formed in June 2013 when the \u201cold\u201d News Corp. was split into Fox and the \u201cnew\u201d News Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NWSA, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                 which holds the formerly combined company\u2019s publishing businesses, including Dow Jones, which includes the Wall Street Journal and MarketWatch.', u'Burnstine said Fox was trading at a discounted valuation to other media companies, and that he was impressed by the buildup of its regional sports network, and its offer to acquire the 60% of Sky PLC that it doesn\u2019t already own.', u'According to Burnstine, Discovery Communications Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DISCK, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                CEO David Zaslav\u2019s strategy of focusing the company\u2019s various content networks to specific audience demographics will pay off. ', u'Such targeting helps Discovery\u2019s networks stick out from the crowd for viewers who have over 100 stations to chose from, which can set up the company \u201cto fight the next battle, including \u2018over-the-top\u2019 distribution,\u201d which means distributing content directly to consumers, as Netflix                                                                                                                                                                                                           NFLX, -0.92%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0 does.']

Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                 fell 6.03 points to close at 19,884.91 while the Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                 lost 6.45 points, or 0.1%, to end at 5,636.20. The S&P 500 bucked the trend to edge up 1.3 points to finish at 2,280.85. ', u'Stocks logged modest gains on Wednesday after the Fed held steady on interest rates and offered a positive view of the economy, but the central bank declined to telegraph the timing of its next hike, which fostered some concern that the Fed may fail to produce three interest-rate increases in 2017, as its most recent forecasts imply.', u'But political actions appeared to command attention away from market fundamentals and the economy. Late Wednesday, the White House delivered a rebuke to Iran over a recent ballistic missile test, warning that the country could face new sanctions.', u' Trump also reportedly told Mexico that he might send U.S. troops to the country to stop \u201cbad hombres,\u201d according to news reports. And Trump tweeted that he would be studying a \u201cdumb deal\u201d with Australia to \u201ctake in thousands of illegal immigrants.\u201d That came after reports he berated and hung up on Australian Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull on Saturday.', u' Other markets: European stocks The number of Americans who applied for unemployment benefits at the end of January fell by 14,000 to 246,000, an extremely low level. The data came on the heels of better-than-expected report on private-sector hiring on Wednesday and ahead of official nonfarm payrolls due on Friday.', u' Earnings: Facebook Inc. The social media network posted stronger-than-expected fourth-quarter earnings, and advertising revenue soared 53% year-over-year. Analysts began raising price targets in reaction to that news Thursday.', u' Read:  Facebook\u2019s growth may have peaked, so what\u2019s next? ', u'   Philip Morris International Inc. Shares were up 3%.', u' Ralph Lauren Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           RL, -0.46%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares sank 12% after the fashion retailer delivered disappointing quarterly results and announced its chief executive will step down after less than two years at the helm of the company. ', u'Shares of Deutsche Bank AG                                                                                                                                                                                                          DB, -0.41%                                                                                                                                                                              DBK, -0.79%                                                                                                                                                \xa0were down more than 5% after the German bank posted a $2 billion loss on legal costs.', u'Shares of Mead Johnson Nutrition Co. Name: Kite Pharma, Inc.
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         Kite Pharma launches public stock sale following recent price surge\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of Kite Pharma Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KITE, +1.43%                                                                                                                                                 slumped 5.2 in premarket trade Thursday, after the developer of cancer treatments launched a public offering of 4.75 million common shares. The move comes after the stock rocketed 51% over the past three days, amid positive results from a study of its treatment for aggressive non-Hodgkin\'s lymphoma. Kite said all the shares will be sold by the company. With about 50.2 million shares outstanding through Wednesday, according to FactSet, the offering would increase that total by 9.5%. The underwriters of the offering have been granted options to buy up to an additional 712,500 shares. The stock has rallied 48% over the past 12 months, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 21%.']

', u' See also:  The next anchor at your mall could be a food hall ', u' See also:  The restaurant recession dturned even more damaging in December ', u'Brinker shares closed Friday up 0.6%, and are down 10.7% for the last 12 months. Name: Viacom Inc.
Article: 2 : [u"\r\n         Paramount Pictures' $1 billion film financing partnership is in jeopardy: report\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Viacom Inc.-owned                                                                                                                                                                                                           VIAB, +1.07%                                                                                                                                                 Paramount Pictures could lose its $1 billion slate financing deal with China\'s Huahua Media and Shanghai Film Group, according to a report by industry publication The Wrap. Huahua has been a financial and marketing partner for past Paramount films, such as "Transformers: Age of Extinction." The Chinese company had agreed to be acquired by Oriental Time Media for about $158 million, but regulatory concerns reportedly caused OTM to withdraw its offer on March 9. Sources told The Wrap this would most likely prevent Huahua from funding Paramount\'s film slate. That is a major blow to the studio that is in dire straits after a disappointing 2016 at the box office, coming in behind all of the Hollywood major studios in revenue for the last five years. Paramount Chief Executive Brad Gray announced in February he would step down as Viacom\'s new CEO Bob Bakish laid out a plan to turn around the company that includes focusing on getting Paramount Pictures back on track. Shares of Viacom\'s publicly-owned class B shares were down more than 2% in afternoon trade on Friday, but have gained nearly 14% in the trailing 12-month period. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                 is up almost 19% during the same time frame.']

Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Energy stocks are falling while the S&P is climbing \u2014 and that\u2019s a buying opportunity\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Yet energy is the absolute worst performer among the S&P 500\u2019s 11 sectors this year. It was down 5.5% through Monday, compared with a 6.1% gain for the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                 Exxon                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.42%                                                                                                                                                 one of the best-quality names in the space, is trading near 52-week lows. UPDATE', u' Insider vote of confidence ', u'Let\u2019s start with the insiders. I\u2019ve tracked insiders for clues about the market for decades, and their buying is a core part of how I come up with a short list of stocks to research for my stock letter Brush Up on Stocks. Two key lessons on insiders support a bullish call on energy now. ', u'That looks like the case with energy stocks right now. Over the past few weeks there\u2019s been significant insider buying in over a dozen energy stocks, including Halliburton                                                                                                                                                                                                           HAL, -1.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in services, Hess                                                                                                                                                                                                           HES, -1.86%                           \xa0and Matador Resources          in production, and Marathon Petroleum                                                                                                                                                                                                           MPC, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 in refining. (I\u2019ll list the others, below.)', u' Inventories rising ', u'It takes six weeks or more for oil to arrive by boat to the U.S., the market of last resort for energy. But as it did, U.S. inventories began to build this year, unsettling investors. \u201cThe market looks at the big build up in U.S. inventories and gets nervous,\u201d says Jonathan Waghorn who helps manage the Guinness Atkinson Global Energy Fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           GAGEX, -0.80%                                                                                                                                                 Investors are still shellshocked after a U.S. inventory glut helped suppress oil prices and crush energy stocks two years ago. So any sign of a repeat has them selling. ', u' U.S. producers: They\u2019re baack! ', u'Thanks to higher energy prices, U.S. shale producers are back. They\u2019re deploying a lot more rigs. The rig count is back up over 600 compared with a low of 316 in May 2016 \u2014 and they are fracking a lot more. This also brings back bad memories of hefty losses for energy investors. ', u'OPEC, for example, will probably remain disciplined on production because of national budget constraints in Saudi Arabia, says John Groton, director of equity research at Thrivent Financial, who has followed the energy space for years. He thinks Saudi Arabia needs oil in the upper $60-per barrel range to balance its national budget. Oil                                                                                                                                                                                                          US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0 has traded recently in the mid-$50 range. ', u' One for the quants ', u' How to play this ', u'Another is to follow the insiders. Besides Halliburton, Oasis, Matador, Hess and Marathon Petroleum, which has a four out of five star rating at Morningstar, insiders were also recently buying in significant amounts at Carrizo Oil & Gas -0.28%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Parker Drilling                                                                                                                                   ', u'Breard, at Hodges Capital Management, follows Comstock Resources CRK, -3.79%                                                                                                                                                 closely. He has made some great contrarian calls on the company, favoring it last spring when it traded below $4, ahead of a move above $12. He likes the name in the current pullback into the $8-$9 range. \u201cComstock looks awfully cheap,\u201d he says, especially considering that over the next several weeks they are bringing several wells online in untapped territory, which suggests they will be particularly productive. He also likes Parsley Energy. which he says has good properties in the Permian and Delaware basins. ', u'Top holdings at Guinness Atkinson Global Energy Fund include Newfield, Devon Energy                                                                                                                                                                                                           DVN, -1.28%                                                                                                                                                 Carrizo, QEP Resources, Apache                                                                                                                                                                                                           APA, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                 Occidental Petroleum                                                                                                                                                                                                           OXY, -0.77%                                                                                                                                                 ConocoPhillips                                                                                                                                                                                                           COP, -0.96%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Noble                                                                                                                                                                                                           NE, +0.94%                                                                                                                                                 ', u'What about Exxon? If oil prices really are going back up to $70 over the next few years, it might not be the best energy name to own. In this scenario, investors will favor smaller, lower quality energy companies that use more leverage to fund development over more conservative, larger players like Exxon, Chevron                                                                                                                                                                                                           CVX, -0.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and ConocoPhillips. ', u' Michael Brush is a Manhattan-based financial writer At the time of publication, he had no positions in any stocks mentioned in this column. Over the past several years, he has suggested HAL, HES, OAS, MTDR, CRK, MMLP, PHX, DVN, APA, OXY, COP, CVX and XOM in his stock newsletter Brush Up on Stocks.  ']

Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         New competition took a bite out of J&J\u2019s drug sales, but don\u2019t expect the trend to dominate this earnings season \r\n    ']
Body: [u'The company\u2019s anti-inflammatory Remicade, which has been on the market for nearly two decades, took a nearly 2% U.S. sales hit after the launch of Celltrion\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           068270, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0competing biosimilar drug. ', u'Just five \u2014 Amgen Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMGN, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0biosimilar for anti-inflammatory Humira, Eli Lilly & Co.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           LLY, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0biosimilar insulin, Novartis\u2019                                                                                                                                                                                                           NVS, -0.47%                                                                                                                                                \xa0biosimilars of anti-inflammatory Enbrel and Neupogen, which prevents infection after chemotherapy, and Celltrion\u2019s biosimilar of anti-inflammatory Remicade \u2014 have been approved so far, according to BioMedTracker data. ', u'But over time they could reduce U.S. drug costs by up to $250 billion, costing drugmakers those big bucks in the process.', u' Read more:  These drugs could cut American health costs by $250 billion (if only we could take them) ', u'Drugmakers have also launched a fierce fight to patent various aspects of their valuable drugs and fend off competition. ', u' Related:  Pfizer to sell biosimilar arthritis drug, for less ', u'For now, blockbusters including AbbVie\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           ABBV, -0.27%                                                                                                                                                \xa0anti-inflammatory Humira and Amgen\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMGN, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                 Neulasta, which prevents infection after chemotherapy, are being watched the closest. ', u' See more:  Why Amgen\u2019s positive biosimilar news isn\u2019t as good as it seems ', u'In the next couple of years, Roche\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           ROG, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0chemotherapy drugs Avastin, Herceptin and Rituxan are likely to also face challenges, said Porges. ', u'Biogen Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           BIIB, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Enbrel biosimilar brought in $53 million by making inroads on markets already selling a competing anti-inflammatory biosimilar for Remicade, made by Pfizer. ', u'Bringing in $1.17 billion in U.S. sales in the fourth-quarter, Remicade is \u201can important product but not a critical product,\u201d Porges said. Johnson & Johnson shares have declined 2.5% over the last three months, compared with a 7.5% rise in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                ']
