Article: 13 : [u'\r\n         Warren Buffett\u2019s big bet on Apple may have made him $1.1 billion in just six weeks\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The famed billionaire investor\u2019s investment vehicle, Berkshire Hathaway Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          BRK.B, -1.51%                                                                                                                                                 , disclosed in a regulatory filing Tuesday that it loaded up on Apple\u2019s stock during the fourth quarter, increasing its stake to 57.36 million shares as of Dec. 31, up from 15.23 million shares as of Sept. 30.', u'Apple\u2019s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                          AAPL, -1.15%                                                                                                                                                rose 2.5% during the fourth quarter. But since then, aided by stronger-than-expected first-fiscal-quarter results, reported Jan. 31, the stock has shot up $19.20, or 16.6%, closing Tuesday at a record level for a second straight day. ', u'Among other moves Buffett\u2019s Berkshire made during the fourth quarter, it slashed its stake in Wal-Mart Stores Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          WMT, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                to 1.39 million shares from 12.97 million shares. With the stock down 0.7% so far in 2017, Buffett may have saved $5.33 million by selling Wal-Mart shares.', u'Berkshire also added a new 8.04 million\u2013share stake in Monsanto Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          MON, -0.89%                                                                                                                                                 , a new 166.64 million\u2013share bet on Sirius XM Holdings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SIRI, -2.26%                                                                                                                                                and a new 43.2 million\u2013share investment in Southwest Airlines Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          LUV, -2.94%                                                                                                                                                 , while selling off his entire 20 million\u2013share stake in Kinder Morgan Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          KMI, -1.18%                                                                                                                                                and cutting his bet on Verizon Communications Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          VZ, -0.16%                                                                                                                                                to just 928 shares from 15 million shares.', u'Berkshire more than doubled its stake in American Airlines Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          AAL, -3.07%                                                                                                                                                to 45.54 million shares as of Dec. 31 from 21.77 million shares on Sept. 30. His stake in Delta Air Lines Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          DAL, -2.84%                                                                                                                                                spiked nearly tenfold to 60.03 million shares from 6.33 million shares during the same time, while his investment in United Continental Holdings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          UAL, -3.27%                                                                                                                                                rose more than sixfold to 28.95 million shares from 4.53 million shares.', u' Don\u2019t miss: Warren Buffett\u2019s investment in wearable tech? \u2018Simply updating\u2019 a \u2018safe bet.\u2019 ', u'Berkshire\u2019s stock has risen 2.4% so far in 2017, closing Tuesday at a record high, while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, -1.24%                                                                                                                                                has climbed 4.4% this year, also booking a record close on Tuesday.']

Name: Shake Shack, Inc.
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         Shake Shack shares slide on subdued 2017 revenue outlook  \r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of Shake Shack Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHAK, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                 fell in Wednesday\'s extended session after the casual restaurant chain issued a tepid 2017 revenue outlook. Shake Shack reported its fourth-quarter earnings rose to $5.5 million, or 15 cents a share, from $3 million, or 7 cents a share, a year ago. On an adjusted basis, it would have earned 9 cents a share. Revenue grew 43.5% to $73.3 million while same-store sales climbed 1.6%, slowing sharply from an increase of 11% a year ago. Analysts surveyed by FactSet had forecast earnings of 9 cents a share on revenue of $70.7 million. The burger chain forecast 2017 revenue in a range of $349 million to $353 million, below analysts\' average estimate of $354.5 million. It also projected same-store sales of 2% to 3%. Shake Shack shares slid more than 3.7% after hours. ']

Name: ConocoPhillips
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         ConocoPhillips earnings: Where will the company go next? \r\n    ']
Body: [u'Wall Street is expecting another loss for ConocoPhillips                                                                                                                                                                                                           COP, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                 but slightly higher production numbers quarter-on-quarter. ', u'ConocoPhillips\u2019 results will come on the heels of disappointing earnings for Chevron Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CVX, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                 which last week reported earnings that were significantly below analyst predictions on weaker refining margins. Rival Exxon Mobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is slated to report quarterly earnings on Tuesday.', u' Read also: Chevron\u2019s road back to profitability goes through Texas\u2019 Permian Basin ', u' Results: Analysts polled by FactSet expect ConocoPhillips to report a fourth-quarter adjusted loss of 40 cents a share, which would be narrower than the adjusted loss of 90 cents a share the company logged in the fourth quarter of 2015. ', u' Revenue: The analysts surveyed by FactSet expect fourth-quarter revenue of $7.30 billion for the company, which would be up from $6.77 billion in the year-ago quarter and the highest sales since the third quarter of 2015. ', u' Stock price: Shares of ConocoPhillips have outperformed the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in the last 12 months, rising nearly 22% to the index\u2019s 17% gains. ', u' Other issues: ConocoPhillips announced in November a capital spending plan of $5 billion and a $5 billion to $8 billion asset sale program for 2017, so expect analysts to home in on details about both plans, particularly where ConocoPhillips might be looking to sell next. ', u' Related: The U.S. is increasingly looking at this Texas region for oil ']

Name: Electronic Arts Inc.
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         Electronic Arts volatile following third-quarter results\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of Electronic Arts Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           EA, +0.34%                                                                                                                                                 were volatile in Tuesday\'s extended session after the video game publisher behind such popular titles as Battlefield and FIFA 17 released its quarterly results. Electronic Arts reported its third-quarter loss narrowed to $1 million from $45 million a year earlier. On a per share basis, Electronic Arts broke even versus a loss of 14 cents in the year-ago period. Revenue rose to $1.15 billion versus $1.07 billion. In the fourth quarter, the company expects earnings of $1.64 a share and revenue of $1.48 billion. Shares swung in and out of negative territory after hours to slide 1.1%.']

Name: The Charles Schwab Corporation
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         Robo advisers are picking up human advisers for clients\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Betterment, which manages more than $7 billion in client assets, has added two new services to its platform, both involving human advisers interacting with clients, the New York-based company announced on Tuesday. This comes a month after Charles Schwab & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SCHW, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, the San Francisco-based brokerage and banking firm, created a hybrid digital service with human advisers, nearly two years after launching direct-to-consumer robo adviser. By pairing humans and technology, these companies, including others in a \u201chybrid\u201d model such as San Carlos, Calif.-based robo adviser Personal Capital, are providing people with options to receive financial advice.', u' See:  The fiduciary rule is coming \u2014 Here\u2019s how investors can prepare ', u'Matching robo advisers with human advisers seems to work, and has been for companies like Personal Capital and Financial Engines                                                                                                                                                                                                           FNGN, -1.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, one of the original robo advisers that manages employer-sponsored retirement accounts and in 2015 acquired a brick-and-mortar advisory firm to include advisers as part of its offering to clients. Malvern, Penn.-based investment firm Vanguard Group also took a hybrid approach to its robo adviser with a call center when it launched. ', u'Robo advisers have revolutionized investment allocation, making it simple for anyone with some money to try on their own or with the help of advisers (some robo advisers have models for advisers to use with their clients). The technology has also commoditized the fee structure of investment allocation, since they opt for low-cost passive options, such as exchange-traded funds.', u' See also: How do startup robo advisers stack up against the big banks? ', u'But they\u2019re not always enough on their own, especially as investors may begin to experience more complex financial situations, such as home ownership and saving for children\u2019s educations, experts say. ', u'Betterment clients, for example, could previously call the company to ask questions about their accounts, but their employees could not provide financial advice, Benke said. There\u2019s also the fear investors will get nervous at the sight of a market downturn, and make the wrong decisions, said Shannon Pike, president of the Financial Planning Association, a professional organization based in Denver. These concerns are leading robo advisers to shift to providing financial advice in a digital manner, as opposed to simply digital investing. \u201cYou cannot just have some robotic investment advice,\u201d Pike said. \u201cIt\u2019s a tool.\u201d']

Name: Hasbro, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Hollywood blockbusters are becoming a bigger driver of toy sales\r\n    ']
Body: [u'In 2016, on the back of Walt Disney Co.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u201cStar Wars: The Force Awakens\u201d and Marvel superhero flicks, toy industry revenue grew 5%, reaching $20.4 billion, according to data from NPD Group.', u' Also read: Disney is betting big on \u2018Star Wars\u2019 merchandise with unboxing extravaganza ', u'Because of this growing focus on film and TV content in the industry, Goldman Sachs initiated coverage of Hasbro Inc.\xa0                                                                                                                                                                                                          HAS, -0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0with a buy rating and $110 12-month price target, which represents a nearly 12% premium to Monday trading levels.', u' Check out: Unlike Mattel, Hasbro says the holidays weren\u2019t much different from years past ', u'With seven Marvel films currently slated for release in 2018, three back-to-back \u201cTransformer\u201d movies through 2019 and two \u201cStar Wars\u201d films in the next two years the boys toy category should see strong revenue numbers, Ng wrote. And Hasbro\u2019s Disney Princess line, which it snatched from Mattel Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MAT, -1.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in 2015, is expected to benefit from a host of live-action remakes, including 2017\u2019s \u201cBeauty and the Beast\u201d and \u201cMulan,\u201d expected in November 2018.', u' Also see: Mattel\u2019s earnings miss has some analysts questioning the company\u2019s turnaround ']

Name: Finisar Corporation
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Harry Boxer\u2019s stocks to watch: biotechnology and technology\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Esperion Therapeutics Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ESPR, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                 is absolutely rocketing. The clinical-stage biopharma, which is focused on developing drugs that treat cardiovascular disease, popped 29% on Friday in response to good clinical news from Amgen                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMGN, +0.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0regarding its own cardiovascular drug. The stock followed through on Monday and then again Tuesday, up $2.48, or 14%, to $20.14 on nearly 3.4 million shares traded. The stock pulled back toward the close, testing the bottom of its rising channel and resting in a tight wedge formation. This formation looks poised to break to the upside, with the next target at the channel top near $22.', u' Exelixis Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           EXEL, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                 also had a strong session on Tuesday, up 54 cents, or 2.7%, to $20.57, on nearly 6.7 million shares traded. The cancer-drug company\u2019s stock needs to get through the rising trendline, near $21, connecting the most recent tops from September, December and January. The challenge beyond that would be the mid-channel line at around $22.75, a break through that could accelerate the stock into the high $20s.', u' Finisar Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FNSR, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                 edged above resistance on Tuesday, though closed slightly below it, up 76 cents, or 2.5%, to $30.89, on 2.7 million shares. The provider of optical subsystems for data communications recently traversed from the top of its price channel at around $37 in December to the bottom just above $27 on January 23, before rallying in the last two weeks. The stock did close above its 50-day moving average at $30.77 on Tuesday, and a break above current levels could get it to $33.25 next, followed by $35.50.', u' KEMET Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KEM, +0.26%                                                                                                                                                 has been in a steady rising channel since its breakout in November. The stock last week bounced off the channel bottom and rallied after the electronic-capacitor maker beat Wall Street\u2019s third-quarter earnings and revenue forecasts. The stock popped on Thursday and Friday, had an inside day on Monday (remaining inside the price range from Friday), and on Tuesday it had another solid day, up 17 cents, or 2.2%, to 7.81, on 652,900 shares traded. The stock looks like it\u2019s about to take out the $7.90 area, and run up toward the channel top in the $9-$9.75 area.', u'See Harry\u2019s video chart analysis on these and other stocks. ', u' The writer has no investments in the stocks mentioned in this column. ', u' Harry Boxer is the founder of TheTechTrader.com, a live trading room featuring his stock picks, technical market analysis and live chart presentations. ']

Name: First Trust Multi Cap Value AlphaDEX Fund
Intuit Inc.
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         Why almost everybody should apply for college financial aid\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Question:  I\u2019m told I should fill out financial-aid forms for college, even if I think I don\u2019t qualify. But realistically, how much income is the likely cutoff? ', u' Also read:  Can I use \u2018529\u2019 college money overseas? ', u' My grandson has graduated from college with student loans. If he cashes in savings bonds to repay the loans, would that be considered an education expense for which savings-bond interest isn\u2019t taxable? ', u'One potential bright spot: Student-loan interest can be reported as a tax deduction on your tax return. \u201cThis has the potential to lower your tax liability,\u201d says Bob Meighan, a vice president at Intuit\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                          INTU, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 TurboTax unit.', u' Is it possible to set up a Upromise 529 account for future grandchildren not yet born? In that way, the account could benefit from my purchases without me having to put any personal money in until I have grandchildren. ', u'Upromise, a product offered by Sallie Mae,                                                                                                                                                                                                          SLM, -0.52%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 incorporates both your contributions and loyalty bonuses based on your purchases from participating shopping partners to fund either a regular savings account or a 529 account, Meighan says. However, you\u2019ll need a living beneficiary \u2014 not a future grandchild\u2014before you can establish a 529. \u201cWhile you cannot set up a 529 for anyone not currently alive, you can set up a 529 for yourself as the beneficiary and make a change of beneficiary at some point in the future,\u201d Schmansky says.', u' My children are three years apart, so they will overlap at college for one year. I have a 529 for my older child. In the year they overlap, can I use that account to pay senior-year tuition for the older one, then retitle the beneficiary to the younger one and pay freshman-year tuition? ', u' Also read:  What to expect on student debt from Betsy DeVos, the most divisive secretary of education in recent memory ', u' Are 529 withdrawals equal to the amount of a merit scholarship considered taxable income? ', u' I have a New York state 529 college-savings plan for my daughter, who is now attending school in Michigan. Should I transfer the money to a Michigan plan first and then to the school, or pay the school directly from the New York plan? ', u' We are longtime retirees in our 80s. Can we use one of our existing IRAs to fund a 529 for our new grandson? ', u' Also read:  How much can grandparents contribute to a 529? ', u'The article \u201cWhy almost everybody should apply for college financial aid\u201d first appeared on WSJ.com.']

Name: Teva Pharmaceutical Industries Limited
Article: 13 : [u'\r\n        ', u' These 3 stocks may be the only true value plays left \r\n    ']
Body: [u' If you\u2019ve been watching this red-hot run since November and starting to get that sinking feeling in your stomach as the market                                                                                                                                                                                                          DJIA, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 loses steam, I don\u2019t blame you. History has shown that pullbacks are normal, and that even a bad month or a bad quarter for stocks\xa0 doesn\u2019t mean the end of the world. But it\u2019s still hard to just sit there and watch your portfolio decline.', u' Read: Trump effect is the big theme for this earnings season ', u'If you haven\u2019t given Pitney Bowes Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PBI, -1.07%                                                                                                                                                 much thought in the last decade or so, I don\u2019t blame you. The company was built on postage meters, among other physical mailing and marketing services, and in the age of e-commerce it has been under a whole lot of pressure. Shares are off about 65% still from their 2007 peak as a result, and the company slashed its dividend by 50% in 2013.', u'From a valuation perspective, the stock trades for about 8.8 times next year\u2019s earnings, compared with a forward price-to-earnings ratio of around 18 for both the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and the Nasdaq-100                                                                                                                                                                                                           NDX, +0.59%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 indexes. It also trades for a roughly 10% discount to next year\u2019s revenue.', u'After all, my colleague Philip van Doorn recently pointed out that more than half of Wall Street analysts are bullish on the stock \u2014 and the other half aren\u2019t bearish, just neutral. So if you\u2019re looking for undiscovered values, don\u2019t wait too long before pulling the trigger on Pitney Bowes.', u' Also read: 20 dividend stocks with yields up to 7.5% \u2014 and these companies are set for sales and earnings gains ', u'General Motors Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GM, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has been getting a little bit of love lately on the hope that an \u201cAmerica first\u201d agenda under President Donald Trump and a Republican Congress will boost the company in 2017. However, the modest run since November hasn\u2019t removed the value status of GM stock; right now, the company boasts a forward price-to-earnings ratio of just 6.6 compared with a reading of about 18 for the major indexes. Furthermore, it has a forward price-to-sales ratio of less than 0.4. ', u'With the GOP salivating over the prospect of carving up the Affordable Care Act, many investors have been focused on medical-device companies or high-margin pharmaceutical plays that could benefit from fewer regulations in 2017 and beyond. However, while boring generic drugs giant Teva Pharmaceuticals                                                                                                                                                                                                           TEVA, +0.01%                                                                                                                                                 isn\u2019t getting the same amount of attention, that doesn\u2019t mean it isn\u2019t worth a look.', u' In the wake of the EpiPen outrage last year and allegations that drug companies like Mylan                                                                                                                                                                                                          MYL, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 were unfairly gouging patients for much-needed medication, generic drugs may also get a lift from changes in health-care policy. President elect Donald Trump said at his news conference that the industry is \u201cgetting away with murder,\u201d so increasing access to generics may be a rare bipartisan issue in 2017, one Teva could profit from.', u' Read: Mylan CEO Heather Bresch says keeping drug price hikes below 10% isn\u2019t the answer ']

Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Clothing retailers slide as Mizuho downgrades stocks after slow spring start\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Analyst Betty Chen downgraded DSW Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          DSW, -1.63%                                                                                                                                                 , Express Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          EXPR, -1.88%                                                                                                                                                 , Finish Line Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          FINL, -4.92%                                                                                                                                                and Tailored Brands                                                                                                                                                                                                          TLRD, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                to neutral from buy, and downgraded Guess Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          GES, -2.48%                                                                                                                                                to underperform from neutral.', u' Don\u2019t miss: From a risk-of-bankruptcy standpoint, the retail business is the new oil and gas ', u' Also:  Number of distressed U.S. retailers at highest level since Great Recession ', u'The move comes at a time when retailers are struggling with a range of factors that are hurting their business, from a competitive onslaught by giant Amazon.com Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          AMZN, +0.22%                                                                                                                                                to slowing mall traffic, changing consumer behavior and pressure on consumer spending as rents and drug prices rise.', u'The sector is expected to replace oil and gas this year as the most distressed, according to the major debt-rating agencies. A number of retailers filed for bankruptcy protection filed for Chapter 11 protection this year, including Hhgregg; Eastern Outfitters, whose chains include Eastern Mountain Sports and Bob\u2019s Stores; and the Limited, whose January filing led the company to close all stores.', u' Read also: Amazon\u2019s aggressive warehouse and shipping strategy is paying off ', u'The SPDR S&P Retail ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                          XRT, -0.83%                                                                                                                                                 a popular way for investors to invest in the overall retail space, is down 4.7% thus far this year, compared with a rise of 5.8% for the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                over the same period. By contrast, an ETF that limits its holdings to online-focused shops has seen strong results. While the Retail ETF is down 12.5% over the past three months, the Amplify Online Retail ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                          IBUY, -1.02%                                                                                                                                                is up nearly 2% over the same period.', u'Express fell 12% on Wednesday to close at a record low of $9.51. The stock touched $9.03 in intraday trade, its lowest level since the company went public in May 2010 at an issue price of $17.', u' See also:  Dick\u2019s Sporting Goods dumping 20% of vendors to focus on private brands ', u' See:  Sears\u2019 restructuring plan lacks the one thing it needs most: a way to drive sales ', u'Additionally, a \u201cdisappointing collaboration\u201d in tuxedo rental with the department-store chain Macy\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                          M, -1.57%                                                                                                                                                exerted an unexpected $19 million to $20 million in pressure on earnings before interest and tax, or about 26 cents a share, \u201cand is disrupting what had traditionally been a high-margin business for [Tailored Brands] that may now be open to competition,\u201d Chen wrote. ', u'On a brighter note, Chen reiterated her buy rating on Children\u2019s Place Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          PLCE, +0.31%                                                                                                                                                and raised her stock-price target to $140 from $110. That retailer surprised investors Wednesday with an earnings beat and an improved outlook. The company also doubled its dividend and said its board has approved a new $250 million share buyback program.', u'She said she is sticking with a neutral rating on Urban Outfitters Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          URBN, -1.51%                                                                                                                                                as she had correctly anticipated the weak spring start reported by that company. ', u' Don\u2019t miss:  11 retailers still thriving as Amazon threatens on all fronts ', u'  MarketWatch ETF and funds reporter Ryan Vlastelica contributed to this report. ']

Name: CEB Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Nasdaq notches new closing high as broader stock market sags\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, -0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed up 10.93 points, or 0.2%, at 5,487.94, following a day of slight gains and losses. Shares of Amazon.com Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0supported the index with a 3.1% gain. The last time the Nasdaq notched a record close was Dec. 27.', u'Meanwhile, the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 42.87 points, or 0.2%, to close at 19,899.29, paring losses after being down by as much as 131 points. Among the biggest decliners were Travelers Cos.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TRV, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 shedding 1.6%, and Exxon Mobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          XOM, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                 down 1.5%. J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JPM, +0.10%                                                                                                                                                 finished down 0.9% and Goldman Sachs Group Inc.,                                                                                                                                                                                                          GS, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0declined 0.7%, paring sharp losses from earlier in the session. ', u'The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                \xa0declined 1.75 points, or 0.1%, to finish at 2,269.00. The financial sector was the index\u2019s biggest drag, falling 1%, while retailers, Kohl\u2019s Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          KSS, -1.12%                                                                                                                                                 and Macy\u2019s Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          M, -1.51%                                                                                                                                                 were taking it on the chin after disappointing holiday sales and announcing stores closures. ', u'Shares of Macy\u2019s\xa0plummeted to close down 14% after the department-store chain late Wednesday announced plans to close 68 stores and lay off 10,000 employees in 2017. Fellow retailer Kohl\u2019s, saw its worst trading day ever, finishing down 19%, after it cut its fiscal 2016 earnings outlook late Wednesday, following volatile holiday sales.', u'\u201cWhat\u2019s interesting is that yesterday we saw some shift in terms of higher-than-expected inflation out of the eurozone and that took starch out of the dollar\u2019s rally,\u201d Stone said. ', u' Read: Will surging Chinese yuan wreck the dollar rally? ', u' See: \u2018Trump rally\u2019 could end when president-elect takes office: Morgan Stanley ', u'Financials could be particularly vulnerable to profit-taking; the group has accounted for the bulk of the market\u2019s postelection advance.', u' Economic news: The market digested two reads on the labor market that pointed to mixed conditions. The private sector added 153,000 jobs in December, according to ADP, a rate that was below forecasts, while first-time jobless claims fell 28,000 in the latest week, dropping to a nearly 43-year low.', u' See: 4 things to watch in the December jobs report ', u'Separately, a read on the U.S. services sector held steady at a 12-month high in December, suggesting growth in nonmanufacturing activity, mainly the service sector, remains strong.', u' Also see: MarketWatch\u2019s economic calendar ', u' Other markets: A weaker dollar gave a boost to gold                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:GCG7                                                                                                                                                 which settled sharply higher. Oil prices                                                                                                                                                                                                          US:CLG7                                                                                                                                                \xa0settled up 0.9% at $53.76 a barrel, rebounding after drifting lower in late-morning trade.', u' Asian markets closed mainly higher, and stocks rose in most European markets. ', u' Movers and shakers: L Brands Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LB, -2.99%                                                                                                                                                 Nordstrom Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          JWN, -1.93%                                                                                                                                                 and Signet Jewelers Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SIG, -0.71%                                                                                                                                                \xa0joined other retailers as some of the worst performing stocks on the S&P 500 as the SPDR S&P Retail ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XRT, -0.88%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 2.6%.', u' CEB Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CEB, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0jumped 21% after Gartner Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          IT, -0.61%                                                                                                                                                \xa0announced it would buy the company in a cash-and-stock deal valued at about $2.6 billion. Gartner shares finished down 11%.', u'Shares of Nvidia Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          NVDA, +0.95%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 2.5% after news late Wednesday that the chip maker is joining with Audi AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           NSU, -0.76%                                                                                                                                                \xa0to bring a fully self-driving car to the market. ', u' Alexion Pharmaceuticals Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ALXN, +0.40%                                                                                                                                                \xa0picked up 12% after the biotech company filed a delayed quarterly report and affirmed its outlook.', u'  \u2014Sara Sjolin in London contributed to this article.   ']

Name: Wal-Mart Stores, Inc.
Article: 11 : [u'\r\n         Wal-Mart upgrades app to speed up pharmacy refills, money transfers\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Wal-Mart                                                                                                                                                                                                           WMT, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 said it will start rolling out the new capabilities in March, and they should be available at almost all of its 4,700 stores by the fall.', u'Wal-Mart has been refocusing on improving customer service at its stores in an effort to better compete with brick-and-mortar rivals as well as Amazon.com Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.64%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 The effort is paying off so far \u2014 last week the retail giant reported improved holiday sales and quarterly earnings that beat Wall Street expectations.']

Name: Lowe's Companies, Inc.
Article: 10 : [u"\r\n         Lowe's names Marshall Croom CFO effective March 3\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Lowe\'s Companies Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LOW, +0.60%                                                                                                                                                 said Tuesday it has named Marshall Croom chief financial officer, replacing Robert Hull, who is retiring. Croom is a 20-year veteran of the home-improvement store chain, and will take on his new role on March 3. The executive has been in charge of internal audit and enterprise risk management since 2009. Croom joined Lowe\'s after a stint at Ernst & Young. Lowe\'s shares have gained 4.6% in the last 12 months, underperforming the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 which has gained 20%.']

Name: Sprint Corporation
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Wireless carrier stocks fall amid budding price war in unlimited data\r\n    ']
Body: [u'A budding price war in unlimited data plans sent shares of the major wireless carriers lower in, after AT&T Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                 and T-Mobile U.S. Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TMUS, +1.10%                                                                                                                                                 fired the latest salvos on Monday. AT&T\'s stock slid 1.4% in afternoon trade after the company lowered the price of its unlimited plan to $90 from $100, less than two weeks after opening up the plan to all subscribers. T-Mobile\'s stock shed 0.6% after the company said early Monday that it was giving a free line of service for a limited time to virtually all of its customers with at least two voice lines. On Feb. 14, Verizon had finally caved to competition by reintroducing unlimited wireless plans, in response similar moves by its competition. Verizon\'s stock slumped 1.6% in afternoon trade Monday. Elsewhere, Sprint Corp.\'s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           S, +1.39%                                                                                                                                                 shed 0.3%. Meanwhile, the iShares U.S. Telecommunications ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           IYZ, -0.79%                                                                                                                                                 tacked on 0.3%. AT&T shares have gained 6.5% over the past three months, while T-Mobile\'s stock has rallied 13%, Verizon shares have lost 1.7% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.23%                                                                                                                                                 has climbed 7.1%.']

Name: Oclaro, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         4 momentum stocks that are breaking out\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Allegheny Technologies Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ATI, -0.77%                                                                                                                                                 broke out on Tuesday with a major thrust, up 31% to $22.28, on 20.7 million shares traded. The move broke the stock out of a falling wedge and through lateral resistance at the December high just above $19, a level that has been keeping the stock at bay for about a year and a half. When you get that kind of a move, it usually means the stock is going higher. The next target is $26, with the secondary target near the channel top in the low- to mid-$30s.', u' CF Industries Holdings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CF, -1.75%                                                                                                                                                 like many stocks in the agricultural-chemicals sector, ran on Tuesday, up 4.5% to $36.85, on 10.5 million shares. This stock has been up three days in a row, bouncing off lateral support as well as the rising channel bottom under $32 to gain 5 points in the three days. Watch for a test of its spike high at $37.72 reached in March of last year. If it gets through that, the next line of resistance is around $39 1/2. ', u' Oclaro Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           OCLR, -0.68%                                                                                                                                                 appears to be setting up for a strong move, pressuring its triple top just above current levels. On Tuesday, it gained 7.3% to $9.99, on 11.2 million shares traded. The stock intraday got right near overhead resistance above $10 near where it touched in November and December. Having also recently broken out of a declining wedge and held support in the $8 range on several occasions, the stock looks like it wants to blow through this triple top area for a move to the channel top near $13.', u' Potash Corp. of Saskatchewan Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           POT, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                 another stock in agricultural chemicals, was up 5% to $19.87, on 16.6 million shares traded Tuesday. That\u2019s the best volume since August. The stock is up 10% since Friday, when it bounced off its channel bottom near $18 and ran. It looks like it wants to see $21, and then $22 1/2. ', u' See Harry\u2019s video chart analysis on these stocks. ', u' The writer owns no securities mentioned in this article. ', u' Harry Boxer is founder of TheTechTrader.com, a live trading room featuring his stock picks, technical market analysis, and live chart presentations. ']

Body: [u'The S&P 500\u2019s financial sector has surged in the past year, returning 39%, and now that President Trump aims to roll back regulations, big banks\u2019 gains may have just begun.', u'So says Bill McMahon, chief investment officer of ThomasPartners, a Boston-based subsidiary of Charles Schwab Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SCHW, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0with about $10.2 billion in assets under management that specializes in stocks that pay dividends. Name: Exelon Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Now there\u2019s a way to invest and save democracy at the same time\r\n    ']
Body: [u'A key turning point was in 2010, when the Supreme Court ruled against government restrictions on corporate political spending in Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission. Since companies have deep pockets, their interests may trample those of average voters. ', u'A list of \u201csustainable investing\u201d themes from Arabesque Asset Management, which you can find in this note, appears comprehensive. It includes 30 topics of interest \u2014 everything from carbon emissions and community relations, to diversity and CEO pay. What about political campaign contributions and investing in sustainable democracy? Nowhere to be seen. ', u'The first stop for investors wanting to invest in sustainable democracy is the Center for Political Accountability (CPA) website. CPA examines the websites of S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0companies to gauge whether they have 24 qualities that CPA says companies need in the realm of campaign contributions. The big picture is that CPA is looking for the three qualities I mentioned above: transparency, policy and board oversight. ', u'CPA then ranks S&P 500 companies on a scale of 0-100. You can find a spreadsheet with rankings here. This ranking serves two purposes:', u'Morgan Stanley seems to be in the middle, concluding in this note that sustainable investments have \u201cusually met, and often exceeded, the performance of comparable traditional investments.\u201d', u' 1. Better governance  ', u' 2. Better results  ', u'To test how you\u2019d do if you used CPA\u2019s system as a sustainable democracy investment guide, I looked at how well CPA\u2019s top 48 companies did against the Guggenheim S&P 500 Equal Weight ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                          RSP, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 I chose this ETF because I used a simple equal weighting of the companies, so this ETF is the fairest comparison. (In contrast, the S&P 500 Index that most people track uses a market-cap weighted system. This means that smaller companies have a smaller impact on overall index returns.)', u'Some of the best-performing stocks in this group, in either time frame, included: Bank of America Corp. Name: CarMax Inc
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Dow closes above 21,000 as stocks soar after Trump speech\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Some analysts suggested that the absence of protectionist comments as well as his overall tone that was perceived as \u201cpresidential\u201d instilled confidence among investors, sending global equity markets higher. Stocks even rose slightly higher following the release of the Fed\u2019s Beige Book, which pointed out that business optimism has cooled a bit since the election. ', u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                 broke through the 21,000 barrier, surging 303.31 points, or 1.5%, to close at a record 21,115.55, led by more than 2% gains in J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          JPM, +0.05%                                                                                                                                                , American Express Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          AXP, +0.57%                                                                                                                                                 Travelers Cos.                                                                                                                                                                                                          TRV, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                 ExxonMobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          XOM, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 and Boeing Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          BA, +0.23%                                                                                                                                                 The index is up 6.9% year to date. ', u'The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rallied 32.32 points, or 1.4%, to close at a record 2,395.96 after reaching a new intraday high of 2,400.98, as nine of the 11 main sectors finished higher. Financials led gains, finishing up 2.8%, with energy stocks gaining 2.1%. Defensive sectors were the sole decliners, with utilities down 1% and real estate down 0.3%. The benchmark index is up 7% since the start of the year. ', u' See: This stock-market rally isn\u2019t all about Trump\u2019s newfound \u2018tone\u2019 ', u'Meanwhile, the Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                 surged 78.59 points, or 1.4% to close at a record 5,904.03. The tech-heavy index has outperformed other benchmarks year to date, rising 9.7%.', u'Small-caps also joined in with the Russell 2000 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.30%                                                                                                                                                \xa0closing at a record, up 1.9% north of 1,413 by the close, for a 4.1% gain on the year. ', u'The surge for stocks, on the heels of Trump\u2019s speech, also comes as the expectation for a rate increase by the Federal Reserve as early as mid-March have increased significantly. The probability for a March rate increase stands at 66%, up from a probability of 35% on Tuesday, according to CME Group\u2019s FedWatch tool. ', u' Read:  This stock-market rally isn\u2019t all about Trump\u2019s newfound \u2018tone\u2019 ', u'Adding to that, on Tuesday, New York Fed President William Dudley said the case for a U.S. interest rate increase has become \u201ca lot more compelling.\u201d', u'The Dow industrials ran from clearing 20,000 for the first time to clearing 21,000 in 24 sessions, tying a record set in 1999 for the shortest 1,000-point gain. While the current jump is smaller on a percentage basis, it\u2019s still psychologically compelling, especially when it took nearly two years for the Dow to reach 19,000 after it first passed 18,000, as markets were dealing with an earnings recession, Detrick said.', u'The manufacturing index from the Institute for Supply Management rose to 57.7% in February, its best level in more than two years. Meanwhile, construction spending declined 1% in January. Car sales for February were mixed with General Motors Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          GM, -0.99%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sales rising and Ford Motor Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          F, +0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sales declining.', u' Trump delivered his address to Congress after the market\u2019s close Tuesday. In what many saw as a rather reserved speech, the U.S. president said he would push for around $1 trillion in infrastructure spending, and promised \u201cmassive tax relief\u201d for the middle class and tax cuts for corporations. Otherwise, the speech was lacking in firm details about his economic plans. ', u' Read: Trump asks leaders for unity over overhauling taxes and health care. ', u'Analysts said investors will be looking for more hints to the Fed\u2019s plans for interest rates from the central bank\u2019s chairwoman, Janet Yellen, who will deliver a speech on Friday.', u' Stock movers:   Best Buy Co.
