Name: Texas Roadhouse, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u"\r\n         Chili's restaurant operator Brinker's stock slumps after Morgan Stanley downgrade\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Shares of Brinker International Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           EAT, -1.04%                                                                                                                                                 slumped 1.1% in morning trade Tuesday, after the operator of Chili\'s Grill & Bar and Maggiano\'s Little Italy restaurant chains was downgraded at Morgan Stanley, which cited concerns over decelerating industry trends. Analyst John Glass cut his rating to underweight from equal weight and lowered his price target to $47, which is just 0.8% above current levels, from $51. "While market expectations for sales have been reduced and shares have already faded from their postelection highs...we see risk to the consensus estimates in [fiscal 2017] as broader industry trends continue to weaken...and [Brinker\'s] core Chili\'s business has seen its sales trail the industry average over the last seven quarters (though the gap narrowed in the most recent quarter)," Glass wrote in a note to clients. Brinker\'s stock has run up as much as 12% after the election to a 15-month high on Nov. 23, but has since tumbled 15%. He also downgraded Blooming Brands Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BLMN, +0.89%                                                                                                                                                 which operates Outback Steakhouse and Carrabba\'s Italian Grill, to underweight from equal weight. Meanwhile, Glass upgraded Texas Roadhouse Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TXRH, -0.16%                                                                                                                                                 to equal weight from underweight. Brinker\'s stock has lost 1.5% over the past 12 months, while Bloomin\' shares have gained 2.6%, Texas Roadhouse\'s stock has soared 31% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                 has climbed 21%.']

Name: Avis Budget Group, Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Avis Budget shares fall after earnings, revenue miss\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Avis Budget Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CAR, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                 shares declined in the extended session Wednesday after the car rental company\'s quarterly earnings fell below Wall Street estimates. Avis shares fell 6.5% to $38 after hours. The company reported adjusted fourth-quarter earnings of 15 cents a share on revenue of $1.88 billion. Analysts surveyed by FactSet had estimated earnings of 17 cents a share on revenue of $1.97 billion. For 2017, Avis sees adjusted earnings of $3.05 to $3.75 on revenue of $8.8 billion to $8.95 billion. Analysts had estimated earnings of $3.46 a share on revenue of $9.01 billion. ']

Name: Viacom Inc.
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         YouTube looks to cash in on streaming with new service | FCC won\u2019t review AT&T-Time Warner deal | What to know about Snap IPO\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Good afternoon, MarketWatch readers. Thanks for showing interest in the latest edition of the Swerve newsletter. We\u2019ve been away for a spell, but have news and updates you may have missed concerning AT&T Inc.\u2019s\xa0                                                                                                                                                                                                          T, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0proposed $85.4 billion acquisition of Time Warner Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWX, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                 as well as new streaming entrants and early acquisition talks in the publishing industry. Sign up to receive Swerve: Time Warner, AT&T and the future of media. ', u' YouTube TV: The increasingly competitive online TV streaming space got a tad more crowded this week thanks to Google\u2019s YouTube Inc., owned by Alphabet Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOGL, +0.51%                                                                                                                                                                              GOOG, +0.48%                                                                                                                                                 The dominant online video arm of Google announced it is launching a $35-a-month subscription service with a collection of 40 networks. The service includes the four major networks \u2014 ABC                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, +0.13%                                                                                                                                                 CBS                                                                                                                                                                                                           CBS, +0.76%                                                                                                                                                 NBC                                                                                                                                                                                                           CMCSA, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Fox                                                                                                                                                                                                           FOXA, +1.58%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 as well as additional cable channels such as ESPN. It\u2019s a live-streaming service in the vein of Dish Network Corp.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           DISH, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Sling TV or AT&T\u2019s DirecTV Now. Notably missing from the service are any channels for Viacom Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           VIAB, +1.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Time Warner, which is on the verge of being bought by AT&T. YouTube executives said the company is always in talks with content partners about coming on board, but it will be interesting to see whether Time Warner will, with YouTube TV being in direct competition with AT&T\u2019s DirecTV. YouTube also said this week that users world-wide watch a total 1 billion hours of content on YouTube every day.', u' No review from FCC: The new Chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, Ajit Pai, said this week that people should not expect the commission to play a role in reviewing the AT&T-Time Warner deal, reports The Wall Street Journal\u2019s Thomas Gryta. FCC regulatory review was expected to be the key barrier to the deal going through. However, Time Warner and AT&T have apparently structured the deal so no airwave licenses are changing hands, which is one of the key triggers for FCC review. Time Warner recently sold its Atlanta TV station to Meredith Corp. for $70 million, which, according to the Journal, removed a significant factor in prompting FCC review.', u' Deal talk: There\u2019s chatter of possible movement in the publishing and media and entertainment industries. Shares of Time Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TIME, +1.31%                                                                                                                                                \xa0were up 7% on Wednesday following a Bloomberg report saying the company is seeking acquisition offers by next week. The board apparently wants to gauge the value of the company and determine whether it makes more sense to sell the entire company or specific magazine titles. In the TV world, Sinclair Broadcast Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SBGI, +1.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has approached Tribune Media Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TRCO, +0.67%                                                                                                                                                \xa0to engage in deal talks, according to Reuters. Shares of Sinclair were up more than 4%, while Tribune shares were up more than 7%. ', u' Snap IPO: Snap Inc., the parent company of popular messaging app Snapchat, is set to price its shares Wednesday night and begin trading Thursday morning. Here are six things to know about the company ahead of its initial public offering. ', u' Don\u2019t miss: Snapchat still a mystery to investors, and that\u2019s a problem for Snap IPO ', u' And the winner is...: Lions Gate Entertainment Corp.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           LGF.A, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0movie musical darling \u201cLa La Land\u201d won the top award for best... actually, independent art-house film \u201cMoonlight\u201d from A24 took home the Oscar for best picture, in a dramatic twist blunder. A partner from PwC, the trusted partner of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, mixed up the award envelopes and the wrong movie title was originally read for best picture. In other news, Amazon.com Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.57%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Netflix Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NFLX, -0.66%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 took home their first Oscars in a watershed moment for the streaming industry in Hollywood. This year\u2019s Oscars broadcast was the lowest in nine years.', u' Also read: Why the Oscars probably won\u2019t fire accounting firm PwC over best picture snafu ', u' Shaking things up: Barstool Sports, a scrappy, satirical and irreverent website covering sports and news, is aiming to become a bigger player in the digital media landscape with a broader audience. More than a year after receiving an investment from Peter Chernin\u2019s Chernin Group and bringing on a new CEO, the brand is growing and taking on bigger risks, recently joining with Comedy Central for live broadcasts during the Super Bowl. Barstool Sports was the No. 1 show on the network across the week that it aired.', u' Thanks for reading Swerve. If you\u2019re interested in staying abreast of the AT&T\u2013Time Warner deal and in keeping an eye on the future of media, sign up for the newsletter. For critical information before the markets open each morning, sign up for MarketWatch\u2019s Need to Know, sent daily at 7:30 a.m. Eastern time. ', u' Follow Trey Williams on Twitter: @Trey3Williams, and write to him at twilliams@marketwatch.com ']

Name: Buffalo Wild Wings, Inc.
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         Buffalo Wild Wings adds $400 million to share buyback program\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Buffalo Wild Wings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BWLD, +0.52%                                                                                                                                                 shares are up 1.2% in premarket trading after the restaurant chain added $400 million to its share repurchase program, bringing the total authorization to $900 million. The company also set a new goal for reaching its leverage ratio target of 1.5 times debt to earnings before interest, tax, depreciation and amortization to the end of fiscal 2017. The previous goal was the end of fiscal 2018. Buffalo Wild Wings shares are nearly flat for the past year while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                 is up 18.8% for the same period.']

Name: Yum! Brands, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Olive Garden, Taco Bell and Burger King want to help you celebrate Valentine\u2019s Day\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Valentine\u2019s Day is the top day for takeout orders, according to Darden Restaurants Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DRI, +0.40%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, the parent company of the Italian restaurant chain. Olive Garden is just one restaurant chain feeling the love this Valentine\u2019s Day.', u'Burger King, a Restaurant Brands International Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           QSR, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                \xa0chain, is offering an \u201cadult meal\u201d that comes with a special toy, starting at 6 p.m. The meal will also include two Whopper sandwiches, two orders of fries, and two beers, according to AdWeek.', u'And Taco Bell, a Yum Brands Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           YUM, -0.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 chain, has launched a sweepstakes that will give one winning couple an all-expense-paid wedding at the Taco Bell Cantina flagship on the Las Vegas Strip. Entries will be accepted between Valentine\u2019s Day and Feb. 26.', u'In addition to takeout, Lee said that two of the company\u2019s promotions were also stand outs in the most recent quarter: the Never Ending Pasta Bowl, which generated a lot of publicity, and the buy-one-take-one promotion, which allowed customers to buy one entree and take a second one home. Both were \u201cstrong value promotions,\u201d he said.', u' See also: Olive Garden\u2019s \u2018pasta passes\u2019 for sale on eBay for as much as $4,500 ', u'Olive Garden\u2019s strength during lunchtime, a daypart that many restaurant chains have struggled with, was attributed in part to the perceived value of its menu options, Lee said. ', u' See also:  Yum beats profit expectations, misses on revenue ', u' See also: Burger King, Tim Hortons owner\u2019s sales rise ', u' See also: Trump border tax would be a major blow for the troubled retail and restaurant sector ', u'Darden Restaurant shares are up 29.6% for the past year, Restaurant Brands shares are up 60.8% for the period, and Yum Brands shares are up 41.4%. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 is up 25.2% for the last 12 months.']

Name: Allegiant Travel Company
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Warren Buffett loves cheap airline stocks, which could get a boost from Trump\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The decision by Warren Buffett\u2019s Berkshire Hathaway to load up on Apple shares is making big news. But the billionaire investor also put money in four airline stocks. ', u'In the fourth quarter, Berkshire Hathaway Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BRK.B, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                \xa0built a new stake of 43.2 million shares in Southwest Airlines Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LUV, -0.27%                                                                                                                                                 while also adding to its holdings of American Airlines Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAL, -2.50%                                                                                                                                                 Delta Air Lines Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DAL, -1.25%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and United Continental Holdings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UAL, -0.93%                                                                                                                                                 Most airlines are expected by analysts to post declining profits in 2017 as fuel prices rise. Industry profits are expected to be healthy in 2018, with those four airlines expected to generate double-digit increases in earnings per share.', u' Don\u2019t miss:  20 companies that have met a high bar this earnings season ', u'FactSet estimates that the average effective income tax rate over the past 12 reported months for S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 member companies was 26.4%. The highest U.S. corporate tax rate is 35%, and, of course, many companies pay state and local income taxes as well. It is reasonable to argue that a reduction in the federal corporate tax rate will help some companies more than others, and airlines might be among the biggest beneficiaries.', u'We decided to broaden our review by looking at the nine airlines included in the S&P 1500 Composite Index, which is made up of the S&P 500, the S&P 400 Mid-Cap Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           MID, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and the S&P Small-Cap 600 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SML, +0.12%                                                                                                                                                ', u'(For SkyWest Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SKYW, -0.56%                                                                                                                                                 we are showing the effective income tax rate for 2015, because the company posted an operating loss for 2016.)']

Name: Alaska Air Group, Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Airline shares slump as Delta warns of higher costs\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Airline stocks fell in tandem Monday after Delta Air Lines Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DAL, -1.47%                                                                                                                                                 lowered its forecast operating margins for the year at the Raymond James Institutional Investors Conference in Orlando, Fla. In a presentation, Delta said margins would likely contract as cost increases outpaces revenue growth with the worst of it occurring in the March quarter, calling 2017 "a transition year." Delta said fuel prices have jumped 55% for the quarter. Shares of Delta fell 3.3%, while United Continental Holding Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UAL, -1.10%                                                                                                                                                 shares declined 4.2%, American Airlines Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAL, -2.85%                                                                                                                                                 shares shed 4.7%, Southwest Airlines Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LUV, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                 fell 2.4%, and Alaska Air Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ALK, -0.71%                                                                                                                                                 shares declined 2.5%.']

Name: Arconic Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Will Trump\u2019s boost for defense stocks still stand after tonight?\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Read also:  Trump\u2019s $30 trillion debt dilemma ', u'Trump made the promise to governors at the White House Monday and said that the bump would be funded by savings across all other government departments. The president is scheduled to address Congress at 9 p.m. Eastern and analysts are expecting him to offer details of his plans for military spending. ', u'The Office of Management and Budget said Monday that the budget would seek $54 billion in extra spending on defense, equal to a 10% rise. Trump\u2019s budget proposal will be released in mid-March, according to OMB communications director John Czwartacki, and the focus on military spending will likely require Congress to pass a new deal to lift caps on military spending, which are slated to return in 2018.', u' See: Trump: U.S. will be \u2018at the top of the pack\u2019 on nukes ', u'\u201cWith a world on fire, America cannot secure peace through strength with just 3 percent more than President [Barack] Obama\u2019s budget. We can and must do better,\u201d McCain said in a statement. ', u'Defense stocks have performed strongly since the November presidential election as investors bet Trump\u2019s victory would be a boon for the sector. The iShares U.S. Aerospace & Defence exchange-traded fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           ITA, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has seen about $$1.2 billion in inflows since Nov. 9, more than doubling its assets. ', u'The SPDR S&P Aerospace & Defense ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XAR, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has seen inflows of $236.8 million, according to ETF.com, while the PowerShares Aerospace & Defense ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           PPA, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has attracted $172 million in inflows. ', u' The three ETFs have all gained since the election, with the SPDR ETF up about 20%, as the chart below illustrates.', u'Among individual stocks, Boeing Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BA, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained about 21% in the last three months, General Dynamics Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GD, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 10% and Arconic Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ARNC, +0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 44.7%. The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 7.5% in the same period, and the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is up 9%.', u'The news boosted defense stocks in Europe and Asia overnight, fueling expectations that they will win supply contracts. ', u' See also: Putin, in the news in the U.S., faces an enemy at home ']

Name: Exxon Mobil Corporation
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         There\u2019s another land of opportunity in the reflation trade \u2014 Europe\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Financial markets worldwide have been lifted by U.S. President Donald Trump\u2019s promise to ramp up fiscal spending and reform taxes. The hope is that these projects will spur economic growth in the U.S. and help drive up inflation.', u'In anticipation, investors have been buying stocks \u2014 sending some global benchmarks to record highs \u2014 as well as the U.S. dollar                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. At the same time, they have been dumping safe-haven assets such as bonds, sending yields rising as their prices fall.', u' Read:  Bond market looks doubtful about Trump fiscal stimulus ', u'Just as headline inflation has risen in the U.S., it has marched up in Europe, too. In the eurozone, it jumped to 2% in February, outstripping the European Central Bank\u2019s target. In the U.K., inflation has hit 1.8%, driven to multiyear highs by rising oil prices and a double-digit slide in the British pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.1843%                                                                                                                                                \xa0since the Brexit vote.', u'Given that prospect, how can investors play the potential European and British reflation trade? Strategists provided some suggestions for funds and exchange-traded funds to consider, focusing on various types of stocks. Financials are one sector they highlight.', u'McGrade suggested looking at Old Mutual UK Alpha Fund, which has an overweight position in banks, and Investec UK Special Situations Fund, which has lenders HSBC\xa0                                                                                                                                                                                                          HSBA, -0.90%                                                                                                                                                                              HSBC, -0.47%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Barclays                                                                                                                                                                                                           BARC, -2.63%                                                                                                                                                \xa0among its top five holdings. ', u'Peter Garnry, head of equity strategy at Saxo Bank, also sees banks getting a boost. He suggested the iShares Stoxx 600 Banks ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJXSF, +35.36%                                                                                                                                                                              EXV1, -1.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, whose 45 components include Spain\u2019s BBVA                                                                                                                                                                                                           BBVA, +0.81%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, France\u2019s Soci\xe9t\xe9 G\xe9n\xe9rale                                                                                                                                                                                                           GLE, -1.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and U.K.\u2019s Lloyds Banking Group                                                                                                                                                                                                           LLOY, -1.99%                                                                                                                                                                              LYG, -1.44%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. ', u'Life insurers to look at include U.K.-based Prudential PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           PRU, -2.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Old Mutual PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           OML, -1.24%                                                                                                                                                 Legal & General PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           LGEN, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                 Standard Life PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           SL., -2.54%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Amsterdam-based Aegon NV                                                                                                                                                                                                           AGN, -2.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, he said. ', u' Read: How to give yourself a midlife insurance audit ', u'The resources sector is another to consider as part of a reflation-trade strategy, which is predicated on the prospect of strengthening economic growth, said McGrade. The International Monetary Fund in January raised its 2017 growth outlooks for the U.S. and Europe. ', u' For exposure to metals and energy producers, McGrade pointed to the Guinness Global Energy Fund, a long-only fund of 30 equally weighted positions, and First State Global Resources Fund, whose holdings include miner BHP Billiton                                                                                                                                                                                                           BLT, -1.95%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and oil heavyweight Exxon Mobil                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                 .', u'One driver in the upswing has been oil prices, which have moved up considerably over the past year, from lows of about $29 a barrel to current levels of about $50. But those gains could stagnate as an increase in U.S. shale production has reignited fears about oil oversupply. A glut could hurt efforts by the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries to balance the oil market.']

Name: Realty Income Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' 3 low-risk dividend plays to survive a stock-market correction\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 is up 9.9% since Election Day through Friday and sets new highs seemingly each week, including Friday. The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                          DJIA, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                 which has set seven straight record closes through Friday,\xa0remains comfortably above 20,000 and looks like it will stay there.', u'Furthermore, while markets hung tough during Federal Reserve Chairwoman Janet Yellen\u2019s latest visit to Capitol Hill, we saw a tremendous spike of about 20% in the CBOE Volatility Index                                                                                                                                                                                                          VIX, -1.20%                                                                                                                                                 over just a few days. That\u2019s a clear sign many traders are feeling uncertain about what the future holds in regards to interest rates and how that may impact the stock market.', u'And let\u2019s not forget that all this optimism in recent weeks may not materialize in the form of real economic growth. Recently, the World Bank warned that economic expansion in the developed world is painfully small, with just a 1.8% a growth rate expected this year.', u' Realty Income ', u'With dividends paid since 1969, Realty Income Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           O, -1.05%                                                                                                                                                 should be on every income investor\u2019s radar. But equally compelling is the fact that dividends are paid on a monthly basis instead of a quarterly basis \u2014 providing much more regular paydays than your typical dividend payer.', u' AT&T ', u'Yes, even boring old AT&T Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.87%                                                                                                                                                ! Of course, if you have been paying attention, you\u2019d know AT&T is anything but boring after gains of almost 20% in 2016.', u'The ride is far from over. While everyone is obsessed with the future of the company\u2019s proposed $85 billion merger with Time Warner Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          TWX, -0.43%                                                                                                                                                 the important thing to remember is that this stock is an income powerhouse that won\u2019t quit regardless of what happens with its content plans.', u'Sure, AT&T would love to bolster streaming content offerings and have a stake in properties like CNN and HBO that are owned by Time Warner. But look elsewhere and you\u2019ll see this isn\u2019t the only bet AT&T is making, as it has forged ahead with a faster 5G network that supports the public\u2019s reliance on mobile browsing. As a result, while rival Verizon Communications Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           VZ, -1.08%                                                                                                                                                recently issued weak guidance amid anemic wireless growth in January, AT&T earnings showed improved its \u201cchurn\u201d rate and is making headway.', u' Brookfield Infrastructure Partners ', u'All these things perfectly describe Brookfield Infrastructure Partners L.P.                                                                                                                                                                                                          BIP, +0.78%                                                                                                                                                 an industrial player that builds, buys and operates a wide array of infrastructure assets. Name: Exxon Mobil Corporation
Article: 12 : [u'\r\n         Trump Today: President signs revised order restricting travel to U.S.    \r\n    ']
Body: [u' NEW TRAVEL BAN  ', u'\u2022 In the morning, Trump signed the new travel ban, which bars people from six nations from entering the U.S. for 90 days. In a change from a previously issued order, the new one does not ban Iraqi citizens. The administration says the order will strengthen U.S. national security, while opponents call it a \u201cMuslim ban.\u201d The affected countries are Iran, Libya, Somalia, Sudan, Syria and Yemen. ', u' Also read: FBI investigating more than 300 refugees for terror activities, Sessions says. ', u' PENCE LUNCH ', u' TILLERSON MEETING  ', u' FCC\u2019S PAI GOES TO WHITE HOUSE ', u'\u2022 Federal Communications Commission Chairman Ajit Pai paid Trump a visit at the White House in the afternoon. Trump elevated Pai to the FCC chairmanship in January. Pai has worked to try to undo rules pushed through under his Democratic predecessor, reportedly including taking nine companies out of a subsidy program for internet access. ', u' CONGRATULATING EXXON ', u'\u2022 Trump congratulated Exxon Mobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 for a $20 billion investment program in the Gulf Coast region. \u201cThis is exactly the kind of investment, economic development and job creation that will help put Americans back to work,\u201d Trump said in a statement. Exxon said its investments began as early as 2013 \u2014 in other words, predating the Trump administration.', u' HUDDLING WITH THE NEC  ', u' Also read: Opinion: Trump supporters are the buyers driving the stock market\u2019s record run. ', u' SEEING SHULKIN ', u' MULVANEY AND PRICE DINNER  ']

Name: PPG Industries, Inc.
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         This is where the real risk for oil prices kicks in\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Oil is throwing a massive tantrum right now, just in time to spoil the 8th anniversary of the stock market\u2019s bull run.', u'Even if equities largely pay no mind to calendar dates, and yesterday\u2019s stock slide wasn\u2019t too severe, the slick stuff is tossing some shade this morning as Wednesday\u2019s sell-off reloads. (Thank shale-oil pioneer Harold Hamm\u2019s oil-killer comment for that meltdown, say some). ', u'\u201cIf we were vulnerable to a collapse, it would have happened by now. Most likely we are setting up for another sideways consolidation like we saw between December and February,\u201d he says on his blog.', u'Our call of the day is sticking to crude, compliments of a tweet from Raoul Pal:', u'The Global Macro Investor founder and former Goldman Sachs alum been here before. Like others, he\u2019s been warning that oil is vulnerable to a change of heart from big money managers and hedge funds. They\u2019ve been piling into the commodity for months, on a bet prices will keep moving higher, but may now jump out.', u'Those bullish bets on crude are becoming less popular, going by data last week from the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. It was the first reduction in three weeks and the strongest since early November for Brent, said Commerzbank. But the bank warned earlier this week that there are still too many long positions and that high optimism could turn into a \u201csword of Damocles\u201d threat to prices if selling by those investors intensifies.', u'Echoing that $45-a-barrel warning this morning, analysts at National Bank, say it\u2019s a \u201creasonable target\u201d right now. Meanwhile, Saxo Bank\u2019s chief commodity guy, Ole Hansen, says $47.18 a barrel opens a path to $42.20 a barrel.', u'Oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           CLJ7, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0is under $50 a barrel and the Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and the Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are all under some pressure.', u'Don\u2019t forget Thursday is European Central Bank meeting day. Name: iShares Nasdaq Biotechnology Index Fund
Article: 14 : [u'\r\n         How Trump\u2019s presser threatened to wreck his own stock-market rally\r\n    ']
Body: [u' U.S. equities tumbled after the presser started, with comments from Trump that drug companies were \u201cgetting away with murder\u201d with respect to pricing. However, the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                 the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.01%                                                                                                                                                 and the Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0all closed higher in the wake of the hourlong conference.', u'The biggest losers from those comments have been health-care shares, on fears of more stringent price controls. The iShares Nasdaq Biotechnology Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           IBB, +0.32%                                                                                                                                                \xa0finished the day down 3%, but the Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                rang up an all-time closing high. ', u'Read: MarketWatch\u2019s blog of the Trump press conference', u'With the drop in stocks, the CBOE Volatility Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           VIX, -0.80%                                                                                                                                                 known as Wall Street\u2019s fear gauge, while still at historically low levels, climbed 4% to a intraday high of 12.23, but eased off to close down 1.9% at 11.27. Although the index is below the 20 level that usually indicates genuine panic has gripped investors, the move represented the sharpest daily rise in about two weeks, according to FactSet data. ', u' Treasury yields dropped extended a downdraft after the news event concluded with the 10-year Treasury                                                                                                                                                                                                           TMUBMUSD10Y, -1.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0touching a session low of 2.324%. A recent, precipitous climb in yields in the wake of Trump\u2019s election win in November, which saw the benchmark bond hit a peak of 2.6% mid December, has been held in check, with yields tipping lower as the multimonth selloff abated. Bond prices move inversely to yields. The benchmark 10-year Treasury note finished Thursday\u2019s session at 2.379%.', u'In currencies, the U.S. Dollar index                                                                                                                                                                                                          DXY, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0dropped to trade at a session low of 101.28. By the close, the index was down 0.3% at 101.73. The Mexican peso                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote up bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/38313971/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.000000"}\'>MXNUSD, +0.237741%                                                                                                                                                \xa0hit an all-time low against the greenback as Trump continued his push to keep more U.S. jobs out of Mexico. Trump has threatened to end longstanding trade agreements with Mexico and has discussed plans to build a wall along the U.S.-Mexico border, a plan which he doubled down on during his Wednesday presser.']

Name: Westpac Banking Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         An outperforming portfolio manager recommends a shift to non-U.S. dividend stocks\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Back in May, Michael Binger, a senior portfolio manager with Gradient Investments LLC, told MarketWatch about six of his favorite dividend stocks at that time.', u'Gradient Investments is a registered investment adviser based in Arden Hills, Minn., with about $1.3 billion in assets under management for affiliated advisers. The Gradient 50 strategy, one of several strategies Binger and his colleagues pursue, seeks to outperform the benchmark S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0by selecting stocks of what they consider \u201chigh quality\u201d U.S. companies, and where dividend yields exceed that of the index. They will sell stocks that have become expensive relative to earnings or cash flow and seek opportunities to buy shares of companies that have temporarily fallen out of favor with the market.', u'When MarketWatch spoke with Binger in May, he had just sold the G50\u2019s holdings of AT&T Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.75%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Verizon Communications Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           VZ, -0.90%                                                                                                                                                 But as long-term interest rates shot up after Donald Trump\u2019s election in November, the share prices of both companies declined sufficiently for Binger to buy them again.', u'Binger saw another bargain in Kohl\u2019s Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KSS, -0.82%                                                                                                                                                 which sank 19% on Jan. 5 as investors showed their ire over disappointing holiday sales.', u'\u201cThe drop from $52 to $42 in one day looked like an opportunity for us,\u201d Binger said, \u201cso we bought that position and exited another position, Diebold Nixdorf Inc.\u201d                                                                                                                                                                                                           DBD, +0.43%                                                                                                                                                ']

Name: Icahn Enterprises L.P.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Icahn Enterprises raises Federal-Mogul offer price to $10 per share vs. $9.25\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Icahn Enterprises L.P.                                                                                                                                                                                                           IEP, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 said Tuesday it is raising its offer price for powertrain parts maker Federal-Mogul Holdings Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           fdml                                                                                                                                                 to $10 a share from $9.25. The investing arm of activist Carl Icahn said the offer is its best and final one and represents a premium of 8.1% over the previous offer price and a premium of 101% over the closing price of the shares on Feb. 26, the last trading day prior to its initial offer. The new offer will expire at midnight on Jan. 17. Federal-Mogul shares were down 2.2% in early trade, while IEP was up 1.2%. ']

Name: Tiffany & Co.
Article: 5 : [u"\r\n         Tiffany's stock slumps after CEO steps down \r\n    "]
Body: [u'Shares of Tiffany & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TIF, +0.50%                                                                                                                                                 slumped 3.2% in premarket trade, after the high-end jewelry retailer said over the weekend that Chief Executive Frederic Cumenal stepped down, effective immediately, after 22 months in the role. Cumenal had joined Tiffany in March 2011 from LVMH Group, and was named CEO as of April 1, 2015. Tiffany\'s stock has declined 6.6% through Friday with Cumenal as CEO, while online jewelry seller Blue Nile Inc. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           nile                                                                                                                                                 have soared 40.1% over the same time, Signet Jewelers Ltd. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           SIG, -0.29%                                                                                                                                                 have plunged 44.7%, the SPDR S&P Retail ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XRT, -0.60%                                                                                                                                                 has tumbled 14.4% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.22%                                                                                                                                                 has climbed 11.5%.']

Name: Express, Inc.
Article: 5 : [u"\r\n         Express's stock tumbles after warning of first-quarter profit and sales miss\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Shares of Express Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           EXPR, -1.58%                                                                                                                                                 tumbled 8% in premarket trade Wednesday, after the apparel retailer provided a downbeat outlook for the fiscal first quarter along declines fourth-quarter profit and sales. For the quarter to Jan. 28, earnings fell to $22.8 million, or 29 cents a share, from $56.1 million, or 67 cents a share, in the same period a year ago. The FactSet consensus was for earnings per share of 29 cents. Revenue fell to $678.8 million from $765.6 million, but topped the FactSet consensus of $676 million. Same-store sales dropped 13%, compared with expectations of a 12.2% decline. "As expected, our store performance continued to be impacted by challenging mall traffic and a promotional retail environment," said Chief Executive David Kornberg. Looking ahead, Express expects first-quarter same-store sales to be in the "negative high single-digits" percentage range, compared with expectations of negative 5.3%. The company expects a per-share loss of 4 cents to breakeven for the quarter, compared with the FactSet EPS consensus of 15 cents. The stock has lost 12% over the past three months, while the SPDR S&P Retail ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XRT, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                 has declined 13% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 5.4%.']

Name: Abercrombie & Fitch Company
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         Abercrombie earnings miss expectations\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Abercrombie & Fitch Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ANF, -2.27%                                                                                                                                                 reported fourth-quarter net income of $48.8 million, or 71 cents per share, down from $57.7 million, or 85 cents per share, for the same period last year. The FactSet consensus was 75 cents. Sales for the quarter were $1.04 billion, down from $1.11 billion last year and just below the $1.05 billion FactSet consensus. Same-store sales for the company fell 5%, with the Abercrombie & Fitch brand seeing a 13% decline and Hollister up 1%. The FactSet consensus was for a 5.4% decline. Abercrombie shares are unchanged in Thursday premarket trading, and down 61.6% for the past year. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                 is up 20.6% for the last 12 months.']

Name: Chesapeake Energy Corporation
Article: 11 : [u'\r\n         Bank of America earnings: what to watch for\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The results will come amid hopes of the dawning of a Goldilocks age for the banking industry, with President-elect Donald Trump promising reduced regulations, lower corporate taxes and fiscal stimulus, which could lead to higher interest rates.', u'Continued increases in oil and other commodity prices during the fourth quarter should have also provided a boost to Bank of America\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0results, as TD Securities said that has provided for further stabilization in the credit quality of banks\u2019 oil and gas exposures, and for a more upbeat credit outlook.', u' Don\u2019t miss:  What President-elect Trump means for every U.S. industry.', u' See also:  End of a stock market era: Alcoa breaks tradition of being first to report earnings.', u' Earnings: BofA is expected to report earnings per share of 38 cents for the quarter ended Dec. 31, according to the average estimate of 27 analysts compiled by FactSet, up from 28 cents in the same period a year ago. The FactSet EPS consensus has increased from 36 cents at the end of the third quarter.', u' Revenue: Total revenue is expected to come in at $20.84 billion, according to FactSet, up from $19.53 billion a year ago, and compared with expectations of $20.57 billion at the start of the quarter. The Estimize consensus is for revenue of $20.90 billion', u'Expectations have increased since the quarter started, as the yield on the 10-year Treasury                                                                                                                                                                                                           TMUBMUSD10Y, -1.48%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rocketed 83.8 basis points (0.838 percentage points) during the quarter, the biggest quarterly surge since the first quarter of 1994. Meanwhile, the average rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages increased 74 basis point, according to Freddie Mac.', u' Stock price: BofA\u2019s stock has gained the day of its last three quarterly reports, by an average of 2.0%.', u'The shares closed down 0.7% on Thursday, to sit just 1% below the Dec. 15 eight-year closing high of $23.16. They have run up 46% since the end of the third quarter through Wednesday, propelled by a 35% surge since the election. Meanwhile, the SPDR Financial Select Sector exchange-traded fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLF, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has rallied 17% since the election and the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has climbed 6.1%.', u' See also:  Bank ETFs still favored as investors see growth and Trump bump ahead.', u'The average daily volume in the stock over the past 30 days has been 111.6 million shares, or more than double that of Chesapeake Energy Corp. Name: Microsoft Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Apple says it\u2019s already dealt with \u2018many\u2019 hacks in WikiLeaks\u2019 CIA dump\r\n    ']
Body: [u'WikiLeaks on Tuesday released thousands of documents and files purported to come from a CIA archive, calling the unauthorized disclosure the biggest ever \u201cpublication of confidential documents on the agency.\u201d Neither the CIA nor the White House would comment on the data dump, which WikiLeaks has dubbed \u201cVault 7.\u201d', u'The unverified files suggest the spy agency was able to breach the security on a range of internet-connected devices, including Android smartphones, Samsung Electronics Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           005930, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                 smart TVs, and Windows, Linux and Mac computers. They also indicate that one piece of CIA software will remain effective on an iPhone even after a reboot.', u'In response, Apple                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.57%                                                                                                                                                 said many of the issues laid out in the documents were dealt with some time ago. The iPhone maker cited updates to the iOS operating system used on its handsets.', u'The incident revived interest in Apple\u2019s refusal in 2015 to unlock a suspect\u2019s iPhone after the terrorist attack in San Bernardino, Calif., which left 14 people dead. The company\u2019s chief executive, Tim Cook, maintained that could open the floodgates to more violations of privacy by U.S. officials and give the White House \u201cdangerous power.\u201d', u'As for smart TVs, WikiLeaks claimed a \u201cfake-off mode\u201d had been created by British intelligence and the CIA for Samsung sets. The TV would seem to be switched off, but would still be able to pick up audio and maybe video in a room.', u'Microsoft Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          MSFT, +0.47%                                                                                                                                                                              MSFT, +0.47%                                                                                                                                                 , whose Windows was among the operating systems said to be targeted by CIA hackers, reportedly told the Wall Street Journal and the BBC that it was looking into the issue. The company has not responded to a request for comment.']
