Name: United States Steel Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Should Wall Street let God guide stock-market investments?\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Inspire Global Hope Large Cap ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           BLES, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                \u2014which made its debut on Tuesday, along with a small and midcap fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           ISMD, -0.46%                                                                                                                                                 with an identical strategy\u2014was designed for religious investors looking to have their portfolio holdings align with their personal beliefs.', u'Religious investing has a long history on Wall Street, with a number of mutual-fund providers offering Christian or Islamic products that adhere to the particulars of those faiths. Shariah-compliant funds for Muslim investors, for example, don\u2019t invest in banks because the religion forbids charging interest. ', u'Among ETFs, there is the Global X S&P 500 Catholic Values ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           CATH, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                 which was launched in April 2016 and is built around the investment guidelines of the U.S. Council of Catholic Bishops. Those guidelines prohibit investing in companies based on their services\u2014including ones that provide abortion, weapons, or which work with embryonic stem cells\u2014or other practices. It bars companies that discriminate on the basis of race or gender, and it doesn\u2019t include screens for sexual orientation.', u'Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.88%                                                                                                                                                 whose chief executive Tim Cook is openly gay, is the top component of the Catholic Values fund; it is not a holding of the Inspire ETF.', u'The Global X fund dipped 0.2% on Tuesday, though it is up 5.9% thus far in 2017, slightly better than the 5.6% rise of the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                 ', u'Based on data about the underlying index, the equally weighted fund\u2019s top holding is Mead Johnson Nutrition Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MJN, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                 though it only comprises 0.31% of the portfolio. Other top names include Idexx Laboratories Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           IDXX, +2.41%                                                                                                                                                 U.S. Steel Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           X, +2.84%                                                                                                                                                 and Invesco Ltd                                                                                                                                                                                                           IVZ, -0.43%                                                                                                                                                 The fund has heavy overseas exposure. While 46.3% of its composition is U.S. names, an additional 20% is from Great Britain (9.1%), Australia (7.8%), and China (3.5%). The remaining third is from \u201cother\u201d countries.']

Name: Abbott Laboratories
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         10 \u2018Dividend Aristocrat\u2019 stocks expected to rise up to 22% as you get paid to wait\r\n    ']
Body: [u'And the proof is that, last year, dividend stocks kept pace with the broader S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                \xa0despite the fact that the Federal Reserve had at the end of 2015 raised official rates for the first time in nine years. ', u' Also see: Follow the money \u2014 sell health-care stocks and buy dividend shares ', u'You might be familiar with the S&P 500 Dividend Aristocrats Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPDAUDP, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                 which is maintained by S&P Dow Jones Indices and is made up of the 50 companies in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                 that have raised their dividends on common shares for at least 25 straight years. That\u2019s a track record any company would be proud of, and it certainly makes management teams think twice before considering a dividend cut. Since this is the only criterion, the dividend yields aren\u2019t necessarily very high. The idea is that consistently raising the payout might be correlated with good long-term performance.', u'An easy way to invest in the entire index is the ProShares S&P 500 Dividend Aristocrats ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           NOBL, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                ', u'To broaden our horizons, we\u2019re focusing today on the S&P High Yield Dividend Aristocrats Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPHYDA, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 which is also maintained by S&P Dow Jones Indices and includes the 106 components of the S&P 1500 Composite Index that have raised their dividends on common shares for at least 20 consecutive years. Since the S&P 1500 Composite Index includes the S&P 500, (along with the S&P 400 Mid-Cap Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           MID, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and the S&P Small-Cap 600                                                                                                                                                                                                           SML, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                ), any Dividend Aristocrat is also a high-yield dividend aristocrat.', u' Don\u2019t miss:  This fund manager is finding profits in the wreckage of corporate Europe ', u'An easy way to invest in the entire High Yield Dividend Aristocrats Index is the SPDR S&P Dividend ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           SDY, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0', u' So our first list is simply 10 stocks among the High-Yield Dividend Aristocrats with the highest current dividend yields: ', u' Here are the 10 high-yield dividend aristocrats with majority \u2018buy\u2019 ratings that have the most implied upside potential over the next year, based on analysts\u2019 price targets: ']

Article: 2 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Now there\u2019s a way to invest and save democracy at the same time\r\n    ']
Body: [u'A key turning point was in 2010, when the Supreme Court ruled against government restrictions on corporate political spending in Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission. Since companies have deep pockets, their interests may trample those of average voters. ', u'A list of \u201csustainable investing\u201d themes from Arabesque Asset Management, which you can find in this note, appears comprehensive. It includes 30 topics of interest \u2014 everything from carbon emissions and community relations, to diversity and CEO pay. What about political campaign contributions and investing in sustainable democracy? Nowhere to be seen. ', u'The first stop for investors wanting to invest in sustainable democracy is the Center for Political Accountability (CPA) website. CPA examines the websites of S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0companies to gauge whether they have 24 qualities that CPA says companies need in the realm of campaign contributions. The big picture is that CPA is looking for the three qualities I mentioned above: transparency, policy and board oversight. ', u'CPA then ranks S&P 500 companies on a scale of 0-100. You can find a spreadsheet with rankings here. This ranking serves two purposes:', u'Morgan Stanley seems to be in the middle, concluding in this note that sustainable investments have \u201cusually met, and often exceeded, the performance of comparable traditional investments.\u201d', u' 1. Better governance  ', u' 2. Better results  ', u'To test how you\u2019d do if you used CPA\u2019s system as a sustainable democracy investment guide, I looked at how well CPA\u2019s top 48 companies did against the Guggenheim S&P 500 Equal Weight ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                          RSP, -0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 I chose this ETF because I used a simple equal weighting of the companies, so this ETF is the fairest comparison. (In contrast, the S&P 500 Index that most people track uses a market-cap weighted system. This means that smaller companies have a smaller impact on overall index returns.)', u'Some of the best-performing stocks in this group, in either time frame, included: Bank of America Corp. Name: United Technologies Corporation
Article: 10 : [u'\r\n        ', u' How to invest in the Trump era: Buy shares of private companies\r\n    ']
Body: [u'For individual investors, that presents a suggestion that private businesses might be a good way to diversify at a time when the Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has just topped 20,000 for the first time.', u'Even before taking office, Trump made no mystery of the fact that he plans to pressure large U.S. corporations, the likes of United Technologies\u2019                                                                                                                                                                                                           UTX, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Carrier, Ford                                                                                                                                                                                                           F, +0.77%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Boeing                                                                                                                                                                                                           BA, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                 to retain jobs at home rather than moving them to countries such as Mexico. Now, with major stock indices at all-time highs, Trump\u2019s push to demand that major corporations adopt policies that he deems more patriotic suggests headwinds for U.S. large-cap stocks. ', u'One common misconception is that investing in private companies means putting your money in a smaller basket. That\u2019s not the case: Small businesses employ as many people in the United States as public companies. Of America\u2019s 6 million employers, nearly all are private \u2014 only 0.08% of firms are listed on a national stock exchange, according to Harvard University and New York University research. And more than 85% of U.S. firms with 500 or more employees are private, among them such stable workhorses as Koch Industries, Mars, Ernst & Young and Toys \u201cR\u201d Us. ', u'Also, private companies typically invest more in growth and are more responsive to investment opportunities, accounting for 53% of non-residential fixed investment, the Harvard/NYU study finds. That yields strong investment returns. Actual returns on private investment is about 8.5%, according to Richard Zerbe Jr., writing in the Cato Institute\u2019s Regulation magazine. Many such companies tend to be family-run, a structure that a report by McKinsey says encourages a long-term perspective to management that leads to outperforming the S&P500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0over 10 years by an average of about 3 percentage points.', u'Those opportunities could include such things as commercial real estate, which has lagged residential real estate in recent years, manufacturing companies \u2014 a sector now undergoing strong growth thanks to precision engineering advances and new technology \u2014 and companies in the services sector, particularly those with significant tangible assets, such as valuable real estate holdings. Such pooled investment vehicles will typically invest only a small portion of their cash in startups \u2014 firms that are on the one hand more likely to fail but can also, on occasion, produce outsized investment returns from such young firms as Uber or Facebook\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, +0.51%                                                                                                                                                \xa0WhatsApp.', u'Investors looking to invest in startups can contact incubators and accelerators and join an angel network. For example, Y Combinator twice a year invests $120,000 in about 100 companies, and Techstars has invested more than $2.75 billion in more than 880 companies that are now valued at over $7.5 billion. Investors can research private investment opportunities at places like equities.com and Crunchbase, and the site crowdfundinsider.com lists Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) filings of private companies. ', u'Among the others are Crowdfunder, which offers investments in everything from companies developing apps to a firm building energy-efficient homes. Group Capital, my firm, plans to focus on more mature, middle-market private businesses. Others like IndieGogo allow individuals to invest $100 or more in smaller opportunities, from restaurants to book publishing. And SharePost connects buyers and sellers of shares in private companies, acting as a marketplace for investors.', u' Douglas Fink is the CEO of crowdfunding platform Group Capital. ']

Name: Pfizer, Inc.
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n        ', u' 5 reasons to bank on biotech stocks now\r\n    ']
Body: [u'From early 2013 to mid-2015, the sector went on an amazing run; while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 gained about 50%, major biotech ETFs like the iShares Nasdaq Biotechnology Index ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           IBB, +0.49%                                                                                                                                                 and the SPDR S&P Biotech ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XBI, +1.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0roughly tripled. If you were bold enough to pick individual names, like Inovio Pharmaceuticals Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           INO, +1.70%                                                                                                                                                 which quickly went from $2 to $11 during that stretch, you could have done even better.', u'  Don\u2019t sweat regulatory rhetoric: After Congressional hearings last year for Mylan NV                                                                                                                                                                                                          MYL, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0over allegations of price gouging with its EpiPen treatment, biotech stocks came under pressure as investors feared price controls could limit margins. And while the election of President Donald Trump and a firm Republican majority to Congress had some breathing a sigh of relief, remarks from Trump in January that biotech stocks were \u201cgetting away with murder\u201d hinted it may not be easy going after all. ', u' Still good growth options: While some picks are seeing top-line pressures, many biotech stocks have growth stories that are unmatched elsewhere on Wall Street. Take Celgene Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CELG, -0.55%                                                                                                                                                 which just saw strong fourth-quarter sales growth of 16% thanks to its blockbuster Revlimid cancer treatment churning out double-digit sales growth again with no sign of slowing. Of course, some one-time charges held back profits, but excluding those items, earnings jumped 36%. Admittedly, growth might not match the go-go days of years past, but the question going forward is simply whether the growth is promising enough vs. the alternatives in a challenging market.', u' Biotechs are fairly priced: It\u2019s also important to remember that because of Wall Street\u2019s negative view on biotech, these stocks have been deeply discounted vs. prior norms in the sector. Take one-time darling Biogen Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BIIB, +0.47%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, which has seen its shares go nowhere for about a year and a half. Sure, Biogen saw a nearly flat top line and another slide in profits when it reported fourth-quarter numbers recently. But after struggling for a while, it now trades at a little more than 12 times next year\u2019s earnings. ', u'When staples stocks like Hershey Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSY, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                 are trading for 22 times earnings and utilities like Sempra Energy                                                                                                                                                                                                           SRE, +0.60%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are trading for forward P/E\u2019s of 20, it\u2019s pretty clear the bad news is priced in for many names across the biotech sector.', u' Rock-solid and recession-proof: While companies face specific challenges based on their drug approvals and patents, the good news is that once a biotech stock creates a successful treatment, it is very difficult to unseat that company. Many biotechs are focused on \u201corphan\u201d drugs where patients have no other options, such as BioMarin Pharmaceutical Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BMRN, +0.40%                                                                                                                                                 which has gone after rare genetic disorders. This grants them a virtual monopoly when treatments prove successful. Furthermore, these drugs aren\'t discretionary expenses that will be cut back on when times get lean. Patients will do whatever they can to afford treatments that improve their quality of life, and that means recession-proof revenue for biotech in a time when many industries are facing uncertainty.', u' Buyout bait: The hope of a big buyout premium has lured many investors into smaller biotech stocks over the years. Sometimes those deals never transpire, but in 2017, those hopes of big-time acquisitions could prove well-founded. As I wrote recently, there was a record $1.7 trillion in M&A last year, with 80% of that going toward strategic deals by competitors or peers. That trend is sure to continue this year, particularly with a more sympathetic regulatory environment in Washington. ', u'It\u2019s also worth pointing out that while many investors focus on Big Pharma heavyweights loaded with cash \u2014 such as Pfizer Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PFE, +0.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sitting on roughly $24 billion in cash and investments \u2014 smaller players are also sitting on big war chests. Case in point: Gilead Sciences Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GILD, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                 which has more than $31 billion in cash and investments at present. With big-time cash at the top of the food chain and smaller biotech stocks trading at relatively low levels compared with prior years, 2017 may be a big year for consolidation in the space.']

Name: J.M. Smucker Company (The)
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' After Warren Buffett\u2019s Kraft Heinz backs down on Unilever, where should investors look? \r\n    ']
Body: [u'President Trump is imploring American companies to invest in America. Warren Buffett, a big supporter of Hillary Clinton and perhaps the best-known American investor, last week made a surprise announcement to move billions of dollars abroad: Kraft Heinz                                                                                                                                                                                                           KHC, +0.44%                                                                                                                                                 which is controlled by Buffett and Brazilian firm 3G Capital Partners, made a $143 billion bid for Anglo-Dutch global giant Unilever                                                                                                                                                                                                           UN, +0.90%                                                                                                                                                                              UL, +0.44%                                                                                                                                                                              ULVR, +0.15%                                                                                                                                                ', u'Less than 48 hours after the audacious bid, the bid was withdrawn. In my opinion, the main reason, although unstated, is political blowback.', u' The business background behind Kraft\u2019s bid for Unilever ', u'Kraft is in the packaged-food business. Unilever is in the personal-goods and packaged-food business. To understand what pushed Kraft to make a bid, let us start with this annotated chart.', u'It compares popular packaged-food company General Mills                                                                                                                                                                                                           GIS, -1.51%                                                                                                                                                 \u2014 the best representation of the packaged-food industry\u2019s business trends \u2014 with the Dow Jones Industrial Average represented by SPDR Dow Jones Industrial Average ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIA, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                 The vertical axis is the percentage of gains for each since May 2007. Until July of last year, the stock market appeared oblivious to ills of the packaged-food industry and relentlessly ran up General Mills\u2019 share price because investors were focused on its dividend. In late July 2016, investors woke up to the following facts about the packaged-food industry:', u'Since then, packaged-food stocks have dramatically underperformed the Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                          DJIA, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                 Kraft Heinz, with a pricey stock but suffering from stagnant sales, needs a deal that would let it drastically cut costs and juice its bottom line \u2014 and had the currency, through its stock, to do it.', u' What\u2019s happening to packaged-food stocks ', u'Following Kraft\u2019s bid for Unilever, there was notable selling in five packaged-food stocks: General Mills, Campbell Soup                                                                                                                                                                                                           CPB, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                 Kellogg                                                                       MDLZ, -0.10% Smucker                                                                                                                                                                                                           SJM, -0.29%                                                                                                                                                 The reason was that there had been speculation that Kraft would bid for one of these companies that bid up share prices, so investors were disappointed when Kraft chose another company. ', u' What about personal-goods companies? ', u'Previously there was little buyout speculation in personal-goods stocks. After the Kraft bid, strong buying was seen in four personal-care stocks: Colgate-Palmolive                                                                                                                                                                                                           CL, +0.13%                                                                                                                                                 Kimberly-Clark                                                                                                                                                                                                           KMB, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                 Edgewell Personal Care                                                                                                                                                                                                           EPC, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                 and Clorox                                                                                                                                                                                                           CLX, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                ', u' isclosure: Subscribers to The Arora Report may have positions in the securities mentioned in this article or may take positions at any time. Name: MetLife, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Why companies are paying for IVF for their workers but don\u2019t want to talk about it\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Yet a handful of states might finally be giving reproductive health the attention it deserves: A new bill to expand infertility coverage was introduced in the New York state legislature last month and similar efforts are underway in Mississippi, New Jersey and South Carolina.', u'The proposed legislation comes as more companies dangle ever-generous infertility benefits packages as part of a \u201cfamily-friendly\u201d perks race intended to retain female employees. In the latest high-profile announcement, American Express now offers employees up to $35,000 in coverage for baby-making services, including IVF and medication. ', u'Companies are increasingly filling the void because the U.S. health care system doesn\u2019t deem treating infertility \u2014 a condition affecting 1 in 8 U.S. couples \u2014 a medical necessity. Only 15 states require that policies cover any kind of infertility benefits, and only eight mandates include IVF, which fertility doctors regard as the gold standard of treatment. ', u'Although the number of employers offering infertility benefits has remained steady over the last few years \u2014 at 26%, according to the Society for Human Resource Management \u2014 there are two trends worth noting: A handful of companies, such as Intel                                                                                                                                                                                                           INTC, +0.49%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and AmEx                                                                                                                                                                                                           AXP, +0.39%                                                                                                                                                 recently upped their coverage. And despite tech companies leading the charge to keep more women in their field, other industries are also being represented, says Anderson-Bialis, whose FertilityIQ ranked the top companies to work for as fertility patients. ', u'For example, chemical giant BASF                                                                                                                                                                                                           BASF, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added a $10,000 benefit in 2015. Insurance provider                                                                                                                                                                                                           MET, -0.39%                                                                                                                                                \xa025,000 benefit comes with a call-in advice nurse service to walk patients through the process. And Bank of America                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 offers unlimited coverage for IVF and medications. \u201cWhen these big companies provide these benefits, they are normalizing that this is something that\u2019s important,\u201d says Stapleton.', u' Sarah Elizabeth Richards writes extensively about fertility and is the author of \u2018Motherhood, Rescheduled: The New Frontier of Egg Freezing and the Women Who Tried it.\u2019']

Name: AllianceBernstein Holding L.P.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' U.S. stocks riding a bull market in corruption\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Now imagine my pride if that had actually happened. Or if the 5% gain in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0that has happened, or even the 8% climb in the narrower Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                          DJIA, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 \u2014 which has  failed for the 15th day to gain the last 250 points needed to cross 20,000 \u2014 were based on fundamentals. ', u'Instead, this recent rally is rooted mostly in corruption \u2014 now and in the future. And a rally built on corruption is bound to fail. Here\u2019s why:', u'Financial stocks are responsible for much of the U.S. market\u2019s recent move, and the rally in financials is rooted in hopes for government deregulation of the industry. Financial stocks represent about a third of the S&P and are up around 17% since the election. Take them out and there is no rally, Trump or otherwise. ', u'Except that interest rates aren\u2019t behind most of the rally. Instead, the enthusiasm for financials is more about prospects for repeal of the Dodd-Frank bank reform bill, as well as the Obama administration fiduciary rule that requires financial advisers, brokers, and asset managers to put clients\u2019 financial interests ahead of their own. Just look at how shares of investment managers have performed lately. Giant asset managers such T. Rowe Price Group                                                                                                                                                                                                           TROW, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Alliance Bernstein Holding                                                                                                                                                                                                           AB, -0.68%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose as much as 22% post-election. Clearly, asset managers aren\u2019t interest-rate plays, dispensing of the notion that rising rates are what\u2019s pumping the financials. ', u'Much of the rest of the rally is due to energy stocks. The money on oil now is a bet that recent OPEC production quotas will hold up. That bet has failed repeatedly \u2014 crude prices only keep up with inflation, since 1973, during brief fits of effective manipulation. Eventually, kleptocrats always choose stable home fronts over stable prices, and cheat on quotas to achieve it. They will again. Soon. Energy stocks are about 8% of the S&P 500 and are up 9.4% since the election.', u'Health care, too, sees investors betting on corruption in that industry. Drug stocks account for all of the gains in health-care stocks since Election Day. Meanwhile, hospital shares including HCA Holdings                                                                                                                                                                                                           HCA, -0.73%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 are down, as are medical-device stocks such as Medtronic                                                                                                                                                                                                           MDT, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and ACA-exposed Molina Healthcare                                                                                                                                                                                                           MOH, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                 The industry caterwauled about a device tax helping to finance the Affordable Care Act, but prospective ACA repeal and Medicare cuts are apparently worse.', u'There\'s no mystery about why Republicans won\'t allow it, either, forbidding negotiation since passing Medicare Part D in 2003. The drug industry spends $250 million a year on lobbying and its campaign contributions run 3-2 in favor of Republicans. The drug rally may be small-C corruption, but it\'s corruption still \u2014 the kind of corruption that favors Martin Shkreli over grandma, while 82% of Americans favor Medicare negotiations.', u'The Dow\xa0is likely to cross 20,000, but that doesn\'t validate Trump. U.S. stocks tripled under President Barack Obama. They went up under former President George W. Bush, too \u2014 until they didn\'t \u2014 and have risen about 10% a year since 1928. \xa0They\'ll rise in 2017 too if corporate profits beat expectations built into prices already.']

Name: Pepsico, Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         PepsiCo will change Naked Juice labeling as part of settlement with healthy foods watchdog\r\n    ']
Body: [u'PepsiCo Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PEP, +0.35%                                                                                                                                                 will change the labeling of its Naked Juice smoothie products as part of a settlement agreement with the watchdog Center for Science in the Public Interest. The changes, which PepsiCo plans to implement over the next eight months, include changes to the naming system to explicitly state the nature of the product -- such as "fruit juice" or "fruit and veggie juice" -- and what\'s inside of it, for example, "kale flavored blend of 8 juices with other natural flavors," according to the agreement. Any imagery on the labels and descriptive statements will also reflect the product\'s most significant ingredients, and the claim "no sugar added" will be displayed less prominently, along with the disclaimer that the product is not a low-calorie food. The company also said it will not use "unsubstantiated health-content or health-based claims" in marketing or advertising of Naked juices. The settlement does not count as an admission of wrongdoing, PepsiCo and Naked Juice said. CSPI, which advocates for a healthier food system, commended PepsiCo on its cooperation and "commitment to transparency." "Consumers deserve to know at a glance what they\'re buying, and Naked\'s labeling and marketing enhancements accomplish that," litigation director Maia Kats said. According to the agreement, the various labeling and marketing commitments expire in five years maximum, and could expire earlier depending on changes in the products or relevant regulations that would affect the entire agreement. PepsiCo agreed to remove the "all natural" claim from its Naked line in 2013 as part of a $9 million lawsuit settlement. PepsiCo shares were up a scant 1.0% in morning trade Tuesday. Shares have surged 6.9% over the last three months, compared with a 7.0% rise in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                 ']

Name: Target Corporation
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         5 survival stocks to thrive, come hell, high water or a bubble\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Sure, there\u2019s been a lot of talk about a stock bubble. But when President Donald Trump makes his not-a-State-of-the-Union address to Congress later, don\u2019t be surprised if it turns out to be a call to action (even if history shows such speeches aren\u2019t always big stock movers).', u'That brings us to our call of the day, which finds respite from the often-unclear world of politics in some come-hell-or-high-water stocks. These would be great adds to any portfolio, says Bret Jensen, blogging for Investors Alley.', u'Jensen zeroes in on real estate, a sector that he says has been buoyed by recent data and has held up pretty well despite last November\u2019s U.S. interest-rate rise. ', u'He likes Toll Brothers                                                                                                                                                                                                           TOL, -1.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, specifically for the 20% order backlog it recently reported, and says D.R Horton                                                                                                                                                                                                           DHI, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                 is another good overall pick for the housing sector, given its geographic diversity and strong balance sheet.', u'Other favorites include smaller builder Williams Lyon Homes                                                                                                                                                                                                           WLH, -1.94%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and hotel real-estate-investment-trust Chatham Lodging Trust                                                                                                                                                                                                           CLDT, -0.73%                                                                                                                                                 . Investors should just buy and hold the latter, Jensen says. Diamondrock                                                                                                                                                                                                           DRH, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Hersha Hospitality Trust                                                                                                                                                                                                           HT, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are two more. ', u'Check out the whole post for his entire rationale for those picks and the sector. Plus, here are 20 more stocks that will help you sleep at night.', u'It\u2019s the last trading day of the month, and this market has potential to go out with a bang. One more record close from the Dow industrials                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u2014 Monday marked No. 12 \u2014 and we\u2019re in no man\u2019s land. The Dow, S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.45%                                                                                                                                                 are struggling for any kind of headway. ', u'In other markets, gold                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCJ7, +0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and crude                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0are lower. See the Market Snapshot column for the latest action. ', u'Mark Arbeter sees further gains for the sector, as he looks at key levels for the Health Care SPDR ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLV, +0.15%                                                                                                                                                 He said that ETF has now run up to a target/resistance level that he flagged earlier this month, and he\u2019s now set new goals.', u'\u201cAnybody who wants to make the economy grow at 4% a year in real terms has a big job to do. I don\u2019t think it\u2019s even possible for anybody. The economy has certain limits, which are irrespective of whoever sits in the White House.\u201d \u2014 That was Vanguard founder Jack Bogle, talking to BBC Radio 5 earlier Tuesday about the limits of Trump\u2019s plans to revitalize the U.S. economy.', u' Read: Warren Buffett: Jack Bogle is a \u2018hero\u2019 to investors ', u'Target                                                                                                                                                                                                           TGT, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has plunged 14%, after a disappointing fourth-quarter report. Shares are set to suffer the biggest slide since the retailer went public 45 years ago.', u'Valeant                                                                                                                                                                                                           VRX, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0posted a wider loss as revenue fell, and shares are down about 5%.', u'SeaWorld                                                                                                                                                                                                           SEAS, -1.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0posted a bigger-than-expected loss, though shares aren\u2019t moving. ', u'Ross Stores                                                                                                                                                                                                           ROST, +0.41%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Etsy                                                                                                                                                                                                           ETSY, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Salesforce                                                                                                                                                                                                           CRM, +0.39%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 will report after the close.', u'Apple\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +1.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0next iPhone will have a curved screen, The Wall Street Journal reports, citing sources. ', u'Elon Musk\u2019s SpaceX plans to send tourists to orbit the moon in roughly two years.', u'Starbucks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SBUX, +0.72%                                                                                                                                                \xa0will open its first European Roastery in Milan.', u'Wal-Mart                                                                                                                                                                                                           WMT, +0.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has upgraded its mobile app, and will now offer customers paperless transactions and \u201cexpress lanes\u201d to skip lines.', u'Hundreds accuse Sterling Jewelers, which operates Kay Jewelers and Zales, of fostering an environment of \u201crampant sexual harassment and discrimination,\u201d in a class-action lawsuit.', u'  Read: 10 best-performing stocks in February include Monopoly maker Hasbro ', u'The S&P 500 index has gained 90.88 points, or 3.99% for February, with one day left in the month. Name: TD Ameritrade Holding Corporation
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n        ', u' The Trump factor: Should investors be bullish or bearish \u2014 or neither?\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Donald Trump is starting his first full week as U.S. president. Bearish investors have been out in full force, proclaiming, with high confidence, that it\u2019s time to sell stocks. At the same time, bullish gurus are saying just the opposite.   So who\u2019s right? ', u'Let\u2019s explore the answer. First, we need to develop some concepts through which we can find a sensible conclusion.   The middle road   For those who wish to know what The Arora Report is doing now, I will share with you an annotated chart that shows our actions since the election.   Please click here for the annotated chart.   The Arora Report\'s current call is to hold cash or Treasury bills (18%-28% of the portfolio) and short- to medium-term hedges (15%-25%) and very short-term hedges (15%) based on individual risk preference. (The numbers don\u2019t add up to 100% because of the mix of long exposure and hedging.)   The foregoing is derived from our adaptive ZYX Global Multi Asset Allocation Models that automatically changes itself with market conditions.   Bold promises, but can Trump deliver?   Trump has made bold promises. He has talked about achieving 4% growth in gross domestic product, massive deregulation and lower taxes for corporations. To figure out if the bulls or the bears are right, we need to know if Trump can deliver.   The bullish argument   Bullish gurus have put forward a variety of arguments. Most don\u2019t withstand rigorous analytical scrutiny, so I will not address them. Here\u2019s the main bullish argument that carries some weight.   Assuming Trump can deliver, the math is straightforward. The present consensus for earnings of the S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.23%                                                                                                                                                \xa0(often traded using the popular SPDR S&P 500 ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPY, +0.28%                                                                                                                                                ), is $133. The Arora Report has analyzed Trump\'s proposals. His proposed tax cuts could add about $13 to S&P 500 earnings. Deregulation could add another $7. If GDP were to start growing by 4% by the end of Trump\'s first term, S&P 500 earnings may reach as high as $190.   Given the potential growth in the economy if Trump succeeds, the price-to-earnings (P/E) ratio may stay in the range of 18 to 21 in spite of the Federal Reserve raising interest rates. A P/E of 20 applied to $190 in earnings leads to 3,800 in S&P 500.   That means Trump would generate a 67% return in the benchmark index. To some readers, such a projection may seem outrageous, but remember that under President Obama, the stock market returned 166%.', u' The bullish argument \u2014  part  two ', u' The bearish argument   Just like most of the bullish arguments, most of the bearish ones don\u2019t pass rigorous analytical scrutiny, so I won\u2019t address them either. Here\u2019s the main bearish argument that does carry some weight.   Assuming Trump\'s policies cause a deep recession, S&P 500 earnings could shrink to $90. The P/E multiple could dwindle to 14. That would drop the S&P 500 to 1,260, a stunning 44% decline. Bulls may think that\u2019s outlandish, but in the recession of 2008, the market fell by about one-half.   How to determine which scenario is right   As an American, I wholeheartedly wish Trump success. I also know that my fellow Americans, including those vigorously opposed to him, would rather see the new president succeed than fail for the good of the country (and the world).   Wishing, however, is not a good investment strategy. We simply need to determine the probability of Trump\'s success. Notice that I used the word \u201cprobability.\u201d My longtime readers already know what has come to be known as Nigam\'s Second Law of Investing: \u201cNo one knows with certainty what is going to happen next.\u201d Yes, that includes me. In the absence of certainty, the best way to \u201cknow\u201d is to invest based on probability.   Trump is promising major change. \u201cThere is nothing more difficult to carry out, nor more doubtful of success, nor more dangerous to handle, than to initiate a new order of things," said Niccolo Machiavelli, the Italian Renaissance philosopher. Based on my own experiences of creating change through two Inc. 500 fastest-growing companies that I founded and more than 50 ventures, I am so convinced that Machiavelli was right that his words are the opening words in my book, \u201cTheory ZYX of Successful Change Management: A Definitive Guide to Reach the Next Level.\u201d The changes I created were infinitely smaller than what Trump is trying to do.   As Trump proceeds, he is going to discover the truth that all change agents ultimately face: Those who are benefiting from the status quo will fight that change tooth and nail. Since the change has not yet happened, there are not many who have actually benefited from the change, even though they hope to. But their fervor often does not match the determination of those who want to hold on to the status quo.   My whole investing success is based on change. I follow the ZYX Change Method that consists of six screens. One of the screens is designed to judge if a change will be successful \u2014 before Wall Street finds out.   When I apply this screen to understand the probability of 4% GDP growth and the probability of a deep recession, the odds of the former are somewhat higher; still, there is simply not enough margin between the two odds to know which scenario is likely to come true.', u'Will Trump succeed? In plain English, the answer is not knowable with any reasonable confidence at this time. In my analysis, the confidence displayed by both bulls and bears is wrong.   The prudent course   The prudent course of action for investors is to take the middle road. Consider focusing on areas such as banks and brokers. Name: Pure Storage, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Pure Storage plunges after earnings\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Pure Storage Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PSTG, -0.78%                                                                                                                                                 fell as much as 11% in late trading Wednesday after reporting earnings that beat expectations but coming up short in its forecast for the current quarter. The flash-storage firm reported a net loss of $42.9 million, or 21 cents a share, on sales of $227.9 million. After adjustments for stock-based compensation and other effects, Pure Storage claimed a loss of 2 cents a share. Analysts on average expected adjusted losses of 8 cents a share on sales of $224.5 million, according to FactSet. For the current quarter, though, Pure Storage predicted revenue of $171 million to $179 million, well short of analysts\' average forecast of $201 million, according to FactSet. Pure Storage was more in line with analysts\' forecasts for the full fiscal year, predicting revenue of $975 million to $1.025 billion, while FactSet reports analysts on average projecting sales of $1.01 billion. ']

Body: [u'Stocks took only a single session to digest the ostensibly bad news about the Trump administration\'s immigration ban. They then began to rebound, led by the de facto leading index, the Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.11%                                                                                                                                                ', u' Click here for a larger version of the chart. ', u'Another negative is the action of some of the liquid glamours, those senior growth names that are beloved by institutional investors for their above-average, recession-resistant earnings growth. None.', u'Among the names is Alibaba                                                                                                                                                                                                          BABA, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                 China\u2019s biggest online retailer. Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         YouTube looks to cash in on streaming with new service | FCC won\u2019t review AT&T-Time Warner deal | What to know about Snap IPO\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Good afternoon, MarketWatch readers. Thanks for showing interest in the latest edition of the Swerve newsletter. We\u2019ve been away for a spell, but have news and updates you may have missed concerning AT&T Inc.\u2019s\xa0                                                                                                                                                                                                          T, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0proposed $85.4 billion acquisition of Time Warner Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWX, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                 as well as new streaming entrants and early acquisition talks in the publishing industry. Sign up to receive Swerve: Time Warner, AT&T and the future of media. ', u' YouTube TV: The increasingly competitive online TV streaming space got a tad more crowded this week thanks to Google\u2019s YouTube Inc., owned by Alphabet Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOGL, +0.48%                                                                                                                                                                              GOOG, +0.47%                                                                                                                                                 The dominant online video arm of Google announced it is launching a $35-a-month subscription service with a collection of 40 networks. The service includes the four major networks \u2014 ABC                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                 CBS                                                                                                                                                                                                           CBS, +0.77%                                                                                                                                                 NBC                                                                                                                                                                                                           CMCSA, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Fox                                                                                                                                                                                                           FOXA, +1.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 as well as additional cable channels such as ESPN. It\u2019s a live-streaming service in the vein of Dish Network Corp.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           DISH, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Sling TV or AT&T\u2019s DirecTV Now. Notably missing from the service are any channels for Viacom Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           VIAB, +1.47%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Time Warner, which is on the verge of being bought by AT&T. YouTube executives said the company is always in talks with content partners about coming on board, but it will be interesting to see whether Time Warner will, with YouTube TV being in direct competition with AT&T\u2019s DirecTV. YouTube also said this week that users world-wide watch a total 1 billion hours of content on YouTube every day.', u' No review from FCC: The new Chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, Ajit Pai, said this week that people should not expect the commission to play a role in reviewing the AT&T-Time Warner deal, reports The Wall Street Journal\u2019s Thomas Gryta. FCC regulatory review was expected to be the key barrier to the deal going through. However, Time Warner and AT&T have apparently structured the deal so no airwave licenses are changing hands, which is one of the key triggers for FCC review. Time Warner recently sold its Atlanta TV station to Meredith Corp. for $70 million, which, according to the Journal, removed a significant factor in prompting FCC review.', u' Deal talk: There\u2019s chatter of possible movement in the publishing and media and entertainment industries. Shares of Time Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TIME, +1.57%                                                                                                                                                \xa0were up 7% on Wednesday following a Bloomberg report saying the company is seeking acquisition offers by next week. The board apparently wants to gauge the value of the company and determine whether it makes more sense to sell the entire company or specific magazine titles. In the TV world, Sinclair Broadcast Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SBGI, +0.89%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has approached Tribune Media Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TRCO, +0.67%                                                                                                                                                \xa0to engage in deal talks, according to Reuters. Shares of Sinclair were up more than 4%, while Tribune shares were up more than 7%. ', u' Snap IPO: Snap Inc., the parent company of popular messaging app Snapchat, is set to price its shares Wednesday night and begin trading Thursday morning. Here are six things to know about the company ahead of its initial public offering. ', u' Don\u2019t miss: Snapchat still a mystery to investors, and that\u2019s a problem for Snap IPO ', u' And the winner is...: Lions Gate Entertainment Corp.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           LGF.A, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0movie musical darling \u201cLa La Land\u201d won the top award for best... actually, independent art-house film \u201cMoonlight\u201d from A24 took home the Oscar for best picture, in a dramatic twist blunder. A partner from PwC, the trusted partner of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, mixed up the award envelopes and the wrong movie title was originally read for best picture. In other news, Amazon.com Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.64%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Netflix Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NFLX, -0.65%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 took home their first Oscars in a watershed moment for the streaming industry in Hollywood. This year\u2019s Oscars broadcast was the lowest in nine years.', u' Also read: Why the Oscars probably won\u2019t fire accounting firm PwC over best picture snafu ', u' Shaking things up: Barstool Sports, a scrappy, satirical and irreverent website covering sports and news, is aiming to become a bigger player in the digital media landscape with a broader audience. More than a year after receiving an investment from Peter Chernin\u2019s Chernin Group and bringing on a new CEO, the brand is growing and taking on bigger risks, recently joining with Comedy Central for live broadcasts during the Super Bowl. Barstool Sports was the No. 1 show on the network across the week that it aired.', u' Thanks for reading Swerve. If you\u2019re interested in staying abreast of the AT&T\u2013Time Warner deal and in keeping an eye on the future of media, sign up for the newsletter. For critical information before the markets open each morning, sign up for MarketWatch\u2019s Need to Know, sent daily at 7:30 a.m. Eastern time. ', u' Follow Trey Williams on Twitter: @Trey3Williams, and write to him at twilliams@marketwatch.com ']
