Name: Pandora Media, Inc.
Article: 13 : [u'\r\n         Pandora gains after layoffs, which is just silly\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Pandora                                                                                                                                                                                                           P, -0.65%                                                                                                                                                \xa0managed to cloud the bad news by also reporting that it beat its own forecast for revenue in the fourth quarter, but investors should remember that Pandora\u2019s guidance for the quarter was well below Wall Street expectations. In fact, Pandora had to reduce its full-year revenue guidance in both July and October, so it is about time the company managed to exceed repeatedly reduced expectations.', u'According to FactSet, 50% of analysts on Wall Street rate Pandora a buy, 41% rate it a hold, and 9% rate it underperform or sell. In the past year, there has been a lot of speculation that the company would be acquired, with Sirius XM Holdings                                                                                                                                                                                                           SIRI, -1.73%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 often cited as the most likely contender. But comments by a Sirius executive at a Citigroup conference during CES last week were interpreted as throwing cold water on those hopes, and fueled a 4% drop in Pandora\u2019s shares.', u'Unless investors want to bet that Pandora will be acquired, they should consider staying on the sidelines, waiting to see if the company can reverse a decline in its user base and be the first to make a profitable business out of internet music, especially after Friday\u2019s gains.']

Name: Amphastar Pharmaceuticals, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Amphastar Pharma stock plummets 16% after FDA fails to approve nasal spray for opioid overdoses\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Amphastar Pharmaceuticals Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMPH, -0.30%                                                                                                                                                 shares plummeted 15.8% in morning trade Tuesday after the company said the Food and Drug Administration failed to approve its nasal spray for opioid overdoses. The FDA said the company needed to resolve various issues, including studying users\' ability to understand and administer the product correctly and evaluation of the device itself, according to Amphastar, which currently sells the opioid overdose treatment naloxone in pre-filled syringes. Chief Executive Officer Dr. Jack Zhang said the company will work with the FDA to address the regulator\'s concerns. Naloxone nasal sprays are seen as the easiest to use in an emergency situation, and amid an opioid crisis across the U.S., prices have spiked. Amphastar shares have dropped 22.0% over the last three months, compared with a 7.6% rise in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                 ']

Name: Intuit Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Why more people are delaying filing their taxes this year\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of Intuit Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           INTU, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and H&R Block                                                                                                                                                                                                           HRB, -0.51%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 fell recently after Intuit, which sells tax-preparation software including TurboTax, issued a profit warning and said that the tax season is \u201cforming more slowly than usual.\u201d The company cited Internal Revenue Service data which said total tax return volume through Jan. 27 was down 33% from a year ago.', u' Why so many Americans are waiting to file ', u'This year, the IRS started accepting taxes filed online Jan. 23, and the final deadline to submit taxes is April 18, just after the traditional April 15 deadline. That\u2019s one possible reason filing could be off to a slow start. ', u'It\u2019s also possible that because of comments President Donald Trump made during his campaign and as recently as this week about tax reform, some filers are waiting to see if anything will change before they file.', u'For example, Trump has advocated for lower tax rates for most of the top tax brackets, so some higher-income individuals may be hoping they would get that benefit this year by waiting to book certain income. ', u'Tax changes could happen shortly into Trump\u2019s presidency. But any such changes Trump makes in 2017 would impact 2017 taxes at the earliest, said Howard Gleckman, a senior fellow at the Tax Policy Center, a joint venture of social and economic policy group Urban Institute and research group Brookings Institution based in Washington, D.C. ', u' See also: This chart shows how Republicans and Democrats feel about their money right now ', u'General uncertainty about taxes and other topics in the tense political climate may also contribute to some filers\u2019 anxiety, and as a result, cause them to file later, said Linda Hagen, an assistant professor of marketing at the University of Southern California\u2019s Marshall School of Business. Studies have shown a link between procrastination and anxiety \u2014 something sometimes confused with laziness. \u201cI would not be surprised if people worry about taxes and money a lot more at the moment and feel a greater sense of uncertainty around it because there is a good chance things are going to change,\u201d she said.', u'However, a more likely reason for the delay is a law enacted in late December 2015, which is impacting 2016 taxes, Gleckman said. It mandates that the IRS cannot issue a refund on tax returns claiming the Earned Income Tax Credit or Additional Child Tax Credit until Feb. 15. If those filing are aware of that law, it may be a reason they waited, he said.', u'What\u2019s more, knowing one\u2019s refund will be lower could be another factor that adds to procrastination: People who expect to receive higher refunds tend to file their returns earlier than those who expect smaller refunds, a 2015 survey of about 1,000 tax filers by Georgetown University\u2019s Institute for Consumer Research found. Similarly, people who expect to owe a smaller amount of money file earlier than those expecting to pay larger amounts. ', u' How to convince yourself to file earlier ', u'The more time you have to file, the less stressful (in theory) it should be. There is plenty of time remaining to file, which could offset initial trends in the remaining weeks until the deadline. The amount of receipts that are self-prepared and filed electronically actually seems to be growing, as do visits to IRS.gov, according to IRS data. ', u'Those who want to file earlier should think about what types of things motivate them, she said. For some, it may be thinking about a specific splurge they\u2019d like to buy with their refund, or debt they\u2019d like to wipe out, she said. For others, it may be a reward that reinforces their positive feelings about taking control of their lives and acting responsibly, such as buying items for their home office. Financial experts recommend saving money from tax returns instead of spending frivolously, but for those with larger tax returns, it may be possible to save and still buy a reasonably-priced treat as a reward. ']

Name: Nordstrom, Inc.
Article: 11 : [u'\r\n        ', u' U.S. stocks\u2019 direction will depend on the dominance of either a \u2018good\u2019 or \u2018bad\u2019 Trump\r\n    ']
Body: [u'He even will give Wall Street a special gift by delaying or eliminating the fiduciary rule, under which companies that manage retirement assets have to act in the best interests of clients, not themselves. And he talks about building $1 trillion worth of new infrastructure, perhaps paid for by tax breaks, tolls or private-public partnerships. That is the \u201cpro-growth,\u201d or \u201cgood,\u201d Trump.', u'The second Donald Trump shuts down immigration from seven Muslim-majority countries that have histories of, or ties to, terrorism, including U.S. green-card and visa holders. He conducts raids on hundreds of allegedly illegal immigrants, many of whom have criminal records. He talks loudly about building a Great Wall on the Mexican border, and boasts he could bring the cost down even as he pledges to make Mexico foot the bill, perhaps through a 20% import tax.', u'He bullies U.S. CEOs to keep jobs in the U.S. as he threatens to impose a border tax on goods manufactured abroad and imported back into the U.S. (Imagine the howls of outrage if a Democratic president, like Barack Obama or Hillary Clinton, had said that!) He repeatedly promises to exit or renegotiate the North American Free Trade Agreement, and doesn\u2019t shy away from talk of trade wars with Mexico or China. That is the \u201ceconomic nationalist,\u201d or \u201cbad,\u201d Trump.', u'The \u201cgood\u201d Trump has prevailed, so far, for investors. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.23%                                                                                                                                                 is up 9.9% since the election. On Friday, the S&P 500, the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                 and the Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.41%                                                                                                                                                 \u2014 hit all-time highs, and the Russell 2000 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.41%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 set a record on Wednesday. The market value of the S&P 500 exceeded $20 trillion for the first time ever. ', u'Last week, stocks rallied when the president said: \u201cWe\u2019re going to \u2026 lower the overall tax burden on American businesses big league \u2026 We\u2019re going to be announcing something, I would say, over the next two or three weeks.\u201d But on Jan. 30, they sold off after the chaotic roll-out of his travel ban. ', u'His comments have hurt individual stocks and sectors most. On Jan. 16, shares of German auto makers fell sharply after Trump threatened them with a 35% U.S. import tariff. The stock price of Constellation Brands                                                                                                                                                                                                           STZ, +0.12%                                                                                                                                                 a stupendous performer that sells Mexican beers Corona and Modelo, at one point was down more than 10% since the election. Health-care stocks sold off when he said the U.S. needed more competitive drug pricing. Shares of Lockheed-Martin Corp.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           LMT, -0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0stock fell twice in December and once in January, after Trump slammed pricing of the F-35 fighter. Last week, Nordstrom Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           JWN, -0.86%                                                                                                                                                \xa0stock apparently broke the Trump tweet curse after it fell and then rebounded when the president criticized the upscale retailer for dropping his daughter Ivanka\u2019s poorly selling clothing line.', u'Markets are a lot higher since Election Day, and some of these stocks have bounced back nicely after getting Trumped. But they speak to a risk that the president may not be able to get all the \u201cgood\u201d stuff Wall Street wants, such as tax reform and infrastructure spending, both of which must overcome significant obstacles and well-organized interest groups and opposition in Congress, while enacting the \u201cbad\u201d stuff Wall Street hates.', u'Problem is, many Trump voters like that \u201cbad\u201d stuff \u2014 the Wall, immigration restrictions, even protectionism \u2014 while Wall Street\u2019s traditional Republican agenda leaves them cold. Otherwise we might have had a President Jeb Bush or John Kasich. So, although Trump\u2019s agenda so far has been a boon to Wall Street, don\u2019t expect him to \u201cmoderate\u201d his views or \u201ccome around\u201d on the things his supporters love and Wall Street hates.', u'With stocks at all-time highs and the CBOE Volatility index                                                                                                                                                                                                           VIX, -1.44%                                                                                                                                                \xa0near multiyear lows, complacency reigns supreme. I\u2019m still bullish for now, but a lot will depend on whether we see the best of Trumps or the worst of Trumps in the months ahead.', u' Howard R. Gold is a MarketWatch columnist and founder and editor of GoldenEgg Investing, which offers exclusive market commentary and simple, low-cost, low-risk retirement investing plans. Follow him on Twitter @howardrgold. ']

Name: Zynga Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Snap IPO boils down to one question: Do you trust Evan Spiegel?\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Buying shares in Snap                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +7.56%                                                                                                                                                 amounts to a risky bet on the two co-founders, Chief Executive Evan Spiegel, 26, and Chief Technology Officer Robert Murphy, 28. The two former Stanford University fraternity brothers have a combined 88.6% of the voting power in the company, which will not be diluted because the shares issued in the IPO will have absolutely no voting power.', u'While many Silicon Valley companies have established two tiers of stock to ensure founders and early investors maintain control of public companies, most still offer some sort of voting power at IPO time. For instance, Facebook Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, +0.43%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Chief Executive Mark Zuckerberg\u2019s preferred shares carried 10 votes apiece while shares sold in the IPO received only one. At Alphabet Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOGL, +0.41%                                                                                                                                                                              GOOG, +0.42%                                                                                                                                                 Google\u2019s parent company, according to its most recent proxy, co-founders Larry Page and Sergey Brin have a combined voting power of 52.9%, but investors with Class A and Class B common stock can still make a statement with votes and shareholder proposals. ', u' Read also: Six things we know about Snap ahead of the IPO ', u'The dark side of this kind of structure can be seen at struggling Viacom Inc.,                                                                                                                                                                                                           VIA, +1.26%                                                                                                                                                 where the ailing, 93-year-old controlling shareholder, Sumner Redstone, has been the center of legal battles over his mental capacity. In Silicon Valley, take a look at Zynga Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ZNGA, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                 which gave Mark Pincus a supersize 70 votes for each of his preferred shares and investors could only watch as he led the social mobile-game company into a tailspin.', u'\u201cThe founder(s) is usually worried about losing control down the line and wants to obtain supervoting rights with their shares via this dual class common stock system,\u201d wrote Ryan Roberts, a partner at Roberts Foster LLC, in his blog, Startup Lawyer last December. Roberts added, though, that a dual-class stock structure \u201ccan set off a red flag to a potential investor or hire that the founder already thinks he or she is Mark Zuckerberg.\u201d ', u'Indeed, Spiegel has been alternately compared with Zuckerberg, Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.85%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 co-founder Steve Jobs and Microsoft Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MSFT, +1.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0co-founder Bill Gates. He has commonalities with all of these tech founders and legends. Like all three, he dropped out of college, but in Spiegel\u2019s case it was Stanford University, not Harvard or Reed College. Like Gates, Spiegel is the son of a lawyer, but grew up in the swanky Pacific Palisades area of Los Angeles. ', u'Like Zuckerberg, Spiegel had a major falling out with another co-founder and settled a lawsuit over his role in the founding of Snap. Zuckerberg\u2019s snide instant messages about how he decided to found Facebook would end up in a deposition and were played out in the movie \u201cThe Social Network.\u201d Spiegel made graphic and derogatory comments about partying and women in an email while he was in a Stanford fraternity, for which he would later apologize. ', u' See also: The two views of Snap \u2014 an app that has peaked or a platform set to blossom? ', u' See also: How Snap stacks up against Facebook and Twitter ', u'Snap\u2019s executive team and board does include an interesting mix of media, finance and tech experience, but there is not one executive position that seems equivalent to a president or COO role. Chairman Michael Lynton was, until very recently, the CEO of Sony Entertainment Inc., a Sony Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNE, +0.38%                                                                                                                                                \xa0subsidiary, stepping down from that position last month after more than 12 years so he could focus on his position at Snap, according to an email he sent employees.', u'Another high-profile executive is Imran Khan, who has been Snap\u2019s chief strategy officer since 2015, after more than a decade on Wall Street. Two of its highest ranking executives with the most credentials in tech are Timothy Sehn, its senior vice president of engineering, who spent a decade at Amazon.com Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.57%                                                                                                                                                \xa0before joining Snap in 2013. Steven Horowitz, vice president of engineering, joined from Google\u2019s former Motorola Mobility business, right after it was sold to Lenovo in early 2015, and also has worked at a range of other tech giants.', u'The company\u2019s road show video was released on Friday and initially features the two founders, especially the charismatic Spiegel, talking about what Snapchat is and how with it, the camera has become the primary input for the smartphone. Khan is the third Snap executive to be featured, talking about its innovation engine, followed by Chief Financial Officer Andrew Vallero, who notes that Snap is in its second phrase of monetization, having only started selling ads in mid-2015.', u'Spiegel doesn\u2019t seem to believe those executives are serving that COO function, though. In 2015, at the Re/code conference, he was asked in an interview about management turnover at the time, and if he was looking for a partner such as Zuckerberg found in Sandberg, to join him at Snap. Spiegel said, \u201cI have a great partner named Bobby, who started the business with me.\u201d', u' Reuters reported, according to sources, that no investors asked executives about the corporate governance issues during a big roadshow meeting Tuesday with over 400 investors in New York. Spiegel also reportedly brushed aside concerns about Snapchat\u2019s slowing growth. ', u' Read also: The math Snapchat doesn\u2019t want you to see ', u'The company recently sent an email to employees that they too will be able to sell their shares 150 days after the offering, according to The Information, which was not noted in the company\u2019s latest S-1. ', u'Just as many are divided in their views on Snap, investors may initially be divided on Spiegel. Is he a spoiled child of privilege who will make an initial fistful of money in the IPO, while investors with no votes are left holding the bag? Or is he a visionary building a major new messaging platform, with a possible future in augmented reality, among other things?']

Name: Harley-Davidson, Inc.
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         Harley-Davidson shares dip after company reports Q4 earnings below expectations\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Harley-Davidson Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HOG, -0.91%                                                                                                                                                 shares fell nearly 2% in premarket trade on Tuesday after the motorcycle manufacturer reported fourth-quarter earnings that fell short of Wall Street expectations. Net income for the quarter came in at $47.2 million, or 27 cents per share, compared with $42.2 million, or 22 cents during the same quarter a year ago. FactSet\'s per-share earnings consensus was for 31 cents. Sales hit $933.0 million during the quarter, down from $1.0 billion in the year-earlier period. Consolidated revenue was $1.1 billion for the quarter. FactSet had forecast sales to hit $977.0 million. Harley-Davidson said it expects full-year 2017 margins to be in line with 2016 and shipments of motorcycles to be flat to down compared with 2016. Shares of Harley-Davidson are up 45% in the trailing 12-month period, while the S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                 are up more than 17%.']

Name: General Electric Company
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         GE expands its German 3-D metal printer Concept Laser with plans for bigger headquarters\r\n    ']
Body: [u'General Electric Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GE, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                 said Wednesday it is aggressively expanding German 3-D metal printing company Concept Laser GmbH, in which it purchased a 75% stake in mid-December. GE has increased the number of employees at the company to 244 from 200 and is expected to reach 350 to 400 people by early 2018. Most of the new hires will be in engineering and technicians, GE said in a statement. GE is planning a big expansion of the company\'s headquarters in Lichtenfels with new space planned for manufacturing, product development, testing and administration. The company also has operations in the U.S., in Grapevine, Texas, and in China. GE has been on a buying spree of 3-D metal printing companies of late. In 2016, it acquired Sweden\'s Arcam AB and Germany\'s SLM Solutions Group AG for a combined $1.4 billion. Those moves were aimed at pushing the company into 3-D printing as a way to make aircraft components and other parts. 3-D printing involves using digital designs and modeling software with laser technology to create parts that are usually lighter and more durable than traditionally manufactured parts because they need less welding and machining. But much of the promise of the market is the extra design possibilities for engineers. GE shares were flat Wednesday, and are down 5.5% in the year so far. The Ark Invest\'s 3D Printing ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           PRNT, -0.76%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 5% in the same time frame, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 5.7%.']

Body: [u'Yet energy is the absolute worst performer among the S&P 500\u2019s 11 sectors this year. UPDATE', u' Insider vote of confidence ', u'Let\u2019s start with the insiders. I\u2019ve tracked insiders for clues about the market for decades, and their buying is a core part of how I come up with a short list of stocks to research for my stock letter Brush Up on Stocks. Two key lessons on insiders support a bullish call on energy now. ', u'That looks like the case with energy stocks right now. Over the past few weeks there\u2019s been significant insider buying in over a dozen energy stocks, including Halliburton (I\u2019ll list the others, below.)', u' Inventories rising ', u'It takes six weeks or more for oil to arrive by boat to the U.S., the market of last resort for energy. But as it did, U.S. inventories began to build this year, unsettling investors. \u201cThe market looks at the big build up in U.S. inventories and gets nervous,\u201d says Jonathan Waghorn who helps manage the Guinness Atkinson Global Energy Fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           GAGEX, -0.80%                                                                                                                                                 Investors are still shellshocked after a U.S. inventory glut helped suppress oil prices and crush energy stocks two years ago. So any sign of a repeat has them selling. ', u' U.S. producers: They\u2019re baack! ', u'Thanks to higher energy prices, U.S. shale producers are back. They\u2019re deploying a lot more rigs. The rig count is back up over 600 compared with a low of 316 in May 2016 \u2014 and they are fracking a lot more. This also brings back bad memories of hefty losses for energy investors. ', u'OPEC, for example, will probably remain disciplined on production because of national budget constraints in Saudi Arabia, says John Groton, director of equity research at Thrivent Financial, who has followed the energy space for years. He thinks Saudi Arabia needs oil in the upper $60-per barrel range to balance its national budget. Name: Fitbit, Inc.
Article: 10 : [u'\r\n         Fitbit earnings to reveal an abysmal holiday quarter\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Last month, Fitbit warned that it only sold 6.5 million devices for the fourth quarter, which would amount to revenue in the range of $572 million to $580 million, compared with the company\u2019s previous guidance range of $725 million to $750 million. It also said at the time that it would miss its earnings guidance, and lowered its non-GAAP earnings-per-share estimate to a range of a 51-cent loss to a 56-cent loss, from a profit of 14 cents to 18 cents previously. ', u' Also see:  Fitbit may have stumbled, but wearable craze isn\u2019t dead yet ', u' Here\u2019s what to expect: ', u' Earnings: Sell-side analysts surveyed by FactSet expect Fitbit                                                                                                                                                                                                           FIT, -1.87%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 to report a loss of 54 cents a share, compared with a profit of 35 cents in the year-earlier period. Contributors to Estimize, a software platform that uses crowdsourcing from hedge-fund executives, brokerages and buy-side analysts to predict earnings, expect Fitbit to perform slightly better, with a projected 39-cent loss. In the past few quarters, Fitbit has come in slightly shy of the Estimize consensus estimate but ahead of the FactSet one. ', u' Revenue: The company is expected to report revenue of $576 million, compared with $712 million in the year-earlier period, according to the FactSet consensus estimate. Estimize is forecasting Fitbit sales of $591 million. Fitbit marginally missed both revenue numbers last quarter, but it topped the FactSet consensus estimate in every other quarter since its 2015 IPO.', u' Read also:  Fitbit and GoPro woes show hardware is still a risky investment ', u' Stock reaction: Shares of Fitbit have vastly underperformed the S&P 500 both in the past three months and the past year. The stock has declined by 30% in the three months since its last earnings report, compared with an increase of 7.5% for the index. They\u2019re down more than 61% from a year ago, compared with a 23% increase for the S&P 500. During the quarter, the stock plunged to an all-time low following the company\u2019s bleak profit warning. The average rating on Fitbit\u2019s stock is the equivalent to hold, while the average price target is $7.20. ', u' What to watch for: Fitbit\u2019s tumultuous past few quarters have weighed heavily on its stock price, even as the company has made moves in recent months to expand its software products to try and adapt an Apple Inc.-like App Store model that may help to loosen its dependency on hardware hits.']

Name: iShares 20+ Year Treasury Bond ETF
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n        ', u' New England Patriots are a beacon of hope for stock market bears\r\n    ']
Body: [u' \u201cJust remember, once you\u2019re over the hill, you begin to pick up speed.\u201d \u2014 Arthur Schopenhauer ', u'First, from a long-term perspective, volatility is likely to be much higher for the S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                 and returns much lower. Charlie Bilello, our director of research here at Pension Partners, did a great post on our blog showing that the U.S. stock market\u2019s CAPE ratio (cyclically adjusted price-to-earnings ratio) is in the 94th percentile dating to 1928. It will be hard to make America great again when history suggests where we are now isn\u2019t exactly the setup for being No. 1. This isn\u2019t based on emotion, but fact. Volatility                                                                                                                                                                                                           VXX, +0.37%                                                                                                                                                 on a forward-looking basis tends to be much higher where we are now \u2014 from a valuation perspective.', u'Now, am I saying stocks are going to crash or enter a big bear market? No. But between valuations where they are, and the fact that bond yields                                                                                                                                                                                                           TLT, +0.52%                                                                                                                                                 are having a hard time pushing up much more than they have, bears finally have some hope that they may be right about the future being not as rosy as bulls think it will be. ', u' Michael A. Gayed, CFA, co-author of four award-winning papers that challenge market efficiency, is chief investment strategist and co-portfolio manager at Pension Partners LLC, an investment adviser that manages mutual funds and separate accounts. ']

Name: Intel Corporation
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Chip sales have best monthly growth in over six years\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The semiconductor market has gotten off to a good 2017, with the best monthly growth in over six years, boosted by strong sales growth in China, according to data provided by the Semiconductor Industry Association. Global chip sales jumped 13.9% from a year ago to $30.6 billion in January, the largest year-over-year growth since November 2010, SIA said. Sales to China soared 20.5%, followed by 13.3% growth in the Americas, 12.3% in Japan and 4.8% in Europe. "The global semiconductor industry is off to a strong and encouraging start to 2017, posting its highest-ever January sales and largest year-to-year sales increase in more than six years," said SIA Chief Executive John Neuffer. The PHLX Semiconductor Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SOX, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                 has rallied 11% over the past three months, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.01%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 7.3%. Among individual stocks, Intel Corp.\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           INTC, +0.40%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 3% over the past three months and Advanced Micro Devices Inc.\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMD, +0.10%                                                                                                                                                 has run up 38%.']

Name: Cabot Oil & Gas Corporation
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         Energy companies are about ready to loosen the purse strings\r\n    ']
Body: [u' See also: 13 \u2018black swans\u2019 that could hit oil investors in 2017 (including Elon Musk) ', u' To face the precipitous price declines, companies have cut their expenses, laid off employees, and sold so-called \u201cnon-core\u201d assets. Name: Dick's Sporting Goods Inc
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         These stocks are outrunning the bull market with quadruple-digit gains\r\n    ']
Body: [u'And no one\u2019s in the mood to go chasing Snapchat\u2019s parent                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +2.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0either, it seems. The Snap stock is down over 6% in early action, on top of Monday\u2019s 12% drop.', u'Until then, here\u2019s some bull-market birthday trivia (squabble among yourselves about the date) to pass the time. That\u2019s via our chart of the day, which offers a look at the S&P 500 companies that have performed best \u2014 and survived on the index \u2014 since its bottom in 2009. ', u'At the top is drugmaker Incyte                                                                                                                                                                                                           INCY, -5.25%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, which dazzles with a roughly 6,455% climb from the market\u2019s March 9, 2009 low. Just behind it, equipment-rental giant United Rentals                                                                                                                                                                                                           URI, -3.98%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, which scored around a 4,183% gain. Airlines like American                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAL, -3.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, as well as Amazon                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, -1.61%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and Starbucks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SBUX, -0.48%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, made the cut with quadruple-digit gains. ', u'As for the worst-performing S&P 500 survivors, these are littered with energy names such as Southwestern Energy                                                                                                                                                                                                           SWN, -2.74%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and First Solar                                                                                                                                                                                                           FSLR, -4.28%                                                                                                                                                 , each off around 70%. Check out that full list here.', u' Also:  The real winners of the bull market? ETFs and passive investing ', u'The Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -1.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -1.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, -1.83%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have opened lower. Elsewhere, oil prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0are up, gold                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCJ7, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is off and the British pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.3045%                                                                                                                                                \xa0hit a 7-week low against the dollar.', u'See the Market Snapshot column for the latest action.', u'In the meantime, check out the heady run for one of the world\u2019s rarest precious metals. ', u'The bets against cocoa, which has been battered by bumper crops and health-conscious consumers cutting down on chocolate snacks , are the biggest they\u2019ve been in more than 12 years, says Sjuggerud. Bets have been that big only three other times. In one of those, prices soared 250%, from the low of 2000 to the 2002 high.', u'He said cocoa\u2019s not a screaming buy yet, but it\u2019s on his radar and his finger is on the trigger. Read the full post here.', u' Pharma and biotechs are slumping after President Donald Trump sent this tweet.', u'Michael\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           MIK, -1.51%                                                                                                                                                 is up 7% after an earnings beat and upbeat outook, while Dick\u2019s Sporting Goods                                                                                                                                                                                                           DKS, -1.36%                                                                                                                                                 is headed the other way on its results. Brown-Forman                                                                                                                                                                                                           BF.A, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0also reported. Urban Outfitters                                                                                                                                                                                                           URBN, -2.59%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and H&R Block                                                                                                                                                                                                           HRB, -2.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are due after the close. ', u'Facebook\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, -1.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0under fire in the U.K. for failing to remove child exploitation images. When BBC journalists working on the story sent Facebook examples of the images, the company reported them to the police.', u'IBM                                                                                                                                                                                                           IBM, -1.04%                                                                                                                                                 and Salesforce.com                                                                                                                                                                                                           CRM, -1.63%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 are merging their AI technologies in a bid to boost sales of the data that\u2019s being harvested.', u'GM                                                                                                                                                                                                           GM, -3.25%                                                                                                                                                \xa0will ax about 1,100 workers at its Michigan SUV plant, the latest in a string of job cuts.', u' Read: The workers that are in hot demand, don\u2019t need a college degree and make nearly 6 figures ', u'On its heels were Canada, the U.K., Germany and Japan, in that order. The U.S. is No. 7. See the full list here. ', u' Read: Sam Eisenstadt, a supreme forecaster, has bad news for stock investors ', u'\u201cThe immigrants made the choice to come to America. They saw this country as a land of opportunity. In contrast, slaves were forced here against their will and lost all their opportunities. We continue to live with that legacy.\u201d \u2014 That was Ben Carson, Secretary of Housing and Urban Development, clarifying those comments likening immigrants to slaves on his Facebook page.', u'That iconic bronze bull statue on Wall Street has a new pal. Girl power!', u'Wisconsin hosts the cheesiest contest ever. ', u'Check out MarketWatch\u2019s sister site Moneyish, where you can meet the \u2018marijuana moms\u2019 and learn how to exit a bad Tinder date from an FBI hostage negotiator.', u' Need to Know starts early and is updated until the opening bell, but sign up here to get it delivered once to your email box. Be sure to check the Need to Know item. The emailed version will be sent out at about 7:30 a.m. Eastern. ', u' Or Follow MarketWatch on Twitter or Facebook.']

Name: Caterpillar, Inc.
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         Stocks retreat from records, but Snap skyrockets in debut\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 112.58 points, or 0.5%, to close at 21,002.97 as Caterpillar Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CAT, -0.38%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares slumped 4.3% as federal agents searched the company\u2019s offices. The Wall Street Journal said the search appeared to be related to an investigation into tax issues involving one of the company\u2019s Swiss subsidiaries.', u'The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slid 14.04 points, or 0.6%, to end at 2,381.92. The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 42.81 points, or 0.7%, to finish at 5,861.22.', u'Shares in Snap Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +6.57%                                                                                                                                                \xa0jumped 44% in their highly anticipated debut, the culmination of the biggest initial public offering since 2014. Because Snap is not a component of the Dow or S&P 500, and because it trades on the New York Stock Exchange as opposed to the Nasdaq, it didn\'t have a direct impact on the major indexes. However, the strong reception could reaffirm the upbeat sentiment that has helped to underpin the recent record run of the market.', u'Snap\u2019s strong IPO has already pushed the company\u2019s market cap above Twitter Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWTR, +0.65%                                                                                                                                                 Research shows that people using Snap have been steadily rising while growth in Twitter users has stagnated over the past couple of years, according to Bespoke Investment Group (see chart below).', u' Read more: Snap IPO\u2014Why it may be the next Facebook ', u'Meanwhile, Attorney General Jeff Sessions held a news conference after the market\u2019s close, announcing he would recuse himself from any investigation into Trump\u2019s campaign following reports that he had met with the Russian ambassador to the U.S. ahead of his confirmation hearing. The Democrats have called for his resignation for his failure to disclose the meetings. ', u' Economic news: Jobless claims fell by 19,000 to 223,000, setting a fresh postrecession low and illustrating the strength of the U.S. labor market.', u'Gradual interest-rate hikes are likely to be appropriate soon, Fed Gov. Lael Brainard said late Wednesday.', u'Analysts said investors will be looking for more hints on the Fed\u2019s plans for interest rates from the central bank\u2019s chairwoman, Janet Yellen, who will deliver a speech on Friday.', u' Stock movers: Shares in Shake Shack Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SHAK, -1.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 2.6% a day after the burger chain\u2019s 2017 revenue outlook fell short of expectations.', u' Box Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BOX, -1.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sank 8.1% after the file-sharing company late Wednesday predicted the current quarter wouldn\'t live up to analysts\u2019 expectation. ', u' Kroger Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KR, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 4.3% despite posting quarterly results that topped Wall Street\u2019s forecasts late Wednesday.', u' Abercrombie & Fitch Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                            ANF, -3.81%                                                                                                                                                 shares soared 14% despite posting weaker-than-expected earnings. ', u' Barnes & Noble Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BKS, -1.42%                                                                                                                                                \xa0skidded 8.6% after the book retailer posted earnings that missed expectations. ', u' Monster Beverage Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MNST, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0jumped 13% after the energy-drink maker posted higher earnings and announced a new $500 million stock repurchase plan late Wednesday.', u' Other markets: European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.69%                                                                                                                                                were mixed, while Asian markets closed mostly higher. A key dollar index                                                                                                                                                                                                          DXY, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                 added to the prior day\u2019s gain. Oil futures                                                                                                                                                                                                          CLJ7, -1.49%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell more than 2% while gold futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCJ7, +0.27%                                                                                                                                                \xa0settled lower.', u' --Victor Reklaitis contributed to this article.  ']

Trump is also a stickler for costs, and he\u2019s already called out Lockheed Martin                                                                                                                                                                                                           LMT, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                 and Boeing                                                                                                                                                                                                           BA, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                 for what they charge the government. So it\u2019s tough to know which companies might do well, and which ones might get hurt by Trump\u2019s concerns about costs. For now, it\u2019s probably better to stay away from this group, as a Trump play. ', u' Infrastructure plays ', u'This group is another tough one. Yes, our nation\u2019s infrastructure is crumbling. You see this all the time when you drive around. And Trump\u2019s plan to boost infrastructure spending would no doubt help this space, especially materials companies like Vulcan Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           VMC, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                 Martin Marietta Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           MLM, -0.81%                                                                                                                                                 and Summit Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           SUM, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                 ', u' At the time of publication, Michael Brush had no positions in any stocks mentioned in this column. Brush has suggested DG, AMZN, DIS, BRK.B, PNC, JPM, DHI, NKE, XOM, GILD, CELG, COP, HES, CMG and GOOGL in his stock newsletter, Brush Up on Stocks. Brush is a Manhattan-based financial writer who has covered business for the New York Times and The Economist group, and he attended Columbia Business School in the Knight-Bagehot program.  ']

Name: Broadcom Limited
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Five unpopular, but prudent, things for investors to do near Dow 20,000\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Two charts ', u'The charts compare five currently over-owned stocks in five sectors of the S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                 The first is a daily chart of the period since Donald Trump\'s election. The second is a monthly chart since the start of the current bull market.', u' Please click here for the annotated chart comparing five popular stocks in five popular sectors since Donald Trump\'s election. ', u' Please click here for the annotated chart comparing five popular stocks in five popular sectors since the start of the current bull market. ', u'The popular stocks that will help you understand the actions described below are Martin Marietta                                                                                                                                                                                                           MLM, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                 Pfizer                                                                                                                                                                                                           PFE, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                 General Mills                                                                                                                                                                                                           GIS, -1.49%                                                                                                                                                 Duke Energy Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DUK, +0.59%                                                                                                                                                 and Nvidia                                                                                                                                                                                                           NVDA, +1.55%                                                                                                                                                 These stocks are compared with the S&P 500 ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPY, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                 in the charts. If you are uninitiated in inter-market analysis, these charts may at first seem intimidating. I suggest you look at them for a few minutes, and you will see several insights jumping out at you.', u' Over-owned ', u'Some readers may say that the five stocks listed above have good fundamentals and technicals. Name: Intel Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         AMD investors get spooked by Ryzen\u2019s mixed reviews \r\n    ']
Body: [u'AMD\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMD, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                 largest investor even dropped a chunk of shares, as a regulatory filing showed Mubadala Development Company PJSC sold 45 million shares with a market value of $613 million. The sovereign-wealth fund of Abu Dhabi has been an investor in AMD since 2007 and still retains a roughly 10% stake of AMD\u2019s 941 million shares. ', u'AMD\u2019s shares closed down 6.3% at $13.03 on Friday. Still, the stock is up 52.8% in the past three months and 428.7% in the past year, far outperforming the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and the S&P 500 index.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.01%                                                                                                                                                \xa0', u'Since the company\u2019s much anticipated launch of its Ryzen chips for desktop PCs and video gaming, several reviews have come out in the trade and gaming press that seem mixed. One much quoted review is from PC Gamer, which wrote that \u201cAMD\u2019s gaming performance during my initial testing is far lower than expected in a variety of titles.\u2026Based on the CPU-centric testing, I expected Ryzen to be right in the mix, matching [Intel Corp.\u2019s] Broadwell-E. But while that happens in a few games, in others it comes up well short, sometimes by 20 % or more.\u201d', u'However, a review on Guru3d.com said the new AMD chips offer a lot of value for the money, as AMD\u2019s highest-end chip is priced 50% below Intel\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           INTC, +0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. ', u' Read also: AMD plans to find Zen and challenge Intel ', u'Comparisons based on price may not last long, though. Another tech publication recently reported, as some investors have anticipated, that several of Intel\u2019s chips have received \u201cmassive price cuts\u201d just ahead of AMD\u2019s Ryzen launch, citing slashed prices found on Micro Center website.', u'AMD CEO Lisa Su appeared Friday morning on CNBC and was asked about the chips\u2019 performance and negative reviews. She said that in most applications\u2014such as content creation, running and editing videos and high performance games\u2014Ryzen is performing very well, meeting or beating the competition. But she added that where the chips are struggling, such as in lower-resolution games, AMD is working closely with software developers.', u' Don\u2019t miss: Want to invest in self-driving cars? Check out the chips ', u'Some analysts have warned that investors were getting a bit ahead of themselves, since the chips were just launched, and they wanted to see financial results before making any further pronouncements on AMD. In addition, the far more important impact on AMD\u2019s revenue and earnings is expected to come from re-entering the corporate server market with its new Zen-based chips, which is not expected to begin until the second quarter.']
