Article: 12 : [u'\r\n         Target, Gap, Best Buy among retailers headed to Washington to oppose border tax: report\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Chief executives from Target Corp., Gap Inc., Best Buy Co., AutoZone Inc. and other retailers will be in Washington, D.C., to meet with congressional leaders and President Trump on Wednesday in opposition to a proposed border adjustment tax, Reuters reports.', u'The CEOs are expected to meet with Rep. Kevin Brady, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, and members of the Senate, according to Reuters. Other delegates from J.C. Penney                                                                                                                                                                                                          JCP, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 , Tractor Supply                                                                                                                                                                                                          TSCO, +0.48%                                                                                                                                                and Jo-Ann Stores are expected to attend as well.', u' See also: TJX, Burlington, and other off-price retailers could benefit most from 2017 tax reform  ', u' See also: Here\u2019s why Trump is playing nice with Canada\u2019s Trudeau on trade ', u'Retailers and brands including Target                                                                                                                                                                                                          TGT, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                 , Gap                                                                                                                                                                                                          GPS, -0.55%                                                                                                                                                 , Nike Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NKE, -6.09%                                                                                                                                                 , Dollar Tree Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          DLTR, +0.60%                                                                                                                                                and Sears Holding Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SHLD, -15.33%                                                                                                                                                are among the companies that have stepped up their lobbying efforts, according to a report published recently by the Hill. ', u'Apparel retailers and department stores like Macy\u2019s Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          M, -1.41%                                                                                                                                                are already under pressure from shifting consumer buying habits toward \u201cexperiences,\u201d the move to e-commerce, and declining mall traffic.', u'Target shares are down 6.2% for the past year, Gap shares are up 2%, Best Buy                                                                                                                                                                                                          BBY, +0.86%                                                                                                                                                 stock is up 61.1% and AutoZone shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           AZO, +0.33%                                                                                                                                                 are up nearly 1% for the period. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, +0.22%                                                                                                                                                is up nearly 25.4% over the past 12 months.']

Name: Netflix, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         10 best, 10 worst stocks in the eight-year bull market\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Five months after George W. Bush signed the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, which included the bank bailout, money manager Doug Kass made a prescient call when he said March 9, 2009, was a \u201cgenerational low\u201d for the U.S. stock market.', u'Since March 9, 2009, the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has risen 249%, without reinvested dividends. The benchmark index had dropped 57% from a closing high of 1,565 on Oct. 9, 2007, through the closing low of 657 on March 9, 2009. From its pre-crisis high on Oct. 9, 2007, the index has risen 52% (and returned 86%, with reinvested dividends) through March 8 of this year.', u'You can see that, over the past 10 years, the S&P 500\xa0has had a total return (with dividends reinvested) of 109%. But if you have been making regular contributions to an S&P 500 index fund within a 401(k) or other employer-sponsored retirement account, the big bear market and any subsequent sustained declines have been good for you. That\u2019s because the lower prices you paid with contributions during market dips have boosted your long-term returns. This perfectly illustrates why a non-professional investor with decades to go until retirement is better off not trying to time the market.', u'The 314% bull-market return for the entire index illustrates how important dividends are, since the index was up a much more modest 249% without reinvested dividends. It\u2019s also important to keep in mind that these very high return numbers were set up by massive declines during the crisis.', u' Here are the 10 S&P 500 stocks that have had the biggest total returns (with reinvested dividends) from the index\u2019s closing bottom on March 9, 2009, through March 8, 2017: ']

Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Democrats blast Price over share purchase ahead of confirmation hearing \r\n    ']
Body: [u'CNN reported Monday that Price, a Georgia Republican, bought between $1,001 to $15,000 worth of shares last March in Zimmer Biomet                                                                                                                                                                                                           ZBH, +0.77%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. Tuesday morning, the Democratic National Committee blasted out an email to reporters describing Price\u2019s \u201clatest corruption scandal,\u201d and Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer said the CNN report showed \u201ca clear and troubling pattern of Congressman Price trading stock and using his office to benefit the companies in which he is investing.\u201d', u'Late Monday, the Trump transition team said the stock purchase was not directed by Price but by a broker, Reuters reported. Price himself did not become aware of the stock buy until well after the legislation was introduced, the report said. ', u' Read: Trump health secretary nominee has bought and sold $300,000 in health-care stocks while in office. ', u'Sen. Name: Rent-A-Center Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Rent-A-Center CEO departs, founder returns to helm on interim basis\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Rent-A-Center Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           RCII, +0.58%                                                                                                                                                 announced late Monday afternoon that Chief Executive Robert Davis had resigned and been replaced on an interim basis by founder and former CEO Mark Speese. Davis replaced Speese nearly three years ago, but the rental-furnishings chain struggled last year thanks to a large impairment charge and sales declines that Davis blamed on a new point-of-sale system. "I am extremely proud of what our team has accomplished in the past three years, during a dynamic and challenging environment," Davis said in the news release announcing the change. Speese, who had been serving as chairman of Rent-A-Center\'s board, previously served as CEO from 2001 to 2014. Rent-A-Center shares, which had fallen 21.8% in the past year, were steady in late trading Monday afternoon.']

Name: Arista Networks, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Arista Networks, a Cisco competitor, rockets to record high\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Arista Networks Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ANET, +0.67%                                                                                                                                                 rocketed 18% to a record high Friday, following the company\'s strong earnings report. In after-hours trade Thursday, Arista, which sells communications switches that compete with Cisco Systems Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CSCO, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                 topped fourth-quarter sales and non-GAAP earnings expectations and provided a revenue outlook for the current quarter well above the consensus estimate. Friday\'s moved mark Arista stock\'s second-biggest percentage-gain in history, helping the stock to notch an all-time high. Its shares have climbed more than 34% in the past three months and nearly 98% in the past year, vastly outperforming the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                 up 7.4% in the past three months and 22% in the past year. Earlier this week, Cisco also reported earnings that topped expectations but revenue declines in its core switching and routing businesses. ']

Name: Argos Therapeutics, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Argos Therapeutics cancer treatment study recommended to be discontinued for futility\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Argos Therapeutics Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ARGS, -2.42%                                                                                                                                                 said an independent data monitoring committee recommended the Phase 3 trial of its treatment for renal cell carcinoma be "discontinued for futility," based on an interim data analysis. The committee said the study as unlikely to demonstrate a statistically significant improvement in overall survival, which is the study\'s primary endpoint. "We are extremely disappointed with these results, which included seventy-five percent of the targeted events needed to permit the primary analysis and assessment of overall survival in the study," said Argos Chief Executive Jeff Abbey. Argos said it will determine the next steps for the treatment after it discusses the data with the Food and Drug Administration. The stock, which is currently halted for news until 8:30 a.m. ET, has lost 12% over the past 12 months, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 7.4%.']

Name: Dow Chemical Company (The)
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         Dow CEO calls Trump administration most pro-business since founding fathers\r\n    ']
Body: [u'WASHINGTON (MarketWatch) - Dow Chemical CEO Andrew Liveris on Thursday said President Donald Trump was leading "the most pro-business administration since the founding fathers." In comments after a meeting between manufacturers and the president, The Dow CEO                                                                                                                                                                                                           DOW, -1.64%                                                                                                                                                 said the "language of business" is being spoken at the White House. He said that manufacturing jobs will be brought back to the U.S. as a result of the tax policy and regulatory reforms under discussion. ']

Name: Controladora Vuela Compania de Aviacion, S.A.B. de C.V.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Airline stocks are about to take a breather after taking flight in fourth quarter\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Analysts said they are taking a more defensive stance on the sector heading into 2017, as they downgraded six stocks, including American Airlines Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          AAL, -2.83%                                                                                                                                                and United Continental Holdings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          UAL, -0.51%                                                                                                                                                 . Gains made after the November presidential election on improving demand and yields were mostly due to price-to-earnings multiple expansion, meaning improved expectations for the sector, and not due to fundamentals, said Cowen analysts, led by Helane Becker.', u' See also:  These bets helped Warren Buffett become biggest-gaining billionaire of 2016 ', u'Investor expectations for the sector are elevated, she wrote. Delta Air Lines Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          DAL, -1.41%                                                                                                                                                has guided analysts toward flat unit revenue for the first quarter, and investors, Becker said, should expect that to be the case for the rest of the industry. ', u' See:  5 places deal-savvy travelers should visit in 2017 ', u'Cowen downgraded the stock of American Airlines, Air Canada                                                                                                                                                                                                          AC, -0.54%                                                                                                                                                 , Alaska Air Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          ALK, -0.74%                                                                                                                                                 , JetBlue Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          JBLU, -1.42%                                                                                                                                                 , Spirit Airlines Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SAVE, -0.84%                                                                                                                                                and United Continental to market perform from outperform. It upgraded the stock of WestJet Airlines Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                          WJA, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                to market perform from underperform. It said Delta Air Lines is its top pick in the sector, followed by Southwest Airlines Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          LUV, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                 , SkyWest Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SKYW, -0.29%                                                                                                                                                and Volaris Aviation                                                                                                                                                                                                           VLRS, -1.41%                                                                                                                                                 . ', u' Read: Here\u2019s how these 2016 ETF picks worked out ', u'Airline stocks were trading higher Wednesday, led by Spirit Airlines, which closed up 1.8%. The NYSE Arca Airline exchange-traded fund                                                                                                                                                                                                          XAL, -0.58%                                                                                                                                                was up 1.8% and has gained 35% in the last 12 months, while the S&P                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                is up 12.8%. ']

Name: Wal-Mart Stores, Inc.
Article: 10 : [u'\r\n         Target suffers record stock price plunge\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Target reported before the open bell fiscal fourth-quarter profit that missed expectations, and provided first-quarter and full-year guidance that was well below analyst projections. The company said that investments it would make as it transitions to a new financial model will weigh on results in the short term.', u'That drove the stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           TGT, -0.39%                                                                                                                                                \xa0down $8.14, or 12.2%, to the lowest price seen since Aug. 20, 2014. Recent volume of over 37 million shares was nearly six-times the full-day average.', u'Target\u2019s disappointing results were in contrast to better-than-expected earnings reported by rival Wal-Mart Stores Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           WMT, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Home Depot Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HD, +0.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0last week.', u'Target shares have now tumbled 24% over the past three months, while the SPDR S&P Retail exchange-traded fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           XRT, -0.93%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has lost 6.8% and the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 7.4%.']

', u'The deal, for a mixture of cash and stock, substantially expands the health-care provider footprint of UnitedHealth                                                                                                                                                                                                           UNH, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, which is already the parent of the biggest U.S. health insurer, UnitedHealthcare. Name: Twitter, Inc.
Article: 9 : [u'\r\n         Stocks retreat from records, but Snap skyrockets in debut\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 112.58 points, or 0.5%, to close at 21,002.97 as Caterpillar Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CAT, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares slumped 4.3% as federal agents searched the company\u2019s offices. The Wall Street Journal said the search appeared to be related to an investigation into tax issues involving one of the company\u2019s Swiss subsidiaries.', u'The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slid 14.04 points, or 0.6%, to end at 2,381.92. The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.38%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 42.81 points, or 0.7%, to finish at 5,861.22.', u'Shares in Snap Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +6.92%                                                                                                                                                \xa0jumped 44% in their highly anticipated debut, the culmination of the biggest initial public offering since 2014. Because Snap is not a component of the Dow or S&P 500, and because it trades on the New York Stock Exchange as opposed to the Nasdaq, it didn\'t have a direct impact on the major indexes. However, the strong reception could reaffirm the upbeat sentiment that has helped to underpin the recent record run of the market.', u'Snap\u2019s strong IPO has already pushed the company\u2019s market cap above Twitter Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWTR, +2.13%                                                                                                                                                 Research shows that people using Snap have been steadily rising while growth in Twitter users has stagnated over the past couple of years, according to Bespoke Investment Group (see chart below).', u' Read more: Snap IPO\u2014Why it may be the next Facebook ', u'Meanwhile, Attorney General Jeff Sessions held a news conference after the market\u2019s close, announcing he would recuse himself from any investigation into Trump\u2019s campaign following reports that he had met with the Russian ambassador to the U.S. ahead of his confirmation hearing. The Democrats have called for his resignation for his failure to disclose the meetings. ', u' Economic news: Jobless claims fell by 19,000 to 223,000, setting a fresh postrecession low and illustrating the strength of the U.S. labor market.', u'Gradual interest-rate hikes are likely to be appropriate soon, Fed Gov. Lael Brainard said late Wednesday.', u'Analysts said investors will be looking for more hints on the Fed\u2019s plans for interest rates from the central bank\u2019s chairwoman, Janet Yellen, who will deliver a speech on Friday.', u' Stock movers: Shares in Shake Shack Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SHAK, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 2.6% a day after the burger chain\u2019s 2017 revenue outlook fell short of expectations.', u' Box Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BOX, -1.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sank 8.1% after the file-sharing company late Wednesday predicted the current quarter wouldn\'t live up to analysts\u2019 expectation. ', u' Kroger Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KR, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 4.3% despite posting quarterly results that topped Wall Street\u2019s forecasts late Wednesday.', u' Abercrombie & Fitch Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                            ANF, -3.50%                                                                                                                                                 shares soared 14% despite posting weaker-than-expected earnings. ', u' Barnes & Noble Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BKS, -0.85%                                                                                                                                                \xa0skidded 8.6% after the book retailer posted earnings that missed expectations. ', u' Monster Beverage Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MNST, +0.79%                                                                                                                                                \xa0jumped 13% after the energy-drink maker posted higher earnings and announced a new $500 million stock repurchase plan late Wednesday.', u' Other markets: European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.42%                                                                                                                                                were mixed, while Asian markets closed mostly higher. A key dollar index                                                                                                                                                                                                          DXY, -0.16%                                                                                                                                                 added to the prior day\u2019s gain. Oil futures                                                                                                                                                                                                          CLJ7, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell more than 2% while gold futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCJ7, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0settled lower.', u' --Victor Reklaitis contributed to this article.  ']

Name: Merck & Company, Inc.
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         The Dow\u2019s 21,000 rally was powered by Apple\u2019s 15% rally since Jan. 25 \r\n    ']
Body: [u' Check out: Dow matches fastest 1,000-point march to a milestone in history', u'Apple\u2019s nearly 15% rise since the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                 first hit 20,000 on Jan. 25 has contributed about 123 points to the Dow\u2019s rally to the milestone. That makes the Cupertino, Calif.-based iPhone maker, which has enjoyed a renaissance on the back of better-than-expected quarterly results and renewed enthusiasm over iPhone 8, the Dow\u2019s largest driver. Coming in second was industrial component Boeing Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BA, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                 which added 113 points over the past three weeks for a 10% gain.', u'Because the Dow is a price-weighted average, rather than a market-value weighted gauge like the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0price moves in the Dow\u2019s 30 components influence the equity benchmark rather than the weighted-average percentage changes of the S&P 500\u2019s members.', u'That price-weighting came into play when the Dow\u2019s surge to 20,000 in January was led by a surge in shares of Goldman Sachs Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GS, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                 which is trading at around $253 and has a market cap of about $99 billion, compared with Apple\u2019s shares at around $139 and a market cap of nearly $720 billion, as of Wednesday trade. ']

Name: Cisco Systems, Inc.
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Palo Alto Networks on pace for record stock drop as Cisco threat looms\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of Palo Alto Networks were on track for their worst daily decline on record, plummeting 23.6% to less than $116 in afternoon trade. The previous record decline was 13% on Oct. 28. The stock is now down 9.3% in the past three months and 21% in the past year, vastly underperforming the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, which is up 9.4% in three months and 21% in the past year.', u'Among the brokerages to sound off on Palo Alto\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           PANW, -0.51%                                                                                                                                                \xa0earnings were UBS, which downgraded the stock to neutral from overweight and slashed its price target to $130 from $160; J.P. Morgan, which downgraded the stock to neutral from overweight and axed its target to $140 from $170; Wunderlich Securities, which downgraded the stock to hold from buy and reduced its target to $150 from $190; and RW Baird, which downgraded the stock to neutral from outperform and sliced its target to $130 from $175. ', u'The selloff and barrage of negative analyst notes follow disappointing sales numbers from Palo Alto Networks late Tuesday. The Santa Clara, Calif., company reported adjusted earnings per share of 63 cents, a penny higher than the average forecast by analysts, according to FactSet. However, sales of $422.6 million fell short of the $430 million consensus estimate, and the company blamed its own executive issues, which it said it was \u201cmoving quickly to address.\u201d', u'Others looked beyond the execution issues and said competition, particularly from Cisco Systems Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CSCO, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and other large companies with burgeoning security arms, will be a persistent issue. In February, Cisco reported stronger-than-expected quarterly earnings and sales, buoyed by a 14% increase to $528 million in its security business. ', u' See also: Subscription focus helps Cisco stock turn around ']

Name: Edwards Lifesciences Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Now there\u2019s a way to invest and save democracy at the same time\r\n    ']
Body: [u'A key turning point was in 2010, when the Supreme Court ruled against government restrictions on corporate political spending in Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission. Since companies have deep pockets, their interests may trample those of average voters. ', u'A list of \u201csustainable investing\u201d themes from Arabesque Asset Management, which you can find in this note, appears comprehensive. It includes 30 topics of interest \u2014 everything from carbon emissions and community relations, to diversity and CEO pay. What about political campaign contributions and investing in sustainable democracy? Nowhere to be seen. ', u'The first stop for investors wanting to invest in sustainable democracy is the Center for Political Accountability (CPA) website. CPA examines the websites of S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0companies to gauge whether they have 24 qualities that CPA says companies need in the realm of campaign contributions. The big picture is that CPA is looking for the three qualities I mentioned above: transparency, policy and board oversight. ', u'CPA then ranks S&P 500 companies on a scale of 0-100. You can find a spreadsheet with rankings here. This ranking serves two purposes:', u'Morgan Stanley seems to be in the middle, concluding in this note that sustainable investments have \u201cusually met, and often exceeded, the performance of comparable traditional investments.\u201d', u' 1. Better governance  ', u' 2. Better results  ', u'To test how you\u2019d do if you used CPA\u2019s system as a sustainable democracy investment guide, I looked at how well CPA\u2019s top 48 companies did against the Guggenheim S&P 500 Equal Weight ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                          RSP, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 I chose this ETF because I used a simple equal weighting of the companies, so this ETF is the fairest comparison. (In contrast, the S&P 500 Index that most people track uses a market-cap weighted system. Name: Regency Centers Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Mall REITs rocked by news of J.C. Penney store closures \r\n    ']
Body: [u'J.C. Penney                                                                                                                                                                                                          JCP, -1.95%                                                                                                                                                said it will close 130 to 140 stores in the next few months, to \u201chelp align the company\u2019s brick-and-mortar presence with its omnichannel network, thereby redirecting capital resources to invest in locations and initiatives that offer the greatest revenue potential.\u201d', u'\u201cIt\u2019s having a negative effect on all REITs as J.C. Penney is another one of the high-profile retailers closing physical stores,\u201d said Edward Mui, an analyst at Morningstar. REITs are loved by investors for their high dividend yields, as MarketWatch\u2019s Philip Van Doorn has reported.', u' Read now: 10 REITs that look like big winners for 2017 ', u'In the last several months, Macy\u2019s Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          M, -1.51%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Sears Holding Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SHLD, -13.30%                                                                                                                                                and Guess Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          GES, -2.48%                                                                                                                                                have announced store closures. Macy\u2019s and Sears are often viewed as anchor stores that help draw traffic to malls and other shopping centers, and specialty stores, such as Gap Inc. Name: Twenty-First Century Fox, Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         R-rated \u2018Logan\u2019 tears up weekend box office with $85.3 million\r\n    ']
Body: [u'One year after 21st Century Fox Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           FOX, +1.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 movie studio opened \u201cDeadpool\u201d to a phenomenal $132.4 million, it debuted \u201cLogan,\u201d starring Hugh Jackman as Wolverine, to a strong $85.3 million in the U.S. and Canada, according to studio estimates. Both movies feature characters from Walt Disney Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DISN, +3.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0-owned Marvel\u2019s \u201cX-Men\u201d universe, for which Fox has controlled the big-screen rights since the 1990s.', u'Conventional wisdom in Hollywood has held that superhero movies should be rated PG-13 to maximize their box office by drawing teenagers. Every film from Disney\u2019s Marvel Studios and Time Warner Inc\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWX, -0.43%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 Warner Bros.\u2019 DC superhero unit has carried that more family-friendly rating. But with the raunchy \u201cDeadpool\u201d and, now, the dark and ultraviolent \u201cLogan,\u201d Fox has demonstrated that significant profits can also be found with movies aimed squarely at adults.', u'Riding fantastic word-of-mouth, ticket sales for \u201cGet Out\u201d dropped only 22% on its second weekend in theaters. Released by Comcast Corp.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           CMCSA, +0.01%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 Universal Pictures, the race relations-themed horror film grossed $26.1 million, bringing its domestic box office total to $76 million.', u' An expanded version of this report appears on WSJ.com. Name: Total S.A.
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         Heresy? These 7 actively managed funds are winners\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Investors have been stripping money out of active funds and stuffing it in passive ones at a record pace, and following the herd has never looked so smart. But for tactical investors, the timing might be good for a contrarian move. All that cash pouring into index funds might have flattered the relative performance of the indexes in recent years. And the broad U.S. stock market trades at an elevated valuation. \u201cI have no religious objection to index funds,\u201d says Larry Pitkowsky, co-manager of the GoodHaven fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOODX, -0.87%                                                                                                                                                 launched in 2011. \u201cBut investors are stepping on the gas with valuations high. If anything, it\u2019s better to use an index when the market is cheap.\u201d', u'This year will mark the 15th anniversary of a publication that causes active fund managers to toss in their 1,020 thread-count sheets. It\u2019s the Spiva Scorecard. The acronym stands for Standard & Poor\u2019s Indices Versus Active. Among other things, the biannual report now published in eight world regions shows the percentage of active funds that fail to beat their benchmarks. In 2015, 66% of large-cap funds did worse than the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. That was almost cause for popping Champagne corks. Just a year earlier, 86% came up short. When the 2016 numbers come out, expect them to be damning, too. Since 2000, there have only been three years when most U.S. large-cap managers succeeded at what they do for a living. Results across other size and style categories are poor, too.', u'The Spiva reports beget a steady flow of news stories about the failings of active funds, and investors have been taking action. Over the past five years, passive funds have received inflows of more than $1 trillion. Last year, active funds saw withdrawals of more than $200 billion, a postcrisis high. Active funds still hold two-thirds of mutual fund money.', u'\u201cI think the big inflows have perpetuated the \xadperformance of passive,\u201d says John Linehan, manager of the $22.7 billion T. Rowe Price Equity Income fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           PRFDX, -1.32%                                                                                                                                                 \u201cIf you own companies outside the index, you\u2019ve been disadvantaged. Nothing can go on like that forever.\u201d In Linehan\u2019s view, passive portfolios will reach a breaking point when valuations become too skewed relative to those in active portfolios, and fund flows are no longer pushing the indexes to outperform. \u201cWhen people are piling into a trade, it can pay to take the other side,\u201d he says. That happened just after the dot-com stock bubble, which is one of the periods when even average active managers beat the benchmarks. Another such period occurred around the market top in 2007.', u'The stock market doesn\u2019t have to tumble for good active managers to earn their fees now, however. All that\u2019s needed are some changes in the pattern of individual stock returns. One change that could already be underway is a long-awaited comeback for value stocks. Barron\u2019s predicted just such a comeback in \u201cMove Over, Facebook and Netflix: Value Investing Is \xadRebounding\u201d (March 12, 2016). Since then, the iShares Russell 1000 Value exchange-traded fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           IWD, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has returned 18.1%, versus 10.9% for iShares Russell 1000 Growth                                                                                                                                                                                                           IWF, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                 Such shifts can play out over many years. During the last good run for value stocks, after the dot-com bust, they beat growth in five out of seven years by \xaddouble-digit percentages.', u' Read: Mark Hulbert on the real message behind those plunging stock-market correlations ', u' AllianzGI NFJ Dividend Value                                                                                                                                                                                                            PNEAX, -1.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0requires that all of its holdings pay dividends. It also demands that they be modestly priced, which keeps the fund from loading up on the sort of packaged-food makers that trade at 20 times earnings and grow at 5% a year. Major holdings recently included Royal Dutch Shell                                                                                                                                                                                                           RDS.A, -0.59%                                                                                                                                                                              RDSA, -0.59%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0and AT&T                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.76%                                                                                                                                                 The portfolio yields close to 3%. While the A shares of the fund come with a feature most appropriate for people who don\u2019t like money\u2014an upfront sales charge of up to 5.5%\u2014you can avoid it by buying through a mutual-fund marketplace like the one at Charles Schwab.', u' DFA U.S. Large Cap Value                                                                                                                                                                                                            DFLVX, -1.75%                                                                                                                                                \xa0isn\u2019t quite an autonomous vehicle, but it\u2019s close. Its managers screen the market to select the cheapest slice based on the relationship between share prices and the value of a company\u2019s assets. They then favor smaller and more-prosperous companies. The approach keeps costs and turnover low for an active fund, but not returns. Over the past 15 years, the fund has beaten the S&P 500 by nearly two percentage points a year. You\u2019ll need to buy this fund through an \xadadvisor specifically educated by parent firm Dimensional Fund Advisors.', u' Dodge & Cox Stock                                                                                                                                                                                                            DODGX, -1.96%                                                                                                                                                 has eight co-managers, but its portfolio doesn\u2019t look crowdsourced. Financial, technology, and health-care holdings make up 65% of the portfolio, 20 points more than the S&P 500. Top holdings include giant consensus favorites like Alphabet                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOG, +0.38%                                                                                                                                                                              GOOGL, +0.41%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and smaller outcasts like HP Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPQ, +0.47%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and Hewlett Packard \xadEnter\xadprise                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPE, +0.70%                                                                                                                                                 Four out of the top five holdings are financials, a group that stands to benefit from rising interest rates and looser regulation under the next \xadpresident.', u' The GoodHaven fund is managed by a pair of alumni from the Fairholme fund, which is known for concentrated positions and spectacular periods of over- and underperformance, mostly the former. This has added up to long-term returns well ahead of the market, but also plenty of discomfort along the way. Launched in 2011, GoodHaven, too, is keeping things interesting. Last year, it beat the S&P 500 by eight percentage points. The year before it trailed by 20. Top holdings \xadrecently included Verizon Communications                                                                                                                                                                                                           VZ, -0.96%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Staples                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPLS, -0.74%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u2014\xadand, as a sign management is unafraid to shop in truly \xadunloved industries, even an active \xadmutual fund manager, Federated Investors                                                                                                                                                                                                           FII, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                ', u' Read:  Two veteran stock pickers at GoodHaven win by going where others see \u2018fear or disinterest\u2019 ', u' The Sound Shore fund                                                                                                                                                                                                            SSHFX, -1.57%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is contrarian in that it looks for companies that have fallen out of favor on Wall Street but haven\u2019t lost their earnings power. It sells stocks when their valuations revert to what it calculates as their normal levels. Top holdings \xadinclude credit-card issuer Capital One \xadFinancial                                                                                                                                                                                                           COF, +0.32%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and CBS                                                                                                                                                                                                           CBS, +0.64%                                                                                                                                                 The fund has a minimum initial investment of $10,000.', u' T. Rowe Price Equity Income has a new manager in John Linehan, who has added health-care exposure and reduced cash, while continuing to favor dividend payers with good growth prospects. In a recent conversation with Barron\u2019s, he talked about the merits of 21st Century Fox                                                                                                                                                                                                           FOXA, +1.41%                                                                                                                                                 a former corporate sibling of Barron\u2019s owner News Corp, which he views as having little to lose from the trend toward skinny cable bundles, and Total                                                                                                                                                                                                           TOT, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                                              FP, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                 the French oil concern, which trades at a deep discount to Exxon Mobil                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 The fund\u2019s dividend yield is only a touch above that of the market, and while its active share, at 67%, isn\u2019t exceptionally high, neither are its fees.', u' Vanguard U.S. Value                                                                                                                                                                                                            VUVLX, -1.91%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has the lowest active share on our list, for good reason. Its managers start with an index portfolio and then slightly tweak weightings according to valuation, momentum, and other factors. That kept the fund from getting clobbered in 2015 but also helped it outperform the S&P 500 by more than four percentage points last year. Fees are blessedly low at 0.23%. That compares with 1.13% for the average large-cap value fund. Vanguard U.S. Value isn\u2019t a closet indexer. It\u2019s an out-of-the-closet indexer that adds an active component\u2014and comes at a bargain price.', u'  This article first appeared in Barron\u2019s  ']

Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Joining IEX, NYSE plans \u2018speed bump\u2019 for some stocks\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The NYSE, a unit of Intercontinental Exchange                                                                                                                                                                                                           ICE, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, says it will ask the Securities and Exchange Commission to allow for a 350-microsecond delay for trading in small- to mid-cap companies that trade on what was formerly called the American Stock Exchange.', u' See also: \u2018The Big Short\u2019 author Michael Lewis says this is where you should put your money']

Name: United Technologies Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         The Dow\u2019s 21,000 rally was powered by Apple\u2019s 15% rally since Jan. 25 \r\n    ']
Body: [u' Check out: Dow matches fastest 1,000-point march to a milestone in history', u'Apple\u2019s nearly 15% rise since the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                 first hit 20,000 on Jan. 25 has contributed about 123 points to the Dow\u2019s rally to the milestone. That makes the Cupertino, Calif.-based iPhone maker, which has enjoyed a renaissance on the back of better-than-expected quarterly results and renewed enthusiasm over iPhone 8, the Dow\u2019s largest driver. Coming in second was industrial component Boeing Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BA, +0.29%                                                                                                                                                 which added 113 points over the past three weeks for a 10% gain.', u'Because the Dow is a price-weighted average, rather than a market-value weighted gauge like the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0price moves in the Dow\u2019s 30 components influence the equity benchmark rather than the weighted-average percentage changes of the S&P 500\u2019s members.', u'That price-weighting came into play when the Dow\u2019s surge to 20,000 in January was led by a surge in shares of Goldman Sachs Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GS, -1.01%                                                                                                                                                 which is trading at around $253 and has a market cap of about $99 billion, compared with Apple\u2019s shares at around $139 and a market cap of nearly $720 billion, as of Wednesday trade. ']

Name: UBS AG
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         European stocks snap 7-day winning streak as Nestl\xe9, banks fall\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Stoxx Europe 600 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 0.4% to end at 370.10, pulling back from a more-than-one-year closing high reached on Wednesday. ', u'Stock markets globally, including in Europe, have rallied in recent days after interest rate-hike signals from the U.S. Federal Reserve and pledges from President Donald Trump to announce a \u201cmassive\u201d tax plan soon. ', u' Banks pause for breath: Bank shares in particular have been driven higher, as investors welcomed the prospect of higher interest rates. Higher rates are seen as a positive for lending margins at financial institutions. However, on Thursday the sector took a breather, as the Stoxx Europe 600 Banks Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           FX7, -0.49%                                                                                                                                                \xa0finished down 0.8%.', u'Shares of Banco Santander SA                                                                                                                                                                                                           SAN, +1.13%                                                                                                                                                                              SAN, +2.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 1%, UBS Group AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           UBSG, -1.58%                                                                                                                                                                              UBS, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0dropped 1.3%, and Deutsche Bank AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           DBK, -0.66%                                                                                                                                                                              DB, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 2%.', u' Other movers: Shares of Nestl\xe9 SA                                                                                                                                                                                                           NESN, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0also weighed on the pan-European index, ending down 1%. The move came after the consumer-products giant said sales slowed in 2016, as it forecast subdued growth in 2017. ', u'Royal Dutch Shell PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           RDSB, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                                              RDS.B, -0.39%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 2.2% and BP PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           BP., -0.71%                                                                                                                                                                              BP, -0.59%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slid 2% after both companies went \u201cex-dividend.\u201d On the ex-dividend date, new investors in the stock will no longer be entitled to the next round of dividend payouts. The oil giants\u2019 drops came as oil prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLH7                                                                                                                                                                              UK:LCOJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0headed lower.', u'Drug maker AstraZeneca PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           AZN, +0.81%                                                                                                                                                                              AZN, +1.71%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was also trading ex-dividend, helping to send the stock down 0.2%. ', u'Shares of Cobham PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           COB, -1.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sank 15% after the U.K. defense and aerospace supplier warned on profit and said its balance sheet is too weak.', u'Schneider Electric SE                                                                                                                                                                                                           SU, -0.92%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 4.2% after the power-equipment supplier reported 2016 profit that fell short of forecasts.', u'On an upbeat note, shares of Air France-KLM SA                                                                                                                                                                                                           AF, -1.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rallied 13% after the airline said operating profit rose 35% in 2016 on a sharp drop in fuel costs. ', u'Other airlines tracked Air France higher. Shares of Deutsche Lufthansa AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           LHA, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                 finished up 2.2%, while British Airway-parent International Consolidated Airlines Group SA                                                                                                                                                                                                           IAG, -2.71%                                                                                                                                                                              ICAGY, -2.43%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 0.6%. ', u'Coca-Cola HBC AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           CCH, +0.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 4.9% after the bottling company said profit rose last year as it benefited from cost cuts and efficiency improvements. ', u' Economic news: Unemployment in France ticked down to 10% in the fourth quarter, from 10.1% in the previous three-month period. Among people under the age of 25, the jobless rate declined to 23.8% in the fourth quarter, the lowest rate since early 2014.', u' Minutes from the European Central Bank\u2019s January meeting revealed that officials saw \u201cno room for complacency\u201d at their latest policy meeting, agreeing to continue their support for the eurozone\u2019s economy to help offset potential political risks. At the Jan. 17 meeting, the ECB kept policy on hold and said it saw no signs of a sustained pickup in inflation. ']
