Name: Heico Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Defense ETFs charge on Trump\u2019s plan to boost military spending\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Exchange-traded funds tied to the defense industry rallied on Monday, after President Donald Trump said his first budget proposal would include a \u201chistoric increase\u201d in military spending.', u'The iShares U.S. Aerospace & Defense ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           ITA, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 1% on the day, as did the SPDR S&P Aerospace & Defense ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XAR, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 The PowerShares Aerospace & Defense                                                                                                                                                                                                           PPA, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 0.7%. All three easily outperformed the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                 which was unchanged on the day.', u'The rally in defense stocks was so broad that only one of the 39 components of the iShares fund was lower on the day. Among the biggest gainers, Triumph Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TGI, -0.61%                                                                                                                                                \xa0surged 3.2%, Heico Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HEI, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 2.7%, and Lockheed Martin Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LMT, -0.30%                                                                                                                                                \u2014which has faced criticism by Trump recently\u2014rose 1.8%.']

Name: U S Concrete, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         How the \u2018Trump Wall\u2019 gets built: U.S. Concrete\u2019s CEO explains\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Proponents see a wall as a crucial step in curtailing illegal immigration. Critics have assailed it as unrealistic, impractical, and expensive, with the estimated cost ranging from $12 to $15 billion.', u'Plenty of key details remain unknown about the potential wall, including its size, the materials that would be used, the specific cost and how it will be paid for, but companies have already rallied on the theme. U.S. Concrete Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           USCR, -1.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has been a primary beneficiary of the chatter, soaring more than 37% since the election in early November, including a jump of 8.8% this week alone. Those gains took it to a new intraday record on Thursday, although it ultimately ended lower on the session.', u' See also: Trump\u2019s wall stocks may already be too high, analyst says ', u'Democrats are expected to fight the proposed wall, which has led to the first significant diplomatic rift between Mexico and the U.S. in decades, although Trump signed an executive order on Wednesday ordering its construction. ', u' Read: Company best positioned to benefit from a \u2018Trump Wall\u2019 is Mexican ']

So it seems like defense stocks would be a no-brainer. But be careful here. Trump is also a stickler for costs, and he\u2019s already called out Lockheed Martin                                                                                                                                                                                                           LMT, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                 and Boeing                                                                                                                                                                                                           BA, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 for what they charge the government. So it\u2019s tough to know which companies might do well, and which ones might get hurt by Trump\u2019s concerns about costs. For now, it\u2019s probably better to stay away from this group, as a Trump play. ', u' Infrastructure plays ', u'This group is another tough one. Yes, our nation\u2019s infrastructure is crumbling. You see this all the time when you drive around. And Trump\u2019s plan to boost infrastructure spending would no doubt help this space, especially materials companies like Vulcan Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           VMC, +0.34%                                                                                                                                                 Martin Marietta Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           MLM, +0.37%                                                                                                                                                 and Summit Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           SUM, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                 ', u' At the time of publication, Michael Brush had no positions in any stocks mentioned in this column. Brush has suggested DG, AMZN, DIS, BRK.B, PNC, JPM, DHI, NKE, XOM, GILD, CELG, COP, HES, CMG and GOOGL in his stock newsletter, Brush Up on Stocks. Brush is a Manhattan-based financial writer who has covered business for the New York Times and The Economist group, and he attended Columbia Business School in the Knight-Bagehot program.  ']

Name: Anthem, Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Does Trump really know how to fix Americans\u2019 health care?\r\n    ']
Body: [u'\u201cGreat meeting with CEOs of leading U.S. health insurance companies who provide great healthcare to the American people,\u201d Trump tweeted after his big summit with health insurance honchos.', u' Are you angry about your  health insurance premiums? You should be. Last year, $130 billion of your private health insurance money was spent \u2014 wasted, mostly \u2014 on administrative costs. That\u2019s 12% of your total bill, and just over $1,000 per American household. Those figures come from the independent Kaiser Foundation.', u'So how nice it was that Stephen Hemsley, CEO of UnitedHealth Group                                                                                                                                                                                                           UNH, -0.96%                                                                                                                                                \xa0stopped by for some glad-handing with the president. Last year his company billed its customers $35.5 billion to pay for administrative costs and stockholders\u2019 income. That\u2019s before paying for a single pill, doctor, scalpel, or CAT scan.', u'Now if you are a UnitedHealth customer, and the company is currently holding out on your medical bills, you might be interested to know that if Hemsley ever suffers from a disability the company will pay him $48 million. Here\u2019s the  relevant section from page 62 of the company\u2019s most recent proxy statement.', u'And how nice to see Joe Swedish from Anthem                                                                                                                                                                                                           ANTM, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, eager to thank the president for the \u201cswift and decisive action\u201d Trump promises take to rescue the American patient from the evils of Big Government.']

Article: 2 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Forget Buffett \u2014 four unsung investment gurus are picking these eight stocks for 2017\r\n    ']
Body: [u'One problem here is that you\u2019ll have trouble identifying the best investment letter writers in the future. That\u2019s because Mark Hulbert sadly pulled the plug on his long-standing letter-writer ranking service last year. ', u'As a stock-letter writer myself, it\u2019s tempting to chime in here. But I\u2019ve never been ranked by Hulbert, so I will stay out of this, other than to mention that Seattle Genetics                                                                                                                                                                                                           SGEN, +1.36%                                                                                                                                                 was recently a top suggestion in my own letter, Brush Up on Stocks. ', u' Go with turnarounds ', u'George Putnam, a money manager who pens Turnaround Letter, expects modest market gains of around 3% in 2017. \u201cThe economy is still pretty strong, and I think earnings are going to be OK. But the S&P 500 has had a great run over last several years, and it may run out of gas,\u201d says Putnam. ', u' Crocs                                                                                                                                                                                                            CROX, -0.84%                                                                                                                                                 Recent price: $6.85', u'People either love or hate Crocs\u2019 weird rubber shoes. There\u2019s not much in between. Ten years ago, Crocs lovers ruled the day. The company\u2019s stock was a high flyer, trading above $70 in 2007. Then Crocs crashed and burned. It brought in new management. But they didn\u2019t have the right experience, so the company had to reset again in 2013, with help from Blackstone Group                                                                                                                                                                                                           BX, -0.97% And they enjoy barriers to entry, because building ships is so expensive.', u' Amgen                                                                                                                                                                                                            AMGN, +0.13%                                                                                                                                                 Recent price: $146', u'Amgen has important drugs like Repatha, for controlling cholesterol. I don\u2019t know of anyone who can constantly do that, and certainly I can\u2019t.\u201d ', u' Starbucks                                                                                                                                                                                                            SBUX, +0.27%                                                                                                                                                 Recent price: $55.50', u' Priceline                                                                                                                                                                                                            PCLN, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                 Recent price: $1,466', u' Use this little-known trick to spot value ', u'Near term, there could be market trouble because the Trump rally may fade, says Investment Quality Trends editor Kelley Wright. \u201cThere\u2019s an awful lot of enthusiasm right now. I am not sure how long it will last, when the reality sets in on how hard it is to get through a legislative agenda.\u201d Ultimately, though, greater infrastructure spending will spur jobs and wage growth, and help produce 8%-10% gains for the S&P 500 this year, says Wright. ', u' Franklin Resources                                                                                                                                                                                                            BEN, +0.05%                                                                                                                                                 Recent price: $40 ', u' Eaton Vance                                                                                                                                                                                                            EV, -0.47%                                                                                                                                                 Recent price: $42', u' At the time of publication, Michael Brush owned shares of SGEN. Body: [u'A landmark Brexit speech and the Davos hootenanny are also helping to wake up anyone who remembered the \u201cI have a dream\u201d man by sleeping in, as eToro analysts put it.', u'The combo of the big change at the White House on Friday and the fresh info on Brexit today is making investors anxious, says Gary Huxtable from Atlantic Pacific Securities. Hertz Global Holdings, Inc
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         Earnings releases are still a confusing mess, and it\u2019s investors who pay the price\r\n    ']
Body: [u'On Thursday, Ford Motor Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          F, +0.47%                                                                                                                                                released one of the most unclear quarterly reports MarketWatch has seen, failing even to offer a year-earlier number for its earnings \u2014 or, in this case, loss \u2014 per share. The car company even flipped its financial table to show the prior-year numbers before the current ones. It\u2019s a basic financial-reporting principle that tables are read from left to right, so some readers could easily have mistaken the 2016 numbers for the 2015 ones. ', u' Read also:  Here\u2019s how investors are duped each earnings season ', u' Don\u2019t miss: The tax hit that made Google miss on earnings, and the big change that will keep it from happening again', u'The Ford release did not have any purpose other than to direct investors to the company\u2019s website to see the results. By the time several clicks had finally produced a report, the share price had moved. The commentary provided by Chief Executive Mark Fields and Chief Financial Officer Bob Shanks was only about the full-year performance, which showed the company swinging to a profit from 2015, with no mention of the company\u2019s $800 million loss for the fourth quarter.', u'MarketWatch has written before about the delay caused when companies make investors, and the reporters who serve them, search for earnings on a website, which almost invariably crashes under the strain of so many attempting to access it at the same time. ', u' See also: T-Mobile\u2019s accounting slammed by investor group in letter to SEC ', u'The worst offender, in our view, is the video-streaming giant Netflix Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          NFLX, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0.', u'This earnings season, General Electric Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          GE, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                and International Business Machines Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          IBM, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                both listed their diluted earnings per share above basic earnings per share. While the companies are not doing anything technically wrong, one industry expert said it is still a surprising approach.', u' Read: GE and IBM have \u2018unusual\u2019 earnings reports in common ', u' Don\u2019t miss:  GE\u2019s earnings report may not be wrong, but it may still mislead investors ', u' See also: Wal-Mart\u2019s earnings report is still missing something ', u'On Wednesday, another member of the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                          DJIA, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, United Technologies Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          UTX, -0.58%                                                                                                                                                 , did something even more baffling, presenting earnings that obliged investors and reporters to do their own math. Under the \u201cdiluted earnings (loss) per share of common stock\u201d heading, the line item for continuing operations showed $1.26, but the line for discontinued operations just showed a loss of 1 cent. For investors to ascertain net earnings per share, they are required to subtract a penny from $1.26, to get $1.25.', u'Meanwhile, Lockheed Martin Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          LMT, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                unveiled a problem this week with Sikorsky, the helicopter maker it acquired from United Technologies in 2015. Lockheed said it expects to report a material weakness in internal control over financial reporting for Sikorsky in its 2016 annual report at the end of February. The company said management had determined that Sikorsky did not \u201cadequately identify, design and implement appropriate process-level controls for its processes and appropriate information technology controls for its information technology systems.\u201d Its internal control over financial reporting was, therefore, \u201cineffective\u201d as of Dec. 31, 2016, according to the filing. The auditor\u2019s opinion in the annual report is expected to reflect management\u2019s conclusion. ', u' See: Lockheed says numbers from Sikorsky are unreliable due to control weakness ', u'The SEC has been cracking down on the use of metrics that don\u2019t conform with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles in earnings in an effort to make them clearer. The regulator issued updated guidelines on that practice last May and has followed up with comment letters to offenders.', u'The SEC rules allow companies to use non-GAAP numbers to supplement the GAAP ones, but they must provide the GAAP numbers first, give both sets of numbers equal prominence and explain how they are reconciled. The SEC has sent comment letters to companies including GE, General Motors Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          GM, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Coca-Cola Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          KO, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Hertz Global Holdings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          HTZ, -4.59%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Medtronic PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                          MDT, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Whirlpool Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          WHR, -0.54%                                                                                                                                                and Tesla Motor Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          TSLA, +0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, to name a few. The SEC called ConocoPhillips                                                                                                                                                                                                          COP, -0.68%                                                                                                                                                out on its use of a non-GAAP revenue number, just weeks after MarketWatch highlighted the issue. ', u' See also: New competition took a bite out of J&J\u2019s drug sales, but don\u2019t expect the trend to dominate this earnings season ', u'  See: How the biggest companies in the S&P 500 use made-up earnings numbers ']

Body: [u' (Updates to add closing prices for Monday, Feb. 27.) ', u'The benchmark S&P 500 Index has returned 4.2% so far in February, a remarkable performance, considering that the bull market is nearly eight years old and that stocks are looking pricey. But this month is even more amazing when you view this chart:', u'The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                 has returned 17.5% over the past two years (with dividends reinvested). One thing to note is that if you continued to pour money into an index fund through an employer-sponsored 401(k) or similar plan during that time, those two pullbacks helped you beat the market because you paid lower prices during the dips.', u'That\u2019s right \u2014 the so-called Trump rally is responsible for most of the two-year gains, and February\u2019s performance has been icing on the cake, so far.', u' Here are the 10 S&P 500 stocks with the biggest price increases this month: ', u' Here are the 10 S&P 500 stocks that have dropped the most this month: ']

Name: Zillow Group, Inc.
Article: 9 : [u'\r\n         This is how much the White House is worth in 2017\r\n    ']
Body: [u'When Donald Trump took office as the 45th president of the United States last Friday, he got the keys to a nearly $400 million home.', u'The value of the White House, located at 1600 Pennsylvania Ave. NW in Washington, D.C., has grown 15% since 2009, when President Barack Obama first took office, according to real estate website Zillow.                                                                                                                                                                                                           Z, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                 The company estimates home values based on physical property, neighborhood and the market. Comparatively, home values across the country have climbed 9% in the last eight years. ', u' See: Why doesn\u2019t anyone want to live in this fake White House? ', u'Trump, who also lives in a gold-adorned $100 million penthouse in New York City, according to Travel & Leisure Magazine, said before he was elected that he doesn\u2019t plan to change much in his new home, if anything just doing a few touch-ups. Also, some of the more historic areas in the home can\u2019t be changed at all. ', u' See also:  These 4 colors can be the kiss of death when selling your home ', u'Around the country, home prices are increasing, due to tight inventory, an improving economy and high demand for homes. Foreclosures are also dropping, as the economy distances itself from the Great Recession and lenders expect more from borrowers.']

Name: AT&T Inc.
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         Wireless carriers are quietly telling you what videos to watch on your iPhone\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Unlimited wireless plans are back. Last weeks, AT&T                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.95%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 offered unlimited calls, texts and 22 gigabytes of high-speed data for $90 per month on a single-phone plan before being \u201cthrottled\u201d by the network (impacting the speed or quality of the video). This package includes $25 monthly credit toward DirecTV, DirecTV Now or U-Verse TV packages. Watching DirecTV with data won\u2019t count against your overall usage as part of a so-called zero-rating plan. (AT&T bought in July 2015 for $48.5 billion and, under Federal Communications Commission, must \u201crefrain from imposing discriminatory usage-based allowances or other discriminatory retail terms and conditions on its broadband internet service.\u201d) ', u'The company sweetened its unlimited plans after Verizon                                                                                                                                                                                                           VZ, -0.82%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 started offering unlimited data again in recent weeks, and to compete with T-Mobile                                                                                                                                                                                                           TMUS, +1.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Sprint                                                                                                                                                                                                           S, +1.45%                                                                                                                                                 which offer low-cost unlimited data plans, says technology consultant Jeff Kagan. He says other wireless carriers and content providers are already rumored to join forces in order to compete. \u201cEventually all competitors will head in the same direction, but for now AT&T has the lead,\u201d he says. \u201cThis is just the next natural step. This is an attractive bundle at a lower cost.\u201d It\u2019s a turnaround on AT&T\u2019s previous stance on unlimited data. In 2012, AT&T announced that it will no longer allow consumers to use more than an agreed-upon amount of data per month without being charged for it as part of an effort to rein in the heaviest data users. That same year, Verizon also put the kibosh on unlimited data plans for new users. ', u'But all that has changed. \u201cBy using zero rating, internet service providers and mobile providers can juice the landscape by encouraging consumers to choose one content provider over another,\u201d says Aram Sinnreich, professor of communications at the American University in Washington, D.C. \u201cIt\u2019s anti-competitive, especially when the content provider and wireless carrier are part of the same conglomerate.\u201d (Earlier this month, Nese Guendelsberger, the acting bureau chief of the Federal Communications Commission, ended the agency\u2019s review of wireless carriers that exclude their own video-streaming services from customers\u2019 data plan caps, a review started under the previous administration.) ', u' Don\u2019t miss: Chance the Rapper knew something about music that Prince did not  ', u'Quietly influencing what content providers people use creates a barrier to new players and reduces competition for the Netflixes                                                                                                                                                                                                           NFLX, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0of tomorrow, Sinnreich says. \u201cAll the major titans, of the internet like Google                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOG, +0.28%                                                                                                                                                 Facebook                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and Amazon                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                 didn\u2019t exist 20 years ago,\u201d he says. \u201cThe barrier to entry was very low. There were no preferential conditions for legacy companies and that\u2019s what\u2019s happening now. The entire regulatory approach to the internet and digital services are changing. We are seeing a move back towards allowing communications and viewing to be controlled by just a few mega companies.\u201d Without competition and innovation, he says, consumers get stuck paying more and more for the same old stuff.\u201d', u'Under the previous FCC chairman Tom Wheeler, a Democrat, the FCC championed regulation on net neutrality and an open internet, MarketWatch reporter Trey Williams reported in December. \u201cA major industry question, as Trump\u2019s Republican administration heads to Washington, is whether these regulations will be ignored, rolled back or otherwise nixed.\u201d (The FCC did not respond to request for comment.) Sinnreich is not optimistic, and believes that internet and what we watch on it could eventually be controlled by a small group of big corporations. \u201cThe FCC not going to hold these companies to those standards,\u201d he said. \u201cThe real power of the wireless market will be unleashed with 5G marketplace and digital companies want to dominate that.\u201d ']

Name: The Kraft Heinz Company
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         FTSE 100 ends higher, helped by Unilever\u2019s leap and pound\u2019s drop\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The FTSE 100                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose by 0.3% to end at 7,299.96, after trading in the red in morning action. The blue-chip benchmark scored a 0.6% gain for the week and finished just below a one-month closing high hit Wednesday.', u'Shares in consumer-products giant Unilever PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           ULVR, +0.11%                                                                                                                                                                              UN, +0.69%                                                                                                                                                                              UL, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0soared 13%, powered by U.S. packaged-foods heavyweight Kraft Heinz Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KHC, +0.71%                                                                                                                                                \xa0announcing that it made a merger proposal to Unilever that was declined.', u'The pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.1122%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was trading at $1.2416, down from $1.2494 late Thursday, as traders reacted to a January report on U.K. retail sales. The report showed a month-over-month drop of 0.3%, missing forecasts for a rise.', u'The retail sales number was \u201creally weak,\u201d showing British consumers are starting to feel the squeeze due to a pickup in inflation, said Naeem Aslam, chief market analyst at Think Markets UK, in a note. ', u'U.K. investors on Thursday also digested U.S. President Donald Trump\u2019s lengthy press conference on Thursday, in which he said he \u201cinherited a mess\u201d at home and abroad, and blasted the news media.', u' Other movers: Coca-Cola HBC AG\u2019s shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           CCH, +0.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed 4% higher for the FTSE 100\u2019s second-biggest gain. The stock built on Thursday\u2019s jump of 4.9%, which came after the bottling company said profit rose last year.', u'AstraZeneca PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           AZN, +0.62%                                                                                                                                                                              AZN, +1.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 1.6% after the drug company announced positive results from a trial of its breast cancer treatment Lynparza.', u'Asia-focused bank Standard Chartered PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           STAN, -1.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gave up 4.4% for the FTSE\u2019s largest loss. ']

Emirates and two other Gulf airlines, Etihad Airways and Qatar Airways, deny they are subsidized and say they provide flights to destinations in Africa and Asia that U.S. airlines choose not to serve.', u' An expanded version of this article appears at WSJ.com.', u' Popular on WSJ.com: ', u' U.S. Household Net Worth Reaches Record $92.8 Trillion ', u'  Ivanka Trump\u2019s Landlord Is a Chilean Billionaire Suing the U.S. Government ']

Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         J.P. Morgan\u2019s Jamie Dimon says Trump has awakened \u2018animal spirits\u2019\r\n    ']
Body: [u'J.P. Morgan & Co. Chief Executive Officer and prominent Democratic donor Jamie Dimon on Thursday praised President Donald Trump\u2019s purportedly pro-growth agenda, claiming that the president\u2019s victory over Hillary Clinton had awakened \u201canimal spirits\u201d in the market. ', u'Banks have been massive gainers since Trump\u2019s November election, accounting for the bulk of the overall market\u2019s move as investors bet on gains stemming from the twin tailwinds of lower regulation and higher interest rates. J.P. Morgan                                                                                                                                                                                                           JPM, +0.43%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has been a particular beneficiary of the rally, having climbed more than 30% since the election. The overall financial sector                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLF, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is up 24%.']

Name: Procter & Gamble Company (The)
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Bull market\u2019s 8-year anniversary reminds us that the Dow rewards the bold \r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is a benchmark of 30 large U.S. companies and generally serves as a barometer of broader market conditions; among investors here and abroad, the blue-chip average is synonymous with the U.S. stock market, period. ', u'Compared with stocks in Europe and Asia, the Dow is clearly an overachiever. The Stoxx Europe 600 Euro                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.68%                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed 138%, the U.K\u2019s FTSE 100                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, +0.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0advanced 108%, China\u2019s Shanghai Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHCOMP, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 50% and Japan\u2019s Nikkei                                                                                                                                                                                                           NIK, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 175% during the same time frame. ', u'Among the Dow components remaining from 2009, Home Depot Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HD, +0.53%                                                                                                                                                 is the undisputed star, soaring 608%, while American Express Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AXP, +0.54%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Walt Disney Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, +0.01%                                                                                                                                                \xa0both surged more than 500%.', u'Seven companies have joined the Dow after the bull market began its epic climb, doing their share to fuel the Dow\u2019s bullish run. UnitedHealth Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UNH, -0.75%                                                                                                                                                \xa0jumped 752% since the beginning of the bull market and Visa Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           V, +0.80%                                                                                                                                                \xa0skyrocketed 524%. Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.67%                                                                                                                                                 the youngest member of the blue-chip family, has shot up nearly 1,000% since 2009, although it rose only 9.3% since it became a Dow component two years ago. ', u' Newcomers on the Dow  ', u'Yet, not all Dow stocks have posted such stellar returns. Oil major Exxon Mobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has risen a paltry 23% while its competitor Chevron Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CVX, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 87%.', u'International Business Machines Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           IBM, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                 Procter & Gamble Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PG, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                 Verizon Communications Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           VZ, -1.01%                                                                                                                                                 and Wal-Mart Stores Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           WMT, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have also posted comparatively lackluster returns.', u'Only a handful of companies have been booted from the Dow since 2009\u2014AT&T Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.84%                                                                                                                                                 Bank of America Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, +0.39%                                                                                                                                                 Alcoa Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AA, +0.75%                                                                                                                                                 Citigroup Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           C, +0.03%                                                                                                                                                 General Motors Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GM, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                 Kraft Heinz Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KHC, +0.44%                                                                                                                                                 and HP Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPQ, +0.52%                                                                                                                                                 Of the seven, Bank of America\xa0and Citigroup have outperformed their Dow peers Goldman Sachs                                                                                                                                                                                                           GS, -0.56%                                                                                                                                                 and J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JPM, +0.42%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 although AT&T \u2018s                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.84%                                                                                                                                                 77% came up short of Verizon Communications Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           VZ, -1.01%                                                                                                                                                \xa087% gains. Alcoa Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AA, +0.75%                                                                                                                                                 replaced by Nike Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NKE, -5.90%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in September 2013, is up 77%.']

Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         These big oil stocks are expected by analysts to rise up to 41% in 2017\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Oil prices tumbled more than 2% Wednesday, as investors worry that OPEC\u2019s recent deal to prop up prices by cutting production is threatened by increased shale production in the U.S. ', u'Myra P. Saefong recently explained why U.S. shale producers are the biggest winners from OPEC\u2019s oil deal. That $50 price level for oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLG7                                                                                                                                                \xa0is critical for U.S. shale producers, and analysts predict prices will stay above that level, expecting massive increases in domestic spending and production.', u' Also see: The U.S. is increasingly looking at this Texas region for oil ']

Name: E.I. du Pont de Nemours and Company
Article: 16 : [u'\r\n         Stock market closes lower, spooked by Trump immigration ban\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                \xa0finished down 122.65 points, or 0.6%, at 19,971.13, dropping below the psychologically important 20,000 level. Earlier, the average was down by as many as 223 points. The last time the average had a worse day was Oct. 11, according to FactSet data. Shares of Caterpillar Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          CAT, -0.55%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, DuPont                                                                                                                                                                                                           DD, -1.63%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and Chevron Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          CVX, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0weighed on the average.', u'The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shed 13.79 points, or 0.6%, to finish at 2,280.90, recovering from a 27-point deficit for its worst one-day performance since Dec. 28. The day\u2019s losses were broad, with nine of the S&P 500\u2019s 11 primary sectors finishing lower, with energy, materials and tech the worst performers.', u'The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gave up 47.07 points, or 0.8%, to close at 5,613.71, its worst day since Dec. 30. Earlier, the index was down by as many as 82 points.', u'The CBOE Volatility index                                                                                                                                                                                                           VIX, +1.04%                                                                                                                                                 a measure of investor anxiety, surged 11% in its biggest one-day pop in about five months, though at 11.79 it remains well below its long-term average of 20. ', u' Read: Introducing Trump Today, the daily wrap on what the president did and said ', u'While stocks reacted favorably to Trump\u2019s election in November, with major indexes hitting a series of records as investors bet he would push for lower taxes and deregulation, the first week of his administration was marked by confusion and controversy. Tensions have been high between the U.S. and Mexico, while a public outcry that occurred over a travel ban this weekend sowed further doubts among some analysts that lack of equity volatility could continue.', u' Read: Wall Street\u2019s Trump optimism comes with heavy dose of uncertainty ', u'The immigration issue may have become the hot key issue to roil markets as it flies against much of the pro-business sentiment that has been assumed to be baked into the Trump agenda. Several executives decried the immigration ban as being bad for business.', u'Executives from big technology companies such as Alphabet Inc.\u2019s Google Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOG, +0.03%                                                                                                                                                 Facebook and Microsoft Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MSFT, +0.58%                                                                                                                                                \xa0were among those who jumped to criticize Trump\u2019s temporary immigration ban.', u' Read:  Pro-immigrant protests continue at airports, cities around U.S. ', u' Read: Does Trump rally face \u2018one last meltup\u2019 after Dow 20,000? ', u' Fed meeting, data: In the latest economic data, consumer spending rose 0.5% last month, matching the estimate of economists polled by MarketWatch. That is the biggest increase in spending in December since the last month of 2009. The same report showed a pick up in a yearly comparison of inflation, to its highest since late in 2014. Separately, pending home sales rose 1.6% in December.', u' Read:  Jobs report to give clue on early days of Trump White House ', u' Stocks to watch: The coming week will feature reports from one-fifth of the S&P 500 index, plus five Dow components. Crucial for the consumer-reliant technology sector will be Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          AAPL, +0.48%                                                                                                                                                 on Tuesday and Facebook Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0on Wednesday, while Amazon.com Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0reports Thursday. ', u' Read:  Outlooks for the Age of Trump are top focus of the earnings season ', u'  Delta Air Lines Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DAL, -0.97%                                                                                                                                                \xa0said domestic flights were resuming after a computer glitch caused cancellations on Sunday night and into Monday. Shares fell 4.1%. The sector, led by a 4.4% loss in American Airlines Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          AAL, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                 was also pressured by Trump\u2019s executive order to restrict immigration as it led to protests at airports across the country. The US Global Jets ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           JETS, -0.47%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0fell 2.1%.', u'Energy companies led the S&P 500 index lower with shares of Range Resources Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          RRC, -1.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Chesapeake Energy Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          CHK, -1.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Transocean Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                          RIG, +0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and Cabot Oil and Gas Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          COG, -1.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0all falling more than 5%.', u' Mylan NV                                                                                                                                                                                                           MYL, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares declined 0.9% following a report that the drugmaker is facing a U.S. antitrust probe over its EpiPen injector. ', u' Tempur Sealy                                                                                                                                                                                                           TPX, -2.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sank 28% after Mattress Firm terminated contracts with the company.', u' Other markets: The FTSE 100 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.87%                                                                                                                                                \xa0advanced 0.3% while the Stoxx Europe 600                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.73%                                                                                                                                                \xa0declined 0.9%, amid negative reaction to Trump\u2019s immigration ban. In Asia, the Nikkei 225 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           NIK, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed down 0.5%, largely due to yen strength. Most Asian markets were closed for the Lunar New Year holiday. ', u' Oil prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 1% to settle at $52.63 a barrel, while gold prices                                                                                                                                                                                                          GCJ7, +0.30%                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed 0.4% to settle at $1,196.00 an ounce. ', u'  \u2014Barbara Kollmeyer in Madrid contributed to this report.  ']

Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         20 stocks that will help you sleep at night\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Thus, we have compiled a list of stocks that have turned out to be long-term winners \u2014 and may continue to be. We did a similar article in November 2015.', u'But \u201cthe investor of today does not profit from yesterday\u2019s growth,\u201d according to Berkshire Hathaway                                                                                                                                                                                                           BRK.B, -0.41%                                                                                                                                                \xa0CEO Warren Buffett. So we have to look ahead as well.', u' Also see: This little-noticed phenomenon could make stock picking great again', u'To come up with a filtered list of S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0companies with the highest average ROIC, we added some measures of shorter-term performance and also looked ahead. The companies making the list had to show increases in sales per share over the past 12 months and for the past quarter, and analysts\u2019 consensus estimates had to predict increases in sales and earnings in 2017 and 2018.', u' Here are the 20 S&P 500 companies meeting the above criteria that have had the highest returns on invested capital over the past five years, according to FactSet: ', u' Here\u2019s how these companies have grown their sales per share for the most recent reported quarter and 12-month period: ', u' And here\u2019s how analysts expect earnings per share to increase for these companies this year and in 2018: ', u' Here\u2019s a summary of analyst ratings for the group, as well as forward price-to-earnings ratios, based on consensus earnings estimates for 2017 and 2018: ', u'In comparison, the S&P 500 trades for 17.8 times aggregate 2017 EPS estimates and for 15.9 times the 2018 aggregate, according to FactSet. The only company on the list trading below either of those P/E ratios is AutoZone Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AZO, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                ']

Name: Baker Hughes Incorporated
Article: 13 : [u'\r\n         Baker Hughes reports a rise in U.S. oil-rig count for fifth week in a row\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Data from Baker Hughes                                                                                                                                                                                                           BHI, +0.80%                                                                                                                                                 Friday revealed that the number of active U.S. rigs drilling for oil rose by 6 to 597 rigs this week. That marked the fifth weekly increase in a row. The total active U.S. rig count, which includes oil and natural-gas rigs, also rose by 10 to 751, according to Baker Hughes. March West Texas Intermediate crude                                                                                                                                                                                                           CLH7, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                held onto earlier declines after the figures, trading down 15 cents, or 0.3%, at $53.21 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. ']

Name: Whole Foods Market, Inc.
Article: 10 : [u'\r\n         One big sign this commodity\u2019s on the verge of an \u2018epic comeback\u2019\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Oil has been under pressure since the API said late Tuesday that U.S. crude stockpiles spiked by 14.2 million barrels last week. If the EIA data due later follow that trend, it should mark the biggest weekly gain in U.S. supplies since October. Note, the EIA also said Tuesday that the global oil glut is disappearing faster than expected. ', u'And any pickup in pressure on crude comes as hedge funds make record bets that oil prices will rise \u2014 something that\u2019s been going on a while. ', u'Our call of the day deals with another big commodity. From the Daily Reckoning blog, Greg Guenthner thinks gold prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCH7, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0could jump 20% over the next several weeks. ', u'Guenthner says gold\u2019s advance in the first six weeks of 2017 has \u201cperfectly mirrored\u201d action seen in the same period in 2016. The precious metal is looking at its fifth-straight winning session on Wednesday , as signs of instability in Europe add to growing skittishness over POTUS\u2019s political agenda.', u'What could stand in gold\u2019s way? Unrelenting equity gains (see our chart of the day for a dissenting view) and a dollar that keeps moving up.
