Name: Twenty-First Century Fox, Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Heinz passes on pricy Super Bowl ad, gives some employees a day off instead\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The iconic ketchup maker                                                                                                                                                                                                           KHC, +0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0announced that rather than fork out the dough for one of those coveted 30-second spots, it\u2019s giving salaried employees the next day off \u2014 that is Feb. 6, the Monday after Sunday\u2019s NFL championship is played between the New England Patriots and the Atlanta Falcons. Kraft has named and hashtagged it #smunday, in the hopes that they\u2019ll gain some publicity and create a trend.', u'\u201cIt\u2019s really all about how the Monday after the big game is one of the worst days of the year,\u201d Nicole Kulwicki, head of brand build for Heinz told AdvertisingAge. \u201cNobody wants to go back to work.\u201d', u'The company even started a change.org petition to \u201cMake the Monday after the \u2018Big Game\u2019 a National Holiday!\u201d of which over 3,000 supporters to date have signed among the 5,000 name slots requested. The petition will be sent to the U.S. House of Representatives and the Senate. ', u'Here\u2019s the video that Kraft put together, which includes stats about how the country loses $1 billion dollars on the day from lost productivity and employees calling in sick. It even features a cameo appearance from a forlorn \u201cWeiner Stampede\u201d dog from last year\u2019s Super Bowl ad: ', u'However, by giving just salaried workers time off, Heinz may have drawn some unwelcome publicity as well. Comments on Twitter and the company\u2019s Facebook page asked why only salaried, and not hourly, workers get the perk. According to Bloomberg, Heinz\u2019s factories will keep humming on that Monday. ', u'Perhaps one deterrent to engage in the competitive Super Bowl ad race this year is the cost. There\u2019s a $5 million and up price tag reportedly being asked by game broadcaster Fox                                                                                                                                                                                                           FOX, +1.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, a subsidiary of News Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          NWSA, -0.56%                                                                                                                                                                              NWS, -0.58%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. News Corp. is also the owner of MarketWatch, the publisher of this report. That\u2019s more than double the cost in 2010, according to some number crunching from eBay                                                                                                                                                                                                           EBAY, +1.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0-owned online ticket exchange StubHub and marketing group Column Five, which produced this graphic of costs:', u' Read:  Shoppers expected to spend $14.1 billion on Super Bowl LI, down from last year ', u'While Heinz\u2019s employees-first Super Bowl move may or not may not pay off, the ante has already been upped this year, with Mars-owned Snickers readying to air the first-ever live ad, starring actor Adam Driver. The ad will be preceded by a 36-hour live stream from the commercial\u2019s set that will run from noon Eastern on Feb. 2 until the evening of Feb. 3. ']

Name: Kohl's Corporation
Article: 9 : [u"\r\n         Kohl's shares rise after earnings beat, dividend raised\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Kohl\'s Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KSS, -0.88%                                                                                                                                                 shares rose 3.2% in Thursday premarket trading after the retailer announced fourth-quarter earnings that beat expectations and raised its dividend. Net income was $252.0 million, or $1.44 per share, down from $296.0 million, or $1.58 per share, last year. The FactSet consensus was $1.33. Sales were $6.2 billion, down from $6.4 billion last year but meeting the FactSet consensus. The sales slide was attributed to "declines in brick-and-mortar traffic, and offset somewhat by strength in online demand," said Chief Executive Kevin Mansell in a statement. Same-store sales declined 2.2%, while the FactSet consensus was for a 2.1% decline. Kohl\'s quarterly dividend of 55 cents per share is 10% higher year-over-year and payable March 22, 2017 to shareholders of record at the close of business on March 8, 2017. Kohl\'s expects fiscal 2017 EPS of $3.50 to $3.80. The FactSet consensus is $3.66. The company expects a sales change between down 1.3% and up 0.7%. And same-store sales are expected to range from 2% decline to flat. Kohl\'s shares are down 7% for the past year while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                 is up 23% for the same period.']

Name: American Express Company
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Why companies are paying for IVF for their workers but don\u2019t want to talk about it\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Yet a handful of states might finally be giving reproductive health the attention it deserves: A new bill to expand infertility coverage was introduced in the New York state legislature last month and similar efforts are underway in Mississippi, New Jersey and South Carolina.', u'The proposed legislation comes as more companies dangle ever-generous infertility benefits packages as part of a \u201cfamily-friendly\u201d perks race intended to retain female employees. In the latest high-profile announcement, American Express now offers employees up to $35,000 in coverage for baby-making services, including IVF and medication. ', u'Companies are increasingly filling the void because the U.S. health care system doesn\u2019t deem treating infertility \u2014 a condition affecting 1 in 8 U.S. couples \u2014 a medical necessity. Only 15 states require that policies cover any kind of infertility benefits, and only eight mandates include IVF, which fertility doctors regard as the gold standard of treatment. ', u'Although the number of employers offering infertility benefits has remained steady over the last few years \u2014 at 26%, according to the Society for Human Resource Management \u2014 there are two trends worth noting: A handful of companies, such as Intel                                                                                                                                                                                                           INTC, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and AmEx                                                                                                                                                                                                           AXP, +0.15%                                                                                                                                                 recently upped their coverage. And despite tech companies leading the charge to keep more women in their field, other industries are also being represented, says Anderson-Bialis, whose FertilityIQ ranked the top companies to work for as fertility patients. ', u'For example, chemical giant BASF                                                                                                                                                                                                           BASF, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added a $10,000 benefit in 2015. Insurance provider                                                                                                                                                                                                           MET, -1.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa025,000 benefit comes with a call-in advice nurse service to walk patients through the process. And Bank of America                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, -1.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 offers unlimited coverage for IVF and medications. \u201cWhen these big companies provide these benefits, they are normalizing that this is something that\u2019s important,\u201d says Stapleton.', u' Sarah Elizabeth Richards writes extensively about fertility and is the author of \u2018Motherhood, Rescheduled: The New Frontier of Egg Freezing and the Women Who Tried it.\u2019']

Name: Straight Path Communications Inc.
Article: 1 : [u"\r\n         Straight Path's stock rockets after FCC settlement clears way for review of strategic alternatives\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Straight Path Communications Inc.\'s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           STRP, -1.84%                                                                                                                                                 rocketed 54% toward a 15-month high in premarket trade Thursday, after the wireless spectrum holder announced a settlement with the Federal Communications Commissions that clears the way for the company to review strategic alternatives. The stock was on track to open at the highest level since October 2015. As part of the settlement, the FCC has ended its investigation related to Straight Path\'s wireless spectrum licenses, leaving the "vast majority" of its 39 gigahertz spectrum intact, and its 28 gigahertz spectrum unchanged. "With this settlement, we have cleared the way for a review of strategic alternatives to maximize shareholder value," said Chief Executive Davidi Jonas. "To represent us in our endeavors, we have retained Evercore, a premier independent investment banking advisory firm." The stock had more than doubled over the past 12 months through Wednesday, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                 had climbed 17%.']

Name: Prologis, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Prologis boosts dividend by nearly 5%\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Prologis Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PLD, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                 said Thursday that it raised its quarterly dividend by nearly 5% to 44 cents a share from 42 cents a share. The logistic real estate company\'s new dividend will be payable March 31 to shareholders of record on March 15. Based on current share prices, the new annual dividend rate of $1.76 a share represents a dividend yield of 3.49%, compared with the aggregate S&P 500 dividend yield of 2.01%, according to FactSet. The stock, which was up 0.2% in afternoon trade, has run up 33% over the past three months, while the SPDR Real Estate Select Sector ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLRE, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 6.6% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                 has rallied 23%.']

Article: 11 : [u'\r\n         Platts overhauls Brent crude benchmark, adds field\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The existing basket used to set the price includes Brent Ninian Blend, Forties, Oseberg and Ekofisk. The addition of Troll, a field operated by Norway\'s Statoil ASA                                                                                                                                                                                                           STO, -0.75%                                                                                                                                                 should increase deliverable supplies by around 20%. It will also mean Statoil overtakes Royal Dutch Shell PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           RDSA                                                                                                                                                 as the most dominant producer of the streams used to calculate the Brent price.']

Name: Amgen Inc.
Article: 17 : [u'\r\n         S&P 500, Nasdaq end at records after solid jobs report\r\n    ']
Body: [u' The U.S. economy created 156,000 jobs last month, below the consensus of 180,000 forecast by the economists polled by MarketWatch. However, sharp upward revisions for November jobs number and a slight trimming of October number means the latest payrolls were more or less in line, according to analysts. ', u'The main indexes maintained gains after news reports that multiple people have been shot and killed Friday at the Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport. ', u'The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed 7.98 points, or 0.4%, higher at 2,276, with eight of the 11 main sectors were finishing with gains, led by technology and financials shares. The telecoms sector was the biggest laggard, falling 2.7%. Over the week, the benchmark index gained 1.7%.', u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 64.51 points, or 0.3%, to 19,963.80, after coming within a whisker to the psychologically important 20,000 level. At session highs, the Dow hit 19,999.63, setting an intraday record. The blue-chip index rose 1% over the week.', u' See: All of the important Dow milestones in one chart ', u' Also read: What Dow 20,000 means for stock-market investors ', u'The Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was the day\u2019s best performer among stock-market indexes, advancing 33.12 points, or 0.6%, to 5,521.06. The tech-heavy index gained 2.6% over the week.', u'A jobs report that was close enough to the consensus lifted the dollar and yields. The rebound in the dollar comes a day after the greenback dropped by the most since July 2016. That slide came after minutes from the Fed\u2019s December meeting pointed to a number of risks that could change the path of its policy. ', u'The ICE Dollar Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, +0.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 0.7% to 102.24. Meanwhile, the yield on the 10-year Treasury also rebounded, rising 7 basis points to 2.42%. ', u' Fed speakers: There were a number of hawkish comments from Fed speakers on Friday. Cleveland Fed President Loretta Mester said she would like to see the central bank raise interest rates more than the three quarter-percentage-point moves favored by the majority of her colleagues. ', u' Movers and shakers: Shares of Amgen Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          AMGN, +0.11%                                                                                                                                                 jumped 2.5% after a federal judge said rivals Regeneron Pharmaceuticals Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          REGN, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                 and Sanofi SA                                                                                                                                                                                                           SAN, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                                              SNY, +0.61%                                                                                                                                                \xa0must pull their competing cholesterol drug Praluent off the market as a penalty in a patent lawsuit. Regeneron shares sold off, falling 5.8%.', u'Shares of Ruby Tuesday Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          RT, -1.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0plunged 25% after the restaurant chain late Thursday reported a wider second-quarter loss following a double-digit drop in revenue.', u' Gap Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GPS, -0.39%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gave up most of the gains, finishing only 0.4% higher after the retailer late Thursday reported growing holiday sales. ', u' AT&T Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.82%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares plunged 2% after news reports on Thursday that President-elect Donald Trump is still opposed to the merger with Time Warner, a view he expressed during the campaign.', u' Other markets: Stocks in Asia closed mostly lower, and European markets closed mixed. ', u' Gold prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:GCG7                                                                                                                                                \xa0pulled back after a three-day rally, settling 0.7% lower at $1,173.40 an ounce, but still logged a second straight weekly gain. Meanwhile WTI crude-oil futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLG7                                                                                                                                                 settled 0.4% higher at $53.99 a barrel, posting fourth straight weekly gain.']

Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Stock market notches best record run in quarter century\r\n    ']

Morgan Chase & Co. Morgan & Co.) , McDonald\u2019s Corp. Name: The Kraft Heinz Company
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Here\u2019s what to look for Saturday in Warren Buffett\u2019s annual letter\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Berkshire Hathaway\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                          BRK.A, +0.35%                                                                                                                                                                              BRK.B, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                annual letter to investors is set for release at 8 a.m. Eastern. The yearly epistle is eagerly read by an audience much wider than Berkshire investors for insights into the mind-set of the legendary investor and world\u2019s third richest person.', u'Buffett tipped his hand in a December interview with Fortune. While he has made his world-beating fortune picking stocks, he\u2019s virtually evangelical on the allure of the passive, follow-the-market approach for the bulk of investors.', u'Passive investing \u201cwill beat active over time,\u201d he told the magazine. \u201cBut not for the manager. The manager\u2019s going to make money out of active, and the investor\u2019s going to do better with passive. I\u2019m writing a lot about this subject in next year\u2019s annual report. I really am. A lot.\u201d', u' See: This little-noticed phenomenon could make stock picking great again ', u' Also read: Wall Street pushes active management, but investors aren\u2019t biting ', u'On that note, Buffett looks all but certain to win a wager he made in 2007 betting that index funds could outperform hedge funds. Buffett\u2019s pick, the Vanguard 500 Index Fund Admiral Shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           VFIAX, -1.69%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, is easily outpacing the basket of hedge funds selected by asset manager Protege partners. The bet ends Dec. 31, and it would take a massive market drop for Buffett to lose, as the Wall Street Journal noted this week. ', u'But, as MarketWatch\u2019s Francine McKenna noted this week, Berkshire has also used alternative financial metrics over the past three years that are considered to be non-GAAP\u2014instances that Buffett defended in last year\u2019s letter. It will be interesting to see whether Buffett has more to say on the issue this year.', u'Don\u2019t expect the letter to offer much insight into the quickly abandoned bid by Kraft Heinz Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KHC, +0.76%                                                                                                                                                 , which is backed by Berkshire and private-equity firm 3G, for Unilever PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           ULVR, +0.12%                                                                                                                                                 , since the annual missives tend to instead focus on the performance of Berkshire over the past year.', u' See: SEC wants earnings to comply with its rules and it won\u2019t take no for an answer ']

Name: Revlon, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Revlon unveils new corporate structure\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Revlon Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           REV, -1.89%                                                                                                                                                 announced an organizational restructuring Tuesday to focus on four distinct brands, including its namesake Revlon cosmetics brand, the hair coloring and cosmetics brand Elizabeth Arden, which it purchased for $870 million last September, as well as two others focused on fragrances and portfolio brands. The company said the move will streamline and simplify the business, giving it the opportunity to more easily meet its long-term growth targets in the global beauty industry. Shares of Revlon were inactive in premarket trade, but they\'ve underperformed both in the last three months and the past year. They\'ve declined 9% in the past three months, compared with a 7% increase for the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                 and are up 15% from three months ago, compared with an increase of 21% for the index.']

Name: Morgan Stanley
Article: 12 : [u'\r\n         Why stocks are holding up through the Trump turbulence \u2014 and what\u2019s next\r\n    ']
Body: [u'But the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0isn\u2019t sweating much, as it smokes a cigarette just a bit below last week\u2019s record close and cruises toward a modest loss for this week. ', u'The stock gauge has been in \u201cdo nothing\u201d mode in the last few sessions, as our stat of the day shows. Today\u2019s jobs report might be inspiring some buying, but there has been a lot of angst lately.', u'Yet in fact, \u201cpredicting what the market will do based on what is going on in D.C. is just, well, fruitless,\u201d says the Arbeter Investments technical analyst, who provides our call of the day. ', u'It\u2019s telling \u2014 and not encouraging \u2014 that Facebook                                                                                                                                                                                                          FB, +0.45%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and Microsoft\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           MSFT, +1.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0stocks have slumped after initially popping higher on better-than-expected earnings, he adds. Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Dow logs 10th straight record, but Nasdaq stumbles a second day\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                 closed up 34.72 points, or 0.2%, at a record 20,810.32, led by gains in health-care stocks Pfizer Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          PFE, -0.41%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Johnson & Johnson Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          JNJ, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                 ', u' See also: Charting the Dow\u2019s longest record-setting streak since 1987 ', u'The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                 finished up 0.99 points at 2,363.81, just short of Tuesday\u2019s closing record of 2,365.38, led by gains in utilities and telecom shares, but held back by declines in the industrials and consumer-discretionary sectors, even as manufacturing CEOs met with President Donald Trump at the White House Thursday. The benchmark index set a intraday record of 2,368.00 before retreating.', u'The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                          COMP, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                 saw the worst daily performance among the major equity benchmarks, off 25.12 points, or 0.4%, to close at 5,835.51. The index was weighed down by shares of Nvidia Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NVDA, +0.28%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Tesla Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          TSLA, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                Meanwhile, the Technology Select Sector SPDR ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLK, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                 declined 0.1%, snapping a 13-day winning streak, the longest such streak ever for the ETF.', u'The Nasdaq\u2019s decline for a second day in a row marks the first time in 2017 that the index has seen back-to-back drops', u'Markets have been in an uptrend since Trump\u2019s election in November, but concerns have been growing that economic fundamentals don\u2019t justify current market prices. By one measure, stock valuations are at their highest level since 2004.', u' Read: Mnuchin says the stock market is a report card. Here\u2019s where you can find the grade ', u' Oil rally: An oil price rally helped to lift shares of U.S. energy giants. Crude oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0settled up 1.6% at $54.45 a barrel while data showed crude inventories rose by a smaller-than-expected 600,000 barrels in the latest week.', u' Read: Why oil experts think OPEC\u2019s U.S. headache won\u2019t go away this year ', u' And: OPEC chief Barkindo plays down threat from rise in U.S. oil output ', u'Shares of Dow component Exxon Mobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                closed up 1.1%, while shares of Transocean Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                           RIG, +0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 7.8% and Valero Energy Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          VLO, -0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0advanced 1.6%.', u' Stock movers: Among other stock-market movers, shares of Tesla dropped 6.4% after the electric-car maker late Wednesday reported a wider-than-expected quarterly loss, though its beat sales expectations. ', u'Nvidia shares closed down 9.3% after a round of bearish analyst comments prompted investors to take profits from the highflying chip maker, which has more than tripled over the past 12 months. Instinet downgraded the stock to reduce from buy, while BMO Capital Markets cut its price target to $85 from $100.', u'On the other hand, shares of HP Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          HPQ, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rallied 8.6% after quarterly results topped Wall Street estimates. Also, shares of First Solar Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          FSLR, -2.82%                                                                                                                                                \xa0led S&P 500 gainers, rising 11%.', u'On a downbeat note, shares of L Brands Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          LB, -3.25%                                                                                                                                                sank 16% after the Victoria\u2019s Secret parent late Wednesday issued weaker-than-forecast guidance for 2017. ', u' Hormel Foods Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HRL, -0.42%                                                                                                                                                shares lost 5.4% after the food company cut its earnings forecast for the year following a sharp decline in profit from its Jennie-O turkey brand. ', u' Kohl\u2019s Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KSS, -1.38%                                                                                                                                                shares, which had traded higher earlier after earnings beating forecasts, closed down 2.1%', u' Economic news: In the latest economic data, the number of U.S. workers who applied for unemployment benefits rose slightly in the latest week, but layoffs remained near ultralow levels last seen in the early 1970s.', u' See: MarketWatch\u2019s economic calendar ', u' Other markets: Stocks in Asia closed mostly lower as investors pored over the Fed minutes. ', u' European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.76%                                                                                                                                                bounced between gains and losses after a string of corporate updates and finished down 0.1%. ', u'Gold                                                                                                                                                                                                          GCJ7, +0.28%                                                                                                                                                 prices rose 1.5% to settle at $1,251.40, their best finish in three months, while silver                                                                                                                                                                                                          SIH7, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 finished up 0.9%. The ICE Dollar index                                                                                                                                                                                                          DXY, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                was slightly lower at 100.98.', u' \u2014Sara Sjolin in London contributed to this article.  ']

Name: Abbott Laboratories
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Happy St Patrick\u2019s Day! America braces for a multibillion-dollar hangover\r\n    ']
Body: [u'With St. Patrick\u2019s Day falling on a Friday this year, spending is expected to reach a $5.3 billion, up from $4.4 billion last year, according to the industry trade group National Retail Federation; that\u2019s the highest in the federation\u2019s 13-year history of the survey. Some 27% of that money will go on a party or a bar. If New Year\u2019s Day is the Super Bowl for hangover cures, as described by Brenna Haysom, president of Rally Labs, which makes \u201cBlowfish for Hangovers,\u201d then St. Patrick\u2019s Day is March Madness, particularly as most of the time green-clad revellers have to work the next day.', u'Over-the-counter antacids to relieve stomach upsets alone are estimated to reach $810 million in 2021, versus $714 million three years ago, according to Euromonitor. They include products like Alka-Seltzer Gummies and ones specifically marketed for the purpose like Blowfish for Hangovers ($12 for 12 tablets). Herbal and dietary supplements \u2014 including hangover treatments like PartySmart and Drinkin\u2019 Mate \u2014 are projected to hit $2.1 billion in 2021, up from $1.6 billion in 2013. And adult pain relievers \u2014 over-the-counter medicines like aspirin, ibuprofen (including Advil) and acetaminophen (Tylenol) \u2014 will hit $4.1 billion in 2021, up from $3.8 billion in 2013. ', u'Perhaps the most expensive and desperate hangover cures are intravenous drips, typically used successfully to rehydrate people with influenza in hospitals to restore nutrients and fluids, but they\u2019re not covered by health insurance for hangovers. There clinics include Reviv Wellness Spa in Miami, IVme in Chicago and Hangover Heaven in Las Vegas, which rehydrate people intravenously. (The latter has received mostly positive reviews on Yelp.) Although IVme also treats athletes, the clinic has a hangover IV of saline, vitamins and an anti-inflammatory pain medicine, anti-nausea and anti-reflux medications for $129 (or $149 for another IV with oxygen). ', u' Don\u2019t miss: 10 things Coke, Pepsi and the soda industry won\u2019t say  ', u'Americans are also getting creative \u2014 and thrifty \u2014 when it comes to treating their sore heads. Gatorade ($12 for a six-pack) and Pedialyte ($5 for an 8-fluid-ounce bottle) have cult followings as hangover treatments. Pedialyte, an Abbott Laboratories                                                                                                                                                                                                           ABT, -0.15%                                                                                                                                                 brand, was originally marketed to treat dehydration in children with diarrhea. The company\u2019s Twitter handle has the slogan: \u201cNot just for kids, adults can use Pedialyte too.\u201d Gatorade, which is owned by PepsiCo                                                                                                                                                                                                           PEP, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                 is a sports drink that contains sucrose, glucose, fructose, sodium and potassium. And that doesn\u2019t include sales of caffeine-rich energy drinks, seen rising to $21.5 billion by 2017 from $12.5 billion just three years ago, according to market research group Packaged Facts. ', u'Excessive drinking is defined as binge drinking (four or more drinks per occasion for women and five or more drinks per occasion for men), high weekly use and any alcohol use by pregnant women or those under age 21, the CDC says. However, binge drinking \u2014 reported by one in six American adults \u2014 is responsible for about three-quarters of these costs. Another major impact that won\u2019t be cured by tablets: Excessive alcohol use is estimated to kill about 88,000 people in the U.S. each year, shortening those lives by an average of 30 years. Furthermore, excessive drinking was responsible for 1 in 10 deaths among working-age adults aged 20 to 64 years, the CDC adds.']

Name: Alphabet Inc.
Article: 15 : [u'\r\n        ', u' How to trade Snap \u2014 if the stock goes to $10 or $100\r\n    ']
Body: [u'So investors are naturally asking me: How do I trade Snap                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +5.15%                                                                                                                                                ? Will Snap become successful like Facebook                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                ? Will Snap\u2019s stock shoot up like Twitter\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWTR, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                 only to fizzle? Since Snap is marketing itself as a video-camera company, is a comparison to GoPro\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           GPRO, -1.31%                                                                                                                                                 IPO appropriate?', u' How to trade Snap ', u'The annotated chart shows The Arora Report\u2019s calls on Snap. (Please click here for the annotated chart.) The posture that The Arora Report has taken is to trade the stock but not invest in it at this time. We have \u201cjust in case\u201d defensive stops in place and are taking profits on half of the position and continuing to hold the remainder for a little longer to see if momentum drives the stock higher.', u' Comparison to GoPro ', u'GoPro at its core is a hardware company that markets itself as a content company. Its IPO was hotter than Snap\u2019s. The stock shot up several fold in price and then crashed, and it now trades for under $10. Just like GoPro, Snap is marketing itself as a video-camera company, but it is different in that, at its core, it\u2019s an advertising company. When GoPro came public, I did not hesitate to slap a $10 target on it at a time when the stock was popular and soaring. You can see my reasoning here. ', u' Comparison to Facebook ', u'Snap, as I said, is an advertising company \u2014 just like Facebook and Alphabet                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOG, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Bulls contend that Snap can succeed just like Facebook. However, investors must note a big difference: Facebook had a wider appeal from the beginning, whereas Snap so far has appealed to a limited demographic of younger people. ', u'At The Arora Report, we bought the Facebook IPO, took profits on the very first day and exited the trade. We bought it again at $49.92, have stayed steadfastly bullish on it, and still hold it. Please see \u201cMarket correction suggests Facebook may be the next Apple\u201d and \u201cFacebook ad prices double; will the stock also?\u201d ', u' Comparison to Twitter ', u'Please see \u201cBack up the truck and buy the Twitter IPO\u201d and \u201cWhy, and how, you should trade the Twitter IPO.\u201d', u' My take on Snap ', u'My long-time readers know well that my core principle is to be brutally honest with investors. I often tell investors what they do not want to hear. I follow the ZYX Change Method to analyze stocks. According to the ZYX Change Method, the uncertainty surrounding Snap at this time is so great that the stock is simply not analyzable as an investment with a high degree of confidence for the long run. The stock can easily go down to $10 or shoot up to $100. The short term is another story, as it is not driven by fundamentals but by momentum, psychology and market mechanics.', u' Our plan on Snap ', u' Disclosure: Subscribers to The Arora Report may have positions in the securities mentioned in this article or may take positions at any time. All recommended positions are reviewed daily at The Arora Report. ', u' Nigam Arora is an investor, engineer and nuclear physicist by background, has founded two Inc. 500 fastest-growing companies, is the developer of the adaptive ZYX Global Multi Asset Allocation Model and the ZYX Change Method to profit from change in trading and investing. He is the founder of The Arora Report, which publishes four newsletters. Nigam can be reached at Nigam@TheAroraReport.com. ']

Name: V.F. Corporation
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         VF Corp. downgraded on executive turnover, hurdles for The North Face\r\n    ']
Body: [u'VF Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           VFC, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                 was downgraded to hold from buy at Canaccord Genuity on concerns over executive departures and competition facing The North Face brand. The price target was cut to $54 from $64. Shares are down 1.2% in Thursday trading, and hit their lowest point in more than three years. VFC, whose brands include Wrangler and Timberland in addition to The North Face, has a new chief executive, Steven Rendle, as of Jan. 1. The company\'s group president of VF International, Karl Heinz Salzburger, also announced that he would retire at the end of 2017. Canaccord analysts also learned that The North Face\'s Chief Executive Todd Spaletto would be leaving the company after 13 years. Analysts believe these departures, at least, will lead to a period of adjustment or, at worst, could indicate greater challenges. Aside from executive issues, Canaccord analysts are also concerned that cold December weather wasn\'t enough to offset weakness between September and November. With growing competition from brands like Canada Goose and Columbia Sportswear Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           COLM, -1.55%                                                                                                                                                 and a "lull in innovation," the brand has lost market share, analysts said. Canaccord forecasts a "reset likely coming" on the Mar. 30 analyst day "from what had been high-single digit revenue growth to mid-single digit growth for its outlook period." VF Corp. shares are down 10.1% for the past year while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                 is up 16.4% for the same period.']

Name: Pluristem Therapeutics, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Pluristem shares jump 5.4% premarket as FDA approves trial of treatment for critical limb ischemia\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Pluristem Therapeutics Inc. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           PSTI, -1.67%                                                                                                                                                 surged 5.4% in premarket trade Tuesday, after the company said the U.S. Food and Drug Administration has granted approval for a late-stage trial of PLX-PAD cells in the treatment of critical limb ischemia, or CLI. CLI is a condition in which fatty deposits block arteries in the leg, reducing blood flow and causing pain, non-healing ulcers, and gangrene. Patients suffering from CLI often require limb amputation. Pluristem, an Israeli developer of placenta-based cell therapy products, said it will use the Phase III study of its PLX-PAD cells to support an application for a marketing approval for the treatment. The company is aiming to start enrolling patients in the U.s. and Europe in the first half of 2017. Shares have gained 47% in the last 18 months, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 18%. ']

Morgan analyst Rod Hall, who doesn\u2019t have a rating on HPE\u2019s stock, said the report was ugly, while UBS\u2019s Steven Milunovich, who has a buy rating on the stock and a price target of $27, said it was HPE\u2019s \u201cmessiest quarter yet\u201d since spinning off from HP Inc.
