HP Inc. reported earnings late Thursday and topped expectations.', u' See also:  HP revenue grows on PC sales, but challenges ahead ', u'HPE stock fell 7.9% to $22.73 in afternoon trade. Its shares are down 3.5% in the past three months, compared with a 7% increase for the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. The stock has outperformed the S&P in the past year, despite three straight quarters of sales misses, increasing 68% compared with a 22% gain for the S&P. ']

Name: Aon plc
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Northwestern, arguably Big Ten\u2019s brainiest school, is no longer a basketball joke\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Northwestern sold out four men\u2019s basketball games in advance this season. It hadn\u2019t sold out a single game before game day in at least five years, Crain\u2019s Chicago Business reported. ', u'College-sports finance remains one of the most controversial sports topics \u2014 these are, after all, amateur players, kids really, all ostensibly pursuing a degree, but the cutthroat quest for donor money and state-of-the-art playing facilities is notorious. Northwestern student-athletes, in fact, led a failed effort in recent years to unionize in order to better protect their \u201cearnings.\u201d ', u'The arena remodel benefits from a major gift from insurer Aon                                                                                                                                                                                                           AON, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0founder Pat Ryan and others, including funds for an adjacent basketball practice facility. Two more trustees, Tim Sullivan and Jeff Ubben, last month gave the athletic department $3 million. Their names are now attached not to a building, but to a position: head coach Chris Collins will now be named the Sullivan-Ubben head men\u2019s basketball coach. ', u'Seven-figure revenue from Northwestern ticket sales and sponsors are still a fraction of the $40 million-plus that each Big Ten school reportedly will get annually as part of the league\u2019s new six-year, $2.6 billion broadcasting deal with Fox                                                                                                                                                                                                           NWS, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, ESPN                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and CBS                                                                                                                                                                                                           CBS, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0that kicks in later this year, Crain\u2019s noted. That money helps fund non-revenue sports, too. ', u'Some of its loudest fans are Emmy-winning actress Julia Louis-Dreyfus of \u201cVeep\u201d and \u201cSeinfeld\u201d renown and her writer/director/producer husband Brad Hall, who both attended Northwestern. Their son, Charlie Hall, is a walk-on for the Wildcats, and a radio/TV/film major who plays off the bench.', u' This story was originally published March 2, and has been updated to reflect Sunday\u2019s NCAA tournament selection. ']

Name: Time Warner Inc.
Article: 9 : [u'\r\n         R-rated \u2018Logan\u2019 tears up weekend box office with $85.3 million\r\n    ']
Body: [u'One year after 21st Century Fox Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           FOX, +1.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 movie studio opened \u201cDeadpool\u201d to a phenomenal $132.4 million, it debuted \u201cLogan,\u201d starring Hugh Jackman as Wolverine, to a strong $85.3 million in the U.S. and Canada, according to studio estimates. Both movies feature characters from Walt Disney Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DISN, +3.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0-owned Marvel\u2019s \u201cX-Men\u201d universe, for which Fox has controlled the big-screen rights since the 1990s.', u'Conventional wisdom in Hollywood has held that superhero movies should be rated PG-13 to maximize their box office by drawing teenagers. Every film from Disney\u2019s Marvel Studios and Time Warner Inc\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWX, -0.45%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 Warner Bros.\u2019 DC superhero unit has carried that more family-friendly rating. But with the raunchy \u201cDeadpool\u201d and, now, the dark and ultraviolent \u201cLogan,\u201d Fox has demonstrated that significant profits can also be found with movies aimed squarely at adults.', u'Riding fantastic word-of-mouth, ticket sales for \u201cGet Out\u201d dropped only 22% on its second weekend in theaters. Released by Comcast Corp.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           CMCSA, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 Universal Pictures, the race relations-themed horror film grossed $26.1 million, bringing its domestic box office total to $76 million.', u' An expanded version of this report appears on WSJ.com. ', u' Also popular on WSJ.com: ', u' Trump faces furor over unsubstantiated claim Obama wiretapped him. ', u' Keystone pipeline won\u2019t have to use U.S. steel despite Trump pledge. ']

Name: Janus Small/Mid Cap Growth Alpha ETF
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Can Janus make it in the ETF market?\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Janus Capital Group                                                                                                                                                                                                          JNS, -0.71%                                                                                                                                                 once an emblematic superstar money manager of the 1990s, never fully recovered from the subsequent dot-com crash. Assets have dropped from their 2000 peak of $324 billion to $199 billion as of Sept. 30\u2014a 39% decline. The firm has been particularly hard-hit from the more recent industry-wide exodus out of actively managed funds into index products; it lost $1.8 billion to outflows for the 12 months ending Sept. 30. \u201cFlows are concentrated in some very large fund companies with ETFs,\u201d says Patrick Davitt, a partner at Autonomous Research who covers Janus. \u201cJanus hasn\u2019t had a strong position there.\u201d', u'To shore itself up, Janus recently agreed to merge with British fund shop Henderson Group                                                                                                                                                                                                           HGG, -2.23%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in the second quarter of 2017. The merger will be a major cultural shift, giving the company a more global footprint and more than $320 billion in assets.', u'That isn\u2019t exactly true. If one looks at, for instance, Janus Small Cap Growth Alpha                                                                                                                                                                                                           JSML, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                 which opened last February, there are 13 other competing small-cap growth funds, each with their own strategy for picking growth stocks. The $5.5 billion Vanguard Small-Cap Growth                                                                                                                                                                                                           VBK, -0.30%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has the lowest expense ratio in the group, 0.08%, a fraction of the Janus ETF\u2019s 0.5%.', u'Yet Janus brings something unique to the table\u2014a bit of that 1990s star-manager flair. The small-cap ETF and its sibling Janus Small/Mid Cap Growth Alpha                                                                                                                                                                                                           JSMD, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are strategic-beta ETFs, which means the firm essentially codified its active stock-picking decisions into an index. Both were designed in-house by the same analytical team that runs Janus Triton                                                                                                                                                                                                           JATTX, -2.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Janus Venture                                                                                                                                                                                                           JAVTX, -2.01%                                                                                                                                                 two similar funds that have Bronze ratings from Morningstar and are closed to new investors.', u'Perhaps Janus\u2019 most promising new ETF is Janus Short Duration Income                                                                                                                                                                                                           VNLA, +0.11%                                                                                                                                                 which launched in November. Not only is the fund actively managed and thus in the firm\u2019s wheelhouse, but its management team at Kapstream Capital, which Janus acquired in 2015, has an excellent long-term record. \u201cKapstream is run by portfolio managers that Bill Gross originally hired at Pimco, who left to start their own firm in Australia in 2006,\u201d Cherney says. That strategy\u2014the $4.7 billion Kapstream Absolute Return Income, which the new ETF will resemble\u2014has produced a 5.3% annualized return since its inception in May 2007, beating its Australian short-term bond benchmark by 1.4 percentage points a year.', u'Though actively managed stock ETFs have yet to take off, active fixed-income ETFs from Pimco and DoubleLine Capital have done well in terms of both performance and asset-gathering. \u201cActively managed fixed income is the only active story in the ETF space that has attracted significant assets in the last couple of years,\u201d says Dave Nadig, CEO of ETF.com. \u201cJanus is taking a different angle here by offering a truly global fund. It isn\u2019t just buying the same short-term bonds everybody else is buying in the U.S. It falls into a similar category to the Pimco Enhanced Short Maturity Active                                                                                                                                                                                                           MINT, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                \u2014an enhanced cash-replacement fund.\u201d', u'Not all of Janus\u2019 new offerings are as noteworthy. Its thematic index ETFs for the health care sector\u2014Janus Health & Fitness                                                                                                                                                                                                           FITS, -1.75%                                                                                                                                                 Janus Obesity                                                                                                                                                                                                           SLIM, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 Janus                                                                                                                                                                                                           ORG, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 and Janus Long-Term Care                                                                                                                                                                                                           OLD, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \u2014seem gimmicky and dangerous, based more on generating cutesy tickers to market than on meeting legitimate investing goals. Each is focused on a sliver of an industry and is concentrated in just a handful of stocks. In the Long-Term Care ETF, for instance, just two stocks, Welltower                                                                                                                                                                                                           HCN, +0.55%                                                                                                                                                 and Ventas                                                                                                                                                                                                           VTR, +1.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, account for 40% of its portfolio, while Nike                                                                                                                                                                                                           NKE, -5.89%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and adidas Group                                                                                                                                                                                                           ADS, -0.51%                                                                                                                                                                              ADDYY, -0.52%                                                                                                                                                \xa0account for 37% of the Health & Fitness ETF. \u201cHighly concentrated portfolios are something Janus is known for historically, so I don\u2019t think that\u2019s particularly shocking,\u201d Cherney says.', u'  This article was first published in Barron\u2019s.   ']

Name: American International Group, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Stocks eke out gains as energy shares rebound  \r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 2.46 points to close at 20,858.19, while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0edged up 1.89 points to finish at 2,364.87, and the Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                 added 1.25 points to end at 5,838.81.', u'Energy stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLE, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                 which at one point had topped the S&P 500\u2019s losers, recovered to rise 0.6% as crude                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                 pared losses. Earlier, oil prices had fallen below $49 for the first time this year, a move that traders said had few obvious catalysts. ', u'Thursday marks the eighth anniversary of the bull market, based on the fact that the S&P 500 notched its bear-market closing low on March 9, 2009. The benchmark index has gone on to gain 249% since that point.', u' See: Stock investors can\u2019t bank on another 8-year bull-market bonanza ', u' Read: Bull market\u2019s 8-year anniversary reminds us that the Dow rewards the bold  ', u'Still, market action was muted as investors await the closely watched February jobs report due Friday.', u'Meanwhile, the European Central Bank left interest rates unchanged at its latest meeting, as had been widely expected. In a statement, the bank repeated that it expects rates to remain \u201cat present or lower levels for an extended period of time, and well past the horizon\u201d of its bond-buying program, which is scheduled to run through at least December. ', u' Read MarketWatch\u2019s recap of Draghi\u2019s statement and the ECB news conference ', u' Economic data: First-time jobless claims rose by 20,000 in the latest week, more than had been expected, though layoffs remained near a 45-year low. The news comes a day after a blowout read on private-sector employment by ADP.', u' Other markets: European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.56%                                                                                                                                                 rose following Draghi\u2019s comments. Asian markets largely closed with losses. Gold futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCH7, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0settled lower while a key dollar index                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, +0.05%                                                                                                                                                 slid.', u' Stock movers: Shares in Staples Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPLS, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 5.3% after the seller of office supplies posted weaker-than-expected earnings. ', u' Sears Holding Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHLD, -11.54%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 7% after the department store reported fourth-quarter revenue that beat expectations. The retailer has been struggling of late, having lost more than half its value over the past 12 months.', u' American International Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AIG, -0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0reversed gains to fall 0.4% after Peter Hancock, the company\u2019s chief executive, Peter Hancock, informed the board of his intention to resign. ', u' PPG Industries Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PPG, -0.99%                                                                                                                                                \xa0dropped 3.7% after the coatings producer\u2019s $22 billion offer for Dutch paints and chemicals maker Akzo Nobel NV                                                                                                                                                                                                           AKZA, -1.93%                                                                                                                                                                              AKZOY, -1.97%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was rejected. ', u' --Victor Reklaitis contributed to this report. ']

Name: Pandora Media, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Here\u2019s my update on seven stocks \u2014 from Apple to Sony\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Facebook (7) \u2014 The 800-pound gorilla of social networking and the app revolution. Instagram could have twice as many users as Twitter by the end of this year as it heads toward 600,000 million versus Twitter\u2019s somewhat stagnant base in the 300 million range. Then there is WhatsApp, now with over 1.2 billion users and has Facebook as a parent. The stock is at new all-time highs and I am just sitting steady on my large Facebook position for now.', u' Google (7) \u2014 Google has been on a tear since February. Within 2% of its all-time high and up 250% in the past five years, Google has been hot for a while. As a matter of fact, it\u2019s up more than 1,500% since I first bought it on the day it became public. Android is still probably the single biggest driver of this stock right now. Interestingly, Amazon\u2019s Alexa voice-activated artificial intelligent platform is a big threat to Android \u2014 an even bigger threat for Google\u2019s Android operating system than it is for Apple\u2019s iPhone/Siri. The reason is that Apple makes the hardware and Android, as a software platform, gets less relevant as Alexa becomes more dominant.']

Body: [u' Don\u2019t miss: America doesn\u2019t just need more factory jobs; it needs more good jobs ', u' Opinion: Donald Trump can bully auto makers all he wants, but he can\u2019t repeal the laws of economics ', u'The president highlighted his talks with Lockheed Martin Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          LMT, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                Chief Executive Marilyn Hewson over the costs of her company\u2019s F-35 fighter jet, which he said led to a more than $700 million saving for the government. \u201cShe\u2019s tough, but it worked out well I think for everybody,\u201d Trump told the group. ', u' Don\u2019t miss: Mnuchin in no rush to label China a currency manipulator ', u' Also:  Trump may struggle to live up to campaign promises on China ', u'Other prominent attendees included General Electric Co. ', u'On Wednesday, the Business Roundtable, a trade group representing large U.S. companies, delivered a letter to the White House outlining the regulations it would like to see repealed or modified by the Trump administration, as the Wall Street Journal reported.', u' See: Chris Christie reportedly turned down labor secretary offer ', u' See:  Trump is playing a starring role on U.S. companies\u2019 quarterly conference calls ', u'Companies are less enthused by Trump\u2019s stance on immigration and trade, which they fear will hamper their ability to hire foreign talent and could potentially trigger a trade war. ', u'U.S. companies are generally welcoming of deregulatory moves and a lowering of corporate taxes, which are the highest in the world. But they are divided on Trump\u2019s proposed border tax, which would levy as much as a 20% tax on imports, while exempting exporters through rebates. Major exporters, including Dow Chemical, favor the tax, while major importers like retailers are aggressively opposed to it. ', u'U.S. Steel Corp. Inc. Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         USA Today owner Gannett beat Q4 revenue and profit, but print advertising still declining\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Gannett Co. Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCI, -0.99%                                                                                                                                                 shares rose nearly 9% in premarket trade on Thursday after the USA Today owner reported fourth-quarter earnings that were better than Wall Street had forecast. Gannett posted net income of $24.6 million, or 21 cents per share, improved compared with last year\'s $20.4 million, or 17 cents during the same quarter a year ago. Adjusted per-share earnings for the quarter were 50 cents, well above FactSet\'s 39 cents consensus. Revenue for the quarter hit $867.0 million, up from $739.3 million in the year-earlier period, and above FactSet\'s consensus of $849.0 million. Gannett\'s print advertising and circulation demand continued to decline in the quarter, with print advertising revenue at USA Today falling 15.3% in the US and 14.2% in the U.K. Gannett shares are down more than 41% in the trailing 12-month period, while the S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                 is up nearly 24%.']

Name: Wells Fargo & Company
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         Bank stocks get a big boost as jobs data lifts Treasury yields\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Bank stocks rallied in premarket trade Wednesday, boosted by a rise in Treasury yields following a blowout private-sector jobs report. The SPDR Financial Select Sector ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLF, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                 climbed 0.9%. Among the ETF\'s more heavily-weighted banking components, shares of Bank of America Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                 hiked up 1.7%, of Citigroup Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           C, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                 rose 1.3%, of J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JPM, +0.43%                                                                                                                                                 gained 1%, of Goldman Sachs Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GS, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                 tacked on 1.2% and of Wells Fargo & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           WFC, -0.73%                                                                                                                                                 advanced 1%. The U.S. added 298,000 private-sector jobs in February, the most since April 2014, according to ADP. That sent the yield on 10-year Treasurys 5.1 basis points to a 2 1/2-month high of 2.563%. Higher long-term interest rates can boost bank profits, as they increase the spread between what banks earn by funding longer-term assets, such as loans, with shorter-term liabilities. The financial ETF has gained 4.3% over the past three months through Tuesday, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                 has climbed 5.4%.']

Name: International Business Machines Corporation
Article: 4 : [u'\r\n         Earnings releases are still a confusing mess, and it\u2019s investors who pay the price\r\n    ']
Body: [u'On Thursday, Ford Motor Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          F, +0.60%                                                                                                                                                released one of the most unclear quarterly reports MarketWatch has seen, failing even to offer a year-earlier number for its earnings \u2014 or, in this case, loss \u2014 per share. The car company even flipped its financial table to show the prior-year numbers before the current ones. It\u2019s a basic financial-reporting principle that tables are read from left to right, so some readers could easily have mistaken the 2016 numbers for the 2015 ones. ', u' Read also:  Here\u2019s how investors are duped each earnings season ', u' Don\u2019t miss: The tax hit that made Google miss on earnings, and the big change that will keep it from happening again', u'The Ford release did not have any purpose other than to direct investors to the company\u2019s website to see the results. By the time several clicks had finally produced a report, the share price had moved. The commentary provided by Chief Executive Mark Fields and Chief Financial Officer Bob Shanks was only about the full-year performance, which showed the company swinging to a profit from 2015, with no mention of the company\u2019s $800 million loss for the fourth quarter.', u'MarketWatch has written before about the delay caused when companies make investors, and the reporters who serve them, search for earnings on a website, which almost invariably crashes under the strain of so many attempting to access it at the same time. ', u' See also: T-Mobile\u2019s accounting slammed by investor group in letter to SEC ', u'The worst offender, in our view, is the video-streaming giant Netflix Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          NFLX, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                \xa0.', u'This earnings season, General Electric Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          GE, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                and International Business Machines Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          IBM, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                both listed their diluted earnings per share above basic earnings per share. While the companies are not doing anything technically wrong, one industry expert said it is still a surprising approach.', u' Read: GE and IBM have \u2018unusual\u2019 earnings reports in common ', u' Don\u2019t miss:  GE\u2019s earnings report may not be wrong, but it may still mislead investors ', u' See also: Wal-Mart\u2019s earnings report is still missing something ', u'On Wednesday, another member of the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                          DJIA, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, United Technologies Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          UTX, -0.53%                                                                                                                                                 , did something even more baffling, presenting earnings that obliged investors and reporters to do their own math. Under the \u201cdiluted earnings (loss) per share of common stock\u201d heading, the line item for continuing operations showed $1.26, but the line for discontinued operations just showed a loss of 1 cent. For investors to ascertain net earnings per share, they are required to subtract a penny from $1.26, to get $1.25.', u'Meanwhile, Lockheed Martin Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          LMT, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                unveiled a problem this week with Sikorsky, the helicopter maker it acquired from United Technologies in 2015. Lockheed said it expects to report a material weakness in internal control over financial reporting for Sikorsky in its 2016 annual report at the end of February. The company said management had determined that Sikorsky did not \u201cadequately identify, design and implement appropriate process-level controls for its processes and appropriate information technology controls for its information technology systems.\u201d Its internal control over financial reporting was, therefore, \u201cineffective\u201d as of Dec. 31, 2016, according to the filing. The auditor\u2019s opinion in the annual report is expected to reflect management\u2019s conclusion. ', u' See: Lockheed says numbers from Sikorsky are unreliable due to control weakness ', u'The SEC has been cracking down on the use of metrics that don\u2019t conform with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles in earnings in an effort to make them clearer. The regulator issued updated guidelines on that practice last May and has followed up with comment letters to offenders.', u'The SEC rules allow companies to use non-GAAP numbers to supplement the GAAP ones, but they must provide the GAAP numbers first, give both sets of numbers equal prominence and explain how they are reconciled. The SEC has sent comment letters to companies including GE, General Motors Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          GM, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Coca-Cola Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          KO, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Hertz Global Holdings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          HTZ, -4.85%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Medtronic PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                          MDT, +0.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Whirlpool Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          WHR, -0.53%                                                                                                                                                and Tesla Motor Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          TSLA, +0.76%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, to name a few. The SEC called ConocoPhillips                                                                                                                                                                                                          COP, -0.73%                                                                                                                                                out on its use of a non-GAAP revenue number, just weeks after MarketWatch highlighted the issue. ', u' See also: New competition took a bite out of J&J\u2019s drug sales, but don\u2019t expect the trend to dominate this earnings season ', u'  See: How the biggest companies in the S&P 500 use made-up earnings numbers ']

Name: Jack In The Box Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Jack in the Box shares plummet 11% after Q1 profit, revenue misses and disappointing guidance\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Jack in the Box Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JACK, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 shares plummeted 11% in post-market trade Wednesday after the company reported a first-quarter profit and revenue miss. Earnings for the latest quarter rose to $1.14 per share, or $37 million, from 94 cents per share, or $34 million, in the year-earlier period. The latest results include restructuring charges of $2 million, which include facility closing costs and employee severance pay, and lower-than-expected sales and margins at its Qdoba franchise, the company said. Adjusted earnings-per-share were $1.14, below the FactSet consensus of $1.24. Revenue rose to $488 million from $471 million, below the FactSet consensus of $500 million. Jack in the Box expects same-store sales of flat to down 2% at Jack in the Box restaurants and down 1% to 3% same-store sales at Qdoba restaurants in the second quarter. For fiscal year 2017, it said it expects a 2% same-store sales increase at Jack in the Box restaurants and about flat same-store sales at Qdoba restaurants. The company expects adjusted EPS of $4.25 to $4.45 for fiscal year 2017, below the FactSet consensus of $4.71. Jack in the Box shares have declined 3.9% over the last three months, compared with a 7.3% rise in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                 ']

Name: J.C. Penney Company, Inc. Holding Company
Article: 14 : [u'\r\n         J.C. Penney shares rise after profit beat estimates, store closures announced\r\n    ']
Body: [u'J.C. Penney Co. Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JCP, -1.79%                                                                                                                                                 shares rose 1.8% in Friday premarket trading after the company announced fourth-quarter earnings that beat estimates. Net income was $192.0 million, or 61 cents per share, compared with a loss of $131.0 million, or 43 cents per share, last year. Adjusted EPS was 64 cents, beating the 61-cent FactSet consensus. Sales totaled $3.96 billion, down from $4.0 billion last year and just below the $3.98 billion FactSet consensus. Same-store sales fell 0.7%, while the FactSet consensus was a 0.3% decline. J.C. Penney expects full-year 2017 same-store sales to range from a 1% decline to a 1% increase, and adjusted EPS of 40 cents to 65 cents. The FactSet consensus is for a 1.3% increase and EPS of 54 cents. The retailer also announced plans to close 130 to 140 stores and two distribution centers in the next few months. It is initiating a voluntary early retirement program for about 6,000 eligible associates. J.C. Penney expects an annual cost savings of about $200 million. The full list of store closures will be available mid-March with the closures taking place in the second quarter of 2017. J.C. Penney shares are down 11% for the past year while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 is up 22.5% for the same period.']

Name: Apple Inc.
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Why the Republicans\u2019 Obamacare replacement is bad for business\r\n    ']
Body: [u'First, the basics. The GOP\u2019s bill, as expected, begins the task of replacing the health insurance more than 20 million Americans rely upon by repealing taxes that pay for it, nearly all paid by families with incomes over $250,000 and by corporations. (Which has been the point of this exercise all along.) It phases out Obamacare\u2019s expansion of Medicaid eligibility into the working class, stranding 15 million folks who mostly work for companies that don\u2019t offer affordable insurance.', u'Predictably, moderates and liberals think the bill is too chary toward poor and middle-class people \u2014 including four Senate Republicans whose opposition to its Medicaid-expansion phaseout means it won\u2019t pass the Senate without major changes. Just as predictably, there are those on the right who think the bill is too generous. Representing the right is Utah Rep. Jason Chaffetz, a Republican who explained that some people will sacrifice their Apple                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.59%                                                                                                                                                \xa0iPhones to afford family health coverage at $1,500 a month. Because one thing\u2019s exactly like the other.', u' First, no matter how often Ryan calls ACA a job-killer, it ain\u2019t. The current streak of 84 months of positive job creation, by far the record, began in February 2010, the month President Barack Obama signed the ACA. Private employers who were supposed to be scared into submission have created 16 million jobs since, including nearly 6 million at small businesses supposedly frozen into not investing by the prospect of skyrocketing medical costs.', u' Second, the tax on medical-device companies simply didn\u2019t hurt them.', u'Device companies like Medtronic                                                                                                                                                                                                           MDT, -0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0began caterwauling even before the ACA was approved \u2014 a 2.3% excise tax on medical devices helped pay for the plan. Their point was that everybody got something in exchange for supporting the law but them: Hospitals got fewer uninsured patients and more volume, insurers got new customers with subsidized premiums and so on. Device makers, on the other hand, thought they wouldn\u2019t be able to pass the tax along and would have to eat it, in the form of narrower profit margins and languishing stocks.', u'Uh, no. Since 2012, the year before the tax took effect, medical-device stocks have risen an average of 19% yearly. Medtronic has risen 105%, nearly 40 points better than the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                 Device makers\u2019 profit margins held up after the tax took effect, and were always much wider than the rest of corporate America\u2019s.', u' Third, insurance companies don\u2019t face intractable losses under Obamacare.', u'Aetna                                                                                                                                                                                                           AET, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0could hardly have made it clearer last August: The estimated $1.5 billion to $2 billion insurers lost on ACA-compliant insurance last year came from easily corrected problems. In particular, insurers had been caught unprepared for a spike in prescription-drug costs, led by new remedies for hepatitis C that cost nearly $100,000 per patient. \u201cPeople seeking care through these \u2026 products need this care,\u201d Aetna CEO Mark Bertolini said. \u201c[They] aren\u2019t running off to get services that they don\u2019t need.\u201d', u'Insurers had a simple answer for that: Rule changes that cut drug costs, plus mergers that let them make up unexpectedly high medical expenses on some ACA patients by cutting administrative costs. The Obama administration, to its discredit, blocked two big, sensible health-insurance mergers. That\u2019s no reason to kick 20 million people off insurance rolls.', u' Fourth, no matter what Congress says, ACA has been great for health-care companies and health-care stocks.', u'The device makers \u2014 we\u2019ve already covered. Hospital chains like HCA                                                                                                                                                                                                           HCA, -0.58%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Tenet                                                                                                                                                                                                           THC, -2.86%                                                                                                                                                \xa0described the ACA as integral to their profit gains in 2015: HCA\u2019s stock is up 240%, and the S&P 500 Health Care Index has more than doubled over the past five years, handily beating the broader market. Four of the Big Five insurance companies have seen their shares triple since 2012, and the laggard, Aetna, more than doubled.', u'As the venture capitalist Ann Lamont and former Obama aide Ezekiel Emanuel point out, business writ broadly has saved a ton of money under the ACA, because it dramatically slowed increases in health-care costs. The self-appointed party of business would toss that aside to merely redistribute after-tax income and wealth upward, yet again. ', u'  Tim Mullaney is a freelance writer who covers politics and economics. ']

Body: [u' Read:  U.S. adds 235,000 jobs in first full month with Trump in White House ', u'The woes facing the industry have long been apparent. Amazon                                                                                                                                                                                                          AMZN, +0.26%                                                                                                                                                and other internet retailers have been stealing market share and get the benefit of not having to pay rent on physical space to display their wares or pay cashiers. ', u'In fact, fresh data released by Slice Intelligence show that millennials buy more clothes \u2014 clothes \u2014 from Amazon than any other site.', u'The chief executive of J.C. Penney                                                                                                                                                                                                          JCP, -1.87%                                                                                                                                                said its tax rate would vault from 34% to over 170% under a BAT, and that this impact would be similar at other retailers. \u201cWe\u2019re all in this same precarious position because we don\u2019t have a manufacturing capacity that exists in the United States,\u201d Marvin Ellison told CNBC.']

Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Stock market slides for second day as energy shares weigh\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                 declined 6.92 points, or 0.3%, to close at 2,368.39. The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shed 29.58 points, or 0.1%, to end at 20,924.76, and the Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slipped 15.25 points, or 0.3%, to finish at 5,833.93.', u'On Monday, the S&P 500, the Dow and the Nasdaq all closed lower. Analysts blamed the selling in part on geopolitical worries, including concerns sparked by North Korea\u2019s testing of ballistic missiles. ', u'Health-care stocks were notable losers Tuesday after House Republicans unveiled a plan to repeal and replace former President Barack Obama\u2019s signature health-care legislation, the Affordable Care Act. President Donald Trump also tweeted that he was working on a new plan to increase drug-industry competition and reduce pharmaceutical prices. ', u' Stock movers: Michaels Cos. Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                            MIK, -0.51%                                                                                                                                                 gained 2.3% after the arts and crafts chain store\u2019s fourth-quarter earnings beat expectations and as it offered a higher-than-expected outlook for 2017. ', u' Pier 1 Imports Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PIR, +1.38%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rallied 5.6% after releasing preliminary fourth-quarter results that beat expectations. ', u' Ascena Retail Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ASNA, -4.55%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 1.1% on a smaller-than-forecast quarterly loss. ', u' Dick\u2019s Sporting Goods Inc. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           DKS, -0.97%                                                                                                                                                 tumbled 8.6% as the retailer\u2019s quarterly earnings forecast fell short of Wall Street\u2019s consensus estimate. ', u'Shares of Snap Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          SNAP, +5.64%                                                                                                                                                 which made its public debut last week, fell for a second day, sinking 9.8%.', u' Other markets: Oil futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell, while gold futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCH7, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0settled lower, and a key dollar index                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 edged up. European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                          SXXP, -0.54%                                                                                                                                                 were mixed, while Asian markets closed generally higher. ', u' Economic news: A Tuesday report on the U.S.\u2019s trade deficit in January showed it reached its highest level since early 2012, rising 9.6% at $48.5 billion. Imports rose 2.3% to $240.6 billion, and exports rose 0.6% to $192.1 billion on the month. Economists polled by MarketWatch had been forecasting a deficit of $48.8 billion.', u' Check out: MarketWatch\u2019s Economic Calendar ', u' \u2014Victor Reklaitis contributed to this article.  ']

Article: 10 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Trading on Trump\u2019s tweets would have left you sad and poorer\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The president now is aiming at auto companies, trying to bludgeon Ford                                                                                                                                                                                                          F, +0.81%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, General Motors                                                                                                                                                                                                          GM, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                and Toyota                                                                                                                                                                                                          TM, -0.59%                                                                                                                                                into expanding small-car production in the U.S. \u2014 reversing decades-old trends of moving the manufacturing of mostly lower-priced, often-unprofitable cars to Mexico, even as Mexican presidents past and present flip The Donald the bird.', u'Stop quaking. Trump\u2019s Twitter                                                                                                                                                                                                          TWTR, +2.17%                                                                                                                                                missives have no lasting effect on stocks. I created a list of affected companies, generated by Yahoo Finance, then deleted the privately owned ones. This left 37 public companies about which Trump has tweeted nastygrams since 2012. Trump has been wrong, from an investing standpoint, on 29 of them. In fact, if you shorted 100 shares of each of these 37 companies on the day Trump slammed them, you\u2019re down 37% as of Thursday\u2019s close. Sad!', u'What does this tell us? Investors and CEOs should pay no attention to the man behind the curtain. The tweeter-in-chief can huff and puff, but he can\u2019t blow your house down. Investors don\u2019t care what he tweets, and the record shows they\u2019re right not to.', u'It\u2019s amusing to see the breadth of businesses Trump is wrong about. He\u2019s wrong about tech. Wrong about media, mainstream or otherwise. Wrong about wind power. Wrong about Coca-Cola                                                                                                                                                                                                          KO, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Warren Buffett and ESPN. Wrong about Hollywood. Wrong about markets and policy. Wrong about cellphone companies.', u'And atop all this wrongness is Trump\u2019s pan of Facebook\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                          FB, +0.64%                                                                                                                                                2012 initial public offering (\u201chard to believe it could be worth that much\u201d), which came with unsolicited marital advice for founder Mark Zuckerberg \u2014 \u201cGet a prenup!\u201d', u'Lawyers, by the way, say Zuckerberg didn\u2019t really need a prenuptial agreement to protect himself from a divorce, because he got rich before he got married, which was right after the offering. Shareholders got rich later: Facebook shares are up 247%.', u'Trump was bearish on Apple                                                                                                                                                                                                          AAPL, +1.06%                                                                                                                                                in 2014 \u2014 \u201cI sold my Apple\u201d \u2014 because it didn\u2019t match Samsung\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                          005930, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                big-screen phones, until it did. Apple shares since then are up 66%. Trump was bearish on Amazon.com                                                                                                                                                                                                          AMZN, +0.63%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 \u2014 \u201cJeff Bezos ... no-profit company\u201d \u2014 in December 2015. The stock is up 25% since.', u'Trump was wrong about Sony                                                                                                                                                                                                          SNE, +0.31%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u2014 \u201cstupid leadership\u201d \u2014 in December 2014 amid the now-ironic revelation of its hacked emails. Shares of Sony are up 58% since.', u'Trump was wrong about American Airlines Group, panning its USAirways merger in 2013. Since then, American Airlines shares                                                                                                                                                                                                          AAL, -1.18%                                                                                                                                                have gained 241%. ', u'He\u2019s been wrong about the New York Times Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          NYT, +0.53%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, which is up 4% since Trump called it a \u201cdying paper\u201d in 2016. Wrong about Gannett                                                                                                                                                                                                          GCI, -0.74%                                                                                                                                                and Tegna                                                                                                                                                                                                           TGNA, +0.75%                                                                                                                                                 , the since-split-up publishers of \u201cboring\u201d USA Today, which have doubled in value since Trump tweeted in 2012 that he\u2019d canceled his subscription to the newspaper. (Trump overlooked Gannett\u2019s thriving TV business. Which is not, like, really smart! I worked for Gannett at the time \u2014 I made a ton.) ', u'Trump was wrong about Walt Disney                                                                                                                                                                                                          DIS, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, shares of which have doubled since drawing Trump\u2019s ire in 2013 for apologizing after ESPN announcer Brent Musburger got a little too honest on air about the hotness of the girlfriend of the University of Alabama\u2019s quarterback. Trump was wrong about Microsoft                                                                                                                                                                                                          MSFT, +1.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, where he claimed unhappy investors were scheming to fire Bill Gates as chairman in 2013, when the stock was 90% lower. Trump was wrong about J.P. Morgan Chase                                                                                                                                                                                                          JPM, +0.39%                                                                                                                                                 , shares of which are now\xa051% higher, for complaining that it settled lawsuits too easily. \xa0', u'This litany of wrongs goes on with Google parent Alphabet                                                                                                                                                                                                          GOOG, +0.52%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, which Trump accused of suppressing negative news about Democratic presidential candidate Hillary Clinton. With Procter & Gamble                                                                                                                                                                                                           PG, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Trump knocked it for moving its beauty business to Singapore in 2012, which P&G did for the eminently sensible reason that Asia was its fastest-growing market. P&G stock is up 36% Charter Communications                                                                                                                                                                                                          CHTR, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                was another miss. Trump in 2012 tweeted that the company gives bad service (\u201ca disaster\u201d). A disaster, that is, whose shares have quadrupled since. And T-Mobile US shares                                                                                                                                                                                                          TMUS, +1.09%                                                                                                                                                are up 96% since Trump said the same about that company in 2015. ', u'Want more? Trump was wrong about S&P Global                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPGI, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, which has tripled since Trump knocked the bond-rating agency for downgrading U.S. bonds in 2011, responding to the mostly Republican fiscal indiscipline \u2014 on which President Trump now plans to double down. If Trump gets what he wants on taxes, look for more feuding with S&P.', u'He was wrong about Boeing                                                                                                                                                                                                          BA, +0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, criticizing the company in early December about the price of the next-generation Air Force One airplane. He was wrong about Lockheed Martin                                                                                                                                                                                                           LMT, +0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u2014 shares rose in the days after he knocked the company over the cost of F-35 fighters on Dec. 22 and closed Thursday up about 1%. (Lockheed said Tuesday that it will not change its prices.)', u'Trump has been wrong about the automobile industry, too. Fiat Chrysler Automobiles shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           FCAU, +2.10%                                                                                                                                                are up 235% since Trump\u2019s 2012 prediction that the company would move Jeep production to China after that year\u2019s election (wrong about that, too). But score one for Trump with Ford \u2014 down 22% since Trump hit the company in 2015 over Mexico, saying \u201cthe U.S. is getting killed.\u201d ', u'Toyota Motor Corp. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                          7203, -3.33%                                                                                                                                                                              TM, -0.59%                                                                                                                                                didn\u2019t move much after Trump\u2019s tweet earlier this month about plans for a Corolla plant in Mexico, and General Motors, thought to be Trump\u2019s favorite car and truck maker, is up 7% since he attacked it, half-accurately, on Jan. 3 over making Chevrolet Cruze hatchbacks south of the border (the more popular Cruze sedans come from Ohio). The reality is that there\u2019s no discernible Trump effect on car stocks, except in the media\u2019s eyes.', u'Finally, Trump was even wrong the bonds of Vattenfall, sponsor of a wind-power project Trump contends ruins views from one of his Scottish golf courses. \u201cWho would be stupid enough to invest?\u201d Trump tweeted in May 2015. Answer: People who like a 15% capital gain. Plus 6.875% interest.', u'Really, none of this should be a yuuuge surprise, given that Trump and his team have been lying about everything from voters to the size of the president\u2019s ... crowds. But what is surprising, and counter to the hype, is the quantitative proof that the market\u2019s Big Blond Wolf is breath-deprived. Lockheed, for one, is apparently reasoning that if a company is solidly built, Trump can blow all he wants. Other companies, take heed.', u' See: Every Trump tweet activates thousands of computer algorithms ']
