Name: Deckers Outdoor Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Deckers shares drop more than 20% on earnings miss, weak outlook\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Deckers Outdoor Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DECK, -0.95%                                                                                                                                                 shares plunged in the extended session Thursday after the maker of Ugg boots missed Wall Street targets for the quarter and issued a weak outlook. Deckers shares dropped 23% to $43.01 after hours. The company reported adjusted fiscal third-quarter earnings of $4.11 a share on revenue of $760.3 million. Analysts surveyed by FactSet had estimated $4.22 a share on revenue of $789 million. For the fourth quarter, Deckers expects a per-share loss of 10 cents to break-even with a 5% to 6% decline in revenue for the quarter, which works out to an estimate of $355.9 million to $359.7 million. Analysts had forecast earnings of 42 cents a share on revenue of $383 million.']

Name: Charter Communications, Inc.
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Trump could lead to a surge in shareholder activism\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Trump administration plans to roll back the Dodd-Frank law, among other regulations, and he has named prominent activist investor Carl Icahn as a special adviser on overhauling regulation.', u'While it is difficult to anticipate what companies could become a target for activist shareholders, there is an exchange-traded fund that is designed to play this thesis. The Global X Guru Activist                                                                                                                                                                                                           ACTX, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0holds 50 stocks that have been targeted by activist hedge funds, based on their quarterly 13-F filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission.', u' Read:  As hedge funds suffer, so do their imitators ', u'The fund is small, with not even $1.5 million in assets and a 30-day average trading volume below 300 shares. It is also on the pricier side, with an expense ratio of 0.75%. However, it has been a strong performer since the election, having risen 10.3%. That is notably better than the 8.7% rise of the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                ', u'The fund\u2019s largest holdings include CVR Energy Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CVI, -1.22%                                                                                                                                                 Cheniere Energy Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LNG, +0.11%                                                                                                                                                 and Charter Communications Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CHTR, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                 Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                \u2014which had recently been targeted by Icahn, who sold his stake in 2016\u2014is also among the fund\u2019s top five holdings, comprising about 2.3% of the portfolio.', u' Opinion: Carl Icahn\u2019s $2 billion Apple stake was a prime example of investment inequality', u'The current tone on Wall Street is decidedly mixed. High levels of geopolitical uncertainty, when paired against Trump-related optimism, has resulted in a tug of war between the market\u2019s biggest bulls and bears. While stocks have rallied since the election, hitting a series of records, that rally has also made valuations look elevated by some metrics.']

Name: Hortonworks, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Hortonworks shares rally on narrower-than-expected loss\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Hortonworks Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HDP, -2.09%                                                                                                                                                 shares rallied in the extended session Thursday after the business software company turned in a narrower-than-expected loss for the quarter. Hortonworks shares jumped 12% to $11.41 after hours. The company reported an adjusted fourth-quarter loss of 50 cents a share on revenue of $52 million. Analysts surveyed by FactSet had forecast a loss of 60 cents a share on revenue of $48 million. Hortonworks forecast revenue of $52 million for the first quarter, and between $235 million and $240 million for the year. Analysts expect $52 million for the first quarter, and $234.7 million for the year.']

Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         U.S. stocks fall as oil drop weighs on energy shares\r\n    ']
Body: [u'U.S. stocks opened lower as falling oil prices weighed on the shares of energy companies. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                 shed four points, or 0.2%, to 2,288. The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 retreated 53 points, or 0.3%, to 20,038. The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.31%                                                                                                                                                 slipped 12 points, or 0.2%, to 5,662. The American Petroleum Institute said late Tuesday that the U.S. crude supply increased by 14.2 million barrels last week, far beyond the 2.5 million expected. Official weekly inventory data from the Energy Information Administration due later Wednesday will be closely watched. Oil prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           CLH7, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 fell 1% to $51.60 in recent trade. Time Warner Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWX, -0.45%                                                                                                                                                 shares rose after the company reported stronger than expected quarterly earnings. Alaska Air Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AGN, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                 jumped after reporting a double-digit increase in quarterly revenue. Zillow Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           Z, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                 shares fell after the real-estate website forecast a wider loss for the year than Wall Street had expected.']

Name: Intel Corporation
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         Nvidia\u2019s stock suffers record plunge after analysts say it\u2019s time to sell\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Nvidia\u2019s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           NVDA, +1.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0tumbled $10.27, or 9.3%, to suffer the biggest price decline since it went public in January 1999. The one-day percentage selloff was the stock\u2019s biggest since it dropped 9.5% on Aug. 4, 2011. Volume spiked to 39.5 million shares, which was about 2 1/2-times the full-day average.', u'The stock has still more than tripled over the past 12 months, as investors rewarded the company for shifting its focus toward technologies used in artificial intelligence and autonomous cars. That compares with a 61% surge in the PHLX Semiconductor Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SOX, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and the S&P 500 index\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa023% rally over the same time. ', u' Don\u2019t miss: Nvidia stock pulls back as Citron adds to short interest.', u' See also: Nvidia\u2019s stock tumbles toward first close below 50-day moving average in a year.', u'Instinet\u2019s Shah expressed concern that investors may soon become reluctant to pay such a relatively high premium for Nvidia\u2019s stock, given how fickle they have been in the past. Nvidia\u2019s price-to-earning ratio was 39.1, according to FactSet, above the P/E ratio for rival Intel Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           INTC, +0.40%                                                                                                                                                \xa0of 17.1 and for the S&P 500 average of 21.7.', u'For chart watchers, Nvidia\u2019s stock closed below its 50-day moving average for the first time since Feb. 17, 2016. That snapped a 256-session streak of closes above what many technicians view as a short-term trend tracker, the longest such stretch since in the stock\u2019s history.']

Name: CBS Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Northwestern, arguably Big Ten\u2019s brainiest school, is no longer a basketball joke\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Northwestern sold out four men\u2019s basketball games in advance this season. It hadn\u2019t sold out a single game before game day in at least five years, Crain\u2019s Chicago Business reported. ', u'College-sports finance remains one of the most controversial sports topics \u2014 these are, after all, amateur players, kids really, all ostensibly pursuing a degree, but the cutthroat quest for donor money and state-of-the-art playing facilities is notorious. Northwestern student-athletes, in fact, led a failed effort in recent years to unionize in order to better protect their \u201cearnings.\u201d ', u'The arena remodel benefits from a major gift from insurer Aon                                                                                                                                                                                                           AON, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0founder Pat Ryan and others, including funds for an adjacent basketball practice facility. Two more trustees, Tim Sullivan and Jeff Ubben, last month gave the athletic department $3 million. Their names are now attached not to a building, but to a position: head coach Chris Collins will now be named the Sullivan-Ubben head men\u2019s basketball coach. ', u'Seven-figure revenue from Northwestern ticket sales and sponsors are still a fraction of the $40 million-plus that each Big Ten school reportedly will get annually as part of the league\u2019s new six-year, $2.6 billion broadcasting deal with Fox                                                                                                                                                                                                           NWS, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, ESPN                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and CBS                                                                                                                                                                                                           CBS, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0that kicks in later this year, Crain\u2019s noted. That money helps fund non-revenue sports, too. ', u'Some of its loudest fans are Emmy-winning actress Julia Louis-Dreyfus of \u201cVeep\u201d and \u201cSeinfeld\u201d renown and her writer/director/producer husband Brad Hall, who both attended Northwestern. Their son, Charlie Hall, is a walk-on for the Wildcats, and a radio/TV/film major who plays off the bench.', u' This story was originally published March 2, and has been updated to reflect Sunday\u2019s NCAA tournament selection. ']

Body: [u'The nixed Mexican meeting halted the peso\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/15936962/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>USDMXN, -0.1686%                                                                                                                                                \xa0brief rally , and now there are \u201ctough issues\u201d to tackle as Trump chats with Britain\u2019s Theresa May, says TopTradr analyst Tony Cross. Any hints that our dealmaker-in-chief is trying to \u201ctake advantage of the U.K.\u2019s diminished position as it edges out of the EU\u201d could whack the pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.1362%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Cross warns.', u'What to do with all these trade-related tensions? So suggests our call of the day from Steven Jon Kaplan at True Contrarian, a blog/newsletter that says it \u201cidentifies the most unanimous consensus in the financial markets, then goes in the exact opposite direction of that consensus.\u201d', u'The punished peso will bring about \u201cincreased exports, lower wages in U.S. dollar terms, increased multinational relocation, and therefore sharply increased profits within a year,\u201d says the contrarian trader. He says he bought the big Mexico ETF when it changed hands at $41.99 earlier this month, and he plans to buy more if the $1.8 billion fund falls to $40.99.', u' Read more: Mexico ETFs fall as tensions rise between Trump and Nieto ', u' And see: Trump calls U.S.-Mexico trade one-sided \u2014 and here\u2019s the reality ', u'Futures for the Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:YMH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0, S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:ESH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Nasdaq-100                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:NQH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0are little changed. Name: Urban Outfitters, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u"\r\n         Urban Outfitters downgraded to sell at MKM because Anthropologie is 'too edgy' and expensive\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Shares of Urban Outfitters Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           URBN, -0.93%                                                                                                                                                 fell 0.9% in morning trade Monday, after MKM Partners turned bearish on the apparel and accessories retailer because of concerns over sales and margin declines at its Anthropologie stores. Analyst Roxanne Meyer cut her rating to sell, after being at neutral since September 2015. She slashed her stock price target to $20, which is 25% below current levels, from $25. "Our negative thesis is primarily based on our view that sales and margins will deteriorate meaningfully in 2017 at Anthropologie, though we also see risk at Urban Outfitters as it laps reductions in markdowns and as key brands widen distribution," Meyer wrote in a note to clients. "We believe Anthropologie is too edgy, lacks diversity (i.e., over-exposed to bare and cold-shoulder looks) and generally has prices that are too high." Urban Outfitter\'s stock has tumbled 21% over the past three months, while the SPDR S&P Retail ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XRT, -0.81%                                                                                                                                                 has lost 6.1% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                 has climbed 7%.']

Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         FTSE 100 logs 10th day of all-time highs\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The FTSE 100                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed 0.2% to finish at 7,290.49, extending gains to a 12th consecutive trading day, its longest winning streak ever. ', u'The index had been down as much as 0.3% Wednesday morning, but started swinging higher as the pound dropped after U.K. data showed a widening of the country\u2019s trade deficit in November. U.K. stocks also got a boost from Bank of England Gov. Mark Carney stating in front of the Treasury Select Committee that Brexit is no longer the most significant downside risk to the U.K. economy. ', u' Pound selloff: Sterling has been moving lower all week as investors worry about the prospect of a \u201chard Brexit,\u201d which would blunt access by U.K. businesses into the European Union\u2019s single market. Sterling depreciation typically boosts the earnings of U.K. exporters, beneficial to sales for British multinationals. ', u'The pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.1282%                                                                                                                                                \xa0on Wednesday slid to an intraday low of $1.2038, trading around levels not seen the sterling flash crash in October. The pound, however, trimmed losses during U.S. President-elect Donald Trump\u2019s news conference to $1.2123, compared with $1.2167 late Tuesday in New York. ', u' Individual movers: Drugmakers headed lower after Trump in his first full-scale press conference since July lashed out at the drug industry. The president-elect said that more bidding is needed on drug prices, implying legislation that could erode the sector\u2019s profitability. ', u'Shares of Shire PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHP, -0.58%                                                                                                                                                                              SHPG, +0.44%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 3.2%, Hikma Pharmaceuticals                                                                                                                                                                                                           HIK, -1.43%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 1.2%, AstraZeneca PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           AZN, +0.69%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gave up 1.8% and GlaxoSmithKline PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           GSK, -0.51%                                                                                                                                                                              GSK, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slipped 0.8%. ', u'Shares of Sainsbury\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           SBRY, -2.27%                                                                                                                                                 rose 1%. The U.K.\u2019s second-biggest supermarket chain by market share said its total retail sales, excluding fuel, were up 0.8% in the 15 weeks ended Jan. 7. ', u'TUI AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           TUI, -1.97%                                                                                                                                                 fell 4.5% following a ratings downgrade of the travel services company to underperform from outperform at Credit Suisse.', u'Home builder Taylor Wimpey PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           TW., +0.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0said it expects to report 2016 profit at the upper end of market consensus and reaffirmed its medium-term dividend payout target. But shares turned lower, ending down 2.5%. ']

Name: Southwest Airlines Company
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Airline shares slump as Delta warns of higher costs\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Airline stocks fell in tandem Monday after Delta Air Lines Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DAL, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                 lowered its forecast operating margins for the year at the Raymond James Institutional Investors Conference in Orlando, Fla. In a presentation, Delta said margins would likely contract as cost increases outpaces revenue growth with the worst of it occurring in the March quarter, calling 2017 "a transition year." Delta said fuel prices have jumped 55% for the quarter. Shares of Delta fell 3.3%, while United Continental Holding Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UAL, +0.51%                                                                                                                                                 shares declined 4.2%, American Airlines Group Inc. Name: Intellia Therapeutics, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u"\r\n         Editas Medicine's stock soars after favorable ruling in CRISPR patent dispute\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Editas Medicine Inc.\'s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           EDIT, +0.62%                                                                                                                                                 spiked by more than 30% in Wednesday trading, putting it on course for its biggest one-day gain since it went public a year ago, after reports of a favorable decision in a closely watched patent dispute. Editas has an exclusive license to medical breakthroughs stemming from the use of patents awarded to co-founder Feng Zhang of the Broad Institute for CRISPR, a gene-editing technique. The Broad, which is affiliated with Harvard University and Massachusetts Institute of Technology, has been in a dispute with University of California at Berkeley on those patents. Cal scientists developed the technology behind CRISPR, and the Broad showed how it could be used to edit genes in specific species, leading to a dispute over who could claim ownership. Stat News and others reported Wednesday that the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office had ruled in the Broad\'s favor, though the USPTO told MarketWatch that the decision would not be made public until Thursday. Cambridge, Mass.-based Editas suddenly jumped after the news hit Wednesday, trading near $25 a share after opening at $18.71. It has rallied 51% over the past three months, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 7.8%. Among other companies affected by the patent ruling, shares of CRISPR Therapeutics AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           CRSP, -1.79%                                                                                                                                                 tumbled 14% and Intellia Therapeutics Inc.\'s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           NTLA, +0.77%                                                                                                                                                 dropped 12%.']

Name: Sarepta Therapeutics, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Marathon Pharma will pause launch of Duchenne muscular dystrophy drug after outcry over $89,000 price\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Marathon Pharmaceuticals said it would pause the launch of its recently-approved Duchenne muscular dystrophy drug after an outcry over Emflaza\'s $89,000-a-year price tag. The privately-held company said it has heard concerns about the drug\'s pricing and reimbursement details from the DMD community. "Please know we sought FDA approval of Emflaza to improve access to this treatment," Chief Executive Officer Jeffrey Aronin said. "We have and always will support you in that endeavor." He did not say when the drug would be launched, or whether the company would change its price. Under 1,000 patients who receive the drug for free through Marathon\'s expanded access program will continue to do so, Marathon said. Emflaza, which is a corticosteroid, was only the second DMD drug approved in the U.S., although corticosteroids are used for the degenerative disease in other parts of the world. The first DMD drug, made by Sarepta Therapeutics Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SRPT, +3.89%                                                                                                                                                 was approved last year and is priced at about $300,000. Some of the patient community\'s concerns were around whether Emflaza\'s price would effect health insurance coverage of Sarepta\'s drug, Aronin said. Sarepta shares have sunk 30.0% over the last three months, compared with a 7.6% rise in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                 ']

Name: United Technologies Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Trump\u2019s jawboning will hardly deliver enough jobs\r\n    ']
Body: [u'In his address before Congress, President Donald Trump touted his success in persuading major companies to move jobs back to America but his jawboning has delivered a punch much smaller than he advertises and that pales in comparison to the task of significantly improving on President Barack Obama\u2019s record as a jobs creator.', u'The succession of deals announced to create or return jobs to America sounds impressive \u2014 for example United Technologies                                                                                                                                                                                                           UTX, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Fiat Chrysler                                                                                                                                                                                                           FCAU, +2.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and other top-line companies have jumped on board \u2014 but the challenge is too large to be accomplished by simply cajoling CEOs. ', u'The Obama recovery accomplished 2.1% annual economic growth and averaged about 185,000 new jobs each month. Trump would have to create at least 100,000 more jobs each month to bring growth up to 3% to 4% and substantially improve living standards for ordinary working Americans.', u'Generally, company announcements include many jobs that were planned before Trump\u2019s surprise election. For example, Lockheed Martin                                                                                                                                                                                                           LMT, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0CEO Marillyn Hewson promised 1,800 jobs at its Fort Worth factory after meeting with the persuasive president, but those include some 1,000 that were announced in 2015.', u'Volkswagen                                                                                                                                                                                                           VOW, +1.01%                                                                                                                                                \xa0must restructure to accommodate the next generation of automation and mass produce electric vehicles. Thanks to German law, the union and the government of Lower Saxony combine to hold a majority of seats on the company board, creating a decided preference for German over U.S. and other foreign locations.', u'Notably, Mexico has negotiated an extensive network of free-trade agreements. U.S. and foreign auto makers can make cars and parts there for sale duty-free throughout North America, Europe and Japan \u2014 that is not something automakers can do in the United States. Given the dependence of the U.S. industry on components from Mexico, it is not at all clear that the United States would come out the winner in a trade war.', u'Tax and regulatory reform face barriers posed by divisions within the Republican Party in Congress, opposition from Democrats and the bureaucratic requirements of legislation that slow rule changes. And his new trade policy document emphasizes logging individual company complaints against foreign governments instead, for example, of taking on China to accomplish comprehensive compliance with its WTO commitments.', u'As businessmen, they were great at exploiting the system \u2014 including controversial records of lobbying for protection and outsourcing jobs. Now they must try their hands at accomplishing radical systemic reform and need cooperation from Congress and foreign governments, where leaders have ideas of their own and can\u2019t be fired by Trump.']

Name: Goldman Sachs Group, Inc. (The)
Article: 12 : [u'\r\n         Financial ETF hits highest level since 2007 on rate hike hopes\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Financial Select Sector SPDR ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLF, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 2.2% in its biggest one-day advance since Nov. 16. The day\u2019s gain also took the fund to its highest level since December 2007, before the worst of the financial crisis was known.', u' Late Tuesday, New York Fed President William Dudley said that the case for a rate hike had become \u201ca lot more compelling\u201d since November\u2019s presidential election. \u201cIt seems to me that most of the data we\u2019ve seen over the last couple months is very much consistent with the economy continuing to grow at an above-trend pace, job gains remain pretty sturdy, inflation has actually drifted up a little bit as energy prices have increased,\u201d Dudley said in a CNN International interview.', u'Dudley\u2019s comments were merely the latest in a series of ones hinting at a March move. Also on Tuesday, San Francisco Fed President John Williams said that, \u201cin my view, a rate increase is very much on the table for serious consideration\u201d at the March 14-15 meeting.', u'The day\u2019s move in financial ETFs only extended their recent advance. The Select Sector fund, the largest ETF to track the space with $25.3 billion in assets, is up more than 40% over the past 12 months. In addition to growing expectations for higher rates, the industry has also been supported by the prospect of lower regulations under President Donald Trump. Financials have comprised the bulk of the overall market\u2019s postelection move. ', u'Among other ETFs, the Vanguard Financials ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           VFH, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 2.2%, the iShares U.S. Financials ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           IYF, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is up 1.6%, the iShares U.S. Financial Services ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           IYG, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                 is 2.5% higher and the\xa0PowerShares KBW Bank Portfolio                                                                                                                                                                                                           KBWB, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0surged 2.9%. higher.', u'Among the biggest single-stock gains, Fifth Third Bancorp ', u'Bank of America Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 3.2% while Morgan Stanley                                                                                                                                                                                                           MS, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 2.9% and J.P. Name: NeuroDerm Ltd.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Four biotech stocks surging on optimism about drug trials, product launches\r\n    ']
Body: [u' bluebird bio Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BLUE, +3.58%                                                                                                                                                 has popped about 20% in a week to Wednesday\u2019s close of $92.80. On Wednesday alone, the stock rose $5.15 on trading of over 1 million shares, closing just a dime off the high. The company announced the publication of a case study on the first patient with severe sickle cell disease treated with its gene-therapy product. The stock has far surpassed our initial target of $85 and is closing in on the next target of $95. There\u2019s a possibility it may run up to the $106-$107 range, last reached in October 2015, which is the new, near-term target. Short interest of 12.9 times its average volume could fuel the move as short sellers cover on an advance.', u' Amicus Therapeutics Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FOLD, +1.91%                                                                                                                                                 surged 17% on Wednesday, up $1.11 to $7.60, on 12.2 million shares traded, more than three times the average volume. The company CEO\u2019s daughter, Megan Crowley, who has Pompe disease, was highlighted during President Trump\u2019s address to Congress Tuesday night. The company\u2019s fourth-quarter earnings highlighted the international launch of its first commercial product for treating rare and orphan diseases. Wednesday\u2019s surge broke the stock out of a mini-consolidation pattern and across lateral resistance from its December high. Watch for a move next to $8.25, with a secondary target of $9.50.', u' Kite Pharma Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KITE, +2.02%                                                                                                                                                 had a monster Wednesday, up $8.85, or 13%, to $79.62, on 6.9 million shares traded. The stock was up 25% during the previous session after the company released a favorable earnings report and positive clinical data on its lead product candidate for treating patients with rare forms of blood cancer. The next target is $85, and short interest of 14 times its average volume could accelerate the advance.', u' NeuroDerm Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NDRM, +0.77%                                                                                                                                                 also had a big Wednesday on solid mid-stage trial results for its Parkinson\u2019s disease treatment candidate. The stock exploded $6.15, or 27%, to $29.30, on 3 million shares traded, which is 12 times the average volume. The move broke the stock out to a new high since its IPO in late 2014. The next target would be the mid-$30s, but the long-term rising channel points to the $50s. ', u'See Harry\u2019s video-chart analysis on these stocks. ', u' The writer owns no stocks mentioned in this column. ', u' Harry Boxer is founder of TheTechTrader.com, a live trading room featuring his stock picks, technical market analysis and live chart presentations. ']

Name: AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc.
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         AMC will sell more than 19 million shares to payoff loans incurred from recent acquisitions\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Theater chain AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMC, +1.16%                                                                                                                                                 saw shares fall nearly 5% in premarket trade on Wednesday after the company said late Tuesday it was selling more than 19 million shares of the its class A common stock at $31.50 per share. AMC also granted the underwriters a 30-day option to buy up to an additional 2.9 million shares at the same price. AMC, which is owned by Chinese conglomerate Dalian Wanda Group, said it expects to make $579 million on the public offering, which the theater operator plans to use to repay loans incurred from its acquisitions of Carmike Cinemas and Nordic Cinema Group Holding AB. Citigroup, Bank of America Merrill Lynch, Barclays and Credit Suisse will serve as bookrunners for the offering. AMC shares are up more than 60% in the trailing 12-month period, outperforming the S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                 up nearly 24%.']
