Name: Merck & Company, Inc.
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         All eyes will be on Gilead\u2019s hepatitis C franchise as it reports fourth-quarter earnings\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The company\u2019s hepatitis C franchise will again be in the spotlight, this time for flagging sales, when Gilead                                                                                                                                                                                                           GILD, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0reports fourth-quarter earnings, scheduled for Tuesday after the markets close. ', u'Both Sovaldi and sister product Harvoni cure hepatitis C, which Gilead has used as a rationale for their high price tags.', u'New competitive pressures have exacerbated the issue, with Merck & Co. Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           MRK, -0.77%                                                                                                                                                \xa0hepatitis C drug Zepatier expected to make gains on health insurers\u2019 formularies, and an AbbVie Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ABBV, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0drug potentially getting approved later this year, said EvercoreISI analyst Mark Schoenebaum. ', u' Read more:  This is the most expensive drug in America ', u' Here\u2019s what to expect:  ', u' Earnings: Analysts expect Gilead to report earnings of $2.61 per share, down from $3.32 in the year-earlier period. Estimize, a software platform that uses crowdsourcing to garner earnings estimates from hedge-fund executives, brokerages and analysts, has Gilead earning less, or $2.50 per share. Gilead earnings have missed expectations in two of the past three quarters, according to FactSet. ', u' Revenue: Gilead is expected to report $7.14 billion in revenue, down from $8.50 billion in the year-earlier period. Estimize has Gilead reporting significantly more, at $7.20 billion. Gilead revenue has surpassed analyst expectations in all but one of the past 14 quarters, according to FactSet. ', u' Stock reaction: Gilead shares have risen 1.1% year-to-date, compared with a 2.3% rise in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 The average analyst rating on Gilead is overweight, with all but one of the 26 analysts surveyed by FactSet rating the company buy or hold. ', u' What to watch for: As with other pharmaceutical manufacturers, investors will be watching what products Gilead has in development \u2014 it has focused on developing drugs for the liver disease NASH and hepatitis B, and data on the HIV drug Bictegravir is expected soon \u2014 and its capital deployment.', u'After losing a patent lawsuit to Merck, Gilead will have to pay its rival $2.5 billion in royalties on Sovaldi and Harvoni. The company may address how it will book that charge on Tuesday. ', u' Related:  Gilead shares slip as jury sides with Merck in patent lawsuit ', u'Gilead management may discuss the president\u2019s stance on drug prices, or who will be the next head of the Food and Drug Administration. ']

Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Russian stocks, U.S. banks remain clear winners in Trump trade\r\n    ']
Body: [u'As a benchmark, the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                 has advanced 9.8% since the Nov. 8 election, a span of 62 trading days, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has risen 7.7% and the Nasdaq                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.37%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 10%. Since Trump\u2019s Jan. . 20 inauguration (or 14 days of trading), the Dow has gained 1.6%, while the S&P 500 had advanced 1.4% and the Nasdaq has advanced 2.6%.', u' Read: Stock market hits a trifecta of intraday records as energy, banks rally ', u'The biggest heavyweights on the Micex, the natural-gas giant Gazprom                                                                                                                                                                                                           OGZD, +0.66%                                                                                                                                                 Lukoil                                                                                                                                                                                                           LKOH, +8,756.42%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Sberbank of Russia                                                                                                                                                                                                          SBER, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                 have generally outperformed their American counterparts. Since Trump won the election, shares of Gazprom have risen 4.8% in local terms, while Lukoil shares have jumped 10% and Sberbank shares have leapt 19%. In comparison, shares of Exxon Mobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have declined 4.7%, Chevron Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          CVX, -0.16%                                                                                                                                                 shares have gained 4.4% over the same period. Shares of the largest U.S. bank by market cap, however, J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          JPM, +0.69%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have rallied 23%. ', u' See: The biggest ETF winners and losers of 2016 ', u'A rush into Russian assets is also evidenced by the VanEck Vectors Russia ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           RSX, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                 and the iShares MSCI Russia Capped ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           ERUS, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 which have both gained about 17% since the election.', u'While Russian stocks have gained a significant boost since the election, that hasn\u2019t been the case for their Chinese counterparts. Since the election the Shanghai Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHCOMP, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                 has gained a paltry 1.1% based on the Chinese yuan, but has declined 0.4% in U.S. dollar terms, according to FactSet. Similarly, emerging markets ETFs have lagged behind with the Vanguard FTSE Emerging Markets ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           VWO, +0.59%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and the iShares MSCI Emerging Markets ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           EEM, +0.54%                                                                                                                                                \xa0up 1.5% and 1.3%, respectively.', u'Back in the U.S., small-cap stocks have benefited more than their larger counterparts since the election, but not so much since the inauguration. The Russell 2000 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 14% since the election, but less than 1% since Trump was sworn into office. ', u'Since the inauguration, the clear winners have been technology stocks, which lead sectors on the S&P 500 with a 3.6% gain. In turn, tech shares have been paced by a more than 10% gain in Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.94%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares. On the other hand, the worst performing sector since the election has been energy, which has fallen 3.5% since Trump took office.']

Name: Pepsico, Inc.
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         The NBA is changing its D-League to the G-League (G is for Gatorade)\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Gatorade Sports Science Institute (GSSI) intends to work with players in the league on player nutrition and training, according to a statement released on Feb. 14 by the NBA Development League.', u'\u201cAs one of the most iconic brands in the world and a founding partner of the NBA Development League, Gatorade                                                                                                                                                                                                           PEP, +0.35%                                                                                                                                                 is an ideal fit for this first-of-its-kind partnership,\u201d said Mark Tatum, NBA deputy commissioner and chief operating officer.', u'Not only is the D-League \u2014 er, G-League \u2014 cashing in from sponsors, but even NBA teams will be featuring advertisers\u2019 logos in a new place next season: team jerseys. For the first time next season, NBA jerseys can feature advertisements on them. Five teams have struck deals so far, according to Forbes, including General Electric                                                                                                                                                                                                           GE, +0.32%                                                                                                                                                \xa0paying the Boston Celtics around $8 million for a patch on their jerseys, and Blue Diamond almonds paying $5 million to the Sacramento Kings for a jersey ad.']

Name: Citigroup Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Bull market\u2019s 8-year anniversary reminds us that the Dow rewards the bold \r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -1.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is a benchmark of 30 large U.S. companies and generally serves as a barometer of broader market conditions; among investors here and abroad, the blue-chip average is synonymous with the U.S. stock market, period. ', u'Compared with stocks in Europe and Asia, the Dow is clearly an overachiever. The Stoxx Europe 600 Euro                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.61%                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed 138%, the U.K\u2019s FTSE 100                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, +0.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0advanced 108%, China\u2019s Shanghai Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHCOMP, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 50% and Japan\u2019s Nikkei                                                                                                                                                                                                           NIK, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 175% during the same time frame. ', u'Among the Dow components remaining from 2009, Home Depot Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HD, -0.81%                                                                                                                                                 is the undisputed star, soaring 608%, while American Express Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AXP, -1.67%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Walt Disney Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, -0.85%                                                                                                                                                \xa0both surged more than 500%.', u'Seven companies have joined the Dow after the bull market began its epic climb, doing their share to fuel the Dow\u2019s bullish run. UnitedHealth Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UNH, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0jumped 752% since the beginning of the bull market and Visa Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           V, -1.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0skyrocketed 524%. Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, -1.15%                                                                                                                                                 the youngest member of the blue-chip family, has shot up nearly 1,000% since 2009, although it rose only 9.3% since it became a Dow component two years ago. ', u' Newcomers on the Dow  ', u'Yet, not all Dow stocks have posted such stellar returns. Oil major Exxon Mobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has risen a paltry 23% while its competitor Chevron Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CVX, +0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 87%.', u'International Business Machines Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           IBM, -1.04%                                                                                                                                                 Procter & Gamble Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PG, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                 Verizon Communications Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           VZ, -0.16%                                                                                                                                                 and Wal-Mart Stores Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           WMT, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have also posted comparatively lackluster returns.', u'Only a handful of companies have been booted from the Dow since 2009\u2014AT&T Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.80%                                                                                                                                                 Bank of America Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, -5.81%                                                                                                                                                 Alcoa Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AA, -4.81%                                                                                                                                                 Citigroup Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           C, -2.60%                                                                                                                                                 General Motors Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GM, -3.25%                                                                                                                                                 Kraft Heinz Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KHC, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                 and HP Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPQ, -2.33%                                                                                                                                                 Of the seven, Bank of America\xa0and Citigroup have outperformed their Dow peers Goldman Sachs                                                                                                                                                                                                           GS, -3.77%                                                                                                                                                 and J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JPM, -2.93%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 although AT&T \u2018s                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.80%                                                                                                                                                 77% came up short of Verizon Communications Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           VZ, -0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa087% gains. Alcoa Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AA, -4.81%                                                                                                                                                 replaced by Nike Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NKE, -1.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in September 2013, is up 77%.']

Name: Unilever NV
Article: 12 : [u'\r\n         Kraft Heinz confirms merger proposal rebuffed by Unilever\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of both Kraft Heinz Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KHC, +0.66%                                                                                                                                                 and Unilever PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           UL, +0.32%                                                                                                                                                                              UN, +0.66%                                                                                                                                                 rose in Friday premarket trading after Kraft revealed that it made a merger proposal to Unilever that was declined. Shares of Unilever shot up 8.1%, while Kraft Heinz stock rose 3.1%. "While Unilever has declined the proposal, we look forward to working to reach an agreement on the terms of a transaction," Kraft Heinz said in the statement. Kraft brands include Oscar Meyer, Velveeta and Jell-O. Dove, Lipton and Vaseline are among Unilever\'s brands. Kraft stock is up 17.6% in the past year, Unilever shares are down 1.4% over that period, and the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                 is up 21.8% in the past 12 months.']

Name: Zillow Group, Inc.
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Nasdaq ekes out gains for new record, Dow hobbled by financials\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Nasdaq                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.31%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 8.24 points, or 0.2%, to close at 5,682.45, and the Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 fell 35.95 points, or 0.2%, to end at 20,054.34. J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          JPM, +0.41%                                                                                                                                                 Goldman Sachs Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GS, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Visa Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          V, +0.81%                                                                                                                                                \xa0were notable decliners. ', u'The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.15%                                                                                                                                                 edged up 1.59 points to finish at 2,294.67. Utilities and real estate shares topped the gains while financials were big losers. ', u'Financial stocks were pressured by falling yields, with the benchmark 10-year Treasury note\u2019s yield                                                                                                                                                                                                           TMUBMUSD10Y, -0.48%                                                                                                                                                 earlier touching a three-week low at about 2.33%. Low yields tend to hurt banks\u2019 business models.', u' See: Is Trump really unleashing \u2018animal spirits\u2019? Watch this chart ', u' Read: These are the charts to watch for a stock market dip in February ', u' And see: Tug of war between bulls and bears is keeping stock market in check ', u'WTI crude futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained even as data from the Energy Information Administration showed U.S. crude-oil inventories climbed for a fifth straight week. Supplies rose by 13.8 million barrels last week, larger than expected. ', u' Stock movers: Nordstrom Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JWN, -1.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares rose 4.1% after Trump criticized the retailer for its decision to drop Ivanka Trump\u2019s fashion brand. Nordstrom had said the move was a business decision, based on poor performance, rather than political. ', u' Time Warner Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                            TWX, -0.45%                                                                                                                                                 which is waiting on regulatory approval for its proposed $85.4 billion acquisition by AT&T Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.75%                                                                                                                                                 reported fourth-quarter adjusted earnings above consensus estimates. Shares advanced 0.4%. ', u'Shares of Botox maker Allergan PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                          AGN, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed 3.7% after fourth-quarter adjusted profit and sales surpassed expectations. ', u' Gilead Sciences Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                            GILD, +0.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sank 8.6% as Citigroup analysts cut the stock to neutral from buy after disappointing earnings late Tuesday.', u' Alaska Air Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ALK, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                 shares climbed 3.3% after the company reported a double-digit jump in revenue in the latest quarter and said it is raising its dividend.', u'  Zillow Group Inc. shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           Z, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                 skidded 6.4% after the real estate website forecast a wider loss for the year than Wall Street had expected. ', u' O\u2019Reilly Automotive Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           ORLY, +0.54%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares rose 3.6% after the car parts company reported a 13% increase in profits last quarter. ', u' Other markets: The ICE U.S. Dollar Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                 ticked lower while gold futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCJ7, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0were firmer. European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                          SXXP, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                 finished down and Japan\u2019s Nikkei Stock Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           NIK, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Hong Kong\u2019s Hang Seng Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSI, -1.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed higher. ', u' See: Time to sell the dollar on \u2018erratic\u2019 Trump policies, J.P. Morgan says ', u' \u2014Carla Moz\xe9e contributed to this report.  ']

Name: Marathon Petroleum Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Energy stocks are falling while the S&P is climbing \u2014 and that\u2019s a buying opportunity\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Yet energy is the absolute worst performer among the S&P 500\u2019s 11 sectors this year. It was down 5.5% through Monday, compared with a 6.1% gain for the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                 Exxon                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                 one of the best-quality names in the space, is trading near 52-week lows. UPDATE', u' Insider vote of confidence ', u'Let\u2019s start with the insiders. I\u2019ve tracked insiders for clues about the market for decades, and their buying is a core part of how I come up with a short list of stocks to research for my stock letter Brush Up on Stocks. Two key lessons on insiders support a bullish call on energy now. ', u'That looks like the case with energy stocks right now. Over the past few weeks there\u2019s been significant insider buying in over a dozen energy stocks, including Halliburton                                                                                                                                                                                                           HAL, -1.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in services, Hess                                                                                                                                                                                                           HES, -1.83%                                                                                                                                                 Oasis Petroleum                                                                                                                                                                                                           OAS, -2.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Matador Resources                                                                                                                                                                                                           MTDR, -2.38%                                                                                                                                                 in production, and Marathon Petroleum                                                                                                                                                                                                           MPC, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                 in refining. (I\u2019ll list the others, below.)', u' Inventories rising ', u'It takes six weeks or more for oil to arrive by boat to the U.S., the market of last resort for energy. But as it did, U.S. inventories began to build this year, unsettling investors. \u201cThe market looks at the big build up in U.S. inventories and gets nervous,\u201d says Jonathan Waghorn who helps manage the Guinness Atkinson Global Energy Fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           GAGEX, -0.80%                                                                                                                                                 Investors are still shellshocked after a U.S. inventory glut helped suppress oil prices and crush energy stocks two years ago. So any sign of a repeat has them selling. ', u' U.S. producers: They\u2019re baack! ', u'Thanks to higher energy prices, U.S. shale producers are back. They\u2019re deploying a lot more rigs. The rig count is back up over 600 compared with a low of 316 in May 2016 \u2014 and they are fracking a lot more. This also brings back bad memories of hefty losses for energy investors. ', u'OPEC, for example, will probably remain disciplined on production because of national budget constraints in Saudi Arabia, says John Groton, director of equity research at Thrivent Financial, who has followed the energy space for years. He thinks Saudi Arabia needs oil in the upper $60-per barrel range to balance its national budget. Oil                                                                                                                                                                                                          CLJ7, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 has traded recently in the mid-$50 range. ', u' One for the quants ', u' How to play this ', u'Another is to follow the insiders. Besides Halliburton, Oasis, Matador, Hess and Marathon Petroleum, which has a four out of five star rating at Morningstar, insiders were also recently buying in significant amounts at Carrizo Oil & Gas                                                                                                                                                                                                           CRZO, -1.68%                                                                                                                                                 Parsley Energy                                                                                                                                                                                                           PE, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                 Newfield Exploration                                                                                                                                                                                                           NFX, -1.56%                                                                                                                                                 Energy XXI                                                                                                                                                                                                           EXXI, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                 SM Energy                                                                                                                                                                                                           SM, -0.43%                                                                                                                                                 QEP Resources                                                                                                                                                                                                           QEP, -1.52%                                                                                                                                                 Martin Midstream Partners                                                                                                                                                                                                           MMLP, -1.04%                                                                                                                                                 Plains GP                                                                                                                                                                                                           PAGP, -0.65%                                                                                                                                                 Panhandle Oil and Gas                                                                                                                                                                                                           PHX, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Parker Drilling                                                                                                                                                                                                           PKD, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 ', u'Breard, at Hodges Capital Management, follows Comstock Resources                                                                                                                                                                                                           CRK, -3.68%                                                                                                                                                 closely. He has made some great contrarian calls on the company, favoring it last spring when it traded below $4, ahead of a move above $12. He likes the name in the current pullback into the $8-$9 range. \u201cComstock looks awfully cheap,\u201d he says, especially considering that over the next several weeks they are bringing several wells online in untapped territory, which suggests they will be particularly productive. He also likes Parsley Energy. which he says has good properties in the Permian and Delaware basins. ', u'Top holdings at Guinness Atkinson Global Energy Fund include Newfield, Devon Energy                                                                                                                                                                                                           DVN, -1.18%                                                                                                                                                 Carrizo, QEP Resources, Apache                                                                                                                                                                                                           APA, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                 Occidental Petroleum                                                                                                                                                                                                           OXY, -0.77%                                                                                                                                                 ConocoPhillips                                                                                                                                                                                                           COP, -0.93%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Noble                                                                                                                                                                                                           NE, +0.96%                                                                                                                                                 ', u'What about Exxon? If oil prices really are going back up to $70 over the next few years, it might not be the best energy name to own. In this scenario, investors will favor smaller, lower quality energy companies that use more leverage to fund development over more conservative, larger players like Exxon, Chevron                                                                                                                                                                                                           CVX, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and ConocoPhillips. ', u' Michael Brush is a Manhattan-based financial writer At the time of publication, he had no positions in any stocks mentioned in this column. Over the past several years, he has suggested HAL, HES, OAS, MTDR, CRK, MMLP, PHX, DVN, APA, OXY, COP, CVX and XOM in his stock newsletter Brush Up on Stocks.  ']

Name: DineEquity, Inc
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         DineEquity shares slip after CEO resignation, fourth-quarter earnings miss\r\n    ']
Body: [u'DineEquity Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          DIN, -1.64%                                                                                                                                                 shares fell 2.2% in Friday premarket trading after the company announced that Chief Executive Officer Julia Stewart has resigned, effective Mar. 1, and reported preliminary fourth-quarter earnings that missed expectations. Richard Dahl, lead director of the board, will serve as interim CEO while a search for a permanent replacement is conducted. Fourth-quarter net income was $21.1 million, or $1.18 per share, and adjusted EPS was to be $1.37. The FactSet consensus is $1.39. IHOP\'s domestic system-wide same-store sales were down 2.1% for the quarter, compared with a FactSet consensus of 1.2% growth. And Applebee\'s domestic system-wide same-store sales were down 7.2%, compared with a FactSet consensus of a 4.9% decline. The company will report quarterly and full-year earnings on Mar. 1. DineEquity shares are down 21.1% for the past year while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                 is up 21.8% for the same period.']

Article: 14 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Inside the global elite\u2019s bag of financial tricks\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Even Berkshire Hathaway                                                                                                                                                                                                           BRK.A, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                                              BRK.B, -0.54%                                                                                                                                                \xa0headed by traditional investor and legendary stock-picker Warren Buffett, enjoys significant gains through financial engineering, including the use of leverage and derivative contracts. Berkshire uses the insurance premiums received as \u201cfree float\u201d to finance investments. In the last decade, the company has sold long-dated options on international stock indices, credit default swaps on U.S. corporate credits, and insurance against municipal bonds. The premiums received boost its investment capital.', u' Satyajit Das is a former banker. His latest book is\xa0\u201cThe Age of Stagnation\u201d\xa0(published internationally as \u201cA Banquet of Consequences\u201d). He is also the author of \u201cExtreme Money\u201d and \u201cTraders, Guns & Money.\u201d ']

Name: Vanguard Intermediate-Term Corporate Bond ETF
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Investors tap investment-grade bond ETFs, but analysts like high-yield owed to \u2018risk-on\u2019 Trump\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The iShares iBoxx $ Investment Grade Corporate Bond ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           LQD, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                 the largest ETF to track the space, has seen inflows of $2.46 billion thus far in 2017. To compare, the iShares equivalent for junk bonds, the iShares iBoxx $ High Yield Corporate Bond ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           HYG, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                 has seen outflows of $1.1 billion over that same period.', u'Among other widely used funds in the space, the Vanguard Short-Term Corporate Bond ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           VCSH, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has seen inflows of $945.4 million year to date, while $1.95 billion has gone into the intermediate-term                                                                                                                                                                                                           VCIT, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fund.', u'Investment-grade bonds are issued by companies that no matter how remote the risk is, could default on payments. They don\u2019t have the government backing that U.S. Treasurys carry. Still, many high-rated company bonds are considered relatively low risk, as are government bonds. November was the worst month for Treasurys since December 2009.', u'That trend has continued thus far in 2017, with all three investment-grade bond ETFs up about 0.3%. To compare, the iShares high-yield bond fund is up 1.2%. The PIMCO 0-5 Year High Yield Corporate Bond Index ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           HYS, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                 which has seen outflows of $237.2 million year-to-date, is up 1% on the year.', u'Guggenheim also noted that the CBOE Volatility index                                                                                                                                                                                                           VIX, -2.65%                                                                                                                                                 a measure of investor anxiety, was trading at extremely low levels by historical standards. ']

Name: Navient Corporation
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Dow posts worst losing streak in 2 months on eve of Trump\u2019s inauguration\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0came off of its intraday low to slide 72.32 points, or 0.4%, to close at 19,732.40, falling for a fifth session in a row.', u' See: Trump inauguration set to unleash cascade of stock-market anxiety ', u'The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shed 8.20 points, or 0.4%, to end at 2,263.69 and the Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                          COMP, +0.37%                                                                                                                                                 fell 15.57 points, or 0.3%, to finish at 5,540.08.', u' Read: How stocks perform in a new president\u2019s first 100 days ', u'Wall Street closely monitored the Senate confirmation hearing of Steven Mnuchin for the post of Treasury Secretary for his views on the dollar and tax issues.', u' Read: Trump is waving adios to longstanding \u2018strong dollar policy\u2019 ', u'Draghi said there was \u201cno convincing upward trend in underlying inflation\u201d adding the central bank was ready to expand its quantitative-easing program if needed. His comments pushed the euro and the yen lower against the dollar. Earlier, the European Central Bank, as expected, left interest rates unchanged Thursday.', u'In economic news, first-time weekly jobless claim fell by more than expected, signaling continued strength in the labor market. Claims dropped by 15,000 to 234,000, highlighting the continued low levels of layoffs. Separately, housing starts ran at a seasonally adjusted annual pace of 1.23 million in December, 11.3% higher than in November, but about flat compared with the year-ago rate. ', u' Movers and Shakers: Shares of Netflix Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          NFLX, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rallied 3.9% after the streaming video giant posted better-than-expected quarterly results late Wednesday. Netflix added 7.05 million subscribers in the fourth quarter, roughly double the 3.57 million it gained in the third quarter.', u' Read: My dad talked me out of buying Netflix, but he wasn\u2019t wrong ', u' CSX Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CSX, +1.95%                                                                                                                                                \xa0soared 23% to its best daily gain since it went public nearly four decades ago, according to FactSet data. The railroad surged on news that industry veteran Hunter Harrison is teaming up with an activist investor in a bid to shake up CSX\u2019s management.', u'Another railroad operator, Union Pacific Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          UNP, +0.41%                                                                                                                                                 , rose 2.4% after earnings. ', u'Shares of Navient Crop                                                                                                                                                                                                          NAVI, -0.92%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slumped 1.2% after the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau filed a lawsuit against the nation\u2019s largest student loan services, accusing the company of mistreating borrowers.', u' Economic news: Federal Reserve Chairwoman Janet Yellen is due to give a speech at 8 p.m. Eastern at Stanford University, covering the economic outlook and monetary policy. On Wednesday, she said she expects rates to rise a few times a year until the end of 2019.', u' Check out: MarketWatch\u2019s Economic Calendar ', u' Other markets: Crude-oil futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLG7                                                                                                                                                \xa0traded higher, buoyed by data confirming that output by members of the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries fell last month. European stocks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.62%                                                                                                                                                 fell moderately, while Asian markets closed mixed. Gold futures                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:GCG7                                                                                                                                                 settled lower while 10-year Treasury yields                                                                                                                                                                                                           TMUBMUSD10Y, -0.63%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose to 2.46% and a key dollar index                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                 rose 0.2%.', u' --Victor Reklaitis contributed to this article. ']

Name: Novartis AG
Article: 10 : [u'\r\n         What to expect from Pfizer earnings: competition on two fronts\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The global drugmaker                                                                                                                                                                                                           PFE, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0faces rivals on two fronts, with generic drugs encroaching on standbys such as the statin Lipitor and a new class of drugs called biosimilars coming for its anti-inflammatory drug and a major revenue driver, Enbrel, according to Leerink analyst Seamus Fernandez, who rates the stock market perform with a $36 price target. ', u'But in the near-term, uptake is slowing and drugmakers such as Eli Lilly & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LLY, +0.75%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Novartis AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           NVS, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0plan to enter the space, he said. ', u' Here\u2019s what to expect: ', u' Earnings: Analysts expect Pfizer to report earnings per share of 50 cents, down from 53 cents in the year-earlier period, according to FactSet. Estimize, a software platform that uses crowdsourcing to garner earnings estimates from hedge fund executives, brokerages and analysts, has Pfizer earning the same, at 50 cents per share. Pfizer missed earnings expectations in the last quarter, but surpassed them in the prior 13 consecutive quarters. ', u' Revenue: Analysts expect Pfizer to report revenue of $13.6 billion, down from $14.0 billion in the year-earlier period, according to FactSet. Contributors on Estimize are forecasting revenue of $13.5 billion. Pfizer missed revenue expectations last quarter, but surpassed analyst expectations in the nine prior consecutive quarters. ', u' Stock reaction: Shares of Pfizer have slumped 3.0% over the last three months, compared with a 7.5% rise in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                 The average rating on Pfizer is overweight, according to a FactSet analyst survey, with the majority of surveyed analysts rating the company buy or hold.', u' What to watch for: Drug pricing and tax policy are two key issues that could change for the pharma sector in the coming years. The latter could be particularly significant, allowing for repatriation of out-of-U.S. cash that could foster big merger and acquisition activity. ', u' Related:  Big pharma won\u2019t stop raising prices in 2017 \u2014 it\u2019ll just do it smarter ', u' Read:  We\u2019re in the year of the biotech buyout, and here are five prime targets ']

Name: HP Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Whitman\u2019s excuses for Hewlett Packard Enterprise earnings are not enough\r\n    ']
Body: [u'HPE                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPE, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has never found its footing since splitting with HP Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPQ, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0more than a year ago, with year-over-year revenue declines in four of the five quarters since the split, culminating in a 10% quarterly drop reported Thursday. During its time as a separate company, the only constant besides disappointing revenue growth has been the company\u2019s incessant restructuring. HPE is in the process of two more financially driven spin-outs \u2014 computer services and software \u2014 that will likely lead to yet more restructuring costs.', u'Investors were clearly unsettled by the predicted shortfall and by what executives referred to as \u201cexecution issues.\u201d HPE shares tumbled more than 6% in after-hours trading, adding to recent struggles. HP has risen 4.7% in the past three months, trailing the S&P 500 index\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gains of 7.1% in that time, though HPE stock is still up 88.4% in the past year. ', u'Whitman and her executive team gave a string of reasons for the latest earnings mess, which included a slashed annual forecast: an order shortfall from a large, unidentified \u201ctier 1 service provider\u201d; expensive and hard-to-get memory components; and currency fluctuations. But those excuses are not good enough.', u'It appears that HPE\u2019s hybrid cloud strategy may also not be enough to keep all its customers from moving to vendors offering cloud computing for less. Whitman has shown a willingness to make deals that seem more disciplined than past disasters like Autonomy, such as recent acquisitions for SimpliVity and Cloud Corridor in key growth areas. But for HPE to show any real revenue growth now, some of those deals are going to have to start showing up in the company\u2019s top line. ', u'Whitman has yet to deliver on her promise that the new Hewlett-Packard Enterprise would be more agile and better off on its own. As year two begins as a solo company, with excuses running out and restructuring seeming to never end, time is not on her side to show better results. ']

Article: 11 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Mexican beer deserves a voice at the Super Bowl\r\n    ']
Body: [u'In 2011, Anheuser-Busch InBev                                                                                                                                                                                                           BUD, -0.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0paid $1.2 billion to secure the National Football League\u2019s official beer sponsorship for its Bud Light brand and to wrest it away from Molson Coors\u2019                                                                                                                                                                                                           TAP, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Coors Light. ABI later extended that deal through 2022 for another $1.5 billion. In the meantime, it\u2019s held exclusive rights to Super Bowl ad time since 1988 and paid more than $300 million for the privilege since 2006. This year\u2019s Budweiser Super Bowl ad, however, makes a fine argument for another brewery\u2019s presence among the NFL\u2019s big-game ads.', u'When Anheuser-Busch InBev slapped \u201cAmerica\u201d on Budweiser cans last year in a nod to the presidential election, it seemed an odd move for a brand and company that is global in every sense of the word. \u201cBudweiser\u201d traces to the city of \u010cesk\xe9 Bud\u011bjovice in the South Bohemia region of what is now the Czech Republic. That city has been brewing beer since the 1400s, and its German-speaking residents \u2014 who called it \u201cBudweis\u201d \u2014 began brewing Budweiser B\xfcrgerbr\xe4u in 1795. They started shipping that beer to the U.S. in 1875, or about a year before Adolphus Busch made a trip to Bohemia and decided to name his own U.S. beer Budweiser in tribute to the Bohemian brand.', u' Mexican beer powerhouse ', u'When Anheuser-Busch InBev purchased Grupo Modelo in 2013, it was forced by the U.S. Department of Justice to relinquish the rights of its most popular brands \u2014 including Corona, Modelo and Pacifico \u2014 as part of an antitrust agreement. Victor, N.Y.-based Constellation Brands                                                                                                                                                                                                           STZ, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0took those brands off ABI\u2019s hands for $4.75 billion and began building a Mexican beer powerhouse.', u' Read:  This is how much money Americans will spend for the Super Bowl and Heinz passes on pricy Super Bowl ad, gives some employees a day off instead', u' L.A. Rams sponsorship ', u'Though the administration says that tariff would eventually apply to all countries with which the U.S. has a trade deficit, it currently focuses on the $58 billion trade deficit with Mexico. The White House hopes to raise the estimated $12 billion to $15 billion it will cost to build the wall directly through the tariff. Republican Sen. Ben Sasse of Nebraska called it \u201ca tax on American families.\u201d', u'It also penalizes U.S. companies like Constellation Brands in an attempt to remedy an issue that is already fixing itself. If the intent of the wall is to cut off the flow of undocumented immigrants into the U.S. from Mexico, its builders should take into account that more Mexican migrants have been leaving the United States than entering it since 2009. The number of undocumented Mexican immigrants has declined by 1.3 million since 2007, though it\u2019s worth noting that the number of migrants from Central America who\u2019ve cleared fences at both Mexico\u2019s southern and northern borders has risen during that time.', u'That said, the number of total undocumented immigrants has declined since 2009 \u2014 and has dropped drastically in states including California, Nevada and Illinois. Those are all states in which Mexican migrants make up the majority of undocumented workers. In states where the undocumented population grew during that time \u2014 Washington, Utah, Minnesota, Louisiana, Pennsylvania, Virginia and New Jersey \u2014 only the first two have Mexican migrants as the majority of their undocumented immigrants.', u' \u2018F\xfatbol Americano\u2019 ', u'Last season, the NFL held a game in Mexico City for the first time since its \u201cF\xfatbol Americano\u201d matchup between the San Francisco 49ers and Arizona Cardinals in 2005. Though that first event drew more than 103,000 spectators to Estadio Azteca, the 74,000 that the Oakland Raiders and Houston Texans drew in November wasn\u2019t shabby. The NFL has already begun promoting (in Spanish, no less) the Raiders\u2019 return to face the New England Patriots later this year. ']
