Article: 7 : [u"\r\n         Sotheby's annual Americana Week auction generates most sales since 2007\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Sotheby\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           BID, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                 said Friday that its annual Americana Week auction generated $19.4 million in sales, the most since 2007 when it set a record of $29.1 million. The more than 1,000 lots included in this year\'s auction had an 80.4% sell-through rate. Sotheby\'s shares are down 1.8% in Friday trading, but up 77.5% for the last year. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.23%                                                                                                                                                 is up 21.8% for the past 12 months.']

Name: Molson Coors Brewing  Company
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n        ', u' How craft beer lost its craft and gained layoffs\r\n    ']
Body: [u'After we ran an interview with Pabst Brewing Co. owner Eugene Kashper, I began thinking about the Brewers Association\u2019s definition of a craft brewer as it applies to Pabst. There are many reasons to consider Pabst outside the \u201ccraft\u201d beer realm: Its Schlitz brand was once bigger than Anheuser-Busch InBev SA                                                                                                                                                                                                           BUD, -0.57%                                                                                                                                                 its portfolio is heavy with light lager, it now partners with multiple international brands including Mexico\u2019s Minerva and China\u2019s Tsingtao, and it has a strong business in decidedly non-craft flavored malt beverages (FMB) such as Not Your Father\u2019s Root Beer.', u'But various changes to the BA\u2019s definition have not only made Pabst\u2019s status an arguable point, but they\u2019ve also diluted the essence of the term \u201ccraft beer.\u201d The definition has three pillars: \u201csmall,\u201d \u201cindependent\u201d and \u201ctraditional.\u201d While Pabst would never have fit under the Brewers Association\u2019s original limit for \u201csmall\u201d \u2014 2 million barrels of annual production \u2014 the 5.5 million barrels it produced in 2015 fell below the 6-million-barrel mark the BA set when it changed its barrel production limit in 2010 to accommodate the growth of Boston Beer Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SAM, +0.40%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and its Samuel Adams brand.', u'Pabst would also have been easily excluded for producing mostly lager brewed with adjuncts such as corn or rice. However, the Brewers Association changed the \u201ctraditional\u201d portion of its definition in 2015 to include pre-Prohibition brewers, such as D.G. Yuengling and Sons, and August Schell, which have consistently brewed with maize (an ingredient once considered non-traditional by BA). That leaves the \u201cindependent\u201d portion, which states that less than 25% of a brewery can be \u201cowned or controlled (or equivalent economic interest) by an alcohol industry member that is not itself a craft brewer.\u201d Pabst is owned by Kashper and the private-equity firm TSG Consumer Partners, and ownership by private-equity firms has been generally accepted by the Brewers Association.', u'So why isn\u2019t Pabst \u201ccraft\u201d by this definition? Brewers Association spokesman Paul Gatza notes that the barrels of production Pabst sends to other countries, including China, now puts its production above 6 million. Meanwhile, Brewers Association economist Bart Watson notes that beer brewed under contract by other facilities is or isn\u2019t \u201ccraft,\u201d based on the facility brewing it. Since a large portion of Pabst beers are brewed at Molson Coors Brewing Co.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           TAP, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                 MillerCoors facilities \u2014 and MillerCoors isn\u2019t considered \u201ccraft\u201d \u2014 Pabst doesn\u2019t receive the \u201ccraft\u201d designation.', u'Those are some of the lesser consequences of such ambitious capital development. Green Flash Brewing of San Diego opened its Virginia Beach brewery last year, but not before influential brewmaster Chuck Silva left the company to found his own California brewery. Just this month, Green Flash laid off a number of employees in the wake of that expansion. In nearby Escondido, Calif., Stone Brewing Co. ended a year in which it opened new breweries in Richmond, Va., and Berlin \u2014 while losing longtime brewmaster Mitch Steele \u2014 by laying off dozens of employees. ', u'Before the Brewers Association\u2019s definition of a craft brewer and before small brewers even called their product \u201ccraft beer,\u201d the \u201ccraft\u201d portion of that moniker was short for hand-crafted. It implied that the hands producing and selling that beer mattered as much as the beer itself. That small, nimble, creative model is lean by nature and distinguishes itself by making beer and creating beer-based experiences that larger brewers can\u2019t.', u'A-B InBev has since purchased eight other U.S. craft breweries similarly focused on growth. MillerCoors, meanwhile, found willing partners in Saint Archer of San Diego, Oregon\u2019s Hop Valley and Georgia\u2019s Terrapin. Petaluma, Calif.-based Lagunitas and its owner, longtime craft firebrand Tony Magee, sold a half share to Heineken NV                                                                                                                                                                                                           HEINY, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                 for $500 million and has since begun expanding Lagunitas\u2019 presence and buying other breweries. Meanwhile, Ballast Point of San Diego last year announced plans to build an East Coast brewery near Roanoke,Va., but only after being purchased by Constellation Brands Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           STZ, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0for $1 billion about a year earlier.', u' Jason Notte is a freelance writer based in Portland, Ore. His writing has appeared in The New York Times, The Huffington Post and Esquire. Follow him on Twitter @Notteham. ']

Name: Pepsico, Inc.
Article: 15 : [u'\r\n         Coca-Cola earnings: Here\u2019s what is concerning analysts\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Of particular concern for some analysts is the recent weakness in beverage sales at convenience stores (C-store). Wells Fargo analyst Bonnie Herzog said fourth-quarter C-store sales were up 4.1% from a year ago, but that was \u201csignificantly below recent trends,\u201d and comes off \u201cexceptional growth\u201d of 8% last year, partly resulting from \u201csignificantly lower\u201d promotions. Read more about Wells Fargo\u2019s recent downgrade of Coke.', u' Earnings: Coke                                                                                                                                                                                                           KO, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is expected to report earnings excluding nonrecurring items of 37 cents a share for the quarter to Dec. 31, according to the average estimate of 21 analysts surveyed by FactSet. That is down from 38 cents a share in the same period a year ago. The FactSet earnings-per-share consensus has declined from 38 cents as of the end of the third quarter on Sept. 30.', u' Revenue: The FactSet revenue consensus is $9.14 billion, down from $10.01 billion in the same quarter last year. Those crowdsourced by Estimize are projecting, on average, revenue of $9.16 billion. As of Sept. 30, the FactSet consensus was $9.19 billion.', u' Stock price: The stock has been trending lower since peaking at a record close of $46.89 on April 4, 2016. It had lost as much as 14% to a 14-month low close of $40.17 on Dec. 1, before bouncing slightly since then.', u'The stock 0.3% on Wednesday, but has lost 10% since its record close, and 2% since the election. Meanwhile, shares of rival PepsiCo Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PEP, +0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have gained 1.8% since April 4, 2016 and the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has surged 13%.', u'Don\u2019t miss: It\u2019s time to sell Coca-Cola and P&G stocks, Goldman says.', u'Warren Buffett\u2019s Berkshire Hathaway Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BRK.B, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is Coca-Cola\u2019s largest shareholder, with 400 million shares, or 9.3% of the shares outstanding, as of Sept. 30, according to FactSet.', u' Other issues: Coke will likely continue to blame the strengthening of the U.S. dollar as one of the big reasons for the year-over-year decline in sales. In the third-quarter report, net sales fell 7%, but \u201corganic\u201d revenue, excluding the negative effect of currency--a 2% headwind--and acquisitions and divestitures, rose 3%.', u'See also: Coca-Cola\u2019s new CEO should making acquiring Monster a business priority.', u' \u2022 Sales for the North America region: $2.39 billion', u' \u2022 Sales for Latin America: $995.0 million', u' \u2022 Sales for Pacific: $992.0 million', u' \u2022 Volume growth in North America: -0.5%', u' \u2022 Volume growth in Latin America: -0.1%', u' \u2022 Volume growth in Asia Pacific: +1.3%']

Name: Twitter, Inc.
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         Snap\u2019s market cap surpasses Twitter, Hershey\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Snap                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +7.75%                                                                                                                                                 the parent of Snapchat, started trading on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday and closed at $24.53, up 44% from its issue price, which gave it a public market capitalization of $28.4 billion. The closing market cap makes Snap more valuable than Hershey Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSY, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                 and Twitter Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TWTR, +2.06%                                                                                                                                                 among others. ', u'The closing market capitalization also made Snap more valuable than the majority of components in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                 ', u'Snap is often compared with social-media competitors Twitter, which it beats in terms of market cap, and Facebook Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, +0.56%                                                                                                                                                 which it is far surpassed by.', u'It is important to note that there are different calculations of Snap\u2019s value. Some use the market capitalization, calculated by shares outstanding multiplied by the price, which amounts to $28.4 billion. Others use a fully diluted valuation, which includes restricted stock units, options outstanding and other shares. That brings the value closer to $34 billion, according to some outlets. ', u' \u2014 Jess Marmor Shaw contributed to this report.  ']

Name: United Parcel Service, Inc.
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         UPS stock suffers biggest drop in 2 years as e-commerce surge is still causing problems\r\n    ']
Body: [u'UPS reported before the market open fourth-quarter adjusted earnings and revenue that missed expectations, primarily because of what Chief Executive David Abney described on a post-results conference call as \u201ca significant shift in mix towards lower revenue products,\u201d according to a transcript provided by FactSet.', u'The stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           UPS, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0plunged $7.90, or 6.8%, in active trade to the lowest close since Nov. 4. Volume spiked to 12.7 million shares, which was nearly six-times the full-day average.', u'The one-day price and percentage declines were the biggest since Jan. 23, 2015. On that day, the shares plunged $11.32, or 9.9%, the second-biggest-ever percentage slide, after UPS warned it would miss fourth-quarter profit projections. UPS explained back then, that a big jump in deliveries during peak holiday selling days was offset by higher-than-expected peak-related expenses.', u'See also: Investors have to wonder: Can UPS finally get it just right next Christmas?', u' Kuehn announced his retirement, after eight years as CFO and 38 years with the company, three months later. Peretz, who was named as his replacement, has been with the company since 1981.', u' Don\u2019t miss: UPS completes drone test for urgent commercial delivery.', u'UPS shares have climbed 17.1% over the past 12 months, while the Dow Jones Transportation Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJT, +0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has rallied 33.1% and the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 17.5%.']

Name: Walt Disney Company (The)
Article: 9 : [u'\r\n        ', u' A 50-year bond is a great idea from the Trump administration\r\n    ']
Body: [u'At last, some good might come from having all those Wall Street wheeler-dealers in the Trump administration: Someone might be using his business know-how to save the taxpayers a bundle, instead of using them to enrich himself or the rest of the elite.', u'\u201cI think it is something that is a very serious issue of whether we should explore, whether we can raise 50- or 100-year money at a very slight premium is something that makes sense for Treasury to look at,\u201d Mnuchin said in an interview on CNBC. ', u'Trump himself raised the idea last May, suggesting that the U.S. government could refinance some of its debt for a longer period, thus locking in today\u2019s low rates. It was in that same interview last year that Trump shocked financial markets with his off-the-cuff suggestion that maybe the government should threaten to just walk away from its debts as a way to negotiate with bondholders for a better deal, the way Trump had done so often with his hotels and casinos. ', u'The Treasury could issue more long-term debt to extend the average maturity, but it has held back on the advice of the Treasury\u2019s Borrowing Advisory Committee, which is composed of the big Wall Street firms that operate the bond market, buying from the Treasury and selling to the public.', u'Ireland, Belgium and Mexico have recently sold 100-year bonds. Ford                                                                                                                                                                                                           F, +0.77%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 Disney                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Coca-Cola                                                                                                                                                                                                           KO, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 have sold 100-year bonds as well. The Canadian Pacific Corp. sold a 1,000-year bond. ']

Name: Brooks Automation, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Chip stocks index could soar over 35% this year, Credit Suisse analyst says\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Chip stocks are set up for a big rally in 2017, with the PHLX Semiconductor Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SOX, +0.15%                                                                                                                                                 soaring more than 35%, as the industry expected to grow faster than the global economy for the first time since the late 1990s, according to analyst John Pitzer at Credit Suisse. His base-case 12-month target for the chip index (SOX) is 1,000, which is 8.6% above current levels, but he sees upside to 1,250 over the next 12 months, which is 36% above current levels. Pitzer said he expects the SOX to retest its 2000 peak of 1,362 over the next 18-to-24 months, which is 48% above current levels. Despite rising barriers to entry, slowing supply growth, continued industry consolidation and diversifying demand drivers, Pitzer said the sector still trades at a 20% to 25% discount to the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.27%                                                                                                                                                 by his calculation. "We continue to argue that semiconductors are the safest and cheapest way to play what we have described as the data growth paradigm in technology," Pitzer wrote in a note to clients. As part of his industry call, Pitzer upgraded Texas Instruments Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TXN, +0.40%                                                                                                                                                 to outperform from neutral and Brooks Automation Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BRKS, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                 to neutral from underperform, while downgrading Rudolph Technologies Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           RTEC, +0.23%                                                                                                                                                 to neutral from outperform. The SOX, which climbed 1.4% in midday trade, has rocketed 53% over the past 12 months, while the S&P 500 has gained 18%.']

Name: Genesco Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Investors haven\u2019t been this gloomy for a year \u2014 here\u2019s why that\u2019s bullish\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Bearishness among regular folks who invest just climbed to its highest level in more than a year, according to the American Association of Individual Investors.', u"The AAII survey is often used as a contrarian indicator, meaning traders turn upbeat when its readings get gloomier. The iBankCoin financial blog\u2019s Option Addict and CrackedMarket's Jani Ziedins are doing exactly that, and together they deliver our bullish call of the day.", u'\u201cPeople are simply trying to anticipate pain here,\u201d Option Addict writes. \u201cThat means pain is still up.\u201d This is likely a take on what is the \u201cpain trade\u201d right now, meaning how the market might do its usual thing of delivering the maximum amount of punishment to the most investors.', u'\u201cWhen the market isn\u2019t doing what the crowd expects, that means it is getting ready to do the opposite,\u201d he writes.', u'The Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, S&P                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                 and Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.10%                                                                                                                                                 are higher after a stronger-than-expected jobs report. But they are still on track for weekly drops of between 0.2% and 0.7%.', u' Oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0has turned negative, adding to its lousy week.', u'See the Market Snapshot column for the latest action.', u'\u201cOver the past 16 years, the market has generally responded favorably to February\u2019s jobs report released in March,\u201d writes Jeff Hirsch in an Almanac Trader blog post.', u'The U.S. economy added 235,000 new jobs in February in the Trump era\u2019s first full month, as unemployment fell to 4.7%. The solid reading on nonfarm payrolls clears the way for the Fed to hike interest rates at its meeting next week, economists are saying.', u' Check out: MarketWatch\u2019s Economic Calendar ', u'Are you ready for the Winklevoss Bitcoin Trust ETF? The SEC could issue a ruling today on the famous twins\u2019 fund. (By the way: Bitcoin\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:BTCUSD                                                                                                                                                biggest threat has nothing to do with the SEC.)', u'\u201cOne of the key points that the bears on SNAP                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +6.31%                                                                                                                                                 may be missing is that we believe that FB                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                \xa0would love to acquire the company,\u201d says FBN Securities analyst Shebly Seyrafi.', u'Ulta Beauty                                                                                                                                                                                                           ULTA, +0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is higher, bouncing back from premarket losses that came after its outlook wasn\u2019t that stunning. Vail Resorts                                                                                                                                                                                                          MTN, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                and Genesco                                                                                                                                                                                                          GCO, -1.52%                                                                                                                                                are also jumping following their earnings reports before the open.', u'China\u2019s central bank is tightening credit controls and signaling a policy shift, a Wall Street Journal report says.', u' Opinion: China\u2019s economic miracle is over ', u'\u201cIt\u2019s not ideal to expand the conflict by continuing the protests outside on the streets. ... Precious lives were lost during the rallies today, and this must no longer happen.\u201d \u2014 South Korea\u2019s acting head of state, Hwang Kyo-ahn, pleaded today with opponents and supporters of the country\u2019s ousted president, after two men died in protests.', u'On a lighter note, the South Korean judge who leads the court that sent Park Geun-hye packing has gone viral \u2014 for her hair rollers.', u'279 \u2014 That is how many corporate insiders bought their own company\u2019s shares in January. It\u2019s the lowest total in 29 years, according to a WSJ report citing the Washington Service, a provider of insider-trading data.', u' This cop didn\u2019t realize an Uber driver was a lawyer.', u'\u201cMy name is Ozymandias, King of Kings\u201d \u2014 and that\u2019s my statue.', u'Elon Musk is offering to fix South Australia\u2019s power crisis.', u'Mark Zuckerberg and Priscilla Chan are expecting another baby girl.', u'An expert\u2019s live interview was hilariously interrupted by his kids acting up.', u'Big typo: Digit added to IP address, man wrongly accused of being a pedophile.', u'\u201cBuffy the Vampire Slayer\u201d fans have been posting tributes:', u' Need to Know starts early and is updated until the opening bell, but sign up here to get it delivered once to your email box. Be sure to check the Need to Know item. The emailed version will be sent out at about 7:30 a.m. Eastern. ', u'  Or Follow MarketWatch on Twitter or Facebook. ', u' And sign up here to get the Friday email highlighting 10 of the best MarketWatch articles of the week. ']

Name: Collegium Pharmaceutical, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Fund that almost tripled the S&P 500\u2019s gain last year is now big on health-care stocks\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The mutual fund\u2019s Class A shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZAX, -2.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0returned 31.6% in 2016, compared with returns of 12% for the large-cap S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and 21.3% for the small-cap Russell 2000 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0', u'Gregory is chief investment officer of Highland Alternative Investors, a unit of Highland Capital Management, which is based in Dallas and manages about $15.4 billion. He oversees the small-cap stock fund with James Dondero, the president and co-founder of Highland Capital Management. The fund itself is small, with about $55 million in assets. ', u'Two MLP winners in 2016 were Energy Transfer Equity LP                                                                                                                                                                                                           ETE, -1.72%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and SemGroup Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SEMG, -0.67%                                                                                                                                                 each of which gained nearly 100% for the fund last year. But Gregory said the fund had taken \u201cabout two-thirds of the chips off the table\u201d for each position.', u'\u201cSo we have done a good job harvesting our gains and capturing our profit and sizing down to a position we think is appropriate,\u201d Gregory said. He said the price of crude oil\xa0\u201ccan head into the $60s near-term.\u201d West Texas crude oil for March delivery                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed at $52.75 on Jan. 25.', u'One example of a company with a new approach to pain relief is Collegium Pharmaceutical Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           COLL, -3.02%                                                                                                                                                 which has developed Xtampza ER, an oxycodone medication designed to reduce the chances of addiction or abuse through the combination of oxycodone \u201cwith fatty acid and waxes to form small spherical beads (microspheres) that are filled into a capsule.\u201d', u'Another company with an interesting new pain-relief product is Pacira Pharmaceuticals Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PCRX, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                 which makes Exparel, a non-opioid pain reliever used for soft-tissue surgeries and orthopedic procedures. The medication is injected during surgery.', u'Gregory said he was focused on multifamily real estate investment trusts (REITs) and has looked at \u201ca concept we\u2019ve proven ourselves,\u201d through NexPoint Residential Trust Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NXRT, -1.20%                                                                                                                                                 which Highland manages but does not hold within the Highland Small Cap Equity Fund. That concept is acquiring multifamily properties and improving them, justifying higher rents. NexPoint\u2019s stock returned 79.5% last year.', u'The first REIT holding that Gregory mentioned in an interview was Independence Realty Trust Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           IRT, -1.42%                                                                                                                                                 a multifamily REIT he said was \u201cvery similar in strategy\u201d to NexPoint. ', u'The other REIT Gregory said he favored was Jernigan Capital Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JCAP, -1.42%                                                                                                                                                 which invests in self-storage facilities.\xa0\xa0\u201cThink of the demographic boom going on in cities like Dallas, San Antonio, Nashville and Austin. When people move, they need to put their things somewhere, and ... when they do, they never leave. So we get a mid- to high-single-digit dividend yield [of 6.75%], with increasing operating income,\u201d he said.', u'Gregory named two pipeline operators, Western Gas Equity Partners LP                                                                                                                                                                                                           WGP, -0.69%                                                                                                                                                 which has a dividend yield of 4.08% and has what Gregory calls a \u201cvery strong sponsor\u201d in Anadarko Petroleum Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           APC, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                ; and Tesoro Logistics LP                                                                                                                                                                                                           TLLP, -0.38%                                                                                                                                                 which has a dividend yield of 6.36%, and is sponsored by Tesoro Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TSO, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0', u'Highland Alternative Investors acquired the Small Cap Equity Fund from GE Asset Management in 2010. A series of subadvisers helped manage the fund until July 2015, when Gregory and Dondero took over. The fund has three share classes, and it\u2019s important to consider sales charges and expenses carefully by looking at the prospectus for this or any other mutual fund:', u'It\u2019s pretty obvious when looking at the performance of the Russell 2000 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                 that 2016 was a big year for small-cap stocks.', u'The Highland Small Cap Equity Fund\u2019s Class A shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZAX, -2.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have an upfront sales charge of 5.75% and total annual expenses of 1.60% of assets. Class C                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZCX, -2.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares have no upfront sales charge, carry a 1% deferred sales charge for shares sold within six months of purchase, and have total annual expenses of 2.35%. Class Y                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZYX, -2.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares have no sales charge, and annual expenses of 1.35%, but are available only to institutional investors. All of those expense figures reflect the waiver of 0.42% of annual expenses, which will continue at least until Jan. 31, 2018.']

Name: Kate Spade & Company
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Michael Kors downgraded on promotional holiday handbags, fewer Instagram \u2018likes\u2019\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Holiday promotions cut across the handbag industry, according to analysts, though Michael Kors                                                                                                                                                                                                           KORS, -1.44%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Kate Spade & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KATE, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                 which Piper Jaffrey doesn\u2019t cover, were highlighted for being most discounted.', u' See also:  Coach, Michael Kors, Kate Spade go deep on holiday weekend discounts ', u'Michael Kors, along with brands like Ralph Lauren Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          RL, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 has been fighting discounting by reducing merchandise levels at department stores. Michael Kors beat expectations during the most recent period, but some analysts say it wasn\u2019t a \u201cgood\u201d beat due to weak traffic. ', u'Rival handbag company Coach Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           COH, -1.33%                                                                                                                                                 has also cut back on merchandise at department stores, which has hurt sales, but generated support from analysts. Analysts at Jefferies believe that handbags will be an \u201cirreplaceable category with high margins\u201d in 2017, and called out Michael Kors as a beneficiary.', u' See also: Abercrombie & Fitch downgraded on stalled turnaround, but Nike is tops for 2017 ', u' Read also: Kate Spade is a strong takeover candidate for Coach, Michael Kors and others ', u'Michael Kors has 9.3 million Instagram followers.', u' See also:  Here\u2019s why Selena Gomez may be worth $10 million to Coach ', u' See also:  Good luck finding luxury brands like Louis Vuitton, Hermes or even Tesla on sale  ', u'Michael Kors shares are down 0.2% in Tuesday trading, but up 7% for the last year. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                 is up nearly 10% for the past 12 months.']

Name: Edwards Lifesciences Corporation
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Corporate insiders have a stock market surprise for you\r\n    ']
Body: [u'That they\u2019re not selling into recent strength is therefore quite bullish, according to Nejat Seyhun, a finance professor at the University of Michigan and a leading expert on the behavior of corporate insiders.', u'To be sure, the message of the insiders isn\u2019t always right. But history has shown that they\u2019re far more right than wrong. The last time I reported on Seyhun\u2019s research, in October 2015, he projected a 15% return for the broad market over the subsequent 12 months. In fact, the S&P 500\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0total return over those 12 months was \u201cjust\u201d 11%. In the inexact world of stock market forecasting, that October 2015 projection has to be graded as remarkably accurate.', u'David Miller, manager of the Catalyst Insider Buying Fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           INSAX, -1.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, and one of Seyhun\u2019s graduate students at Michigan, draws special attention right now to the financials sector. In an interview, he mentioned four small- and mid-tier banks where there has been noteworthy insider buying: Carolina Financial                                                                                                                                                                                                           CARO, -1.06%                                                                                                                                                 FNB Bancorp                                                                                                                                                                                                           FNBG, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                ; Medley Capital                                                                                                                                                                                                           MCC, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, and Paragon Commercial                                                                                                                                                                                                           PBNC, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0.', u'The other sector that Miller notes for recent insider buying is health care. Five companies in that sector he mentions are: Baxter International                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAX, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                ; Edwards Lifesciences                                                                                                                                                                                                           EW, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                ; Insulet                                                                                                                                                                                                           PODD, -1.51%                                                                                                                                                ; McKesson,                                                                                                                                                                                                           MCK, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Medtronic                                                                                                                                                                                                           MDT, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. (Miller\u2019s funds hold these health-care and bank stocks.)', u' For more information, including descriptions of the Hulbert Sentiment Indices, go to   www.hulbertratings.com  or email   mark@hulbertratings.com   ']

Name: Caterpillar, Inc.
Article: 9 : [u'\r\n         Stocks close lower as financials slump\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Stocks retreated from record levels to close down Thursday with the Dow industrials nearly finishing below the recently attained 21,000 level as financial stocks slumped and defensive sectors gained. The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                 shed 112.58 points, or 0.5%, to finish at 21,002.97, led lower by a sharp drop in Caterpillar Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CAT, -0.38%                                                                                                                                                 shares after federal agents raided the company\'s headquarters. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                 closed down 14.04 points, or 0.6%, at 2,381.92, with financial and materials stocks weighing on the index and utilities and telecoms closing slightly higher. The Nasdaq Composite index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                 finished down 42.81 points, or 0.7%, at 5,861.22.']

Name: Sears Holdings Corporation
Article: 9 : [u'\r\n         Target is adding stores, but analysts say they should be cutting locations instead\r\n    ']
Body: [u'During the company\u2019s financial community meeting, which took place shortly after the release of the retailer\u2019s fourth-quarter earnings, Target                                                                                                                                                                                                           TGT, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0outlined its strategy for the future, which includes a $7 billion investment over the next three years. In that time, the company plans to revamp more than 600 of its approximately 1,800 locations, and open more than 100 small-format stores. ', u' See also: Target suffers record stock price plunge ', u' See also: From a risk-of-bankruptcy standpoint, the retail business is the new oil and gas  ', u'The focus on growing stores is a departure from the store closures we\u2019ve heard from major retailers like J.C. Penney Co Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JCP, -1.95%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Macy\u2019s Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           M, -0.99%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and Sears Holding Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHLD, -15.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 And while analysts are supportive of the changes that Target outlined, some believe a few closures could be a good thing.', u' Read also: Bankrupt American Apparel could help Gildan grow overseas ', u'\u201cThe low-price strategy is notable, in our view, as we find it hard to envision Target effectively competing with Walmart                                                                                                                                                                                                           WMT, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 or Amazon                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 on price,\u201d Stifel wrote in a Tuesday note. \u201cWhile the company is not trying to directly undercut Walmart on prices, it is trying to use everyday lower prices on daily use items to drive customers into remodeled stores that provide a better experience than Walmart.\u201d', u' Read also: J.C. Penney\u2019s store closures are a good move, but could signal bigger problems ', u' See also: Nordstrom says Trump\u2019s tweets after Ivanka\u2019s collections were dropped didn\u2019t hurt results ', u'Target shares closed down 1.6% on Wednesday, and shares are down 28.7% for the past year. The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is up 20.6% for the last 12 months.']

Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Oil closes up amid Libyan output concerns, but posts weekly loss\r\n    ']
Body: [u'On the New York Mercantile Exchange, April West Texas Intermediate crude                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0tacked on 72 cents, or 1.4%, to settle at $53.33 a barrel. It registered a loss of around 1.2% for the week. May Brent crude                                                                                                                                                                                                           LCOK7, -1.28%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 82 cents, or 1.5%, to $55.90 a barrel on London\u2019s ICE Futures exchange\u2014ending about 0.7% lower on the week.', u' Bloomberg reported that an armed faction entered a major Libyan oil terminal Friday. Earlier, it reported that the employees were evacuated from the Es Sider oil port as fighting escalated nearby.', u' Read: Venezuelan oil production may tumble 20% by the end of 2017 ', u'Oil prices dropped more than 2% Thursday, dragged down by the latest expansion in U.S. stockpiles and production, which exacerbated concerns that the market is still oversupplied despite OPEC output cuts. ', u'Data from Baker Hughes                                                                                                                                                                                                           BHI, +0.71%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Friday showed a seventh straight weekly increase in the number of active U.S. rigs drilling for oil. ', u'On Nymex Friday, April gasoline                                                                                                                                                                                                           RBJ7, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0edged up about a cent to $1.653 a gallon, though it ended sharply lower for the week by 4.8%, according to data from Dow Jones. April heating oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           HOJ7, -0.73%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 1.5 cents, or 0.9%, to $1.594 a gallon, for a loss of about 3.3% on the week.', u'Natural-gas prices inched up to finish about 1.4% higher for the week, according to Dow Jones data. The April                                                                                                                                                                                                           NGJ17, -1.49%                                                                                                                                                \xa0ended at $2.827 per million British thermal units, up 2.3 cents, or 0.8%.', u'  --Sarah McFarlane contributed to this article  ']

Body: [u'The nixed Mexican meeting halted the peso\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/15936962/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>USDMXN, -0.0105%                                                                                                                                                \xa0brief rally , and now there are \u201ctough issues\u201d to tackle as Trump chats with Britain\u2019s Theresa May, says TopTradr analyst Tony Cross. Any hints that our dealmaker-in-chief is trying to \u201ctake advantage of the U.K.\u2019s diminished position as it edges out of the EU\u201d could whack the pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.2084%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Cross warns.', u'What to do with all these trade-related tensions? Ignore the hoopla and consider buying the iShares Mexico ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           EWW, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. So suggests our call of the day from Steven Jon Kaplan at True Contrarian, a blog/newsletter that says it \u201cidentifies the most unanimous consensus in the financial markets, then goes in the exact opposite direction of that consensus.\u201d', u'The punished peso will bring about \u201cincreased exports, lower wages in U.S. dollar terms, increased multinational relocation, and therefore sharply increased profits within a year,\u201d says the contrarian trader. He says he bought the big Mexico ETF when it changed hands at $41.99 earlier this month, and he plans to buy more if the $1.8 billion fund falls to $40.99.', u' Read more: Mexico ETFs fall as tensions rise between Trump and Nieto ', u' And see: Trump calls U.S.-Mexico trade one-sided \u2014 and here\u2019s the reality ', u'Futures for the Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:YMH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0, S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:ESH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Nasdaq-100                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:NQH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0are little changed. 18 : [u'\r\n         Buffett praises Bank of America\u2019s buybacks\r\n    ']
Body: [u'\u201cMany of our investees, including Bank of America                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, -0.93%                                                                                                                                                 have been repurchasing shares, some quite aggressively. We very much like this behavior because we believe the repurchased shares have in most cases been underpriced. (Undervaluation, after all, is why we own these positions.),\u201d the Berkshire Hathaway                                                                                                                                                                                                           BRK.A, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                                              BRK.B, -0.53%                                                                                                                                                 chairman wrote in his annual letter to investors, which was released Saturday. ', u'That\u2019s a departure from Buffett\u2019s previous stance, The Wall Street Journal notes. Buffett had previously said Berkshire would probably only exercise the warrants just before expiration.', u'Buffett typically offers little detail on outside investments in the annual letter. For example, investors looking for more detail on Berkshire\u2019s stake in Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.39%                                                                                                                                                 which grew sharply in 2016, won\u2019t find much aside from its listing in a table of Berkshire\u2019s largest 15 common stock investments.', u' See:  Warren Buffett\u2019s big bet on Apple may have made him $1.1 billion in just six weeks ']

Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Time Inc. shares jump more than 9% after report company is seeking acquisition offers\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of publishing company Time Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TIME, +1.04%                                                                                                                                                 were up more than 9% in premarket trade on Wednesday following a Bloomberg report, citing sources saying the company is seeking acquisition offers by next week. According to the report, Time\'s board wants to gauge how others value the company to determine whether Time would be better off selling the entire company or certain magazine titles. Time publishes more than 100 titles, including Sports Illustrated, InStyle, People and flagship magazine, Time. The report comes after months of potential acquisition talks. In December The Wall Street Journal reported that Time had hired Morgan Stanley                                                                                                                                                                                                           MS, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                 and Bank of America Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, +0.11%                                                                                                                                                 to field buyout or partnership interest. And in February, magazine publisher Meredith Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MDP, +1.87%                                                                                                                                                 and an investor group led by Edgar Bronfman advanced their pursuit of Time by signing non-disclosure agreements with the company. Time, which has a market valuation of $1.74 billion, has been struggling with declining advertising and newsstand revenue. Shares of the company are up more than 24% in the trailing 12-month period, while the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                 has gained more than 19% during the same period.']

Name: Molina Healthcare Inc
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         Aetna and Humana end merger deal after 19 months\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Aetna Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AET, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                 and Humana Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HUM, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                 announced Tuesday a mutual agreement to terminate their merger deal, after a U.S. District Court granted the Department of Justice\'s request to block the $34 billion deal announced in July 2015. As a result, Aetna will pay Humana a $1 billion merger termination fee. Aetna will also terminate its agreement to sell certain Medicare Advantage assets to Molina Healthcare Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MOH, -0.66%                                                                                                                                                 and will pay Molina the agreed upon fees. "While we continue to believe that a combined company would create greater value for health care consumers through improved affordability and quality, the current environment makes it too challenging to continue pursuing the transaction," said Aetna Chief Executive Mark Bertolini. Shares of Aetna and Humana were still inactive in premarket trade. Aetna\'s stock has lost 1.6% over the past three months, while Humana shares have gained 4% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                 has climbed 7.6%.']

Name: Southwest Airlines Company
Article: 12 : [u'\r\n         Trump Today: Blumenthal targeted as president still backs Gorsuch\r\n    ']
Body: [u'President Donald Trump said to expect an announcement that\u2019s \u201cphenomenal in terms of tax\u201d in the next two or three weeks, and his spokesman Sean Spicer later put a finer point on it, saying it would involve an outline of comprehensive tax reform. Spicer told reporters it would \u201caddress both the business side of the tax ledger as well as the individual rates.\u201d ', u' BASHING BLUMENTHAL  ', u'\u2022 As he does on most mornings, the president got off to an early start on Twitter, this time lashing out at Sen. Richard Blumenthal of Connecticut. Wednesday, Blumenthal said Trump\u2019s Supreme Court nominee, Neil Gorsuch, called Trump\u2019s attacks on the judiciary \u201cdemoralizing and disheartening.\u201d Gorsuch\u2019s own team confirmed those remarks but Trump apparently doesn\u2019t believe it. ', u' MALIGNING MCCAIN ', u' MEETING THE AIRLINE CHIEFS  ', u'\u2022 Trump made his aforementioned tax comment at a meeting with airline CEOs including the heads of United Continental Holdings                                                                                                                                                                                                           UAL, +0.45%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Delta Air Lines Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DAL, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and Southwest Airlines Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LUV, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 In that meeting he suggested adopting changes to the government\u2019s air-traffic control system and putting a pilot at the head of the Federal Aviation Administration. ', u' Read:  Trump advocates changes to air-traffic control system. ', u' SESSIONS SWORN IN ', u' ORDER UP ', u'\u2022 Trump signed three executive orders Thursday: one creating a task force on crime reduction; another aimed at preventing violence against law enforcement officers; and a third meant to thwart international gangs. ', u' FOREIGN PHONE CALLS ', u' SUPREME COURT \u2018LISTENING SESSION\u2019 ', u' IMMIGRATION OPENING? ', u'President Trump reportedly told lawmakers at the Supreme Court meeting that he would be open to supporting the so-called Gang of Eight immigration bill, a measure that included a path to citizenship for undocumented immigrants. That was according to Manchin. But Trump\u2019s spokesman later walked back the statement, saying the president doesn\u2019t support the Gang of Eight.']

As protectionism heats up, Nvidia\u2019s products could be dropped in favor of those of local companies, damaging earnings of this expensive stock. Body: [u'Shares of both Kraft Heinz Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KHC, +0.65%                                                                                                                                                 and Unilever PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           UL, +0.31%                                                                                                                                                                              UN, +0.66%                                                                                                                                                 rose in Friday premarket trading after Kraft revealed that it made a merger proposal to Unilever that was declined. Shares of Unilever shot up 8.1%, while Kraft Heinz stock rose 3.1%. "While Unilever has declined the proposal, we look forward to working to reach an agreement on the terms of a transaction," Kraft Heinz said in the statement. Kraft brands include Oscar Meyer, Velveeta and Jell-O. Dove, Lipton and Vaseline are among Unilever\'s brands. Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Panera shares higher after company earnings come in above expectations\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of Panera Bread Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PNRA, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                 rose nearly 2% late Tuesday after the fast-casual restaurant chain reported adjusted fourth-quarter earnings above expectations and revenue that met expectations. Panera said it earned $44 million, or $1.92 a share, in the quarter, compared with $1.74 a share on net income of $43 million in the year-ago quarter. Adjusted for one-time items, Panera earned $2.05 a share, compared with $1.88 a share a year ago. Sales rose to $727 million, up from $692 million in the fourth quarter of 2015. Analysts polled by FactSet had expected adjusted earnings of $2 a share on sales of $727 million. Panera stock ended the regular trading day down 0.6%. ']
