Name: Tesla, Inc.
Article: 3 : [u"\r\n         Tesla's Elon Musk offers to help South Australia overcome power outages\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Tesla Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TSLA, +0.94%                                                                                                                                                 Chief Executive Elon Musk on Friday offered to help the state of South Australia overcome power outages by installing 100 megawatt hours worth of battery storage, according to media reports. Musk said he could fulfill a contract within 100 days, and if he failed, he would not charge for what would be about $25 million of battery storage. Mike Cannon-Brookes, the Australian co-founder of Silicon Valley startup Atlassian, on Friday tweeted Musk to ask if Tesla was serious about being able to install the capacity. Musk said Tesla could do it in 100 days of the contract being signed, or else provide it free, adding: "That serious enough for you?" Musk said he would charge $250 per kilowatt hour for 100 megawatt hour systems, which is equal to $25 million. Cannon-Brookes replied on Twitter: You\'re on mate. Give me 7 days to try and sort out politics & funding." South Australia has been hit by power outages after a record-breaking summer. Tesla shares were slightly higher premarket, and are up 19% in the last 12 months, matching the S&P 500\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.22%                                                                                                                                                 gains.']

Name: NexPoint Residential Trust, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Fund that almost tripled the S&P 500\u2019s gain last year is now big on health-care stocks\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The mutual fund\u2019s Class A shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZAX, -2.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0returned 31.6% in 2016, compared with returns of 12% for the large-cap S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and 21.3% for the small-cap Russell 2000 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.42%                                                                                                                                                \xa0', u'Gregory is chief investment officer of Highland Alternative Investors, a unit of Highland Capital Management, which is based in Dallas and manages about $15.4 billion. He oversees the small-cap stock fund with James Dondero, the president and co-founder of Highland Capital Management. The fund itself is small, with about $55 million in assets. ', u'Two MLP winners in 2016 were Energy Transfer Equity LP                                                                                                                                                                                                           ETE, -1.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and SemGroup Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SEMG, -0.89%                                                                                                                                                 each of which gained nearly 100% for the fund last year. But Gregory said the fund had taken \u201cabout two-thirds of the chips off the table\u201d for each position.', u'\u201cSo we have done a good job harvesting our gains and capturing our profit and sizing down to a position we think is appropriate,\u201d Gregory said. He said the price of crude oil\xa0\u201ccan head into the $60s near-term.\u201d West Texas crude oil for March delivery                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed at $52.75 on Jan. 25.', u'One example of a company with a new approach to pain relief is Collegium Pharmaceutical Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           COLL, -4.42%                                                                                                                                                 which has developed Xtampza ER, an oxycodone medication designed to reduce the chances of addiction or abuse through the combination of oxycodone \u201cwith fatty acid and waxes to form small spherical beads (microspheres) that are filled into a capsule.\u201d', u'Another company with an interesting new pain-relief product is Pacira Pharmaceuticals Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PCRX, +0.86%                                                                                                                                                 which makes Exparel, a non-opioid pain reliever used for soft-tissue surgeries and orthopedic procedures. The medication is injected during surgery.', u'Gregory said he was focused on multifamily real estate investment trusts (REITs) and has looked at \u201ca concept we\u2019ve proven ourselves,\u201d through NexPoint Residential Trust Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NXRT, -0.73%                                                                                                                                                 which Highland manages but does not hold within the Highland Small Cap Equity Fund. That concept is acquiring multifamily properties and improving them, justifying higher rents. NexPoint\u2019s stock returned 79.5% last year.', u'The first REIT holding that Gregory mentioned in an interview was Independence Realty Trust Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           IRT, -2.51%                                                                                                                                                 a multifamily REIT he said was \u201cvery similar in strategy\u201d to NexPoint. ', u'The other REIT Gregory said he favored was Jernigan Capital Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JCAP, -1.72%                                                                                                                                                 which invests in self-storage facilities.\xa0\xa0\u201cThink of the demographic boom going on in cities like Dallas, San Antonio, Nashville and Austin. When people move, they need to put their things somewhere, and ... when they do, they never leave. So we get a mid- to high-single-digit dividend yield [of 6.75%], with increasing operating income,\u201d he said.', u'Gregory named two pipeline operators, Western Gas Equity Partners LP                                                                                                                                                                                                           WGP, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                 which has a dividend yield of 4.08% and has what Gregory calls a \u201cvery strong sponsor\u201d in Anadarko Petroleum Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           APC, -0.58%                                                                                                                                                ; and Tesoro Logistics LP                                                                                                                                                                                                           TLLP, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                 which has a dividend yield of 6.36%, and is sponsored by Tesoro Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TSO, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0', u'Highland Alternative Investors acquired the Small Cap Equity Fund from GE Asset Management in 2010. A series of subadvisers helped manage the fund until July 2015, when Gregory and Dondero took over. The fund has three share classes, and it\u2019s important to consider sales charges and expenses carefully by looking at the prospectus for this or any other mutual fund:', u'It\u2019s pretty obvious when looking at the performance of the Russell 2000 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.42%                                                                                                                                                 that 2016 was a big year for small-cap stocks.', u'The Highland Small Cap Equity Fund\u2019s Class A shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZAX, -2.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have an upfront sales charge of 5.75% and total annual expenses of 1.60% of assets. Class C                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZCX, -2.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares have no upfront sales charge, carry a 1% deferred sales charge for shares sold within six months of purchase, and have total annual expenses of 2.35%. Class Y                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSZYX, -2.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares have no sales charge, and annual expenses of 1.35%, but are available only to institutional investors. All of those expense figures reflect the waiver of 0.42% of annual expenses, which will continue at least until Jan. 31, 2018.']

Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         CBS says it will merge its radio business with Entercom Communications\r\n    ']
Body: [u'CBS Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CBS.A, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 said Thursday it has entered an agreement with Entercom Communications Inc                                                                                                                                                                                                           ETM, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                 to merge the latter with CBS radio. The move will give the two a footprint of 244 stations across the country, and in 23 of the the top 25 U.S. markets, according to a news release. The merger is expected to be tax-free to CBS shareholders, who will gain 72% of all outstanding shares of the combined company after the transaction. Existing Entercom shareholders will own 28% of the combined company on a fully diluted basis. "Radio reaches more Americans than any other medium, and offers advertisers outstanding ROI and local activation," Entercom Chief Executive David Field said in a statement. Field will lead the combined company. "This transformational transaction creates scale-driven efficiencies and opportunities to compete more effectively with other media to better serve our listeners and our advertisers." CBS shares have gained 38% in the trailing 12-month period and shares of Entercom have gained 43%, while the S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                 is up 20%. ']

Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Investors are waking up to these stocks \u2014 the \u2018untold story of 2017\u2019\r\n    ']
Body: [u'But that\u2019s not the case for the S&P 500, which, as our chart of the day below shows, hasn\u2019t had a big movement in a while.', u'Judging by what this Citigroup forex trader told clients recently, markets may be cooling their heels for some time. That\'s because big news about POTUS\u2019s economic plans may not come until spring, which could hurt the Trump-on trade, says Citi. Others say there\u2019s plenty stacked against the bulls right now.', u'Enter our call of the day, from Reformed Broker\u2019s Josh Brown, who shares fresh trends from his pals at Riskalyze. Its data from the latest week (up to around Feb. 4) show money flowing into big materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLB, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and financials                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLF, -0.55%                                                                                                                                                \xa0exchange-traded funds.', u'As well, money poured into an ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           ACWI, -0.27%                                                                                                                                                 based on the MSCI All-Country World Index, which aims to provide a broad gauge of global equity-market performance. The index is nearly 52% exposed to the U.S., but the rest is spread throughout the globe, such as 8% in Japan and 3% in China. ', u'\u201cForeign stocks are the untold story of 2017 so far, in my opinion,\u201d says Brown. \u201cWith the dollar easing and Russian stocks being \u2018normalized\u2019 by some intrepid investors, the EEM                                                                                                                                                                                                           EEM, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0(iShares MSCI Emerging Markets ETF) has been able to surge almost 8% year-to-date.\u201d ', u'While storm clouds may be brewing over French elections and on-again Greek debt worries, Brown also notes the Vanguard\u2019s FTSE Europe ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           VGK, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is roughly 100 basis points ahead of the S&P 500 ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPY, -0.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. The Riskalyze data also showed that flows out of FTSE Europe picked up in the period ', u'Things are perking up a bit, with Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:YMH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0and S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:ESH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0futures on the rise. That\u2019s after the big three U.S. indexes \u2014 Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                 S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.05%                                                                                                                                                 slipped into the red on Monday. ', u'In Asia                                                                                                                                                                                                           ADOW, -1.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 , stocks were mostly weaker, and the Nikkei                                                                                                                                                                                                           NIK, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                 fell as the Japanese yen briefly shot higher against the dollar. The greenback is up after Philly Fed President Patrick Harker said a March rate rise is on the table. Earnings are boosting Europe                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.54%                                                                                                                                                \xa0.', u'See the Market Snapshot column for the latest action. ', u'This chart from Pension Partner\u2019s Charlie Bilello drives home the watching-paint-dry situation for the S&P right now: ', u'Gap                                                                                                                                                                                                           GPS, -0.46%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares are up about 3% premarket after an upbeat outlook and stronger-than-expected holiday sales.', u'Michael Kors                                                                                                                                                                                                           KORS, -1.01%                                                                                                                                                \xa0delivered weak sales and guidance and shares are falling. Still to come, Archer Daniels                                                                                                                                                                                                           ADM, +0.49%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, GM                                                                                                                                                                                                           GM, -1.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Mondelez                                                                                                                                                                                                           MDLZ, -0.43%                                                                                                                                                \xa0ahead of the open. Disney                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Panera                                                                                                                                                                                                           PNRA, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Gilead                                                                                                                                                                                                          GILD, -0.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are coming after the close. ', u'Shares of Advanced Micro Devices                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMD, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have shot up 28% over the past five days. Some say the chip maker\u2019s stock run has been too far, too fast.', u'BP                                                                                                                                                                                                           BP, -0.74%                                                                                                                                                                              BP., -0.46%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is tipping south after posting another annual loss on weak oil prices, missing forecasts on underlying earnings.', u'Smart-TV brand Vizio has settled a lawsuit that accused it of tracking info on viewers and then selling their data.', u' Check out:   Wall Street\u2019s evil empire strikes back ', u'\u201cTrump doesn\u2019t like his people to look weak.\u201d \u2014 A top Trump donor and other sources say the U.S. president is most upset that \u201cSaturday Night Live\u201d picked a woman \u2014 Melissa McCarthy \u2014 to spoof White House press secretary Sean Spicer, who has tried to laugh it off.', u'8,000 \u2014 That\u2019s how many opioid overdose kits are being handed out by West Virginia health officials to stem overdoses. The state has the highest rate of overdose deaths \u2014 725 in 2016. ', u'On that note, check out this NPR interview with the author of \u201cGlass House,\u201d which chronicles the decline of an all-American Ohio factory town, including opioid and opiate abuse.', u'Senate Democrats hold all-night protest to block Trump\u2019s education pick Betsy DeVos.', u'Congressional report slams big security gaps at U.S. airports', u'There\u2019s a dangerous new trend among vaping teens', u'Amnesty International says Syria has killed, tortured thousands in prisons since 2011', u'Kanye West may no longer be a Trump fan , and Schwarzenegger wants to \u201csmash his face\u201d', u' Need to Know starts early and is updated until the opening bell, but  sign up here to get it delivered once to your email box. Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Ackman boosted Chipotle holdings, pared Valeant in 4th quarter\r\n    ']
Body: [u'There were no major surprises in activist hedge-fund manager Bill Ackman\'s fourth-quarter filing on Tuesday, which showed his Pershing Square Capital boosted its stake in burrito chain Chipotle Mexican Grill                                                                                                                                                                                                           CMG, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                 and pared its holdings of Valeant Pharmaceuticals                                                                                                                                                                                                           VRX, -1.92%                                                                                                                                                 As previously disclosed, Ackman bought more than 2.3 million shares of Chipotle in the fourth quarter, the filing showed, bringing his stake to 2.882 million shares, or 9.96% of the company, as of Dec. 31. Pershing Square and Chipotle reached a settlement in December that gave the fund two seats on restaurant chain\'s board. Ackman had also disclosed in December that Pershing Square had cut its stake in Valeant by nearly 3.5 million shares to help generate a loss for tax purposes. ']

Article: 13 : [u'\r\n         Dow transports surge as Southwest, Alaska Air stocks soar toward record highs\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Airline stocks soared Tuesday, sparking a sharp rally in the Dow Jones Transportation Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJT, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                 after upbeat December operations updates helped push the shares of Southwest Airlines Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LUV, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 and Alaska Air Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ALK, -0.71%                                                                                                                                                 into record territory. The NYSE Arca Airline Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           XAL, -0.45%                                                                                                                                                 jumped 2.4%, and the Dow transports rallied 1.2%, with the top six gainers being airline stocks. In comparison, the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                 was up 45 points, or 0.2%. Alaska Air shares ran up 5.3%, after the carrier said overall December load factor increased 50 basis points (0.5 percentage points) to 83.1%, as a 140 basis point increase in Alaska Airlines\' load factor offset a 140 basis point decline in Virgin America\'s load factor. Southwest\'s stock climbed 2.9% after boosting Tuesday its outlook for fourth-quarter revenue per available seat miles (RASM) to a decline of 3% to 4% from a decline of 4% to 5% a month ago. Among other airline stocks, United Continental Holdings Inc.\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           UAL, -1.06%                                                                                                                                                 rose 3.4%, JetBlue Airways Corp.\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           JBLU, -0.94%                                                                                                                                                 gained 3%, Delta Air Lines Inc.\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           DAL, -1.41%                                                                                                                                                 surged 3% and American Airlines Group Inc.\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAL, -2.77%                                                                                                                                                 advanced 1.8%.']

Name: UBS AG
Article: 9 : [u'\r\n         Bank jobs leaving U.K.? Some in financial sector blast buzz over Brexodus\r\n    ']
Body: [u'U.K.-based HSBC                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSBA, -0.63%                                                                                                                                                                              HSBC, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0expects to move about 1,000 staff out of London to Paris, and Switzerland\u2019s UBS                                                                                                                                                                                                           UBSG, -1.58%                                                                                                                                                                              UBS, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sees about 1,000 jobs affected, according to comments from execs.', u'Among U.S. banks, Goldman Sachs                                                                                                                                                                                                           GS, -0.51%                                                                                                                                                 is considering cutting its London workforce to roughly 3,000 from 6,000 and transferring key operations to New York and continental Europe, particularly Frankfurt, according to a report from German business newspaper Handelsblatt. And J.P. Morgan Chase                                                                                                                                                                                                           JPM, +0.76%                                                                                                                                                \xa0CEO Jamie Dimon said this month that there \u201cwill be more job movement than we hoped for,\u201d after warning last year that 4,000 U.K. employees could be hit.', u'If Prime Minister Theresa May\u2019s Brexit speech in mid-January was aimed at soothing the City of London and preventing banks from sending jobs elsewhere, early indications are that it flopped, a Financial Times report said. ', u'There have been long-running worries that Britain\u2019s June vote to leave the European Union could hurt London\u2019s status as a financial hub, due in large part to companies losing their key \u201cpassporting\u201d rights that allow them to conduct business across the EU.', u'\u2014 Jes Staley, chief executive at Barclays, in an interview with the BBC', u'\u2014 Jasper Lawler, senior market analyst at London Capital Group, in a note', u' Check out: How Brexit is holding back London\u2019s IPO market ', u' And see: Theresa May urges businesses to \u201cplay by the same rules\u201d ', u'\u2014 Ian Gordon, head of banks research at Investec, in an interview with City A.M.', u'\u2014 David Buik, market commentator at Panmure Gordon, in a note', u' See: Marmitegate \u2014 uproar over beloved spread may be Brexit turning point ', u' And read: Brexwhat? Why Brexit won\u2019t necessarily kill London\u2019s fintech scene ', u' This story was first published on Jan. 19, 2017. ']

Name: Yum! Brands, Inc.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Stock market rallies to records as Trump teases tax-policy announcement\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Stocks, already in the green, gained altitude on the day and the U.S. dollar                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:DXY                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed after Trump referenced a \u201cphenomenal\u201d announcement about his tax plan coming in the next few weeks. Trump\u2019s pledge to cut taxes are expected to have a stimulative effects on asset values, but the president has been scant on details since he won the election back in November.', u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:DJIA                                                                                                                                                \xa0finished up 118.06 points, or 0.6%, at a record 20,172.40, after hitting an intraday all-time high of 20,206.36, led by gains of Nike Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          US:NKE                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Wal-Mart Stores Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          US:WMT                                                                                                                                                ', u'The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:SPX                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 13.20 points, or 0.6%, to close at 2,307.87. Earlier, the broad-market equity index touched an all-time high of 2,311.08.', u'The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:COMP                                                                                                                                                 notched a closing record for a third straight session, rising 32.73 points, or 0.6%, to close at 5,715.18, after reaching an intraday record of 5,722.71.', u'The last time all three major indexes simultaneously closed at records was Jan. 25.', u'Pavlik was referring to Wednesday when stocks were lackluster as the most talked about message out of the White House appeared to be Trump\u2019s defense of his daughter\u2019s fashion line that was dropped from Nordstrom Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          US:JWN                                                                                                                                                \xa0because of poor sales. ', u' Read: Is Trump really unleashing \u2018animal spirits\u2019? Watch this chart ', u' Need to Know:  The stock market\u2019s big winner in any Trump-backed tax reform ', u'Financial stocks were Thursday\u2019s top performers, rising 1.4%, extending their postelection rally. Morgan Stanley                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:MS                                                                                                                                                 rose 2.2% while Bank of America Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:BAC                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 1.8%. Dow components J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          US:JPM                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Goldman Sachs Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          US:GS                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed up 1.6% and 1.4%, respectively.', u'Energy stocks gained 0.9% alongside a 1.3% rise in the price of crude oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLH7                                                                                                                                                 to $53 a barrel. Crude traded higher, supported by supply data that showed rising U.S. gasoline demand. Among the most active energy names, Pioneer Natural Resources Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:PXD                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 5.5%.', u'In the latest economic data, jobless claims fell by 12,000 in the latest week, hitting the second-lowest level of an economic recovery that began nearly eight years ago. ', u'Investors also digested the latest comments from James Bullard, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, who said interest rates could remain \u201cexceptionally low,\u201d and that he didn\u2019t see any undue inflationary pressure building. Bullard also commented on Trump\u2019s economic policies\u2014which have both lifted the market and injected uncertainty into equities\u2014saying they wouldn\u2019t affect the economy this year. ', u' Stock movers: Shares of Twitter                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:TWTR                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed down 12% after reporting a revenue miss and a user count that just beat forecasts. ', u'  Viacom Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                            US:VIAB                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 4.3% after beating earnings and revenue forecasts, and Coca-Cola                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:KO                                                                                                                                                \xa0slipped 1.8% after profit met expectations, but its outlook fell short. ', u'  CVS Health Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                            US:CVS                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares rose 0.4% after posting a profit beat. Yum Brands Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:YUM                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 1.2% after its results.', u' Read: Stephen Curry has pointed reaction to Under Armour CEO\u2019s praise for Trump  ', u' Other markets: In Asia, stocks finished mostly higher with the exception of the Nikkei 225                                                                                                                                                                                                           JP:NIK                                                                                                                                                 while in Europe                                                                                                                                                                                                           XX:SXXP                                                                                                                                                 stocks finished broadly higher. ', u' Read: China tells Bitcoin exchanges they must adhere to rules for currencies ', u'The dollar traded higher against the Japanese yen                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:USDJPY                                                                                                                                                 while gold prices                                                                                                                                                                                                          US:GCH7                                                                                                                                                \xa0settled down 0.2% at $1,236.80 an ounce. ', u' Plus: What these experts would tell Trump at 3 a.m. about the dollar  ', u'   \u2014Barbara Kollmeyer in Madrid contributed to this article. ']

Article: 5 : [u"\r\n         NRG's stock surges after activist investor Elliott discloses large stake\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Shares of NRG Energy Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           NRG, -1.29%                                                                                                                                                 surged 6.2% toward a six-month high in premarket trade Tuesday, after activist investor Elliott Associates disclosed in a filing that it has taken a 6.9% stake in the energy production and distribution company. Elliott also disclosed that it entered into an agreement with Bluescape Resources to form an investor group owning 9.4% of NRG\'s shares outstanding. Elliott said in an SEC filing that it believes NRG\'s stock was "deeply undervalued," and that there are "numerous opportunities to significantly increase shareholder value," including operational and financial improvements and strategic initiatives. Elliott is also considering nominating one or more people to NRG\'s board. NRG\'s stock has rallied 44% over the past 12 months, while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                 has gained 21%.']

Name: Wynn Resorts, Limited
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Wynn shares surge as Palace results overshadow earnings miss\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Wynn Resorts Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                           WYNN, +0.67%                                                                                                                                                 shares rallied in the extended session Thursday even after the casino operator\'s earnings missed Wall Street targets. Wynn shares surged 7.3% to $102.50 after hours. The company reported fourth-quarter earnings of $1.12 a share, up from 86 cents a share in the year-ago period, owing to strong results from its Wynn Palace resort. Revenue rose to $1.3 billion from $946.9 million a year ago. On an adjusted basis, Wynn reported earnings of 50 cents a share. Analysts surveyed by FactSet had estimated adjusted earnings of 87 cents a share on revenue of $1.26 billion.']

Name: Visteon Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         The Trump question and 4 other things to know about this earnings season\r\n    ']
Body: [u' See:  Here\u2019s why Trump\u2019s inauguration could mark a near-term top for stocks ', u'The December jobs report showed wage growth at a seven-year high, its fastest pace since the Great Recession. The economy added 156,000 new jobs in the month. ', u'Trump\u2019s first press conference since July, held Wednesday, covered Russian relations, health care and the conflicts of interest with his now family-run Trump Organization, but didn\u2019t extend to economic policy.', u'Don\u2019t miss: What President-elect Trump means for every U.S. industry.', u'S&P 500 companies\xa0                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are expected to report average earnings growth of 3.2% for the quarter, according to FactSet, after growth of 3.20% in the third quarter. Sales are expected to grow 4.2%, after growth of 2.77% in the third quarter. That was after four straight quarters of declining earnings and five straight quarter of declining sales. ', u' See also:  Energy companies are about ready to loosen the purse strings ', u'This earnings season marks a break with a long-held tradition: Aluminum giant Alcoa                                                                                                                                                                                                           AA, +0.90%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was not the first company to post earnings, following its split into two companies. Instead, three big banks, J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JPM, +0.63%                                                                                                                                                 Bank of America Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BAC, +0.37%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Wells Fargo & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           WFC, -0.64%                                                                                                                                                 led the way Friday.', u'Those results helped the U.S.\u2019s biggest bank by assets ring up a record annual profit of $24.73 billion, beating the previous record of $24.44 billion set in 2015.', u' See: \u2018Bearish divergence\u2019 warns it isn\u2019t safe to buy bank stocks ', u'Bank of America profit rose 43%, but revenue fell slightly short. Wells Fargo profit fell as mortgage revenue dipped and its recent sales-tactics scandal weighed.', u' Don\u2019t miss:  End of a stock-market era: Alcoa breaks tradition of being first to report earnings ', u' See also:  J.P. Morgan earnings: Expect a strong trading quarter and improved credit markets ', u'That\u2019s widely expected to boost share buybacks, which had begun to shrink in 2016 after years of spending. Goldman Sachs expects S&P 500 companies to spend about $780 billion on buybacks in 2017, up 30% from 2016. The bank is expecting 48% of an expected $2.6 trillion in corporate spending to go to shareholder rewards, either in the form of dividends or buybacks. ', u'Companies are likely to wait and see what tax moves are made before finalizing repatriation or buyback plans, so major announcements are unlikely this quarter. Still, General Motors Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GM, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                \xa0said Tuesday it was adding $5 billion to its buyback program, Chipotle Mexican Grill Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CMG, +1.31%                                                                                                                                                \xa0said it would add $100 million to its $2.1 billion authorization and car parts-maker Visteon Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           VC, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0approved a $400 million program. ', u'The ICE U.S. Dollar Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                 which tracks the dollar against the currencies of six major trade partners, soared 7.1% during the fourth quarter, to take it 3.6% above where it was at the end of the same period a year ago. That was the biggest quarterly percentage gain in the buck since the first quarter of 2015. ', u' Don\u2019t miss: Earnings beats are concealing bad results.', u' Also read: Priceline investors are being fooled again.', u'The fact that the bar of expectations hasn\u2019t been lowered as much as usual could make it harder to hurdle. With that in mind, the technology sector could be the most likely of the S&P 500\u2019s 11 key sectors to get tripped up, as it was the only sector that has recorded an increase in expected earnings growth since the start of the quarter, of 1.3%. That contrasts with the average 3.8% drop over the past five years, FactSet said. The SPDR Technology Select Sector exchange-traded                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLK, +0.64%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 1.2% during the fourth quarter, closing at a 16-year high on Dec. 27.', u'The yield on the 10-year Treasury note                                                                                                                                                                                                           TMUBMUSD10Y, -0.55%                                                                                                                                                \xa0soared 83.8 basis points (0.838 percentage points) during the fourth quarter, the biggest quarterly jump since the first quarter of 1994. The rate rally came one quarter after the yield hit a record low.', u'The Federal Reserve raised its target for overnight interest rates during the just-completed quarter for only the second time since the Great Recession, and increased the number of expected rate hikes in 2017.', u'The SPDR Financial Select Sector ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLF, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0soared 20% during the quarter, compared with a 3.3% gain in the S&P 500.', u'Don\u2019t miss: Financial stocks surge as Trump victory soothes regulatory fears, lifts rates.', u' Read: SEC wants earnings to comply with its rules and it won\u2019t take no for an answer ', u'In late December, correspondence released by the SEC showed ConocoPhilips                                                                                                                                                                                                           COP, -0.62%                                                                                                                                                 has changed the way it will report revenue in a letter that showed the SEC took action after MarketWatch flagged the issue. ', u' Don\u2019t miss:  Here\u2019s how investors are duped each earnings season ']

Name: Chevron Corporation
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Energy stocks are falling while the S&P is climbing \u2014 and that\u2019s a buying opportunity\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Yet energy is the absolute worst performer among the S&P 500\u2019s 11 sectors this year. It was down 5.5% through Monday, compared with a 6.1% gain for the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                 Exxon                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.29%                                                                                                                                                 one of the best-quality names in the space, is trading near 52-week lows. UPDATE', u' Insider vote of confidence ', u'Let\u2019s start with the insiders. I\u2019ve tracked insiders for clues about the market for decades, and their buying is a core part of how I come up with a short list of stocks to research for my stock letter Brush Up on Stocks. Two key lessons on insiders support a bullish call on energy now. ', u'That looks like the case with energy stocks right now. Over the past few weeks there\u2019s been significant insider buying in over a dozen energy stocks, including Halliburton                                                                                                                                                                                                           HAL, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in services, Hess                                                                                                                                                                                                           HES, -1.07%                                                                                                                                                 Oasis Petroleum                                                                                                                                                                                                           OAS, -0.79%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Matador Resources                                                                                                                                                                                                           MTDR, -0.53%                                                                                                                                                 in production, and Marathon Petroleum                                                                                                                                                                                                           MPC, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                 in refining. (I\u2019ll list the others, below.)', u' Inventories rising ', u'It takes six weeks or more for oil to arrive by boat to the U.S., the market of last resort for energy. But as it did, U.S. inventories began to build this year, unsettling investors. \u201cThe market looks at the big build up in U.S. inventories and gets nervous,\u201d says Jonathan Waghorn who helps manage the Guinness Atkinson Global Energy Fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           GAGEX, -0.80%                                                                                                                                                 Investors are still shellshocked after a U.S. inventory glut helped suppress oil prices and crush energy stocks two years ago. So any sign of a repeat has them selling. ', u' U.S. producers: They\u2019re baack! ', u'Thanks to higher energy prices, U.S. shale producers are back. They\u2019re deploying a lot more rigs. The rig count is back up over 600 compared with a low of 316 in May 2016 \u2014 and they are fracking a lot more. This also brings back bad memories of hefty losses for energy investors. ', u'OPEC, for example, will probably remain disciplined on production because of national budget constraints in Saudi Arabia, says John Groton, director of equity research at Thrivent Financial, who has followed the energy space for years. He thinks Saudi Arabia needs oil in the upper $60-per barrel range to balance its national budget. Oil                                                                                                                                                                                                          CLJ7, -1.49%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 has traded recently in the mid-$50 range. ', u' One for the quants ', u' How to play this ', u'Another is to follow the insiders. Besides Halliburton, Oasis, Matador, Hess and Marathon Petroleum, which has a four out of five star rating at Morningstar, insiders were also recently buying in significant amounts at Carrizo Oil & Gas                                                                                                                                                                                                           CRZO, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                 Parsley Energy                                                                                                                                                                                                           PE, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                 Newfield Exploration                                                                                                                                                                                                           NFX, -0.79% Plains GP                                                                                                                                                                                                           PAGP, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                 Panhandle Oil and Gas                                                                                                                                                                                                           PHX, +1.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Parker Drilling                                                                                                                                                                                                           PKD, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 ', u'Breard, at Hodges Capital Management, follows Comstock Resources                                                                                                                                                                                                           CRK, -1.66%                                                                                                                                                 closely. He has made some great contrarian calls on the company, favoring it last spring when it traded below $4, ahead of a move above $12. He likes the name in the current pullback into the $8-$9 range. \u201cComstock looks awfully cheap,\u201d he says, especially considering that over the next several weeks they are bringing several wells online in untapped territory, which suggests they will be particularly productive. He also likes Parsley Energy. which he says has good properties in the Permian and Delaware basins. ', u'Top holdings at Guinness Atkinson Global Energy Fund include Newfield, Devon Energy                                                                                                                                                                                                           DVN, +0.23%                                                                                                                                                 Carrizo, QEP Resources, Apache                                                                                                                                                                                                           APA, +0.28%                                                                                                                                                 Occidental Petroleum                                                                                                                                                                                                           OXY, -0.43%                                                                                                                                                 ConocoPhillips                                                                                                                                                                                                           COP, -0.38%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Noble                                                                                                                                                                                                           NE, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                 ', u'What about Exxon? If oil prices really are going back up to $70 over the next few years, it might not be the best energy name to own. In this scenario, investors will favor smaller, lower quality energy companies that use more leverage to fund development over more conservative, larger players like Exxon, Chevron                                                                                                                                                                                                           CVX, -0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and ConocoPhillips. ', u' Michael Brush is a Manhattan-based financial writer At the time of publication, he had no positions in any stocks mentioned in this column. Over the past several years, he has suggested HAL, HES, OAS, MTDR, CRK, MMLP, PHX, DVN, APA, OXY, COP, CVX and XOM in his stock newsletter Brush Up on Stocks.  ']

Name: Caseys General Stores, Inc.
Article: 1 : [u"\r\n         Casey's General Stores shares fall on earnings miss\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Casey\'s General Stores Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           casy                                                                                                                                                 shares declined in the extended session Monday after the convenience-store and gas-station chain\'s quarterly results fell short of Wall Street estimates. Casey\'s shares declined 3.7% to $110 after hours. The company reported fiscal third-quarter earnings of 58 cents a share on revenue of $1.77 billion. Analysts had estimated earnings of 88 cents a share on revenue of $1.81 billion. Casey\'s board also approved the repurchase of up to $300 million in company shares.']
