Tiffany & Co.
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Tiffany\u2019s stock clobbered as latest executive departure startles investors\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Tiffany & Co. shares slid 2.5% Monday as investors digested news of yet another executive departure, this time of Chief Executive Frederic Cumenal, who had held the role since April 2015. ', u'The move comes after the exits of design director Francesca Amfitheatrof in January and of Chief Finance Officer Ralph Nicoletti last May, and follows recent financial results that the company described as disappointing in the statement announcing the news.', u'It also comes in the wake of the departures last week of the CEO of Ralph Lauren Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          RL, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                and the CFO of Under Armour Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          UA, -1.71%                                                                                                                                                 , making for a busy period in executive moves.', u' Read: Ralph Lauren CEO\u2019s departure creates uncertainty about the \u2018way forward\u2019 ', u' Also: Under Armour suffers multiple downgrades on fears the \u2018growth story\u2019 is ending ', u'Mizuho downgraded Tiffany\u2019s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                          TIF, +0.50%                                                                                                                                                to neutral from buy and cut its share-price target to $74 from $90, just below its current trading level of about $78.', u' Don\u2019t miss:  Engagement rings get a makeover with personalized styles outshining size ', u'In January, the company said the turmoil around its flagship Fifth Avenue store in New York City, made famous by Audrey Hepburn\u2019s window shopping in the iconic 1960s film \u201cBreakfast at Tiffany\u2019s,\u201d was hurting traffic. The store is close to Trump Tower, which has been subjected to constant protests and a heavy police presence ever since the November presidential election.', u' See also: The robbery that saw more than 400 pieces of jewelry walk out Tiffany & Co.\u2019s doors ', u'Meanwhile, design director Amfitheatrof has been replaced by Reed Krakoff, former creative director of Coach Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          COH, -0.83%                                                                                                                                                who has been tasked with directing design for Tiffany\u2019s jewelry and luxury accessories and for shaping the overall look and feel of stores, e-commerce, marketing and advertising. ', u'Kowalski said the company is committed to its core business strategy, which it intends to accelerate to compete better in the global luxury market. ', u' Read:  My mother saved $10,000 for my wedding \u2014 but now that I\u2019m 41, should I spend it on a house? ', u'\u201cThe loss (or gain) of any one person is not likely to break (or make) a retailer,\u201d said analysts led by Simeon Siegel. That said, he added, at a valuation of about 20 times Instinet\u2019s earnings-per-share forecast for fiscal 2018 and with Tiffany shares having outperformed over the last 12 months, rising 24% while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, +0.22%                                                                                                                                                has tacked on 20% and the SPDR S&P Retail exchange-traded fund                                                                                                                                                                                                          XRT, -0.60%                                                                                                                                                is up 7%, \u201cwe believe [Tiffany] has been viewed as a relatively safer investment in retail, [and] it seems fair to assume shares will be pressured by the added uncertainty.\u201d', u'The commercial made the Washington Post\u2019s list of five worst Super Bowl commercials, with critics complaining it was more about Lady Gaga than the Tiffany brand.']

Name: Exxon Mobil Corporation
Article: 14 : [u'\r\n         The Dow\u2019s 21,000 rally was powered by Apple\u2019s 15% rally since Jan. 25 \r\n    ']
Body: [u' Check out: Dow matches fastest 1,000-point march to a milestone in history', u'Apple\u2019s nearly 15% rise since the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                 first hit 20,000 on Jan. 25 has contributed about 123 points to the Dow\u2019s rally to the milestone. That makes the Cupertino, Calif.-based iPhone maker, which has enjoyed a renaissance on the back of better-than-expected quarterly results and renewed enthusiasm over iPhone 8, the Dow\u2019s largest driver. Coming in second was industrial component Boeing Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BA, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                 which added 113 points over the past three weeks for a 10% gain.', u'Because the Dow is a price-weighted average, rather than a market-value weighted gauge like the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0price moves in the Dow\u2019s 30 components influence the equity benchmark rather than the weighted-average percentage changes of the S&P 500\u2019s members.', u'That price-weighting came into play when the Dow\u2019s surge to 20,000 in January was led by a surge in shares of Goldman Sachs Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GS, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                 which is trading at around $253 and has a market cap of about $99 billion, compared with Apple\u2019s shares at around $139 and a market cap of nearly $720 billion, as of Wednesday trade. ']

Name: Weight Watchers International Inc
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         Stock market ends near records, powered by auto sales\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed up 12.92 points, or 0.6%, to 2,270.75, led by gains in the consumer-discretionary sector, which includes car makers, and the materials sector. The finish was just shy of the S&P 500\u2019s closing record of 2,271.72 set Dec. 13. Gains were broad-based, with nine of the 11 main sectors ending the session in the green.', u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.01%                                                                                                                                                 rose 60.40 points, or 0.3%, to close at 19,942.16, led by gains in Nike Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          NKE, -6.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and American Express Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AXP, +0.55%                                                                                                                                                 after coming within 44 points of the psychologically significant 20,000 level.\xa0', u'Meanwhile, the Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.38%                                                                                                                                                 closed up 47.92 points, or 0.9%, at 5,477.00, as biotech stocks surged, with the iShares Nasdaq Biotechnology ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           IBB, +0.49%                                                                                                                                                 rising 2.6%.', u'The Russell 2000 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           RUT, -0.38%                                                                                                                                                \xa0finished up 22.46 points, or 1.6%, at 1,387.95, just shy of its record finish of 1,388.07 set on Dec. 9. ', u'The Fed said interest-rate hikes may come at a faster-than-expected pace, according to minutes from the Federal Open Market Committee\u2019s Dec. 13-14 meeting. Following the minutes, stocks gained some traction, nearing highs for the session. That added to early advances following better-than-expected monthly car sales from General MotorsCo.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GM, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                 and Ford Motor Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          F, +0.77%                                                                                                                                                 which helped to boost the broad-market S&P 500.', u' Read: Trump can bully car makers, but he can\u2019t buck economics, says Rex Nutting ', u' Movers and shakers: Shares of General Motors finished up 5.5% after December car sales rose 10%. Rival Ford Motor Company                                                                                                                                                                                                          F, +0.77%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares also surged 4.6%. ', u' Weight Watchers International Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           WTW, +2.29%                                                                                                                                                 shares surged about 21% after the weight-loss company said it program was ranked #1 in several categories of a U.S. News &World Report list of diets. ', u'Shares of Agile Therapeutics Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          AGRX, +0.77%                                                                                                                                                \xa0sank 47% after the women\u2019s health company late Tuesday reported positive results in a study of its Twirla contraceptive patch, but said 51.4% of participants had to discontinue the study. ', u' Tesla Motors Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TSLA, +0.87%                                                                                                                                                \xa0closed 4.6% higher, even as the electric car maker late Tuesday reported on production challenges in the fourth quarter. Startup Faraday Future unveiled an all-electric rival to Tesla\u2019s range at the CES technology trade show on Tuesday.', u' Amazon.com Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 0.5% after the retailer said deliveries for third-party sellers rose 50% during the holiday season. ', u' See: Nvidia, after monster 2016, enters spotlight at CES ', u' Other markets: Asian markets closed mostly higher, with Japan\u2019s Nikkei 225 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           NIK, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0jumping to a 13-month high.', u'The mood was more subdued in Europe, where stocks closed slightly lower after a session of struggling for direction, a day after the Stoxx Europe 600 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                \xa0entered bull-market territory. ', u' Oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLG7                                                                                                                                                \xa0prices settled up 1.8% at $53.26 a barrel while gold                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:GCG7                                                                                                                                                \xa0prices ended 0.3% higher, while the dollar                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                 pulled back from a 14-year high reached on Tuesday. The yield on the 10-year Treasury                                                                                                                                                                                                           TMUBMUSD10Y, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slipped to 2.43%.', u'  \u2014Sara Sjolin in London contributed to this article.  ']

Name: Moneygram International, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u"\r\n         MoneyGram's stock soars after deal to be bought by Alibaba's Ant Financial for $880 million\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Shares of MoneyGram International Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MGI, +0.78%                                                                                                                                                 soared 10% in premarket trade Thursday, after the provider of money transfer services agreed to be acquired by Ant Financial Services Group, which is an affiliate of China-based Alibaba Group Holding Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BABA, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                 for $880 million. Under terms of the deal, Ant Financial will pay $13.25 for each MoneyGram share outstanding, which is 14% above Wednesday\'s closing price of $11.88. The deal connects MoneyGram\'s network of 2.4 billion bank and mobile accounts with Ant Financial\'s users. "The combination of Ant Financial and MoneyGram will provide greater access, security and simplicity for people around the world to remit funds, especially in major economies such as the United States, China, India, Mexico and the Philippines," said Ant Financial Chief Executive Eric Jing. MoneyGram\'s stock has more than doubled over the past 12 months, while Alibaba shares have run up 49% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.10%                                                                                                                                                 has climbed 21%. ']

Name: Puma Biotechnology Inc
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Puma Biotech shares plummet 26% after Roche reports positive results for late-stage breast cancer drug\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Puma Biotechnology Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PBYI, +1.86%                                                                                                                                                 shares dropped 26.3% in pre-market trade Thursday after rival Roche                                                                                                                                                                                                           RHHBBY                                                                                                                                                 said its drug for early breast cancer had positive results in a late-stage clinical trial. Roche said for post-surgical treatment, its Perjeta drug in combination with chemotherapy drug Herceptin and chemotherapy was able to reduce risk of recurrence in a statistically significant way relative to just Herceptin and chemotherapy. This result, assuming no surprises from the data in full, has essentially "eliminated" the commercial opportunity in post-surgical treatment for Puma\'s neratinib drug, which is also being developed for breast cancer, according to RBC Capital Markets analyst Simos Simeonidis. "With Perjeta soon to be on the market, marketed by Roche\'s dominant marketing machine that has owned the HER2+ space for a decade, we believe this active yet difficult to administer agent would have a very tough time being commercially relevant, even if it ended up being approved," he said, lowering his price target by 55% to $17. Puma shares have declined 4.9% over the last three months, compared with a 9.3% rise in the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                 ']

Name: Atlassian Corporation Plc
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Atlassian shares choppy as results beat Street, earnings outlook misses\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Atlassian Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TEAM, +0.31%                                                                                                                                                 shares fluctuated between gains and losses in the extended session Thursday after the business collaboration software company topped Wall Street estimates for the latest quarter but issued an earnings outlook that fell short of the consensus. Atlassian shares, which at first rallied, then slipped into negative territory, traded up 0.3% to $27.50 after hours. The company reported adjusted fiscal second-quarter earnings of 9 cents a share on revenue of $148.9 million. Analysts surveyed by FactSet had estimated earnings of 8 cents a share on revenue of $144 million. For the third quarter, Atlassian sees adjusted earnings of about 6 cents a share on revenue of $155 million to $157 million. Analysts expect third-quarter earnings of 8 cents a share on revenue of $154.4 million.']

Name: Mattel, Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         American Girl\u2019s new boy doll gets right to heart of fans\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Middleton, Wis.\u2013based doll company, owned by Mattel                                                                                                                                                                                                          MAT, -1.16%                                                                                                                                                 creates dolls with detailed stories against the backdrop of historical events, books as well as movies. The doll maker already makes a male infant doll as part of its Bitty Baby line, but never had a boy version of the 18-inch dolls that the company is best known for. ', u'The introduction of the toy this week had many fans cheering, and a Mattel spokeswoman told the New York Times that customers had been asking for one for years \u2014 not just for their sons but for their daughters as well. ', u'The toy market has been lacking boy dolls for decades despite demand, sparking creativity among crafty moms and doll-making startups alike. Gina DeMillo Wagner, a writer and photographer, wrote on her blog that when her then-6-year-old son wanted a male American Girl doll, she made her own by cutting a doll\u2019s hair, removing its makeup with acetone and finding boy doll clothes on Etsy. She gives most of the credit to boy doll manufacturing to startups like Boy Story and Wonder Crew, two companies that proved before Mattel jumped on board that there was a demand for boy dolls, she said. ', u'Doll play is beneficial for girls and boys, because it stimulates developmental skills, including care giving and nurturing, Hains said. As more dads take on care-giving roles, and some stay at home full time, boys can imitate their actions through playing with their dolls. Having dolls that look like them also allows them to connect with the toys, rather than action figures of characters who are older and have \u201crestrictive\u201d body images, such as the stereotypical muscular superhero, she said. ', u'But not everyone agrees boy dolls are necessary, and in some circles boys may be discouraged from playing with such toys, experts said. This isn\u2019t always best for the child, though. Toys attached to strong gender stereotypes were less developmentally beneficial for children, and could focus the children\u2019s attention to traits parents may not want for them, such as prioritizing attractiveness for girls or emphasizing violence for boys, Judith Elaine Blakemore, a professor of psychology and associate dean of arts and sciences for faculty development at Indiana University\u2013Purdue University, told the National Association for the Education of Young Children, a membership organization for children\u2019s learning. ']

Name: Gentex Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         What Apple and a chicken processor have in common for this fund manager\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Sprott Focus Trust\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           FUND, -0.27%                                                                                                                                                \xa0largest holding at the end of December was Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.49%                                                                                                                                                \xa0accounting for 4.7% of the closed-end fund\u2019s assets. Buffett, who\u2019s CEO of Berkshire Hathaway Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BRK.B, -0.41%                                                                                                                                                 made an unusual disclosure this week when he said he had doubled his investment in Apple since the end of 2016. ', u'George sees the same type of value in three other companies he mentioned in an interview this week: Sanderson Farms Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SAFM, +0.55%                                                                                                                                                 Franklin Resources Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BEN, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                 and GameStop Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GME, -0.54%                                                                                                                                                ', u'Sprott Focus Trust                                                                                                                                                                                                           FUND, -0.27%                                                                                                                                                was started in 1988. It was formerly known as the Royce Focus Trust and renamed in 2015 when Sprott Asset Management replaced Royce as the manager. Despite that change, George has been the fund\u2019s sole manager since 2002, and he had been co-manager with Charles Royce beginning in 1996.', u'George said earnings for Sanderson Farms \u2014 the nation\u2019s third-largest chicken processor after Tyson Foods Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           TSN, -0.53%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Pilgrim\u2019s Pride Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PPC, +0.55%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u2014 and its competitors were \u201cimpossible to predict\u201d over the short term, because of the vagaries of chicken prices, feed prices and other factors. He called Sanderson an \u201cincredibly well-run business.\u201d', u'During the nine-year bull market, it has been easy to argue in favor of passive management over active management, because the S&P 500 Index has performed so well, while most stock pickers (including George, although he had a great 2016), have been unable to match or beat its performance. Berkshire Hathaway\u2019s Buffett outlined a strong case in favor of index funds in his most recent annual letter to shareholders (starting at the bottom of page 21), concluding that the main reason for the shortfall for active managers \u2014 especially hedge fund managers \u2014 is fees.', u'One might think GameStop, which sells video games and consoles, might be suffering because of the tremendous success of non-console games played on smartphones, and its holiday-sales decline and new distribution competition from Microsoft Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MSFT, +0.43%                                                                                                                                                \xa0have taken their toll on the shares. But George is impressed by the way the company is taking market share. ', u'\u201dThey have done a good job not to lose all of their market to electronic downloads,\u201d he said. \u201cThey also use their skills at refurbishment, since they have a trade-in service and massive refurbishment business in Texas,\u201d George said. He also touted the company\u2019s \u201cability to manage real estate,\u201d which has enabled it to operate stores for AT&T Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.95%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and stores that sell Apple products.']

Name: Barclays PLC
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         Financials drive FTSE 100 to 1-month high after hawkish signals from Yellen\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The FTSE 100 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.78%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 0.5% to 7,302.41, closing at the highest level since Jan. 16. The London benchmark on Tuesday fell for the first time in six sessions, after choppy trading driven by lower-than-expected inflation data and a round of corporate news. ', u'On Wednesday, banks and insurers were in the driving seat after Fed Chairwoman Yellen in testimony on Tuesday signaled the U.S. central bank could raise rates sooner rather than later. Higher interest rates tend to benefit the financial sector, as they can charge borrowers higher rates. Coming from the world\u2019s largest economy, U.S. interest rates are a driving force for sentiment across other markets.', u'Among U.K. banks, shares of Standard Chartered PLC cap index, the FTSE 250 18,827.20, for a fresh record close. The benchmark has now risen for seven straight sessions, buoyed by economic data showing the British economy is holding up well despite the country\u2019s Brexit vote. ', u' Movers: In other sectors, shares of Anglo American PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAL, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0put on 0.3%. The move came after its Johannesburg-listed subsidiary Anglo American Platinum Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMS, -1.60%                                                                                                                                                \xa0swung to a profit in 2016, as its restructuring efforts started to bear fruit.', u' TUI AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           TUI, -1.43%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slipped 2.7%, paring back after a 5.3% rally on Tuesday, when the travel operator said its loss narrowed in the first fiscal quarter. ', u' Economic news: The U.K. unemployment rate stayed at 4.8% in the three months to December, remaining at its lowest level since 2005. ', u'Meanwhile, U.K. wage growth slowed to 2.6% from 2.7%. With consumer prices rising 1.8% in January compared with 1.6% in December, the data show inflation is now beginning to eat into wage growth, a sign that British consumers may rein in their spending.', u'The pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.3125%                                                                                                                                                \xa0dropped to as low as $1.2383 after the report, down from $1.2467 late Tuesday in New York. ']

Name: Sprint Corporation
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Wireless carriers are quietly telling you what videos to watch on your iPhone\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Unlimited wireless plans are back. Last weeks, AT&T                                                                                                                                                                                                           T, -0.97%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 offered unlimited calls, texts and 22 gigabytes of high-speed data for $90 per month on a single-phone plan before being \u201cthrottled\u201d by the network (impacting the speed or quality of the video). This package includes $25 monthly credit toward DirecTV, DirecTV Now or U-Verse TV packages. Watching DirecTV with data won\u2019t count against your overall usage as part of a so-called zero-rating plan. (AT&T bought in July 2015 for $48.5 billion and, under Federal Communications Commission, must \u201crefrain from imposing discriminatory usage-based allowances or other discriminatory retail terms and conditions on its broadband internet service.\u201d) ', u'The company sweetened its unlimited plans after Verizon                                                                                                                                                                                                           VZ, -1.08%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 started offering unlimited data again in recent weeks, and to compete with T-Mobile                                                                                                                                                                                                           TMUS, +1.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Sprint                                                                                                                                                                                                           S, +0.79%                                                                                                                                                 which offer low-cost unlimited data plans, says technology consultant Jeff Kagan. He says other wireless carriers and content providers are already rumored to join forces in order to compete. \u201cEventually all competitors will head in the same direction, but for now AT&T has the lead,\u201d he says. \u201cThis is just the next natural step. This is an attractive bundle at a lower cost.\u201d It\u2019s a turnaround on AT&T\u2019s previous stance on unlimited data. In 2012, AT&T announced that it will no longer allow consumers to use more than an agreed-upon amount of data per month without being charged for it as part of an effort to rein in the heaviest data users. That same year, Verizon also put the kibosh on unlimited data plans for new users. ', u'But all that has changed. \u201cBy using zero rating, internet service providers and mobile providers can juice the landscape by encouraging consumers to choose one content provider over another,\u201d says Aram Sinnreich, professor of communications at the American University in Washington, D.C. \u201cIt\u2019s anti-competitive, especially when the content provider and wireless carrier are part of the same conglomerate.\u201d (Earlier this month, Nese Guendelsberger, the acting bureau chief of the Federal Communications Commission, ended the agency\u2019s review of wireless carriers that exclude their own video-streaming services from customers\u2019 data plan caps, a review started under the previous administration.) ', u' Don\u2019t miss: Chance the Rapper knew something about music that Prince did not  ', u'Quietly influencing what content providers people use creates a barrier to new players and reduces competition for the Netflixes                                                                                                                                                                                                           NFLX, -0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0of tomorrow, Sinnreich says. \u201cAll the major titans, of the internet like Google                                                                                                                                                                                                           GOOG, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                 Facebook                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and Amazon                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.13%                                                                                                                                                 didn\u2019t exist 20 years ago,\u201d he says. \u201cThe barrier to entry was very low. There were no preferential conditions for legacy companies and that\u2019s what\u2019s happening now. The entire regulatory approach to the internet and digital services are changing. We are seeing a move back towards allowing communications and viewing to be controlled by just a few mega companies.\u201d Without competition and innovation, he says, consumers get stuck paying more and more for the same old stuff.\u201d', u'Under the previous FCC chairman Tom Wheeler, a Democrat, the FCC championed regulation on net neutrality and an open internet, MarketWatch reporter Trey Williams reported in December. \u201cA major industry question, as Trump\u2019s Republican administration heads to Washington, is whether these regulations will be ignored, rolled back or otherwise nixed.\u201d (The FCC did not respond to request for comment.) Sinnreich is not optimistic, and believes that internet and what we watch on it could eventually be controlled by a small group of big corporations. \u201cThe FCC not going to hold these companies to those standards,\u201d he said. \u201cThe real power of the wireless market will be unleashed with 5G marketplace and digital companies want to dominate that.\u201d ']

Name: HP Inc.
Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         HP earnings: Holiday PC sales could be a win, but not a cure\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Reports from third-party analysis firms suggest that the holiday season was stronger than expected for sales of personal computers, and earnings reports from industry titans like Microsoft Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MSFT, +0.90%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0and Intel Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           INTC, +0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0backed up that view. HP                                                                                                                                                                                                           HPQ, +0.29%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is expected to have grown sales of its PCs in the quarter, but IDC and Gartner agreed that it did not overtake Lenovo Group Ltd. for top sales performance on the year.', u' Read also: HP\u2019s holiday wish list \u2014 Retaking the PC throne and making printing cool again ', u'Even if HP is able to beat earnings estimates thanks to strong PC sales, it will have a long way to go in convincing investors that the company has returned to growth. Revenue has been shrinking since the company split from Hewlett-Packard Enterprise Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          HPE, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, and HP\u2019s other main business, printing, is likely to weigh down results even with a large beat from the PC division.', u' Here\u2019s what to expect: ', u' Earnings: Analysts polled by FactSet on average expect HP to report adjusted earnings of 37 cents a share, within HP\u2019s forecasted range of 35 cents to 38 cent a share. Contributors at Estimize, which crowdsources estimates from analysts, fund managers and academics, expect profit of 38 cents a share. In the same quarter a year ago, HP reported adjusted profit of 36 cents a share.', u' Revenue: Analysts on average expect HP to report quarterly revenue of $11.83 billion, down from $12.25 billion a year ago. Estimize contributors are slightly more optimistic, predicting sales of $11.89 billion on average. ', u' Stock reaction: HP has declined after reporting earnings in the last two quarters and four of the past five, including a 4.4% decline a year ago after its holiday-quarter report. Shares declined 6.8% after its most recent quarterly earnings report, in November.', u'Overall, HP shares are up 0.8% in the past three months and 56.3% in the past year, as of Tuesday\u2019s close, compared with increases of 7.6% and 23.3% for the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0during that time. Analysts tracked by FactSet rate the company the equivalent of a hold, with 16 of 26 analysts giving it that rating, with an average target price of $16.18, a nickel higher than Tuesday\u2019s closing price.', u' What to watch for: ', u'Investors hope that HP can manage to at least keep its printing business from shrinking more, with help from a $1 billion deal for Samsung Electronics Co. Ltd.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                          005930, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                \xa0printing business that has not yet closed, while the PC business returns to reliable steady growth. Any signs in Wednesday\u2019s report that HP is reliably on that route would be well-received.', u'RBC Capital Markets analysts were less optimistic in an earnings preview this week, maintaining a sector perform rating and $16 price target. Their main investment thesis for HP is that the company has strong free cash flow, despite a warning on that front from executives last year, and told investors to watch for HP\u2019s dividend.']

Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Investors haven\u2019t been this gloomy for a year \u2014 here\u2019s why that\u2019s bullish\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Bearishness among regular folks who invest just climbed to its highest level in more than a year, according to the American Association of Individual Investors.', u"The AAII survey is often used as a contrarian indicator, meaning traders turn upbeat when its readings get gloomier. The iBankCoin financial blog\u2019s Option Addict and CrackedMarket's Jani Ziedins are doing exactly that, and together they deliver our bullish call of the day.", u'\u201cPeople are simply trying to anticipate pain here,\u201d Option Addict writes. \u201cThat means pain is still up.\u201d This is likely a take on what is the \u201cpain trade\u201d right now, meaning how the market might do its usual thing of delivering the maximum amount of punishment to the most investors.', u'\u201cWhen the market isn\u2019t doing what the crowd expects, that means it is getting ready to do the opposite,\u201d he writes.', u'The Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, S&P                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.03%                                                                                                                                                 and Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                 are higher after a stronger-than-expected jobs report. But they are still on track for weekly drops of between 0.2% and 0.7%.', u' Oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0has turned negative, adding to its lousy week.', u'See the Market Snapshot column for the latest action.', u'\u201cOver the past 16 years, the market has generally responded favorably to February\u2019s jobs report released in March,\u201d writes Jeff Hirsch in an Almanac Trader blog post.', u'The U.S. economy added 235,000 new jobs in February in the Trump era\u2019s first full month, as unemployment fell to 4.7%. The solid reading on nonfarm payrolls clears the way for the Fed to hike interest rates at its meeting next week, economists are saying.', u' Check out: MarketWatch\u2019s Economic Calendar ', u'Are you ready for the Winklevoss Bitcoin Trust ETF? The SEC could issue a ruling today on the famous twins\u2019 fund. (By the way: Bitcoin\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:BTCUSD                                                                                                                                                biggest threat has nothing to do with the SEC.)', u'\u201cOne of the key points that the bears on SNAP                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +6.38%                                                                                                                                                 may be missing is that we believe that FB                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, +0.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0would love to acquire the company,\u201d says FBN Securities analyst Shebly Seyrafi.', u'Ulta Beauty                                                                                                                                                                                                           ULTA, +0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is higher, bouncing back from premarket losses that came after its outlook wasn\u2019t that stunning. Vail Resorts                                                                                                                                                                                                          MTN, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                and Genesco                                                                                                                                                                                                          GCO, -1.34%                                                                                                                                                are also jumping following their earnings reports before the open.', u'China\u2019s central bank is tightening credit controls and signaling a policy shift, a Wall Street Journal report says.', u' Opinion: China\u2019s economic miracle is over ', u'\u201cIt\u2019s not ideal to expand the conflict by continuing the protests outside on the streets. ... Precious lives were lost during the rallies today, and this must no longer happen.\u201d \u2014 South Korea\u2019s acting head of state, Hwang Kyo-ahn, pleaded today with opponents and supporters of the country\u2019s ousted president, after two men died in protests.', u'On a lighter note, the South Korean judge who leads the court that sent Park Geun-hye packing has gone viral \u2014 for her hair rollers.', u'279 \u2014 That is how many corporate insiders bought their own company\u2019s shares in January. It\u2019s the lowest total in 29 years, according to a WSJ report citing the Washington Service, a provider of insider-trading data.', u' This cop didn\u2019t realize an Uber driver was a lawyer.', u'\u201cMy name is Ozymandias, King of Kings\u201d \u2014 and that\u2019s my statue.', u'Elon Musk is offering to fix South Australia\u2019s power crisis.', u'Mark Zuckerberg and Priscilla Chan are expecting another baby girl.', u'An expert\u2019s live interview was hilariously interrupted by his kids acting up.', u'Big typo: Digit added to IP address, man wrongly accused of being a pedophile.', u'\u201cBuffy the Vampire Slayer\u201d fans have been posting tributes:', u' Need to Know starts early and is updated until the opening bell, but sign up here to get it delivered once to your email box. Be sure to check the Need to Know item. The emailed version will be sent out at about 7:30 a.m. Eastern. ', u'  Or Follow MarketWatch on Twitter or Facebook. ', u' And sign up here to get the Friday email highlighting 10 of the best MarketWatch articles of the week. ']

Name: Murphy Oil Corporation
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Dow, S&P 500 close lower as oil prices plummet, rate-hike expectations rise\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0declined 69.03 points, or 0.3%, to 20,855.73, with a 2.8% decline in Caterpillar Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CAT, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                 stock, and shares of Exxon Mobil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                 and Chevron Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          CVX, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0falling nearly 2%. Caterpillar shares were getting hammered after a report commissioned by the government accused the company of tax-accounting fraud, according to a report in the New York Times. ', u'The S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0finished down 5.41 points, or 0.2%, at 2,362.98, as a 2.5% drop in energy stocks offset gains in the consumer-discretionary and health-care sectors. Oil prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                 plummeted 5.4% to settle at $50.28 a barrel after government data showed a rise in crude-oil inventories.', u'The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0narrowly avoided a loss on the session, rising 3.62 points, or less than 0.1%, to close at 5,837.55.', u' Read: Financial ETFs rise as ADP data firm Fed rate-hike expectations ', u'Paycheck-processing firm ADP reported Wednesday the private sector added 298,000 jobs in February. That data comes in advance of government data on jobs due Friday. A weak number could dent expectations for a March hike, the odds of which rose sharply last week, market strategists said, as a bevy of Fed officials signaled their support for raising rates.', u'But the postelection rally has stalled in recent days, in part because the Trump administration has pushed back the timeline for its tax-reform efforts and provided scant details about its other plans. Now, Republicans are squabbling over a plan for repealing and replacing Obamacare that was announced on Monday. ', u' Read: Great jobs report or not, Fed appears bent on raising interest rates ', u' See:  Fed may go \u2018old school\u2019 on rate hikes. says \u2018Bond King\u2019 Jeff Gundlach ', u' See: MarketWatch\u2019s economic calendar ', u' Other markets: Stocks in Asia closed mixed, with markets stuck in a range ahead of the Fed meeting next week. Data from China showed the country recorded a surprise trade deficit in February, its first since 2014, following a surge in imports after the Lunar New Year holiday and a drop in exports. ', u'European stocks also finished mixed. The U.K.\u2019s FTSE 100 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.85%                                                                                                                                                was down 0.1% as Treasury chief Philip Hammond detailed the government\u2019s budget plans. ', u'Gold                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCJ7, +0.29%                                                                                                                                                 prices dropped for a seventh straight session to settle down 0.6% at $1,209.40 an ounce, while the ICE Dollar Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was up 0.3%.', u' Stock movers: Oil companies led decliners on the S&P 500 as crude prices slid. Shares of Marathon Oil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          MRO, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 8.7%, Murphy Oil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          MUR, -0.53%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares dropped 6.7%, Devon Energy Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          DVN, -0.55%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares fell 6.5% and Chesapeake Energy Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          CHK, -0.99%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares dropped 6.1%.', u'Home-builder Hovnanian Enterprises Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          HOV, -0.66%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares finished down 7.5%, after trading higher earlier in the session as the company reported a first-quarter profit. ', u' H&R Block Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HRB, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                 shares jumped 15% after the tax-services company reported stronger revenue growth than anticipated, and a smaller-than-expected loss.', u'Shares of produce company Calavo Growers Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CVGW, -0.77%                                                                                                                                                 fell 1.8% after the company on Tuesday reported quarterly and full-year earnings. ', u' Vera Bradley Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                            VRA, -3.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares finished down 0.5% after the company released a soft forecast for revenue and profit and reported a 12% drop in revenue for the latest quarter. ', u' Dick\u2019s Sporting Goods Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                            DKS, -0.34%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares rose 2.3% after the company said Tuesday that it was dumping a fifth of its vendors to focus on its own brands despite RBC Capital cutting its share-price target to $61 from $65.', u' \u2014Sara Sjolin in London contributed to this article. ']

Article: 5 : [u"\r\n         Sotheby's earnings and profit beat estimates\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Sotheby\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           BID, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                 reported fourth-quarter net income of $65.5 million, or $1.20 per share, compared with a loss of $11.2 million, or 17 cents per share, for the same period last year. Adjusted EPS was $1.35 per share, beating the $1.17 FactSet consensus. Sales totaled $308.7 million, down from $335.8 million last year but ahead of the $269.0 million FactSet estimate. Name: The Health and Fitness ETF
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Can Janus make it in the ETF market?\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Janus Capital Group                                                                                                                                                                                                          JNS, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                 once an emblematic superstar money manager of the 1990s, never fully recovered from the subsequent dot-com crash. Assets have dropped from their 2000 peak of $324 billion to $199 billion as of Sept. 30\u2014a 39% decline. The firm has been particularly hard-hit from the more recent industry-wide exodus out of actively managed funds into index products; it lost $1.8 billion to outflows for the 12 months ending Sept. 30. \u201cFlows are concentrated in some very large fund companies with ETFs,\u201d says Patrick Davitt, a partner at Autonomous Research who covers Janus. \u201cJanus hasn\u2019t had a strong position there.\u201d', u'To shore itself up, Janus recently agreed to merge with British fund shop Henderson Group                                                                                                                                                                                                           HGG, -2.45%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in the second quarter of 2017. The merger will be a major cultural shift, giving the company a more global footprint and more than $320 billion in assets.', u'That isn\u2019t exactly true. If one looks at, for instance, Janus Small Cap Growth Alpha                                                                                                                                                                                                           JSML, -0.24%                                                                                                                                                 which opened last February, there are 13 other competing small-cap growth funds, each with their own strategy for picking growth stocks. The $5.5 billion Vanguard Small-Cap Growth                                                                                                                                                                                                           VBK, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has the lowest expense ratio in the group, 0.08%, a fraction of the Janus ETF\u2019s 0.5%.', u'Yet Janus brings something unique to the table\u2014a bit of that 1990s star-manager flair. The small-cap ETF and its sibling Janus Small/Mid Cap Growth Alpha                                                                                                                                                                                                           JSMD, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are strategic-beta ETFs, which means the firm essentially codified its active stock-picking decisions into an index. Both were designed in-house by the same analytical team that runs Janus Triton                                                                                                                                                                                                           JATTX, -2.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Janus Venture                                                                                                                                                                                                           JAVTX, -2.01%                                                                                                                                                 two similar funds that have Bronze ratings from Morningstar and are closed to new investors.', u'Perhaps Janus\u2019 most promising new ETF is Janus Short Duration Income                                                                                                                                                                                                           VNLA, +0.07%                                                                                                                                                 which launched in November. Not only is the fund actively managed and thus in the firm\u2019s wheelhouse, but its management team at Kapstream Capital, which Janus acquired in 2015, has an excellent long-term record. \u201cKapstream is run by portfolio managers that Bill Gross originally hired at Pimco, who left to start their own firm in Australia in 2006,\u201d Cherney says. That strategy\u2014the $4.7 billion Kapstream Absolute Return Income, which the new ETF will resemble\u2014has produced a 5.3% annualized return since its inception in May 2007, beating its Australian short-term bond benchmark by 1.4 percentage points a year.', u'Though actively managed stock ETFs have yet to take off, active fixed-income ETFs from Pimco and DoubleLine Capital have done well in terms of both performance and asset-gathering. \u201cActively managed fixed income is the only active story in the ETF space that has attracted significant assets in the last couple of years,\u201d says Dave Nadig, CEO of ETF.com. \u201cJanus is taking a different angle here by offering a truly global fund. It isn\u2019t just buying the same short-term bonds everybody else is buying in the U.S. It falls into a similar category to the Pimco Enhanced Short Maturity Active                                                                                                                                                                                                           MINT, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                \u2014an enhanced cash-replacement fund.\u201d', u'Not all of Janus\u2019 new offerings are as noteworthy. Its thematic index ETFs for the health care sector\u2014Janus Health & Fitness                                                                                                                                                                                                           FITS, -1.75%                                                                                                                                                 Janus Obesity                                                                                                                                                                                                           SLIM, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 Janus                                                                                                                                                                                                           ORG, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                 and Janus Long-Term Care                                                                                                                                                                                                           OLD, +0.08%                                                                                                                                                \u2014seem gimmicky and dangerous, based more on generating cutesy tickers to market than on meeting legitimate investing goals. Each is focused on a sliver of an industry and is concentrated in just a handful of stocks. In the Long-Term Care ETF, for instance, just two stocks, Welltower                                                                                                                                                                                                           HCN, +0.94%                                                                                                                                                 and Ventas                                                                                                                                                                                                           VTR, +1.74%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, account for 40% of its portfolio, while Nike                                                                                                                                                                                                           NKE, -6.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and adidas Group                                                                                                                                                                                                           ADS, -0.51%                                                                                                                                                                              ADDYY, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                \xa0account for 37% of the Health & Fitness ETF. \u201cHighly concentrated portfolios are something Janus is known for historically, so I don\u2019t think that\u2019s particularly shocking,\u201d Cherney says.', u'  This article was first published in Barron\u2019s.   ']
