Name: Panera Bread Company
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         This is what Panera did to make its menu \u2018clean\u2019 \r\n    ']
Body: [u' Panera Bread Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          PNRA, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                 in January made good on a promise it made two years ago, saying its food is now free of man-made preservatives, sweeteners, colors and flavors. ', u' WSJ: What made you decide to change your menu to be free of all unnatural additives? ', u' Shaich: We wanted to be part of fixing the food system. In the \u201960s and \u201970s all these additives were put in food for good reason \u2014 to extend the shelf life of products for distribution purposes and to drive better economics. But then you realize maybe all of these things aren\u2019t so good.', u' What kind of supply-chain challenges did this pose? ', u' You revised your popular broccoli cheddar soup 60 times to remove artificial ingredients without losing the taste and texture. Why was it so difficult? ', u' How many menu items had to be reformulated? ', u' How much did the whole effort cost? ', u' Have you raised menu prices? ', u' Do consumers really base their dining decisions on who offers food free of artificial ingredients? ', u' \u201cClean\u201d has become a food-industry buzzword, much as the term \u201cnatural\u201d once was slapped on all kinds of products, resulting in lawsuits. How do you make sure it means something to customers? ', u' You publicly criticized McDonald\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                          MCD, +0.27%                                                                                                                                                 for marketing its Chicken McNuggets as preservative-free. Why did you call them out? ', u' Does declaring yourself virtuous make you a target for critics? ', u' Where is the restaurant industry headed, and how does Panera\u2019s \u201cclean\u201d push fit into that? ', u' How much employee training have you had to do? ', u' Many of your menu items are still high in calories. Do you have plans to offer more healthy choices? ', u'Julie Jargon is a reporter for The Wall Street Journal in Los Angeles. Email her at julie.jargon@wsj.com.', u'The article \u201cWhat Panera had to change to make its menu \u2018clean\u2019\u201d first appeared on WSJ.com.']

Name: Hersha Hospitality Trust
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         5 survival stocks to thrive, come hell, high water or a bubble\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Sure, there\u2019s been a lot of talk about a stock bubble. But when President Donald Trump makes his not-a-State-of-the-Union address to Congress later, don\u2019t be surprised if it turns out to be a call to action (even if history shows such speeches aren\u2019t always big stock movers).', u'That brings us to our call of the day, which finds respite from the often-unclear world of politics in some come-hell-or-high-water stocks. These would be great adds to any portfolio, says Bret Jensen, blogging for Investors Alley.', u'Jensen zeroes in on real estate, a sector that he says has been buoyed by recent data and has held up pretty well despite last November\u2019s U.S. interest-rate rise. ', u'He likes Toll Brothers                                                                                                                                                                                                           TOL, -1.65%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, specifically for the 20% order backlog it recently reported, and says D.R Horton                                                                                                                                                                                                           DHI, -0.75%                                                                                                                                                 is another good overall pick for the housing sector, given its geographic diversity and strong balance sheet.', u'Other favorites include smaller builder Williams Lyon Homes                                                                                                                                                                                                           WLH, -2.28%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and hotel real-estate-investment-trust Chatham Lodging Trust                                                                                                                                                                                                           CLDT, -0.83%                                                                                                                                                 . Investors should just buy and hold the latter, Jensen says. Diamondrock                                                                                                                                                                                                           DRH, -0.84%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Hersha Hospitality Trust                                                                                                                                                                                                           HT, -0.92%                                                                                                                                                \xa0are two more. ', u'Check out the whole post for his entire rationale for those picks and the sector. Plus, here are 20 more stocks that will help you sleep at night.', u'It\u2019s the last trading day of the month, and this market has potential to go out with a bang. One more record close from the Dow industrials                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u2014 Monday marked No. 12 \u2014 and we\u2019re in no man\u2019s land. The Dow, S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                 are struggling for any kind of headway. ', u'In other markets, gold                                                                                                                                                                                                           GCJ7, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and crude                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0are lower. See the Market Snapshot column for the latest action. ', u'Mark Arbeter sees further gains for the sector, as he looks at key levels for the Health Care SPDR ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLV, -0.13%                                                                                                                                                 He said that ETF has now run up to a target/resistance level that he flagged earlier this month, and he\u2019s now set new goals.', u'\u201cAnybody who wants to make the economy grow at 4% a year in real terms has a big job to do. I don\u2019t think it\u2019s even possible for anybody. The economy has certain limits, which are irrespective of whoever sits in the White House.\u201d \u2014 That was Vanguard founder Jack Bogle, talking to BBC Radio 5 earlier Tuesday about the limits of Trump\u2019s plans to revitalize the U.S. economy.', u' Read: Warren Buffett: Jack Bogle is a \u2018hero\u2019 to investors ', u'Target                                                                                                                                                                                                           TGT, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has plunged 14%, after a disappointing fourth-quarter report. Shares are set to suffer the biggest slide since the retailer went public 45 years ago.', u'Valeant                                                                                                                                                                                                           VRX, -1.49%                                                                                                                                                \xa0posted a wider loss as revenue fell, and shares are down about 5%.', u'SeaWorld                                                                                                                                                                                                           SEAS, -1.65%                                                                                                                                                \xa0posted a bigger-than-expected loss, though shares aren\u2019t moving. ', u'Ross Stores                                                                                                                                                                                                           ROST, -0.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Etsy                                                                                                                                                                                                           ETSY, -0.60%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Salesforce                                                                                                                                                                                                           CRM, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 will report after the close.', u'Apple\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, +0.66%                                                                                                                                                \xa0next iPhone will have a curved screen, The Wall Street Journal reports, citing sources. ', u'Elon Musk\u2019s SpaceX plans to send tourists to orbit the moon in roughly two years.', u'Starbucks                                                                                                                                                                                                           SBUX, +0.38%                                                                                                                                                \xa0will open its first European Roastery in Milan.', u'Wal-Mart                                                                                                                                                                                                           WMT, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has upgraded its mobile app, and will now offer customers paperless transactions and \u201cexpress lanes\u201d to skip lines.', u'Hundreds accuse Sterling Jewelers, which operates Kay Jewelers and Zales, of fostering an environment of \u201crampant sexual harassment and discrimination,\u201d in a class-action lawsuit.', u'  Read: 10 best-performing stocks in February include Monopoly maker Hasbro ', u'The S&P 500 index has gained 90.88 points, or 3.99% for February, with one day left in the month. That\u2019s the biggest one-month and percentage gain since March 2016. ', u'Meet the 12 bacteria that are the biggest threat to humans.', u'President Donald Trump tells Fox News that his predecessor is to blame for all those protests', u'Meet \u201cHandle,\u201d Boston Dynamic\u2019s nightmare-inducing robot:', u' Need to Know starts early and is updated until the opening bell, but  sign up here to get it delivered once to your email box. Be sure to check the Need to Know item. The emailed version will be sent out at about 7:30 a.m. Eastern. ', u' Follow MarketWatch on Twitter and Facebook.']

Article: 11 : [u'\r\n         Financials drive FTSE 100 to 1-month high after hawkish signals from Yellen\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The FTSE 100 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.67%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 0.5% to 7,302.41, closing at the highest level since Jan. 16. The London benchmark on Tuesday fell for the first time in six sessions, after choppy trading driven by lower-than-expected inflation data and a round of corporate news. ', u'On Wednesday, banks and insurers were in the driving seat after Fed Chairwoman Yellen in testimony on Tuesday signaled the U.S. central bank could raise rates sooner rather than later. Higher interest rates tend to benefit the financial sector, as they can charge borrowers higher rates. Coming from the world\u2019s largest economy, U.S. interest rates are a driving force for sentiment across other markets.', u'Among U.K. banks, shares of Standard Chartered PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           STAN, -1.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 2.4%, Barclays PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           BARC, -1.85%                                                                                                                                                                              BCS, -0.66%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 1.7%, Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           RBS, -1.01%                                                                                                                                                                              RBS, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed 2.1%, and Lloyds Banking Group PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           LLOY, -1.35%                                                                                                                                                                              LYG, -1.26%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 1.5%.', u' Read: Yellen testimony before the House\u2014live blog and video ', u' FTSE 250: The U.K.\u2019s mid cap index, the FTSE 250                                                                                                                                                                                                           MCX, -0.86%                                                                                                                                                 rose 0.2% to 18,827.20, for a fresh record close. The benchmark has now risen for seven straight sessions, buoyed by economic data showing the British economy is holding up well despite the country\u2019s Brexit vote. ', u' Movers: In other sectors, shares of Anglo American PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAL, +1.72%                                                                                                                                                \xa0put on 0.3%. The move came after its Johannesburg-listed subsidiary Anglo American Platinum Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMS, -1.60%                                                                                                                                                \xa0swung to a profit in 2016, as its restructuring efforts started to bear fruit.', u' TUI AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           TUI, -2.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slipped 2.7%, paring back after a 5.3% rally on Tuesday, when the travel operator said its loss narrowed in the first fiscal quarter. ', u' Economic news: The U.K. unemployment rate stayed at 4.8% in the three months to December, remaining at its lowest level since 2005. ', u'Meanwhile, U.K. wage growth slowed to 2.6% from 2.7%. With consumer prices rising 1.8% in January compared with 1.6% in December, the data show inflation is now beginning to eat into wage growth, a sign that British consumers may rein in their spending.', u'The pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.1042%                                                                                                                                                \xa0dropped to as low as $1.2383 after the report, down from $1.2467 late Tuesday in New York. ']

Name: Valeant Pharmaceuticals International, Inc.
Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Valeant will relaunch \u2018female Viagra\u2019 drug with poor track record\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The company                                                                                                                                                                                                           VRX, -0.47%                                                                                                                                                 which is burdened with debt and desperately needs new drugs and products, positioned Addyi\u2019s March relaunch, and that of dry mouth treatment Neutrasal, as among its more than 50 product launches globally this year.', u'Valeant didn\u2019t say how much revenue it expects the relaunch to generate. The drug\u2019s struggling 2016 sales came at a time of peak troubles for Valeant itself, with its accounting and pricing tactics under attack and debt troubles looming. ', u'The company faces challenges to this day. It reported a fourth-quarter loss and decline in revenues on Tuesday, sending shares down 9.8% in morning trade. ', u' Read more:  Valeant posts wider loss for fourth quarter as revenue dips ', u'Some critics said Addyi\u2019s sales suffered because Valeant didn\u2019t market the drug aggressively enough. Valeant also doubled the price of the drug after purchasing the drug as part of its 2015 acquisition of Sprout Pharmaceuticals. ', u' Related:  Valeant makes small dent in long list of issues raised ', u'For example, it must be taken every day, but those on it aren\u2019t supposed to drink and it\u2019s risky to be on hormonal contraceptives along with the drug, according to the National Women\u2019s Health Network. ']

Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Outperforming money manager says the S&P 500\u2019s gains will accelerate in 2017\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Alcosta Capital Management is a registered investment adviser based in San Ramon, Calif., that manages about $70 million in private accounts. The firm publishes the Alcosta Growth Report, a monthly newsletter. In 2014, Mark Hulbert included Alcosta Capital Management in a list of only six advisers among nearly 200 he was monitoring that \u201cwere able to outperform the Wilshire 5000 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           W5000, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0during both the last bull market and the preceding bear market.\u201d', u' Don\u2019t miss:  Forget Buffett \u2014 four unsung investment gurus are picking these eight stocks for 2017 ', u'In an interview Dec. 28, Ormsby cited research by LPL Financial that was published in May. Looking at market data going back to 1955, when the market fails to hit a new high for 12 months, and then starts setting records again, \u201cthe long-term average annual gain for stocks [is] about 9%,\u201d according to LPL. ', u'The KBW Bank Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           BKX, -0.61%                                                                                                                                                \xa0trades for 12.3 times the weighted average consensus 2018 EPS estimates, while the S&P 500 trades for 15.2 times consensus 2018 EPS estimates.', u'While Ormsby does not believe the health-care sector is \u201cas rich\u201d with opportunities as the financial sector, he thinks UnitedHealth Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UNH, -0.94%                                                                                                                                                 the nation\u2019s largest managed-care provider, is a reasonable play, because of its limited and declining exposure to ACA exchanges. He also called the stock \u201cinexpensive,\u201d trading for 15.1 times the consensus 2018 EPS estimate.', u'Shares of Applied Materials Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMAT, -0.14%                                                                                                                                                 closed at $32.27 on Friday and are \u201cvery inexpensive,\u201d according to Ormsby. The stock trades for 13.5 times the consensus EPS estimate of $2.39 for fiscal 2017, which ends in October. ', u'Among oil exploration and production companies, Ormsby likes Diamondback Energy Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FANG, +0.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0in part for its low debt. The company\u2019s debt-to-equity ratio was just 19.8% as of Sept. 30.', u'Ormsby expects the deal for production cuts between members of OPEC and non-cartel oil producers reached late in November will provide a \u201ctailwind\u201d to oil prices, and that \u201cif we get an economy that grows faster, those two issues should at least stabilize the price of oil to where it is today, and prices may even grind a bit higher.\u201d ', u'West Texas crude oil for February delivery                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLG7                                                                                                                                                \xa0ended 2017 at $53.89 a barrel. If prices indeed stabilize, the production rebound will bode well for U.S. producers, especially ones with low debt.']

Name: Novo Nordisk A/S
Article: 9 : [u'\r\n         Big pharma won\u2019t stop raising prices in 2017 \u2014 it\u2019ll just do it smarter\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Critics found it easy to vilify Mylan Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           MYL, +0.25%                                                                                                                                                 as a heartless corporation making a lifesaving product \u2014 the EpiPen treatment for allergic reactions \u2014 economically out-of-reach for children. And the industry has learned its lessons from the fallout, experts say. ', u'Pharmaceutical companies were once able to decry price hikers as a few \u201cbad actors\u201d that weren\u2019t representative of their industry, but that was in 2015. Mylan was firmly one of their own, and plenty of others were making big price increases in 2016, Sanofi                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNY, +1.13%                                                                                                                                                 AbbVie Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ABBV, +0.31%                                                                                                                                                 Pfizer Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PFE, +0.04%                                                                                                                                                 Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BMY, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Valeant                                                                                                                                                                                                           VRX, +0.23%                                                                                                                                                among them. ', u' Read:  Yes, you are paying a lot more for prescription drugs (and not just the EpiPen) ', u'But after several years of public backlash over big price increases, the industry may need them more than ever. Despite the passage of a law that should speed up drug approvals, drugmakers are facing a new year that heralds fewer new products, less pricing power and formidable new commercial pressures.', u'At about $81,000 for a course of treatment, Gilead Sciences Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           GILD, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Sovaldi \u2014 nicknamed the \u201c$1,000 pill\u201d \u2014 is considered the most expensive drug in the U.S. ', u' Read more:  This is the most expensive drug in America ', u'Setting high prices does risk the initial public outrage Gilead faced over Sovaldi. But the company can then follow by setting small price increases \u2014 a pharmaceutical strategy known as \u201cskimming\u201d \u2014 and perhaps avoid subsequent scandal, experts say. ', u'Evidence suggests this pricing strategy has already begun. Older cancer drugs had much bigger price hikes \u2014 around 23% \u2014 than the 6% increases seen on newer drugs, according to an Oct. 6 analysis published in JAMA Oncology. ', u'This fall, Novum Pharma reportedly jacked the price of its Aloquin dermatologic cream by 128% overnight \u2014 to $9,500. Another drug, the erectile dysfunction treatment Stendra, has seen a 129% price increase over the last 2\xbd years, according to drug price-comparison website GoodRx.', u'They are two examples of major price hikes seen in the lifestyle and dermatology categories of late, said Michael Rea, founder and chief executive officer of Rx Savings Solutions, a software company that works with employers and health plans so patients can comparison shop.', u' See more: Mylan\u2019s EpiPen caught the full force of drug price outrage because it was the perfect target, not because it was the only one ', u'Two skin disorder creams ranked among the branded drugs with the highest percentage increases in retail price over the last decade, according to an AARP report released this week that was co-authored by Purvis. The two Valeant-manufactured creams, which have had price hikes of more than 2,000%, were joined by an insulin product and two medications for mental illness. ', u'The role of PBMs is to leverage drugmakers against each other and bring drug prices down. But rapid consolidation over the last decade has made them more powerful. A handful of players \u2014 Express Scripts Holding Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ESRX, +0.05%                                                                                                                                                 UnitedHealth Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UNH, -0.36%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and CVS Health Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CVS, -0.22%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u2014 now dominate the market.', u'  Read more:  This health care player you\u2019ve never heard of is acting \u2018aggressively\u2019 to keep costs down ', u'At a fourth-quarter guidance call last week, management for Express Scripts Holding Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ESRX, +0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\u2014 the largest PBM in the U.S. \u2014 emphasized the \u201csignificant discounts\u201d the company negotiates for clients and said they expected to make $1.8 billion in client savings possible next year. ', u'Short seller Andrew Left alluded to the PBM debate when he targeted Express Scripts this month. His firm, Citron Research, claimed on Twitter that Express Scripts will be targeted by the president-elect in the effort to bring down drug prices. (Read more about how Trump\u2019s comments brought down shares of biotech and pharmaceutical companies.)', u' Even if it\u2019s done under pressure, drug manufacturers are still the ones raising prices, Purvis said.', u'Drugmakers have responded with programs such as copay savings cards, which provide a discount on out-of-pocket costs for patients with commercial insurance. A partnership announced in December by Eli Lilly & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           LLY, +0.75%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and pharmacy-benefit manager Express Scripts provides up to 40% discounts on insulin for patients with the highest out-of-pocket costs. ', u' Recent research has supported some of these claims, including a National Bureau of Economic Research paper published in October. And more such programs may be on the horizon, market watchers say. ', u'In early September, Allergan                                                                                                                                                                                                           AGN, +0.66%                                                                                                                                                \xa0CEO Brent Saunders did something new and rare for a pharmaceutical company\u2019s leader, disavowing those who\u2019d made \u201caggressive or predatory price increases\u201d and pledging that Allergan would make only single-digit percentage increases once a year.', u'In December, Novo Nordisk A/S                                                                                                                                                                                                           NVO, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0became the second major drugmaker to do so. ']

Name: Apache Corporation
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n         Risk-on financials rally to be tested as earnings season winds down\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Stocks finished Friday higher with closing records from the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.19%                                                                                                                                                 and the Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0. 2 : [u'\r\n         Snap stock falls 7% on track for second straight down day\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Shares of Snap Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SNAP, +6.82%                                                                                                                                                 fell another 7% on Tuesday, putting the stock on track for its second down day since Thursday\'s initial public offering. The social media stock slid to $22.11 a share in morning trade, after closing down more than 12% on Monday. Last week, the stock priced at $17 a share. The declines follow a wave of bearish analyst notes that have hit Snap, which calls itself a camera company, since its market debut. The average rating on the stock is the equivalent to sell, while the average price target is $16.50, according to a FactSet survey of 8 analysts. Many of the analysts have been warning clients that Snap stock is overvalued. Others have cited the company\'s shaky fundamentals, with its widening losses and slowing user growth offsetting strong revenue gains. ']

Name: Randgold Resources Limited
Article: 7 : [u'\r\n         FTSE 100 breaks 14-day winning run ahead of May speech\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The FTSE 100                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0dropped 0.2% to close at 7,327.13, breaking a 14-day winning streak. The index on Friday added 0.6% to 7,337.81, a 12th consecutive all-time closing high. Last week, the London benchmark rose 1.8%. ', u' Sterling slides: Much of Monday\u2019s focus was on the pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.1763%                                                                                                                                                 as the British currency slid by more than 1% to $1.2055 compared with $1.2189 late Friday in New York. ', u'Sterling had hit an intraday low of $1.1987, the lowest since its flash crash in October, on Sunday after British media reported that U.K. Prime Minister Theresa May will push for the country to leave the trading bloc\u2019s single market in exchange for greater control of immigration policy.', u' Read: Why the pound flash crashed, according to the \u2018central bank for central banks\u2019  ', u'May has previously signaled the U.K. will move toward a so-called hard Brexit. She will outline her Brexit outlook in a speech scheduled for Tuesday. ', u'Bank of England Governor Mark Carney is set to appear at the London School of Economics on Monday at 6:30 p.m., or 1:30 p.m. Eastern Time, and investors will watch for any comments he may make about the impact of Brexit on the British economy. ', u' Individual movers: Pound weakness in recent months has pushed up shares of multinational companies, as the profit they make overseas is beefed up when it\u2019s converted into pounds. Among such multinationals, shares of consumer goods products makers Reckitt Benckiser Group PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           RB., -0.28%                                                                                                                                                                              RBGLY, -0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Unilever PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           ULVR, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                                              UL, +0.42%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 1.6% and 0.6% on Monday, respectively. Luxury-goods maker Burberry Group PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           BRBY, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                                              BURBY, -0.58%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 1.6%. ', u'Burberry on Monday said Marco Gobbetti, currently CEO and chairman of C\xe9line, will join Burberry on Jan. 27 and will become chief executive in July.', u'But the prospect of a hard Brexit was weighing on shares of some banks, which rely on passporting rules that allow them to more easily conduct business throughout the EU.', u'Barclays PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           BARC, -1.89%                                                                                                                                                                              BCS, -0.71%                                                                                                                                                 fell 1.8% and Lloyds Banking Group PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           LLOY, -1.44%                                                                                                                                                                              LYG, -1.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gave up 2%. Separately, Royal Bank of Scotland Group                                                                                                                                                                                                           RBS, -1.05%                                                                                                                                                                              RBS, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 2.8% after Goldman Sachs downgraded the lender\u2019s rating to neutral from buy in a note discussing valuations in the European banking sector. ', u'Mining shares were higher, with Randgold Resources Ltd.                                                                                                                                                                                                           RRS, +1.60%                                                                                                                                                                              GOLD, +0.91%                                                                                                                                                \xa0up 1.6% as gold prices                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:GCG7                                                                                                                                                hit an eight-week high. Name: Otter Tail Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Follow the money \u2014 sell health-care stocks  and buy dividend shares\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The health-care sector warrants investors\u2019 attention these days, given potential changes under the new Republican administration. It\u2019s showing signs of cracking. The Health Care Select Sector SPDR ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLV, +0.21%                                                                                                                                                \xa0appears to be breaking down from a technical formation it\u2019s been in since the election, as you can see on this chart: ', u' Also see: 10 \u2018Dividend Aristocrat\u2019 stocks expected to rise up to 22% as you get paid to wait ', u' Dividend stocks on the mend ', u' Utilities ', u'Let\u2019s start with the Utilities Select Sector SPDR ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLU, +0.52%                                                                                                                                                 It made a tentative move above the trendline guiding it lower since last summer and is now easing back to test that break. When a stock or ETF tests a breakout, it trades back down to touch the line or pattern. That gives late bulls a second chance to get in at low prices, and if they take it, we\u2019ll see a nice pop back up. So far, no pop, but no aggressive selling, either. ', u'To be sure, the buy signal has to wait until prices break free from the two-month range they\u2019ve been in. But with strong underpinnings, it pays to keep this one on the radar screen and even dig deeper for individual utility stocks that look even stronger. Otter Tail Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           OTTR, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Unitil Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UTL, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                 come to mind, although these two are thinly traded and therefore present a bit more risk. ', u' REITs ', u'Real estate investment trusts (REITs), via the iShares U.S. Real Estate ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           IYR, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                 look similar. However, here it pays to dig deeper, because shopping REITs, which hold brick-and-mortar retail stores, are hurting. Housing, mortgage and hotel REITs are in much better shape. ', u'Chimera Investment Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CIM, +0.60%                                                                                                                                                 a mortgage REIT, and Pebblebrook Hotel Trust                                                                                                                                                                                                           PEB, +0.36%                                                                                                                                                 a hotel REIT, both have broken out to the upside from short-term patterns. So have many interest-rate sensitive homebuilders such as Beazer Homes USA Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BZH, -1.65%                                                                                                                                                 following Jan. 24\u2019s release of the Case-Shiller index indicating strong demand for homes.', u' Consumer-staples ', u'Finally, the Consumer Staples Select Sector SPDR ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLP, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0broke out to the upside last week (see the following chart). This sector is home to many stocks paying big dividends, and it also got hurt when bonds peaked last summer. However, since finding its low in late November, it has done quite well, coming back to beat its 50-day average and now test its 200-day average.', u'Procter & Gamble Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           PG, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was responsible for the ETF\u2019s breakout as it is the most heavily weighted stock in the group. This stock jumped last week on earnings. But many other stocks are on the verge of individual breakouts, including Colgate-Palmolive Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           CL, +0.37%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Coca-Cola Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KO, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                 Kimberly-Clark Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           KMB, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                 exploded higher Jan. 24 on earnings to score a technical breakout of its own. ', u'I am waiting for Archer-Daniels Midland Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ADM, +0.89%                                                                                                                                                \xa0to make its move from a triangle pattern. With volume-based indicators continuing to inch higher as prices pause, the indication is that the stock will eventually break out to the upside. There is no guarantee, of course, so we\u2019ll have to wait for the actual breakout. ', u' Michael Kahn, a chartered market technician (CMT), is a columnist for MarketWatch as well as Barrons.com, where he writes the \u201cGetting Technical\u201d column. He is the author of three books on charting, contributes to several trading and investing websites, and speaks at industry events. ']

Name: Lockheed Martin Corporation
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Trump\u2019s jawboning will hardly deliver enough jobs\r\n    ']
Body: [u'In his address before Congress, President Donald Trump touted his success in persuading major companies to move jobs back to America but his jawboning has delivered a punch much smaller than he advertises and that pales in comparison to the task of significantly improving on President Barack Obama\u2019s record as a jobs creator.', u'The succession of deals announced to create or return jobs to America sounds impressive \u2014 for example United Technologies                                                                                                                                                                                                           UTX, -0.39%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, Fiat Chrysler                                                                                                                                                                                                           FCAU, +1.45%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 and other top-line companies have jumped on board \u2014 but the challenge is too large to be accomplished by simply cajoling CEOs. ', u'The Obama recovery accomplished 2.1% annual economic growth and averaged about 185,000 new jobs each month. Trump would have to create at least 100,000 more jobs each month to bring growth up to 3% to 4% and substantially improve living standards for ordinary working Americans.', u'Generally, company announcements include many jobs that were planned before Trump\u2019s surprise election. For example, Lockheed Martin                                                                                                                                                                                                           LMT, -0.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0CEO Marillyn Hewson promised 1,800 jobs at its Fort Worth factory after meeting with the persuasive president, but those include some 1,000 that were announced in 2015.', u'Volkswagen                                                                                                                                                                                                           VOW, +0.98%                                                                                                                                                \xa0must restructure to accommodate the next generation of automation and mass produce electric vehicles. Thanks to German law, the union and the government of Lower Saxony combine to hold a majority of seats on the company board, creating a decided preference for German over U.S. and other foreign locations.', u'Notably, Mexico has negotiated an extensive network of free-trade agreements. U.S. and foreign auto makers can make cars and parts there for sale duty-free throughout North America, Europe and Japan \u2014 that is not something automakers can do in the United States. Given the dependence of the U.S. industry on components from Mexico, it is not at all clear that the United States would come out the winner in a trade war.', u'Tax and regulatory reform face barriers posed by divisions within the Republican Party in Congress, opposition from Democrats and the bureaucratic requirements of legislation that slow rule changes. And his new trade policy document emphasizes logging individual company complaints against foreign governments instead, for example, of taking on China to accomplish comprehensive compliance with its WTO commitments.', u'As businessmen, they were great at exploiting the system \u2014 including controversial records of lobbying for protection and outsourcing jobs. Now they must try their hands at accomplishing radical systemic reform and need cooperation from Congress and foreign governments, where leaders have ideas of their own and can\u2019t be fired by Trump.']

Name: Shopify Inc.
Article: 2 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Dow 20,000 notwithstanding, the stock market\u2019s momentum is unstoppable now \r\n    ']
Body: [u'It means the most-watched stock-market barometer in the world is becoming even more watched by individual investors everywhere. And that has positive implications, albeit psychological ones, for the market in general.', u'It is a sign the stock market is doing well, which can engender feelings of not wanting to miss the boat, which can in turn lead to buying. Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                 20,000, then, does have some meaning among average investors.', u'More important than Dow 20,000 is the index most professionals watch: the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                 On Wednesday, it gapped up at the open and broke out of a six-week trading range on volume that was 16% above average. Its 0.8% gain compares with the Nasdaq Composite\'s                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.39%                                                                                                                                                 rise of 0.99%.', u' Below the surface of the major averages, most defensive sectors like health care                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLV, +0.11%                                                                                                                                                 utilities                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLU, +0.60%                                                                                                                                                 and consumer staples                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLP, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                 are lagging behind noticeably. These areas are largely immune to the ups and downs of the economic cycle. Since they are favored during uncertain times or periods of weakening economic growth, their underperformance is a substantial \u201cpositive.\u201d It objectively says investors aren\u2019t interested in playing it safe. A risk-on mindset prevails.', u' Meanwhile, the financials                                                                                                                                                                                                           XLF, +0.02%                                                                                                                                                 are attempting to climb out of their six-week trading range after a hot move into early December. The stocks have been the top performer since this market advance began just before the election. It is hard not to like a market in which this segment, the banks                      and brokers                                                                                                                                                                                                           XBD, -0.23%                                                                                                                                                 in particular, is leading.', u'Elsewhere, market health improved around the start of the year as the Nasdaq began outperforming, thanks to some of its institutional favorites like Amazon.com                                                                                                                                                                                                           AMZN, +0.52%                                                                                                                                                 Alphabet                                                                            FB, +0.63%                                                                                                                                                 This occurred as some of the segments believed to benefit from anticipated Trump administration policies such as deregulation and infrastructure spending remained well-bid.', u' Read: Harry Boxer on four momentum stocks that are breaking out ', u'Among names with favorable chart patterns, Amazon.com is in the midst of a business turnaround. From a loss of 52 cents a share in 2014, it logged a $1.25-a-share profit in 2015, with most Wall Street analysts eyeing a 282% jump to $4.77 a share last year and another leap of 83% to $8.71 this year.', u' Besides Amazon, another institutional favorite has been Facebook                                                                                                                                                                                                           FB, +0.63%                                                                                                                                                 The two are rare birds in this market due to their being expected to put up earnings growth of more than 25% this year, yet retaining ultra-deep liquidity. Institutional investors appreciate the latter, which facilitates the building up and breaking down of large positions.', u' Other growth issues are also forming the right sides of cup patterns, though most are not as ripe for a breakout as Amazon and Facebook. Some of these waiting in the wings are Alibaba                                                                                                                                                                                                           BABA, +0.44%                                                                                                                                                 and Grubhub                                                                                                                                                                                                           GRUB, -0.35%                                                                                                                                                ', u'A number of breakouts have stayed above their entry point, including Eagle Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           EXP, +0.29% back into their chart patterns, a warning sign about general market health would be given.', u' Dow 20,000 conclusion ', u' \u2014 Kevin Marder ', u' For intraday market comments and stock ideas:
