Name: Rite Aid Corporation
Article: 5 : [u"\r\n         Rite Aid's stock plunges after buyout price by Walgreens was slashed\r\n    "]
Body: [u'Shares of Rite Aid Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           RAD, -1.00%                                                                                                                                                 plummeted 17% in active premarket trade Monday, after the drugstore chain and its buyer, Walgreens Boots Alliance Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           WBA, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                 agreed to lower the per-share acquisition price. The new deal calls for Walgreens to pay a minimum of $6.50 for each Rite Aid share outstanding and a maximum of $7 a share. When merger deal was first announced in October 2015, the per-share bid was $9 a share. The final price per share will be determined by how many stores need to be divested to attain regulatory approval of the deal. The price will be set at $7 a share if 1,000 or fewer stores are required for divestiture, and at $6.50 a share if 1,200 stores are required for divestiture. The companies agreed to extend the end date of their merger agreement to July 31, 2017 from Jan. 27, 2017. Rite Aid\'s stock has lost 11% over the past 12 months through Friday, while Walgreens shares have gained 2.2% and the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.18%                                                                                                                                                 has climbed 18%.']

Name: Chevron Corporation
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Dow posts 11th straight record; S&P 500 sees fifth straight weekly gain\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.30%                                                                                                                                                 rose 11.44 points, or less than 0.1%, to end at 20,821.76. The blue-chip average rose for an 11th straight day for the first time since 1992, as well as its 11th straight record closing high\u2014the longest such streak since 1987. The Dow had traded in negative territory for essentially the entire session, only breaking into the green with seconds to spare.', u'The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 3.53 points, or 0.2%, to end at a record of 2,367.34. The Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 9.8 points, or 0.2%, to end at 5,845.31.', u'Among the top drags on the Dow, Goldman Sachs Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          GS, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 1.5% while J.P. Morgan Chase & Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JPM, +0.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 0.9%. The third- and fourth-largest decliners were Exxon Mobil                                                                                                                                                                                                           XOM, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                                              XOM, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                                              XOM, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                 and Chevron Corp                                                                                                                                                                                                          CVX, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                \xa0which lost 0.8% on the day.', u'The Dow is up nearly 9.1% over the past three months, with investors attributing gains largely to Trump\u2019s November election victory. Investors are betting that Trump\u2019s policies on taxes and regulation will accelerate economic growth and boost corporate earnings, but concerns are growing over the administration\u2019s ability to deliver on the tax plans.', u' Read:  Here\u2019s how analysts say you should trade Trump\u2019s speech to Congress ', u' Read: Mnuchin in no rush to label China a currency manipulator ', u' And see: Doubts persist about tax timing as Trump meets with CEOs ', u' Read:  Why oil experts think OPEC\u2019s U.S. headache won\u2019t go away this year ', u' Crude oil                                                                                                                                                                                                           US:CLJ7                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell but held on to a weekly gain after data showed a further rise in the number of U.S. rigs drilling for crude. The U.S. benchmark on Thursday posted its highest close in more than a year and a half.', u'In the latest economic data, consumer sentiment fell from a 13-year high in February, while new-home sales posted a strong rebound in January.', u' Stock movers: Shares of Hewlett Packard Enterprise Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                          HPE, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slumped 6.9% after the IT company late Thursday reported lower sales than expected and cut its earnings projections for the fiscal year. ', u'Shares of RH                                                                                                                                                                                                          RH, +2.53%                                                                                                                                                 the company formerly known as Restoration Hardware, jumped 24% a day after it forecast higher-than-expected quarterly results.', u' Nordstrom Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JWN, -1.99%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rallied 5.7% after the department store chain late Thursday reported earnings that beat forecasts. The retailer has been in focus following a recent decision by the company to drop Ivanka Trump\u2019s fashion label, citing poor sales. President Trump had tweeted that the company was treating his daughter \u201cso unfairly,\u201d although the tweet didn\u2019t have a lasting negative impact on the stock.', u' Foot Locker Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           FL, -2.37%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 9.4% after the shoe retailer reported profit that beat forecasts. ', u' J.C. Penney Co. Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           JCP, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0tumbled 5.8%, also after releasing results. ', u' Other markets: Asian stock markets closed mostly lower, with Europe                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0following the same trend in the early going. ', u'Metals rose across the board, with silver                                                                                                                                                                                                           SIH7, -0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0on track for a ninth straight weeks of gains.', u'The ICE Dollar index                                                                                                                                                                                                           DXY, -0.05%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 0.1%. ']

Name: Exelon Corporation
Article: 3 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Trump\u2019s fake populism in action\r\n    ']
Body: [u'In 1829, President Andrew Jackson gave his inaugural address as populist working man, then invited his rough-hewn supporters to a party at the White House \u2014 which they trashed (by some accounts anyway) in a drunken bacchanal that ended only when the booze was moved outside.', u'In 2017, Donald Trump gave a speech described as Jacksonian by its co-author Steve Bannon (though Steve Sestakovich explains in the Wall Street Journal the many ways that claim is as bogus as a Breitbart News headline). Then the new president went back to the Oval Office, sans the unwashed, and signed an order to begin taking away their health insurance.', u'On Monday, Trump began by meeting corporate titans like Under Armour\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           UA, -2.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Kevin Plank and Lockheed Martin\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           LMT, -0.18%                                                                                                                                                \xa0Marillyn Hewson, promising them less shareholder-unfriendly regulation and a corporate tax cut; then signed orders freezing hiring of (almost entirely middle-income) government workers, barred aid to family-planning organizations outside the U.S., serving virtually all poor and working-class people by U.S. standards, unless they agree never to ever mention abortion; and, oh yes, pulled the U.S. out of the Trans-Pacific Partnership trade deal, which the U.S. had never ratified anyway. ', u' In terms Spicer might understand, the federal workforce has shrunk by the size of Trump\u2019s inaugural crowd, over 24 years in which population growth almost exactly matched the number of people who voted for Hillary Clinton. Who won last November\u2019s popular vote by 2.9 million votes \u2014 just shy of the lower estimates of the number of people who gave up a Saturday to resist Trump. Whose spokesman says the protests were not aimed at Trump at all.', u'Perhaps it\u2019s the part where Republicans repeal the taxes on people who make over $250,000 a year, which pays for health insurance for middle-income folks and sustains Medicare.', u'Unless you judge it by the Environmental Protection Agency action plan leaked to just-debuted news service Axios, which targets the Obama administration\u2019s Clean Power Plan, protested by utilities like Southern Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SO, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Exelon                                                                                                                                                                                                           EXC, +0.75%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and automotive gas-mileage standards for the likes of Ford                                                                                                                                                                                                           F, +0.81%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and General Motors                                                                                                                                                                                                           GM, -0.29%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, both designed to attack climate change, which according to Trump isn\u2019t proven, doesn\u2019t exist, or is a Chinese con to gut U.S. manufacturing, ', u'Bringing back coal would be super-populist, except that the wind-power industry now employs more people. And provides about 40% as much electricity as coal, with zero emissions. So would having cars that get worse gas mileage, making middle-income workers buy more gas.', u'You know what else will be super-populist? The 44,000 extra deaths per year that would result from even 20 million people losing their health coverage. (The Congressional Budget Office says GOP plans would make 32 million people lose insurance). They won\u2019t be hedge-fund managers.']

Article: 15 : [u'\r\n         Rallying bank shares propel European stocks to 1-week closing high\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Stoxx Europe 600 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.46%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gained 0.6% to close at 364.07, trimming its weekly loss to 0.6%. Friday\u2019s jump also took the index to its highest close since Jan. 27. ', u' Banks rule: The financial sector                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXFINP, -0.02%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was putting in the best performance Friday, with the Stoxx 600 Bank Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           FX7, -0.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rising 1.3%. ', u'The moves came after reports Trump on Friday plans to sign an executive action to scale back the 2010 Dodd-Frank financial-overhaul law, as part of a push to dismantle much of the regulatory system put in place after the financial crisis.', u'Shares of Deutsche Bank                                                                                                                                                                                                           DBK, -0.72%                                                                                                                                                                              DB, +0.15%                                                                                                                                                \xa0advanced 3.6%, winning back a portion of Thursday\u2019s loss. The German lending heavyweight\u2019s shares fell 5.2% in the previous session after it posted a worse-than-expected fourth-quarter net loss of 1.9 billion euros ($2.05 billion).', u'Shares of Royal Bank of Scotland PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           RBS, -1.01%                                                                                                                                                                              RBS, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                 picked up 2.7%, France\u2019s BNP Paribas SA                                                                                                                                                                                                           BNP, +0.30%                                                                                                                                                 tacked on 1.5%, and Credit Suisse Group AG                                                                                                                                                                                                           CSGN, -1.85%                                                                                                                                                                              CS, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed 1.8%. ', u'But Banco Popular Espa\xf1ol SA                                                                                                                                                                                                           POP, +0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shares were dragged down 7.4% after the Spanish lender swung to a yearly loss of \u20ac3.5 billion ($3.75 billion), hurt by bad loans and higher provisions. ', u' Miners take a hit: China is a key market for industrial and precious metals, and shares of miners were hit Friday after the country\u2019s central bank raised short-term interest rates, part of a shift by Beijing toward tighter monetary policy. ', u'Glencore PLC\xa0                                                                                                                                                                                                          GLEN, +0.26%                                                                                                                                                                              GLCNF, +0.00%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slumped 4.8%, Boliden AB                                                                                                                                                                                                           BOL, +1.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0gave up 1.7% and steel producer ArcelorMittal SA                                                                                                                                                                                                           MT, -0.88%                                                                                                                                                \xa0declined 2.3%. ', u' Indexes: Germany\u2019s DAX 30 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           DAX, -0.28%                                                                                                                                                 edged up 0.2% to 11,651.49. France\u2019s CAC 40                                                                                                                                                                                                           PX1, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                 put on 0.7% to 4,825.42, and Spain\u2019s IBEX 35                                                                                                                                                                                                           IBEX, +0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0moved up 0.6% to 9,462.70. The U.K\u2019s FTSE 100                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.68%                                                                                                                                                 ended 0.7% higher at 7,188.30, a two-week closing high. ', u'The euro                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote up bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008136/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>EURUSD, +0.0647%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was buying $1.0790, versus $1.0760 late Thursday. ', u' Economic docket: Eurozone output kept up its growth pace in January. Markit\u2019s final composite sector purchasing managers\u2019 index came in at 54.4, the same as in December and slightly above a preliminary reading of 54.3. A reading above 50 signals expansion. ', u'Investors were also looking to the U.S., where the monthly nonfarm payrolls report showed 227,000 jobs were added to the economy in January. Economists polled by MarketWatch expected a print of 197,000. ']

Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Mall REITs rocked by news of J.C. Penney store closures \r\n    ']
Body: [u'J.C. Penney                                                                                                                                                                                                          JCP, -1.95%                                                                                                                                                said it will close 130 to 140 stores in the next few months, to \u201chelp align the company\u2019s brick-and-mortar presence with its omnichannel network, thereby redirecting capital resources to invest in locations and initiatives that offer the greatest revenue potential.\u201d', u'\u201cIt\u2019s having a negative effect on all REITs as J.C. Body: [u'The Nasdaq                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.03%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 8.24 points, or 0.2%, to close at 5,682.45, and the Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.31%                                                                                                                                                 fell 35.95 points, or 0.2%, to end at 20,054.34. Name: Under Armour, Inc.
Article: 6 : [u'\r\n         Tiffany\u2019s stock clobbered as latest executive departure startles investors\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Tiffany & Co. shares slid 2.5% Monday as investors digested news of yet another executive departure, this time of Chief Executive Frederic Cumenal, who had held the role since April 2015. ', u'The move comes after the exits of design director Francesca Amfitheatrof in January and of Chief Finance Officer Ralph Nicoletti last May, and follows recent financial results that the company described as disappointing in the statement announcing the news.', u'It also comes in the wake of the departures last week of the CEO of Ralph Lauren Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                          RL, -0.37%                                                                                                                                                and the CFO of Under Armour Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          UA, -1.88%                                                                                                                                                 , making for a busy period in executive moves.', u' Read: Ralph Lauren CEO\u2019s departure creates uncertainty about the \u2018way forward\u2019 ', u' Also: Under Armour suffers multiple downgrades on fears the \u2018growth story\u2019 is ending ', u'Mizuho downgraded Tiffany\u2019s stock                                                                                                                                                                                                          TIF, -0.43%                                                                                                                                                to neutral from buy and cut its share-price target to $74 from $90, just below its current trading level of about $78.', u' Don\u2019t miss:  Engagement rings get a makeover with personalized styles outshining size ', u'In January, the company said the turmoil around its flagship Fifth Avenue store in New York City, made famous by Audrey Hepburn\u2019s window shopping in the iconic 1960s film \u201cBreakfast at Tiffany\u2019s,\u201d was hurting traffic. The store is close to Trump Tower, which has been subjected to constant protests and a heavy police presence ever since the November presidential election.', u' See also: The robbery that saw more than 400 pieces of jewelry walk out Tiffany & Co.\u2019s doors ', u'Meanwhile, design director Amfitheatrof has been replaced by Reed Krakoff, former creative director of Coach Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                          COH, -1.27%                                                                                                                                                who has been tasked with directing design for Tiffany\u2019s jewelry and luxury accessories and for shaping the overall look and feel of stores, e-commerce, marketing and advertising. ', u'Kowalski said the company is committed to its core business strategy, which it intends to accelerate to compete better in the global luxury market. ', u' Read:  My mother saved $10,000 for my wedding \u2014 but now that I\u2019m 41, should I spend it on a house? ', u'\u201cThe loss (or gain) of any one person is not likely to break (or make) a retailer,\u201d said analysts led by Simeon Siegel. That said, he added, at a valuation of about 20 times Instinet\u2019s earnings-per-share forecast for fiscal 2018 and with Tiffany shares having outperformed over the last 12 months, rising 24% while the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                          SPX, -0.03%                                                                                                                                                has tacked on 20% and the SPDR S&P Retail exchange-traded fund                                                                                                                                                                                                          XRT, -0.93%                                                                                                                                                is up 7%, \u201cwe believe [Tiffany] has been viewed as a relatively safer investment in retail, [and] it seems fair to assume shares will be pressured by the added uncertainty.\u201d', u'The commercial made the Washington Post\u2019s list of five worst Super Bowl commercials, with critics complaining it was more about Lady Gaga than the Tiffany brand.']

Name: Pandora Media, Inc.
Article: 10 : [u'\r\n         Pandora falls after disappointing forecast\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Pandora Media Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           P, -0.65%                                                                                                                                                 reported better-than-expected financial performance in the fourth quarter Thursday, but shares slipped on a disappointing forecast. The internet-radio company revealed a net loss of $19.4 million, or 38 cents a share, on revenue of $392.6 million. After adjustments for stock-based compensation and other effects, the company claimed a loss of 13 cents a share. Analysts on average expected Pandora to report an adjusted loss of 21 cents a share on sales of $374 million, according to FactSet. Last month, Pandora revealed that it would lay off employees despite raking in higher revenue that it originally expected for the quarter. Pandora\'s forecast for the first quarter was well below analyst estimates, however. Pandora predicted revenue of $10 million to $320 million, while analysts on average were expecting revenue of $342 million, according to FactSet. Pandora predicted full-year 2017 revenue of $1.55 billion to $1.7 billion, while analysts expected $1.66 billion. Pandora shares dove more than 5% in after-hours trading after the results were released, but losses calmed down and settled closer to 2% later in the afternoon.']

Article: 8 : [u'\r\n         FTSE 100 slides most since June as May says Britain will leave EU\u2019s single market\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The FTSE 100                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, -0.70%                                                                                                                                                \xa0fell 1.5% to close at 7,220.38, its biggest one-day percentage loss since June 27, according to FactSet data. ', u'May, in a highly anticipated speech in London, said Britain does \u201cnot seek membership of the single market but the greatest possible access to it.\u201d ', u' Read: U.K. leader Theresa May\u2019s plan for Brexit \u2014 text of her speech in full ', u'Sterling                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/16008140/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPUSD, -0.1763%                                                                                                                                                 soared almost 3% to $1.2391 from $1.2046 late Monday, heading toward its largest one-day rise since October 2008. Against the euro, the pound                                                                                                                                                                                                           <span class="quote down bgQuote" data-channel="/quotes/zigman/15934085/realtime/sampled" data-bgformat=\'{"change":"0,0.0000"}\'>GBPEUR, -0.2253%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose to \u20ac1.1586, compared with \u20ac1.1363 on Monday. ', u'The FTSE 100 on Monday dropped 0.2%, breaking a 14-day winning streak. Monday\u2019s loss also broke a string of 12 consecutive all-time closing highs, with the move coming after media reports said May planned to seek a hard Brexit in exchange for greater control of immigration policy. ', u' Movers: A hard Brexit has particular implications for financial institutions based in the U.K., which rely on \u201cpassporting\u201d rights for smooth operation within the EU. Most bank shares were holding to gains after May\u2019s speech. ', u' See: U.K.\u2019s May offers escape hatch to banks, car makers in Brexit plan speech ', u'Barclays PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           BARC, -1.87%                                                                                                                                                                              BCS, -0.75%                                                                                                                                                 rose 0.2% and Royal Bank of Scotland PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           RBS, -1.01%                                                                                                                                                                              RBS, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0picked up 2.5%. Asia-focused Standard Chartered PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           STAN, -1.30%                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed 2.8% as the company said it\u2019s recently wrapped up $1.6 billion in shipping deals. But HSBC PLC                                                                                                                                                                                                           HSBA, -0.87%                                                                                                                                                                              HSBC, -0.44%                                                                                                                                                                              0005, -0.94%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was down 2%.', u'Meanwhile, Rolls-Royce Holdings PLC shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           RR., -1.93%                                                                                                                                                                              RYCEY, -2.24%                                                                                                                                                \xa0jumped 4.4% after the jet-engine maker said Monday it will pay $810 million to settle corruption investigations with U.S., British and other authorities. ', u'British American Tobacco shares                                                                                                                                                                                                           BATS, -0.12%                                                                                                                                                                              BTI, +0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0swung down 3.8%, among the multinational companies on the FTSE 100 feeling the weight of a stronger pound. The tobacco maker early Tuesday said it would pay $49.4 billion for the 57.8% of Reynolds American Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           RAI, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0that it doesn\u2019t already own. The move comes after BAT said in October it had made an offer for Reynolds valued at $56.50 a share, or about $47 billion, to take full control.', u' Economic docket: The U.K.\u2019s annual inflation rate rose to 1.6% in December, with a rise in airfares and food prices contributing to pushing the rate to its highest since July 2014. The rate is moving closer to the Bank of England\u2019s target of 2%. ']

Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Bull market\u2019s 8-year anniversary reminds us that the Dow rewards the bold \r\n    ']
Body: [u'The Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -1.14%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is a benchmark of 30 large U.S. companies and generally serves as a barometer of broader market conditions; among investors here and abroad, the blue-chip average is synonymous with the U.S. stock market, period. ', u'Compared with stocks in Europe and Asia, the Dow is clearly an overachiever. The Stoxx Europe 600 Euro                                                                                                                                                                                                           SXXP, -0.85%                                                                                                                                                \xa0climbed 138%, the U.K\u2019s FTSE 100                                                                                                                                                                                                           UKX, +0.62%                                                                                                                                                \xa0advanced 108%, China\u2019s Shanghai Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           SHCOMP, -0.50%                                                                                                                                                \xa0added 50% and Japan\u2019s Nikkei                                                                                                                                                                                                           NIK, -2.13%                                                                                                                                                \xa0rose 175% during the same time frame. ', u'Among the Dow components remaining from 2009, Home Depot Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           HD, -0.81%                                                                                                                                                 is the undisputed star, soaring 608%, while American Express Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AXP, -1.67%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Walt Disney Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           DIS, -0.85%                                                                                                                                                \xa0both surged more than 500%.', u'Seven companies have joined the Dow after the bull market began its epic climb, doing their share to fuel the Dow\u2019s bullish run. UnitedHealth Group Inc. Apple Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAPL, -1.15%                                                                                                                                                 the youngest member of the blue-chip family, has shot up nearly 1,000% since 2009, although it rose only 9.3% since it became a Dow component two years ago. ', u' Newcomers on the Dow  ', u'Yet, not all Dow stocks have posted such stellar returns. Oil major Exxon Mobil Corp. Article: 3 : [u'\r\n        ', u' Stocks have rallied so much, there are no longer any \u2018resistance\u2019 levels\r\n    ']
Body: [u'If the Dow Jones Industrial Average closes at an all-time high Tuesday, it will be a record 13 days in a row.', u'From a technical-analysis perspective, something happened Monday that I don\u2019t recall seeing: Both the Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and the S&P 500 Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.20%                                                                                                                                                \xa0broke above near-term, mid-term and longer-term resistance levels. Thus, there are no resistance levels at this particular time.', u'Over the past 20 years, while I have been attentive to these patterns, I have never seen the markets in a position where no resistance levels are clearly defined. Article: 5 : [u'\r\n         Trump and the bulls look to rip a hole in oil prices\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Of course, some will tell you all that uncertainty may eventually be good for stocks. But while we\u2019re waiting for President Donald Trump to get stock investors excited, or really scared, it\u2019s worth keeping an eye on other assets, which have triggered volatility for equities in the past.', u'That brings us to oil \u2014 one asset that should never go ignored by investors too long. Our call of the day comes from Raoul Pal, founder of Global Macro Investor. He says it\u2019s time to buck the big-money trend and short oil, because those who produce the black stuff think the price right now really should be at $30. ', u'Pal\u2019s call comes after the latest weekly Commitment of Traders report from the U.S. Commodity Futures Trading Commission (ending Jan. 17) showed hedge funds and other money managers placed more bullish oil positions than any week since 2006. That\u2019s as actual producers upped their short hedges to the highest level since 2007, in a bid to lock in higher prices. Article: 2 : [u'\r\n         Will Trump\u2019s boost for defense stocks still stand after tonight?\r\n    ']
Body: [u' Read also:  Trump\u2019s $30 trillion debt dilemma ', u'Trump made the promise to governors at the White House Monday and said that the bump would be funded by savings across all other government departments. The president is scheduled to address Congress at 9 p.m. Eastern and analysts are expecting him to offer details of his plans for military spending. ', u'The Office of Management and Budget said Monday that the budget would seek $54 billion in extra spending on defense, equal to a 10% rise. Trump\u2019s budget proposal will be released in mid-March, according to OMB communications director John Czwartacki, and the focus on military spending will likely require Congress to pass a new deal to lift caps on military spending, which are slated to return in 2018.', u' See: Trump: U.S. will be \u2018at the top of the pack\u2019 on nukes ', u'\u201cWith a world on fire, America cannot secure peace through strength with just 3 percent more than President [Barack] Obama\u2019s budget. We can and must do better,\u201d McCain said in a statement. ', u'Defense stocks have performed strongly since the November presidential election as investors bet Trump\u2019s victory would be a boon for the sector. The iShares U.S. Aerospace & Defence exchange-traded fund                                                                                                                                                                                                           ITA, -0.33%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has seen about $$1.2 billion in inflows since Nov. 9, more than doubling its assets. ', u'The SPDR S&P Aerospace & Defense ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           XAR, -0.60%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has seen inflows of $236.8 million, according to ETF.com, while the PowerShares Aerospace & Defense ETF                                                                                                                                                                                                           PPA, -0.32%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has attracted $172 million in inflows. ', u' The three ETFs have all gained since the election, with the SPDR ETF up about 20%, as the chart below illustrates.', u'Among individual stocks, Boeing Co.                                                                                                                                                                                                           BA, +0.16%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained about 21% in the last three months, General Dynamics Corp.                                                                                                                                                                                                           GD, -0.10%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 10% and Arconic Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           ARNC, -0.86%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 44.7%. The S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has gained 7.5% in the same period, and the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.25%                                                                                                                                                \xa0is up 9%.', u'The news boosted defense stocks in Europe and Asia overnight, fueling expectations that they will win supply contracts. ', u' See also: Putin, in the news in the U.S., faces an enemy at home ']

Name: Astrazeneca PLC
Article: 1 : [u'\r\n         Pharma says high prices fund drug development \u2014 but this study finds otherwise\r\n    ']
Body: [u'U.S. drug prices, notoriously higher than those in in other countries, generate \u201csubstantially\u201d more revenue for companies than their research-and-development costs, according to a new report published in the journal Health Affairs. ', u'Pharmaceutical manufacturers often defend the high, and growing, cost of their medications by pointing to the high levels of risk involved in drug development. A study by the Tufts Center for the Study of Drug Development, which is funded in part by industry, found that research-and-development costs on average $2.9 billion per new drug \u2014 a figure frequently invoked by drugmakers.', u' Related: Big pharma won\u2019t stop raising prices in 2017 \u2014 it\u2019ll just do it smarter ', u'The report, published Tuesday, could be an important counterweight to those industry figures. President Donald Trump has criticized drug prices several times, saying on Tuesday that he was working on a new system to increase industry competition, but it\u2019s unclear what his approach would be. ', u' Read:  Investors have stopped believing Trump\u2019s drug price threats ', u'The analysis focused on the 20 top-selling U.S. drugs, which are sold by 15 companies, including AbbVie Inc. Name: Unilever PLC
Article: 18 : [u'\r\n         Tempted to cash in on the market rally? Why Tesla may be a good place to start\r\n    ']
Body: [u'Granted, a 0.09% drop for the S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0on Thursday is hardly a convincing selloff, but it may be a sign investors are growing hesitant to shovel more money into what some see as a frothy stock market. ', u'Maybe the biggest tell that we\u2019ve reached the peak came from an unexpected front \u2014 POTUS \u2014 after he cheerfully shared his excitement over the rally in a tweet. ', u' Read: Investors might finally be recognizing risk in the stock market ', u'In our call of the day, Saxo Bank\u2019s Peter Garnry says it\u2019s time to give up on Tesla, given its staggering 50% surge since early December. The electric car maker-turned-energy innovation company is releasing earnings next week, but the preliminary fourth-quarter numbers are \u201cway below expectations,\u201d according to Saxo\u2019s head of equity strategy. ', u' Tesla\u2019s SolarCity acquisition comes with great risks, he argues, and the company will likely need to tap capital markets to fuel growth.', u' Read: Tesla earnings: Expect Model 3 updates amid record stock highs ', u'The Tesla stock was just a few bucks away from breaking its previous intraday record of $291.42 earlier this week, but investors got cold feet. ', u' According to Jeff Hirsch, a.k.a. the Almanac Trader, the S&P tends to decline on both the trading day before and the trading day after the holiday, which falls on Feb. 20 this year. ', u'The Dow                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJIA, -0.04%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, S&P 500                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, +0.19%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Nasdaq Composite                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.37%                                                                                                                                                \xa0\xa0are showing a lack of enthusiasm to push higher, with all off the opening in negative territory. ', u'See Market Snapshot for the latest action.', u'Kraft                                                                                                                                                                                                           KHC, +0.65%                                                                                                                                                \xa0confirmed it has made a merger approach to Unilever                                                                                                                                                                                                           ULVR, +0.15%                                                                                                                                                                              UL, +0.31%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, but the consumer goods giant has declined the initial proposal.', u'Investors have been deciphering Mark Zuckerberg\u2019s 6,000-word \u201cState of the Union\u201d-style mission statement on Facebook                                                                                                                                                                                                          FB, +0.54%                                                                                                                                                \xa0.', u' Deere                                                                                                                                                                                                           DE, +0.57%                                                                                                                                                \xa0, J.M. Smucker                                                                                                                                                                                                          SJM, -0.82%                                                                                                                                                \xa0and Campbell Soup                                                                                                                                                                                                          CPB, -0.11%                                                                                                                                                \xa0were on earnings docket before the bell.', u'Samsung heir Lee Jae-yong has been arrested on bribery charges, as the corruption scandal continues to rock South Korea.', u'On Deck Capital                                                                                                                                                                                                           ONDK, -1.78%                                                                                                                                                 late Thursday reported its biggest quarterly loss ever, and the small-business lender slid 24% after hours.', u'Plans by TransCanada                                                                                                                                                                                                           TRP, +0.38%                                                                                                                                                \xa0 to build the Keystone XL oil pipeline across Nebraska got a second chance. ', u'44% \u2014 That is how much the New York Times stock                                                                                                                                                                                                           NYT, +0.35%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has rallied since Donald Trump was elected president, despite the president\u2019s criticism of the news organization on Twitter.', u'And since those tweets, the stock has gained 31%, as of three days ago, according to media analysis company Axios. In fact, six of the seven companies called out by Trump in tweets are actually trading higher now than before he targeted them, it says.', u'\u201cIt was bizarre theater. He turned a presidential press conference into a reality TV show in which he can be the star and browbeat anyone who objects to him with the power of his office.\u201d \u2014 Douglas Brinkley, a professor of history at Rice University, speaking to Associated Press about Trump\u2019s presser yesterday. That kind of reaction was still spreading on social media Friday.', u' Read: Touting \u2018fine-tuned machine,\u2019 Trump incorrectly states magnitude of election victory ', u'How to poop in space? Problem solved after NASA competition ', u'Trump\u2019s replacement pick for national security adviser turns down the job offer', u'This Uber driver made $507,500 last year (but not by driving)', u'Target                                                                                                                                                                                                           TGT, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0was in the headlines after a man in Florida tried to blow up one of its stores to tank the stock price. ', u' Need to Know starts early and is updated until the opening bell, but sign up here to get it delivered once to your email box. Be sure to check the Need to Know item. The emailed version will be sent out at about 7:30 a.m. Eastern. ', u' Or Follow MarketWatch on Twitter or Facebook.']

For now, it\u2019s probably better to stay away from this group, as a Trump play. ', u' Infrastructure plays ', u'This group is another tough one. Yes, our nation\u2019s infrastructure is crumbling. You see this all the time when you drive around. And Trump\u2019s plan to boost infrastructure spending would no doubt help this space, especially materials companies like Vulcan Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           VMC, +0.34%                                                                                                                                                 Martin Marietta Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           MLM, +0.37%                                                                                                                                                 and Summit Materials                                                                                                                                                                                                           SUM, +0.09%                                                                                                                                                 ', u' At the time of publication, Michael Brush had no positions in any stocks mentioned in this column. Brush has suggested DG, AMZN, DIS, BRK.B, PNC, JPM, DHI, NKE, XOM, GILD, CELG, COP, HES, CMG and GOOGL in his stock newsletter, Brush Up on Stocks. Brush is a Manhattan-based financial writer who has covered business for the New York Times and The Economist group, and he attended Columbia Business School in the Knight-Bagehot program.  ']

Name: Alaska Air Group, Inc.
Article: 10 : [u'\r\n         Airline stocks drop in wake of President Trump\u2019s immigration ban\r\n    ']
Body: [u'The NYSE Arca Airline Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           XAL, -0.45%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slumped 1.7% to the lowest level in nearly eight weeks. That compares with a 0.6% decline in the S&P 500 Index.                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                \xa0See Market Snapshot.', u'That extends the 2.1% selloff suffered on Friday, when Trump signed the order. Also hurting the airline industry on Friday was American Airlines Group Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           AAL, -2.85%                                                                                                                                                \xa0which forecast higher costs resulting from new union contracts and employee profit-sharing, though the company beat fourth-quarter estimate. Read more about American\u2019s results.', u'Trump\u2018s immigration order barred Syrian refugees from entering the U.S., blocked citizens of seven predominantly-Muslim countries from entering the country for 90 days and suspended all refugee admission for 120 days. That sparked protests around the country at major airports over the weekend, as many refugees were detained at airports after the order was signed.', u' Don\u2019t miss: Netflix, Twitter, Starbucks and other company execs speak out against Trump immigration ban.', u' See also: ACLU raises record $24.2 million online after Trump\u2019s immigration ban.', u'Among the sector\u2019s biggest decliners, American\u2019s stock slid 4.4% and shares of United Continental Holdings Inc.                                                                                                                                                                                                           UAL, -1.09%                                                                                                                                                \xa0shed 3.6%. American\u2019s revenue exposure to Africa and the Middle East was 1.8% in 2015, according to data provided FactSet, while United\u2019s exposure is 4.5%.', u'Delta Air Lines Inc.\u2019s stock slumped 4.1%, as computer problems Sunday evening led to widespread flight delays and cancellations. Trump tweeted that Delta\u2019s \u201ccomputer outage\u201d contributed to the \u201cbig problems\u201d at airports.', u'Among other more-active air carrier shares, JetBlue Airways Corp.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           JBLU, -0.94%                                                                                                                                                \xa0dropped 1.5%, Southwest Airlines Co.\u2019s\xa0                                                                                                                                                                                                          LUV, -0.40%                                                                                                                                                \xa0slipped 0.7% and Alaska Air Group Inc.\u2019s                                                                                                                                                                                                           ALK, -0.71%                                                                                                                                                \xa0lost 1%.', u' From the New York Post: Kellyanne Conway: Chaos at airports after immigration order is a small price to pay.', u'The NYSE Arca Airline Index has now lost 5% since Dec. 20, when the index closed at the highest level since March 2002. The S&P 500 has ticked up 0.4% over the same time, while the Dow Jones Transportation Average                                                                                                                                                                                                           DJT, -0.07%                                                                                                                                                \xa0has inched up 0.2%.', u'The downdraft for airline stocks on the day comes as the overall market was retreating firmly, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average                                                                                                                                                                                                          DJIA, -0.29%                                                                                                                                                 the S&P 500 index                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPX, -0.17%                                                                                                                                                 and the Nasdaq Composite Index                                                                                                                                                                                                           COMP, +0.06%                                                                                                                                                \xa0all on pace to see their worst one-day decline since Oct. 11 at its worst levels on Monday, as investors assess Trump\u2019s immigration and trade policies. ']
